<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP CATALYTIC PROCESSES AND MATERIALS </TITLE></head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2><HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">CATALYTIC PROCESSES AND MATERIALS</a></H3>
<PRE>
Group leader:   Prof.  Dr. J.A. Lercher

Senior Scientists:
Dr. T. Fransen
Dr. G.C. Eder-Mirth
Dr. J.G.van Ommen
Dr. K. Seshan

E-mail addresses:
<A HREF="mailto:j.a.lercher@ct.utwente.nl">j.a.lercher@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:t.fransen@ct.utwente.nl">t.fransen@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:g.mirth@ct.utwente.nl">g.mirth@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:j.g.vanommen@ct.utwente.nl">j.g.vanommen@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:k.seshan@ct.utwente.nl">k.seshan@ct.utwente.nl</A>

Phone: (+31)-53-4892860
Fax:     (+31)-53-4894683
</PRE><P>

Research activities aim at the understanding of heterogeneously catalyzed reactions on a meso- and microscopic level and at using this knowledge for catalyst design. This requires detailed information about the nature of the catalyst bulk and surface and its interaction with reactants and products.<BR>
The catalysts are characterized by a variety of physicochemical techniques that were especially adapted for investigation of highly porous solids.<BR>
The techniques include:
<UL>
<LI> FTIR and MAS-NMR spectroscopy,
<LI> IR microscopy,
<LI> trans-mission and scanning electron microscopy,
<LI> X-ray absorption spectroscopy,
<LI> calorimetry, gravimetry (in combination with sorption measurements) and 
<LI> thermal desorption. 
</UL>
Interactions between molecules and the catalysts are monitored with all the techniques in situ using special equipment. These spectroscopic measurements are complemented with a variety of kinetic measurements under steady state and transient conditions. <P> 
Molecular sieves  are the largest fractions of catalysts investigated, the other important catalyst classes investigated being zeolite, oxide and polymer supported metals and complex mixed oxides. <P>
The reactions studied can be grouped into three larger areas: 
<UL>
<LI>transformation of aliphatic hydrocarbons,
<LI>synthesis of organic intermediates (direct amination, selective hydrogen-ation, synthesis of aromatic molecules)
<LI>catalytic purification of waste gas streams.     
</UL>
The group is part of the Dutch School of Catalysis (NIOK) and  is host to the Christian Doppler Laboratory for Heterogeneous Catalysis. Close cooperations on the above-mentioned topics exist with many  industrial and  academic groups within the Netherlands and internationally.<P><HR>
<A HREF="#top"><IMG  SRC ="top.gif" ALT="TOP"></A> Top of this page<P>
