<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP CHEMICAL ANALYSIS</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.01Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H2><IMG SRC="utlogo.gif" ALT="" HEIGHT=98 WIDTH=98>FACULTY OF CHEMICAL
TECHNOLOGY</H2>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><A NAME="top"></A>CHEMICAL ANALYSIS</H3>

<PRE>Group leader: Prof.dr. W.E. van der Linden

Other staff members: 
Dr.ir. M. Bos
Dr. A.J.R.L.Hulst

E-mail addresses: 
<A HREF="mailto:w.e.vanderlinden@ct.utwente.nl">w.e.vanderlinden@ct.utwente.nl
</A><A HREF="mailto:m.bos@ct.utwente.nl">m.bos@ct.utwente.nl
</A><A HREF="mailto:a.j.r.l.hulst@ct.utwente.nl">a.j.r.l.hulst@ct.utwente.nl
</A>Phone: (+31)-53-4892983
Fax:(+31)-53-4894645
</PRE>

<P>The research activities of the Chemical Analysis group focus on three
areas: </P>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#auto">Automation in analysis </A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="#intel">Intelligent analytical instrumentation </A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="#nmr">Advanced NMR techniques</A> </LI>
</UL>

<P><A NAME="auto"></A><B>Automation in analysis<BR>
</B>The research is focused on the development of automated analytical
methods for process and quality control, and the use of on-line computers.<BR>
The techniques used comprise 'wet' analytical methods like titrimetry,
photometry and electroanalysis.<BR>
Continuous flow-through methods and the use of membranes receive special
attention.<BR>
The group participates in the Research Institute for Micro Electronics,
Materials Engineering and Sensors and Actuators (MESA) of the University
of Twente. In this cooperation studies are performed on the use of microsensors
such as Ion Selective Field Effect Transistors (ISFETS) and microscale
sensor-coulometric actuator devices as well as on the development of a
micro Total Analysis System (uTAS).<BR>
Also multiple sensor arrays consisting of micro-electrodes which are individually
and differently modified are currently studied.</P>

<P> <A NAME="intel"></A><B>Intelligent analytical instrumentation<BR>
</B>This part of the research is dealing with the development and application
of techniques from the domain of Artificial Intelligence (AI) and chemometrics.
Attention is paid to the development of knowledge-based systems for expert
advice on (electro)analytical procedures, neural networks, genetic algorithms
and the use of data processing techniques like wavelet transformation and
multivariate analysis. </P>

<P><A NAME="nmr"></A><B>Advanced NMR techniques<BR>
</B>In the framework of this project the structure and dynamics of supramolecular
compounds in solution are studied. Recently also work has been started
in the field of solid state NMR. <BR>
All NMR studies are done in close cooperation with the groups of Organic
Chemistry, Catalytic Materials and Processes, Inorganic Materials Science,
and Material Science and Technology of Polymers.
<HR><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC="top.gif" ALT="TOP" HEIGHT=40 WIDTH=40></A>
Top of this page</P>

