<html>
<head>
   <title>RESEARCH GROUP CHEMICAL ENGINEERING SCIENCE</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/3.0b3Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>

<h2><img src="utlogo.gif" alt="" border=0 height=98 width=98>FACULTY OF
CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</h2>

<p>
<hr></p>

<h3><a name="top"></a>CHEMICAL ENGINEERING SCIENCE</h3>

<pre>Project leaders:
Prof. dr. ir. W.P.M. van Swaaij
Prof. dr. ir. G.F. Versteeg

Part-time professors in the Chemical Engineering Science group:
Prof. dr. ir. H. van den Berg: Processing plant design
Prof. dr. ir. C.J. Asselbergs: Technical and economical evaluation of processes,
Prof. dr. ir. G.F. Versteeg: Application of reactor science in process design.

Scientific staff:
dr. ir. W. Prins
dr. ir. J.A.M. Kuipers
dr. ir. A.B.M. Heesink
ir. D.W.F. Brilman

Technical staff:
ing. H.A. Akse
ing. S. Kuipers
ing. R. Meijer

E-mail addresses: 
<a href="mailto:w.p.m.vanswaaij@ct.utwente.nl">W.P.M.vanSwaaij@ct.utwente.nl
</a><a href="mailto:g.f.versteeg@ct.utwente.nl">G.F.Versteeg @ct.utwente.nl

</a>Phone:      (+31)-53-4892879
Fax:        (+31)-53-4894738
</pre>

<ul>
<li><a href="#activ">Profile of the group</a> </li>

<li><a href="#efforts">Research areas</a> </li>

<li><a href="#career">Career perspectives</a> </li>

<li><a href="#second">The second phase process developer training</a> </li>
</ul>

<p>The <a name="activ"></a><b>activities of the Chemical Engineering Science
group</b> may be described as the basis of process technology. Physical
transport phenomena are of primary importance, of which fluid flow phenomena,
heat and mass transfer are the main topics. These subjects underpin: </p>

<ul>
<li>process technology, </li>

<li>equipment engineering, </li>

<li>physical separation, </li>

<li>scaling-up methods, </li>

<li>modelling, etc. </li>
</ul>

<p>Chemical reactions are added to chemical engineering science by the
discipline kinetics and catalysis of chemical reactor engineering.
<br>In this way elements of physical science, as well as chemical kinetics
and thermodynamics provide a fundamental package through which numerous
problems arising from aspects of process design, development, evaluation
and operation can be solved. Furthermore the subjects of chemical reactor
engineering and physical transport phenomena are of great importance for
material science.
<br>A passive understanding of these subjects is not enough. Students have
to be able to utilize them for solving problems independently. The development
of these skills demands intensive study and practice, which may not be
substituted by passive learning methods. This may be something of a surprise
to a number of students and may demand adjustments. For many, however,
it becomes apparent in their subsequent careers that these subjects form
an important basis with which the chemical engineer is able to find practically
useful solutions and through which increase the professional satisfaction
and efficiency.</p>

<p> The <a name="efforts"></a><b>efforts of the Chemical Engineering Science
group</b> are concentrated in the areas of: </p>

<ul>
<li>chemical reactor engineering, </li>

<li>the development and understanding of new reactors and </li>

<li>subsequent application in the process industry. </li>
</ul>

<p>There is a wide range of final year research projects arising from different
postgraduate studies.</p>

<p> Subsequent to the completion of studies in Chemical Engineering Science
<a name="career"></a><b>numerous opportunities</b> are possible for exciting
positions in industry within the areas of process design, development and
operations, and in many other functions which require process technology.</p>

<p> Where personal suitability is demonstrated, we offer opportunities
for postgraduate research, or for second phase projects to become a process
developer. This latter study fulfills the increasing need for specially
trained personnel for development functions in industry.</p>

<p> <a name="second"></a><b>The second phase process developer training
<br></b>This is a full-time course with intakes in both spring and autumn.
It is a specialist course which is intended for students who have completed
the Chemical Technology phase I courses or related courses. The course
length, dependent on phase I studies, is between 1.5 and 2 years. After
admittance to the course, participants are usually taken as AIOs (assistant
research worker, also referred to as TWAIO due to the two years period)
for the duration of the course.
<br>The course leads to being a designer in process technology and therefore
includes aspects of process research, process development, process design
and process evaluation, which also incorporates economic aspects. The course
emphasizes manufacturing processes and to a lesser extent products.
<br>A detailed brochure is available from the Faculty secretary or from
the second phase course organisation (Prof. G.F. Versteeg or Ing. H.A.
Akse).
<br><a href="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/pds/index.html">Homepage of the process
development school
<hr><a href="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/index.html"><img src="more.gif" border=2 height=40 width=40></a></a>Homepage
Chemical Engineering Science
<hr></p>

<p><a href="#top"><img src="top.gif" alt="TOP" border=2 height=40 width=40></a>Top
of this page</p>

