<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP CHEMICAL PHYSICS</TITLE></head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2><HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">CHEMICAL PHYSICS</a></H3><P>
<PRE>
Project leader: dr. W.J. Briels

Scientific staff:
prof. dr. D. Feil
dr. M. van der Hoef
dr. S. Harkema

E-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:w.j.briels@ct.utwente.nl">w.j.briels@ct.utwente.nl</A></address><P>

Phone: (+31)-53-4892947
Fax: (+31)-53-4894611
</PRE><P>
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="#general">General</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#comput">Computational Statistical Mechanics</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#xray">X-ray diffraction and quantum chemistry</A>
</UL>
<B><A NAME="general">General</a></B><BR>
Research is being done on the relationship between the molecular constitution
of matter and its macroscopic properties. Methods being used are:
<UL>
<LI> Computational Statistical Mechanics:
<UL>
<LI> Monte Carlo
<LI> Molecular Dynamics
<LI> Brownian Dynamics
</UL>
<LI> Quantum Chemistry
</UL>
<B><A NAME="comput">Computational Statistical Mechanics</a></B><BR>
Research is centred around the description of slow processes, mainly slow
diffusion and barrier crossings.<BR>
The rates of conformational transitions of large organic molecules in solution
are governed by the transition state free energy and by the solvent friction.
Up to now only very few studies have been done on the influence of solvent
friction. In our group we apply Molecular Dynamics techniques to calculate
free energies of activation, including solvation effects, and to study the
influence of solvent friction. Our specific examples are conformational
transitions in calixarenes.<P>
A second project concentrates on the diffusion of small molecules through
polymeric membranes. Diffusion takes place by jumps from one absorption
site to another. In our group we model (together with <A HREF="strat.html">the group of prof. Strathmann</A>) the absorption sites and calculate the transition rates to nearby sites. From stochastic simulations on the network of sites we then obtain diffusion coefficients.<P>
As a final example we mention the study of the morphology of growing
crystals. When crystals are grown from solution, the rate determining step is
the incorporation of a solute into what is called a kink, where it is tightly
enough bound to the crystal in order that it does not dissolve again. In order
to be incorporated into the kink the solute has to overcome a free energy
barrier. The rate of this process and the number of kinks on the surface are
the quantities that we concentrate on in our Molecular Dynamics simulations.<P>
<B><A NAME="xray">X-ray diffraction and quantum chemistry</a></B><BR>
The microscopic structure of matter is investigated using experimental as
well as theoretical methods.<BR>
The structure of crystals is determined by means of X-ray diffraction. A
beam of X-rays falling on a crystal is scattered into a few specific directions,
characteristic for the crystal being investigated. By accurately measuring the
scattered intensities, the distribution of electrons in the crystal can be
calculated. These results are compared to the electron distribution obtained
from quantum-chemical calculations.<P><HR>
<A HREF="#top"><IMG  SRC ="top.gif" ALT="TOP"></A> Top of this page<P>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC ="back.gif" ALT="GROUPS"></A> Research groups of the faculty<P><A HREF ="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/index.html"><IMG  SRC=homep.gif ALT="HOMEPAGE"></A> Homepage Faculty of Chemical Technology
</body></html>
