<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP DYNAMICS AND CONTROL OF PROCESSES</TITLE></head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2><HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">DYNAMICS AND CONTROL OF PROCESSES</a></H3>
<PRE>
Group leader:  Prof.dr.ir. B. Roffel
Scientific staff:
ir. B. Betlem

Phone: (+31)-53-4893017
Fax:   (+31)-53-4894821

E-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:b.roffel@ct.utwente.nl">B.Roffel@ct.utwente.nl</A>
</PRE>
In order to improve the operation of a process and to produce better products at reduced costs, improved process control is imperative. Techniques and methods how to achieve improved control is the central research theme of the group.<BR>
This theme can be subdivided into a number of smaller research areas, namely:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#advanced">advanced modelling and control of continuous processes</A>
<LI><A HREF="#dynamic">dynamic data reconciliation</A>
<LI><A HREF="#integration">integration of process design and process control</A>
<LI><A HREF="#batch">dynamic optimization of batch operation</A>
</UL>
<A NAME="advanced"><B>Advanced modelling and control</B></a><BR>
In order to develop better control schemes for control of processes, a good knowledge of the dynamics of the process is necessary. Some processes are relatively easy to model, starting from first principles, such as basic energy, mass and partial mass balances.<BR>
Other processes, e.g. polymerization processes are more difficult to model, since reaction kinetics are often complicated  and traces of impurities may have a large impact on the model. Consequently, a robust model can not so easily be derived. In such cases it is often easier to resort to empirical models.<BR>
Two approaches are followed in this research:
the development of fuzzy models and neuro-fuzzy models. Research focuses on the development of techniques for the derivation of these models from industrial process data and on the development of control schemes which make use of these models.
The advantage of this approach is that also non-linear phenomena can be modelled elegantly and in certain cases these models are superior to linear models.
It will be a major challenge to incorporate fuzzy constraints in the control strategy, and to extend the technology to processes which are multivariable in nature.<P>

<A NAME="dynamic"><B>Dynamic data reconciliation</B></a><BR>
Static data reconciliation is often used to account for measurement and instrument error, such that mass and energy balances become consistent.<BR>
There is a tendency, however, to operate processes in a more dynamic way, e.g. batch processes. Consequently, assuming steady state to apply static data reconciliation is not justified. New techniques have to be developed which perform data reconciliation under dynamic conditions and which are applicable to large scale systems (e.g. a chemical plant).<P>

<A NAME="integration"><B>Integration of process design and control</B></a><BR>
Processes are usually designed by using static equations. Subsequently, a plant is being built. After plant commissioning, process control problems sometimes surface. Many of these problems could have been avoided by analysing the process and the proposed control configuration during the design phase.<BR>
This research looks at ways to change this situation and to develop techniques which enable us to pinpoint control problems already at the process design phase.<P>

<A NAME="batch"><B>Dynamic optimization of batch operation</B></a><BR>
The interest of batch processing grows with the increasing importance of products with high-added value. As the operation is not stationary, automation of batch operation is more complex then that of continuous operation. It requires an other control philosophy (not optimal at every moment but over a serie of batches) and models applicable over a large operation trajectory.<BR>
Issues being studied are:
<UL>
<LI> design of a coordinator hierarchy based on the degrees of freedom at each control level,
<LI> coordinator model assignment,
<LI> object oriented implementation.
</UL>
Generally, the coordinator hierarchy consists of one or more scheduler levels, a conditioner determining the setpoints and a quality controller supporting the optimal operation.<BR>
In a batch distillation case study, different control hierarchies and strategies and different coordinator models are compared (first principle models against adaptive empirical models).<P><HR>
<A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~rooijen/dcp.html"><IMG SRC=more.gif></A> Homepage Dynamics and Control of Processes <HR>
