<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP INORGANIC MATERIALS SCIENCE
</TITLE></head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2><HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">INORGANIC MATERIALS SCIENCE
</a></H3>
<PRE>
Group leader: Prof.dr.ir. H. Verweij

Other staff members: 
Dr. B.A. Boukamp
Dr. H.J.M. Bouwmeester
Dr.ir. K.Keizer, Ing. H. Kruidhof
Dr. G.M.H. van de Velde
Dr. K.J. de Vries
Dr. A.J.A. Winnubst

Phone: (+31)-53-489 2860
Fax:    (+31)-53-489 4683

E-mail addresses:
<A HREF="mailto:h.verweij@ct.utwente.nl">H.Verweij@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:b.a.boukamp@ct.utwente.nl">B.A.Boukamp@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:h.j.m.bouwmeester@ct.utwente.nl">H.J.M.Bouwmeester@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:k.keizer@ct.utwente.nl">K.Keizer@ct.utwente.nl</A>  
<A HREF="mailto:h.kruidhof@ct.utwente.nl">H.Kruidhof@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:k.j.devries@ct.utwente.nl">K.J.DeVries@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:g.m.h.vandevelde@ct.utwente.nl">G.M.H.vandeVelde@ct.utwente.nl</A>
<A HREF="mailto:a.j.a.winnubst@ct.utwente.nl">A.J.A.Winnubst@ct.utwente.nl</A>
</PRE><P>
The research activities of the Inorganic Materials Science group focus on four areas:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="#solid">Solid state electrochemistry</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#dense">Dense membranes and defect chemistry</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#technology">Technology of porous inorganic membranes</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#bulk">Bulk ceramics and powder technology</A>
</UL><P>
<A NAME="solid"><B>Solid state electrochemistry</B></a><BR>
Several solid inorganic oxide systems show appreciable conductivity for oxygen ions (electrically charged oxygen species, O=).  An important application of this property is found in the so-called Solid Oxide Fuel Cell's (SOFC's).  These SOFC's can transform chemical energy directly into electrical energy with high efficiency and without pollution (NOx).<BR>
The basic SOFC consists of three different layers of inorganic materials: two electrodes, which may consist of composite materials, separated by the ceramic electrolyte.  At one electrode (cathode) atmospheric oxygen (O2) is transformed to oxygen ions (O=) which then move through the electrolyte to the other electrode (anode) where they react with the fuel. In the process electrons are forced through the external load, e.g. the electrical power lines.<BR>
Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) has proven to be an important research tool in these investigations, hence also special attention is paid to a further development of this technique.<BR>
The exchange between gaseous oxygen and lattice oxygen of the bulk oxides is an important step in the total transport of oxygen.  Oxygen isotope (18O) exchange is used in the study of these surface exchange processes. <P>

<A NAME="dense"><B>Dense membranes and defect chemistry</B></a><BR>
Besides oxygen ion conductivity a number of inorganic oxides also show appreciable (normal) electronic conductivity.  These materials we call mixed conducting oxides.  With these materials we can make dense membranes which are only permeable for oxygen.  These membranes have potential applications in separation of oxygen gas from gas mixtures as well as for a selectively controlled
supply of oxygen as reactant in a chemical reactor, i.e. electro-catalysis.<BR>
The research on these mixed conducting oxides is mainly focused on the preparation procedure and the (electrochemical) transport properties in which the, thermodynamically controlled, lattice defects play an important role.<P>

<A NAME="technology"><B>Technology of porous inorganic membranes</B></a><BR>
Porous inorganic membranes find widespread use in many applications, such as liquid filtration, gas separation and catalysis.  An advantage of these membranes over the polymer membranes (see <A HREF="strat.html">Membrane Technology</A>) is that they can sustain much higher temperatures.<BR>
The most important parameter to control in the preparation process of the membrane is the pore size and its distribution. The type of application largely dictates the required pore size.  For example, in gas separation is the speed and selectivity of the separation process dependent on the pore size.<BR>
A specific topic of the current research are the micro-porous silica membranes which exhibit very high selectivity for hydrogen (H2). <BR>
Application of these membranes for the separation of H2 in coal gasification systems is studied in cooperation with the Energy Research Centre Netherlands (ECN) in Petten.<BR>
A second research topic is the application of ceramic membranes in high temperature reactors. <P> 
 
<A NAME="bulk"><B>Bulk ceramics and powder technology</B></a><BR>
Dense zirconia ceramics are materials with excellent mechanical properties with respect to strength, toughness  and wear resistance.  Special applications are, for example, found as bearings, extrusion nozzles and cutting tools in mechanical constructions.  Because of this enhanced wear resistance the need for lubricants (like oil and grease) becomes obsolete when ceramic parts are used in moving and
rotating constructions.<BR>
The research relates mainly to the technology of the production of (ultra-) fine grained
(nanocrystalline) powders and ceramics of zirconia. Optimized control of the pressing and sintering procedures results in dense, fine-grained ceramic products.  The relation between the microscopic grain structure of the ceramic and its mechanical and wear resistance properties is investigated<P><P><HR>
<A HREF="#top"><IMG  SRC ="top.gif" ALT="TOP"></A> Top of this page<P>
