<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP MATERIALS SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY OF POLYMERS</TITLE></head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2><HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">MATERIALS SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY OF POLYMERS </a></H3>
<PRE>
Project leader: Prof. dr. G.J. Vancso

Scientific staff:
dr. J.W.A. van den Berg
dr. M.A. Hempenius
Prof. dr. L.C.E. Struik (part-time professor: Physical behaviour of polymers)

Phone:(+31)-53-4892967
Fax:  (+31)-53-4893823

E-mail: <A HREF="macromaterials@ct.utwente.nl">MacroMaterials@ct.utwente.nl</A>
</PRE><P>
The general focus of our research is to understand and predict how the atomic-scale structural characteristics influence the properties of polymeric materials.
Research areas:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="#morphology">Polymer morphology and nano structure</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#thermodynamics">Macromolecular thermodynamies</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#order">Polymers with molecular order</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#novel">Polymers with novel macromolecular architectures</A>
</UL><P>
<A NAME="morphology"><B>Polymer morphology and nano structure</B></a><BR>
With the advent of atomic force microscopy (AFM) a technique became available that
allows us to perform structural studies of polymers from the Angstrom to the
micrometer range.<BR>
Ongoing projects include:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> studies on the coexistence of different crystal structures (poly-morphism)
<LI> short range molecular order and disorder in oriented systems
<LI> macro-molecular conformation in the solid state
<LI> rearrangement of molecules at free surfaces of polymeric solids
<LI> structural organization and structure manipulation on the submicrometer level
</UL>
Model materials include polymers of industrial interest such as amides, rubbers,
polymer mixtures, polyolefines, high-performance fibers and polymer films, as well as biological  macro-molecules, such as special  proteins that form the structural
material in the threads of various spider webs. <BR>
Our interests in polymer surfaces also include understanding friction at a molecular level (so-called nanotribology) by lateral force microscopy, which is a close relative of AFM. <P>

<A NAME="thermodynamics"><B>Macromolecular thermodynamics</B></a><BR>
We study the spatial arrangement of macromolecules by scattering techniques and by a unique method, called inverse phase chromatography (IGC). This technique allows us to determine the spatial distribution of the segments of macromolecules, as well as segment-segment interactions and interactions with other molecules introduced into the polymer matrix (e.g. solvents or ions). <BR>
Ongoing work also includes studies of the spatial partition of solvent-guest molecules in polymer matrices. An interesting application of this research is related to structural and thermodynamic studies of polar polymers modified by metal ions.
<P>

<A NAME="order"><B>Polymers with molecular order</B></a><BR>
Orientation studies are not only important from a scientific point of view, but also play a central role in technological applications, including melt processing. In our research special attention is given to studies of oriented polymers. <BR>
These include:
<UL>
<LI>synthesis and structure-property studies of novel liquid-crystalline polymers which can possess a high degree of orientation
<LI>exploring new ways of forming oriented structures by new spinning techniques (electrospinning)
<LI>characterization of molecular anisotropic polymers
<LI>direction-dependence of properties of a polymer (optical and mechanical performance)
<LI>studies of crystallization under mechanical stress
</UL><P>

<A NAME="novel"><B>Polymers with novel macromolecular architectures</B></a><BR>
This is a long-standing area of research of the group and is an area in which we greatly benefit from collaborations with synthetic chemists.<BR>
Ongoing work includes:
<UL>
<LI>synthesis, characterization and structure-property studies of polyolefines with well-defined molecular architecture obtained by new-generation stereospecific catalysts
<LI>studies of the mechanism and kinetics of various functional initiators for the anionic polymerization of dienes in order to obtain end-reactive polymers with well-defined molecular architecture
<LI>research on novel polymers containing inorganic elements in the main chain (polysilanes, polysiloxanes, polythionylphosphazenes, and polyferrocenylsilanes).
</UL><P><P><HR>
<A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~schuuren"><IMG SRC=more.gif></A> Homepage Natural & Synthetic Polymers <HR>
