<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP POLYMER  CHEMISTRY  AND BIOMATERIALS</TITLE></head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2><HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">POLYMER  CHEMISTRY  AND BIOMATERIALS</a></H3>
<PRE><P>
Projectleader: Prof. dr. J. Feijen

Scientific Staff: 
dr. T. Beugeling
dr. P.J. Dijkstra
dr. L. van der Does
dr. ir. G.H.M. Engbers
dr. ir. F.J. van der Gaag
dr. A.A. Poot
dr. ir. J.G.A. Terlingen
Prof. dr. ir. J.W.M. Noordermeer (part-time professor: Rubber technology).

Phone:(+31)-53 4892968
Fax:  (+31)-53 4893823

E-mail address:  <A HREF="mailto:macrochem@ct.utwente.nl">MacroChem@ct.utwente.nl</A>
</PRE><P>
The research activities of the group focus on five areas:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="#medical">Polymers for medical applications</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#pharm">Polymers for pharmaceutical applications</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#function">Functionalized polymer surfaces</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#networks">Polymer networks</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#rubber">Chemistry and technology of rubbers</A>
</UL><P>
<A NAME="medical"><B>Polymers for medical applications</B></a><BR>
Materials to be used for biomedical applications have to meet several demands.<BR>
<UL>
<LI>With respect to the bulk properties, important parameters are strength, stiffness, creep, flex resistance, stability and permeability. 
<LI>Specific demands related to the medical application are a good blood compatibility, the absence of toxic and immunological reactions, the absence of a strong tissue reaction, avoiding infections, sterilizability and in specific cases a degradation which is well defined in time.
<LI>Furthermore specific demands for the processability may be formulated.
</UL>
In the investigations in the biomaterials field it is necessary to gain insight in the interaction between materials (material surfaces) and the biological system (in vivo) or parts of the system (in vitro). The acquired knowledge and expertise in polymer chemistry may be used to tailor polymers or polymer surfaces for specific applications. <BR>
In the projects the research is either focused on the fundamental aspects of the interaction between well characterized polymers and polymer surfaces and biological components, such as proteins, blood cells and bacteria, or on the synthesis, characterization and evaluation of new biofunctional polymers. <P>

<A NAME="pharm"><B>Polymers for pharmaceutical applications</B></a><BR>
The research is directed towards the controlled delivery of drugs using polymeric systems. The following systems can be distinguished:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>polymer matrices in which the farmacon is not covalently bound. The research is focused on biodegradable systems, where formation of porous membranes is a key item.<P>
<LI>polymers to which the farmacon is covalently bound, where the drug is released through enzymatic and solvolytic erosion of the polymer<P>
<LI>high molecular weight prodrugs, where conjugates of the polymeric carrier and the drug are water-soluble. The conjugates also serve to transport the drug to the target cell. After uptake by the cell intracellular degradation takes place and the drug is released into the target cells. This allows to reduce the toxic side effects of the  drug.<P>
</OL><P>

<A NAME="function"><B>Functionalized polymer surfaces</B></a><BR>
The research is directed towards the preparation of functionalized polymer surfaces. An important step is the gas plasma treatment during which functional groups are introduced on a chemically inert surface. On one hand these groups can be active in deminishing or avoiding the occurrence of adverse tissue reactions, and on the other hand these groups can be used to couple biologically active systems, such as enzymes or anticoagulant moieties onto the surface.<P>

<A NAME="networks"><B>Polymer networks</B></a><BR>
The aim of the research is to gain insight in the relation between structure and physical properties of polymer networks. Especially networks with special properties are under study, such as networks in which the swelling can be influenced by external stimuli (pH, temperature), and highly crosslinked polymer networks for  coating applications.<P>

<A NAME="rubber"><B>Chemistry and technology of rubbers</B></a><BR>
Vulcanization of elastomers is being studied to elucidate the rubber networks. By using sulfur, standard accelerators such as TMTD, but also new types of accelerators, attempts are made to correlate the network structure with the mechanical properties of the rubbers.  ,br.
Bonding of rubbers to metals is another research project and in order to improve the adhesion of rubbers to metals, several metal ion complexing adhesives are studied. After application to the metal, the adhesive can be covulcanized with the rubber, which will probably result in improved bonding strength.<P><P><HR>
<A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~schuuren"><IMG SRC=more.gif></A> Homepage Natural & Synthetic Polymers <HR>
<A HREF="#top"><IMG  SRC ="top.gif" ALT="TOP"></A> Top of this page<P>
