<html><head><TITLE>SUPRA MOLOCULAR CHEMISTRY AND TECHNOLOGY</TITLE></head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2><HR>
<H3><A NAME="top"></a>SUPRA MOLECULAR CHEMISTRY AND TECHNOLOGY</H3>
<PRE><P>
Group leader: Prof.dr.ir. D.N. Reinhoudt

Other staff members:
Dr. J.F.J. Engbersen
Dr. P. Timmerman
Dr.ir. F.C.J.M. van Veggel
Dr. W. Verboom
Prof. dr. F. de Jong (part-time professor: Molecular Technology)

Phone: (+31)-53-4892980
Fax:  (+31)-53-4894645

E-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:smct@ct.utwente.nl"> smct@ct.utwente.nl</A>
</pre><P>
The research of the Organic Chemistry group is centered around the theme of Supramolecular Chemistry and Technology.<BR>
The aim is to transduce molecular (recognition) properties into macroscopic (material) properties.<BR>
The basis is the design and synthesis of molecules that are able to selectively recognize other (guest) species or organize themselves into larger assemblies.<P>
Computational methods are the basis for understanding the recognition properties and the shapes of the molecules.<BR>
A number of selected fields of application are:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Chemical sensors based on chemically modified field effect transistors (CHEMFETs) that can transduce a molecular recognition process in solution directly into an electronic signal. The molecules that recognize ionic species (Na+, K+, Cs+, NO3- etc.) are incorporated in thin polymeric membranes and these layers are attached to the active part of a field effect transistor.<P>
<LI>Membranes that are composed of thin porous polymer films in which carrier molecules are adsorbed can be used for the selective separation of salts. Applications can be found in the purification of nuclear waste streams.<P>
<LI>Diagnostic and therapeutic technologies can be based on the immobilization of radioactive or luminescent ions in the cavities of organic molecules require the design and synthesis of receptor molecules that form kinetically stable complexes. These are linked to biologically active substances for specific targeting and monitoring.<P>
<LI>Chemistry at the atomic level requires the selforganisation of molecules. We are able to  assemble receptor molecules in monolayers on gold and to use this technology for gas sensing.<P>
<LI>Materials with specific optical properties e.g. doubling of the frequency of light or optical amplification, require ordened materials. Supramolecular interactions can achieve these.<P>
</OL><P><P><HR>
<A HREF="#top"><IMG  SRC ="top.gif" ALT="TOP"></A> Top of this page<P>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC ="back.gif" ALT="GROUPS"></A> Research groups of the faculty<P>
<A HREF ="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/index.html"><IMG  SRC=homep.gif ALT="HOMEPAGE"></A> Homepage Faculty of Chemical Technology
</body></html>
