<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP SEPARATION TECHNOLOGY</TITLE> </head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2> <HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">SEPARATION TECHNOLOGY</a></H3>
<PRE>
Group leader:  Prof.dr.ir. T.Reith

Scientific staff:
Dr.ir I.G. Racz
Dr.ir. H.Bosch

Phone:  (+31)-53-4893017
Fax:  (+31)-53-4894821

E-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:t.reith@ct.utwente.nl">T.Reith@ct.utwente.nl</A>
</PRE><P>

The objective of the research is to develop new separation processes and equipment particularly in three areas:
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="#membrane">Membrane technology</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#psa">Gas separation by pressure swing adsorption (PSA)</A>  
<LI> <A HREF="#cleaning">Cleaning of hard surfaces</A>
</UL>
<A NAME="membrane"><B>Membrane technology</B><BR>
Concentration polarisation and fouling reduce driving forces in membrane separations. The research aims at developing membrane modules in which these phenomena are effectively suppressed. <BR>
The basic idea is that creating turbulence by the membrane itself is a more energy effective means for reducing concentration polarisation and fouling than other methods. For this purpose membranes with corrugations and later hollow fiber modules with feed flow perpendicular to the the fiber axis were developed. <BR>
Presently the enhancement of mass transfer by secondary flow in channels of spiral wound membrane modules, resulting from a special geometry of the channels themselves, is investigated. <BR>
Finally industrial application of membrane separations is promoted by projects executed jointly with industry.<BR>
Current PhD research projects include:
<DL>
<DT><I>Transport phenomena in spiral wound membrane modules</I>
<DD>Development of predictive models for pressure drop and mass transfer under secondary flow conditions and experimental validation of the models.
<DT><I>Recycling of process streams in the textile industry</I>
<DD>Aim of the research project is to reduce water consumption and pollution of textile industries. For this purpose an improved washing process is developed featuring membrane separation of water from process streams for reuse within the process. 
<DT><I>Membrane separation in washing processes</I>
<DD>The aim of  the project is to reduce consumption of water, energy and cleaning agents in washing machines and dish washers. Membrane separation of detergents and microsoils  from machine effluents is being studied.
</DL>
<A NAME="psa"><B>Gas separation by PSA</B></a><BR>
PSA is increasingly favoured for gas separation for reasons of its economy. These adsorption processes are dynamic and cyclic and therefore difficult to describe in mathematical models. Design is still an art. <BR>
The research aims at understanding diffusion and adsorption processes in porous materials, developing mathematical process models and finally creating more selective adsorbents. <BR>
Current PhD research projects include:
<DL>
<DT><I>Multicomponent adsorption</I>
<DD>The aim of the project is to  develop methods for measuring equilibrium and diffusion data and to validate models for prediction thereof.
<DT><I>Modeling of PSA processes</I>
<DD>Presently models for prediction of process performance can only be solved numerically, if physically unsound simplifications are introduced. The aim of the research is to develop solution methods which do not need those simplifications and  to validate the models experimentally.
<DT><I>Coated adsorbents</I>
<DD>In a coated adsorbent the features of adsorbents and membranes are combined. It is the aim of the project to develop and test new materials.
</DL>

<A NAME="cleaning"><B>Cleaning of hard surfaces</B></a>
Cleaning of hard surfaces is an important operation in the process industry (removal of fouling in process equipment e.g. heat exchangers) as well as in private homes. The aim of the research is to understand and describe the hydrodynamical and physico-chemical removal mechanisms which both play an important role.<BR>
Currently a PhD research project Removal of fouling from hard surfaces is executed. This project is sponsored by a major process industry.<P><P><HR>
<A HREF="#top"><IMG  SRC ="top.gif" ALT="TOP"></A> Top of this page<P>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC ="back.gif" ALT="GROUPS"></A> Research groups of the faculty<P>
<A HREF ="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/index.html"><IMG  SRC=homep.gif ALT="HOMEPAGE"></A> Homepage Faculty of Chemical Technology
</body></html>

   
