<html><head><TITLE>RESEARCH GROUP POLYMER  TECHNOLOGY</TITLE> </head>
<body><H2><IMG  SRC=utlogo.gif ALT="">FACULTY OF CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGY</H2> <HR>
<H3><A NAME="top">POLYMER  TECHNOLOGY</a></H3>
<PRE>
Group leader: Dr. R.J. Gaymans

Phone:  (+31) - 53 4892970
Fax:   (+31) - 53 4892479

E-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:r.j.gaymans@ct.utwente.nl">r.j.gaymans@ct.utwente.nl</A>
</PRE><P>
Polymers (plastics) are being used at a very large scale. The reason for this is the combination of ease of production with their good properties. Our aim is to improve the performance of these materials by studying the structure-properties relationship. In the research group polymer technology two themes are being studied.<BR>
<OL>
<LI> Engineering polymers with a high degree of order:
<UL>
<LI>polyamides (e.g. nylon 6 and nylon 4,6)
<LI>polyesters (e.g. modified PET and PBT)
<LI>segmented copolymers (thermoplastic elastomers)
</UL>         
<LI> Toughening of polymers:
<UL>
<LI>polyamide- (or polypropylene-) rubber blends
<LI>ABS
<LI>polycarbonate blends
<LI>polymers with long glass fibres
</UL>
</OL>        
Most of the projects in the polymer technology group are studied in co-operation with other university groups and with the polymer industry.<BR>
In engineering polymers the dimensional stability and mechanical properties can be improved by forming network structures. Physical networks can be obtained with a crystalline phase. Polymers with amide groups for a strong inter chain interaction and a high order are investigated. <BR>
Crystallisable units of a uniform length built into the polymer chain are particularly interesting and new.<BR>
Polymer products with a scratch nearly always fracture brittle. The materials can be toughened with a small amount of rubber particles. The function of the rubber is to prevent a sharp crack to grow. Research is focused onto the influence of structural (like rubber concentration and particle size) and test parameters (like temperature and test speed).<BR>
High toughness can also be obtained with long glass fibres. <P><HR>
<A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~schuuren"><IMG SRC=more.gif></A> Homepage Natural & Synthetic Polymers <HR>
<A HREF="#top"><IMG  SRC ="top.gif" ALT="TOP"></A> Top of this page<P>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC ="back.gif" ALT="GROUPS"></A> Research groups of the faculty<P>
<A HREF ="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/index.html"><IMG  SRC=homep.gif ALT="HOMEPAGE"></A> Homepage Faculty of Chemical Technology
</body></html> 
