<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>MULTICOMPONENT, MULTIPHASE REACTION ENGINEERING
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1><CENTER><B>MULTICOMPONENT, MULTIPHASE REACTION ENGINEERING
</B></CENTER></H1>
<P>
<CENTER>R KRISHNA,  J ELLENBERGER, L M C SAGIS,</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>H M LETZEL, B G M van WACHEM, I URSEANU, R BAUR and A
HIGLER<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><I>Collaborators</I>: C M van den Bleek (Delft), R Taylor
(Clarkson) and </CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>J A Wesselingh (Groningen)<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B>Abstract</B> - Our research efforts have the general aim of
developing unifying concepts in chemical engineering.  We are
pursuing three different areas of research.  
<UL>
<LI>We aim to develop a unified theory of mass transfer processes
using the Maxwell-Stefan formulation.  Diffusion in (macro-, meso-
and micro- ) porous media is the current focus of our atttention.
<LI>We are attempting to develop a unified approach to the scale
up of &quot;fluidized&quot; multiphase reactors, e.g. gas-liquid
bubble columns, gas-solid fluidized beds, gas-liquid-solid slurry
reactors.  The unified approach has its basis in hydrodynamic
analogies, which are being investigated in a comprehensive program
of experimentation.  Our unified approach is being put on a firm
fundamental footing by use of CFD models.
<LI>We are developing generic design and scale up procedures for
reactive separation processes, e.g. reactive distillation.  
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<B>PREAMBLE</B>
<P>
 Our research efforts are concentrated in three areas.  In each
area we are seeking unification of ideas and concepts.  We look
to unifying the theories of mass transfer.  We are attempting
to develop a unified approach to the scale up of multiphase reactors.
 We are conceptualising the problem of reactor and separation
synthesis and developing generic design procedures for reactive
separation processes.  Since we work thematically, we prefer to
present our research too in a unified manner.<BR>
<P>
<B>(A) UNIFIED APPROACH TO MASS TRANSFER </B>
<P>
<B>(with Prof J A Wesselingh)</B>
<P>
 Since 1980, Prof Wesselingh and myself have taken up the task
of developing a unified theory of mass transfer processes.
One of the many issues Wesselingh and I are looking at involves
the proper description of diffusion inside porous structures,
especially as concerns the influence of viscous flow. We
firmly believe that chemical engineers should adopt the Maxwell-Stefan
approach to mass transfer in both education and in practice. It
is the only candidate theory, we believe, with the capability
of handling the diverse applications encountered in chemical engineering
practice. A substantial 180-page review entitled <I>The Maxwell-Stefan
Approach to Mass Transfer</I> is shortly to be published in <I>Chemical
Engineering Science</I>. 
<P>
Prof Wesselingh and myself are now
currently working on the second edition of our book <I>Mass Transfer.</I>
My collaboration with Prof R Taylor (Clarkson University) has
resulted in a major treatise <I>Multicomponent Mass Transfer.
 </I>This collaboration is continuing in the area of development
of rigorous design procedures for reactive distillation columns;
see below.
<P>
<B> (B) SCALE UP OF FLUIDIZED MULTIPHASE REACTORS </B>
<P>
(J. Ellenberger, L.M.C. Sagis, H.M. Letzel, B.G.M. van Wachem,
I. Urseanu)
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna1.gif">
<P>
 Fluidized bed and bubble column reactors are finding increasing
use in industrial practice; these two reactor technologies figure
prominently in processes for converting natural gas to liquid
fuels and light olefins. There are considerable reactor design
and scale-up problems associated with these natural gas conversion
technologies; these problems arise because of several special
features of these processes:   (i) large gas throughputs, necessitating
the use of large diameter reactors, typically 5-8 m, often in
parallel, (ii) high pressure conditions, typically 10-80 bar,
(iii) large reactor heights, typically 20-30 m tall, and (iv)
high reaction exothermicity requiring heat removal by means of
cooling tubes inserted in the reactor.  Successful commercialisation
of natural gas conversion technologies is crucially dependent
on the proper understanding of the scaling up principles of fluid
beds and bubble columns for these conditions that fall outside
the purview of most published theory and correlations.   Our research
efforts are directed towards developing a unified scale up strategy
for fludized multiphase reactors relying on hydrodynamic analogies
between these reactor types; see Figure 1. 
<P>
 Research in developing a unified theory of multiphase reactors
is conducted by the following group of people:
<P>
 J&uuml;rg Ellenberger, who successfully defended his PhD dissertation<I>
Analogies in Multiphase Reactor Hydrodynamics</I> in November
1995 and is continuing work in the same area within my group.
<P>
 Jeroen de Swart, a UvA sponsored AIO, who successfully defended
his PhD dissertation<I> Scale Up of a Fischer Tropsch slurry Reactor</I>
in April 1996.  
<P>
 Martijn Letzel, jointly supervised by Prof C M van den Bleek,
who started research in August 1994.  He is involved in applying
Chaos theory to characterise the flow regimes and regime transitions
in G-L bubble columns.  An important component of his work involves
the study of the influence of high pressure on bubble column hydrodynamics.
 The experimental work is carried out in Delft, Amsterdam and
within DSM Research in Geleen. 
<P>
 Berend van Wachem, jointly supervised by Prof C M van den Bleek,
who started research in November 1995.  He is involved in CFD
modelling of G-S fluid beds and is planning to focus attention
on influencing the bubbling characteristics by small perturbations.
<P>
 Leonard Sagis, a PostDoc, sponsored by UvA, who started research
in March 1996.  He has initiated work on CFD modelling of fluidized
multiphase reactors with the ambitious objective of developing
a unified approach.  Initially, scale effects of &quot;large&quot;
bubble rise velocities are being studied along with interactions
between these &quot;large&quot; bubbles.  
<P>
 Miss Ioana Urseanu, from the Polytechnic University of Bucharest,
who will start her PhD studies here as soon as bureacratic hurdles
concerning her AIO appointment are sorted out.  She will be involved
in CFD modelling of bubble column reactors operating in the churn-turbulent
regime.  Ioana will work closely with Leonard, J&uuml;rg and myself.
<BR>
<P>
Some interesting research results of my group are discussed below.<BR>
<P>
<B>Flow regimes and flow regime transitions.</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna2.gif">
<P>
 If one sparges gas into a column filled with a liquid (see Figure
2 (a)), the bed of liquid begins to expand  &quot;homogeneously&quot;
and the bed height increases almost linearly with the superficial
gas velocity <I>U</I>.  This regime of operation of a bubble column
is called the <I>homogeneous bubbly flow regime</I>. The bubble
size distribution is narrow and a roughly uniform bubble size,
in the range 2 - 7 mm, is found.  As the gas velocity is increased
the gas holdup, <I><FONT FACE="MT Symbol">e</FONT></I>,  increases
and at a certain gas velocity <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>trans</FONT>
coalescence of the bubbles takes place to produce the first fast-rising
&quot;large&quot; bubble.  The appearance of the first large bubble
changes the hydrodynamic picture dramatically.  The regime of
operation for superficial gas velocities exceeding <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>trans</FONT>
is commonly referred to as <I>heterogeneous </I>or <I>churn-turbulent
regime</I>; this regime is of importance in industrial reactor
operation. An analogous picture exists for a gas-solid fluid bed.
 When a gaseous phase is introduced uniformly through the bottom
of a packed bed of particles (see Figure 2 (b)) the bed begins
to expand for gas velocities exceeding the minimum fluidization
velocity <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>mf</FONT>.  For fine particles,
say smaller than 200 <FONT FACE="MT Symbol">m</FONT>m, the bed
expands uniformly; this is the regime of <I>homogeneous fluidization.
 </I>This regime of homogeneous fluidization prevails till a certain
velocity  is reached at which bubbles are first observed; the
velocity at this point, <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>mb</FONT>, is usually
called the <I>minimum bubbling velocity</I>.  For the purposes
of drawing analogies with gas liquid systems, we shall denote
this velocity as the transition velocity, <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>trans</FONT>.
The operating gas velocity window between <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>mf
<I> </I></FONT>and <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>trans</FONT> is usually
very narrow and it is usually not possible to operate commercial
reactors in a stable manner in this regime.   On the other hand
in gas-solid beds of large particles, say larger than 1 mm, bubbles
appear as soon as the gas velocity exceeds <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>mf</FONT>
and hence <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>trans</FONT> <FONT FACE="MT Symbol">&#187;</FONT>
 <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>mf</FONT>.  Beyond  the gas velocity corresponding
to <I>U</I><FONT SIZE=1>trans</FONT>,<I><FONT SIZE=1>  </FONT></I>we
have the regime of <I>heterogeneous fluidization</I>.   In the
heterogeneous fluidization regime, a small portion of the entering
gas is used to keep the solids in suspension, while the major
portion of the gas flows through the reactor in the form of bubbles.
 <I><FONT SIZE=1> </FONT></I>Commercial reactors usually operate
in the heterogeneous or bubbling fluidization regime at gas velocities
<I>U </I>exceeding 0.1 m/s, a few orders of magnitude higher than<I>
U</I><FONT SIZE=1>trans</FONT>. Analogous parameters affect the
transition point in gas-solid fluid beds and gas-liquid bubble
columns. 
<P>
 A novel method has been developed to accurately determine the
flow regime transition point using modern chaos analysis. This
was done by analysing the chaotic characteristics of fluctuating
pressure signals. Plotting the Kolmogorov entropy vs. the superficial
gas velocity, a sharp valley can be observed at the regime transition
point. Figure 3 shows a plot of Kolmogorov entropy and holdup
at different gas velocities.  The chaos analysis is superior to
the alternative procedure of using the standard deviations of
the fluctuating pressure signals; this superiority is demonstrated
by comparing the two methods in Figure 4.
<P>
 To study the influence of pressure experimentally, a high pressure
0.15 m ID bubble column has been built in DSM Research, which
can be operated up to pressures of 1.5 MPa. A start has been made
to measure gas fractions in an nitrogen-water system at different
operating pressures and gas velocities. Figure 5 shows gas holdup
data for system pressures of 0.1, 0.5 and 1.0 MPa. The significant
influence of the system pressure is evident.
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna3.gif">
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna4.gif">
<P>
<B>Generalized two-phase model for multiphase reactors</B>
<P>
 Beyond the regime transition point we have the heterogeneous,
or churn-turbulent, flow regime which is the regime of importance
in industrial practice. Our analogous scale up strategy for fluidized
multiphase reactors relies on the generalization of the two phase
model by proper definition of the &quot;dilute&quot; and &quot;dense&quot;
phases; see Figure 6.  On the basis of an extensive program of
investigation carried out in several gas-solid, gas-liquid and
gas-liquid-solid systems in columns of diameters 0.05, 0.1, 0.174,
0.19, 0.38 and 0.63 m, Ellenberger and De Swart, in their respective
PhD dissertations have verified this unified scale up procedure
for &quot;fluidized&quot; multiphase reactors.  
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna5.gif">
<P>
 By performing dynamic gas disengagement experiments with the
system air, He, Ar - fluidized cracking catalyst (FCC) the rise
velocity of the dilute phase was determined in columns of diameters
0.1, 0.19 and 0.38 m.  The rise velocity could be correlated with
the Froude number defined in terms of the superficial gas velocity
through the dilute phase; see Figure 7. The column diameter dependence
can be expected to persist up to 1 m as recommended by Werther
(1992) and, therefore, for columns greater than 1 m in diameter
the correlation is to be used by taking <I>D</I><SUB>T</SUB> =
1 m in the calculation of the Froude number.  Our major contribution
has been to demonstrate that an analogous scale effect is valid
for gas-liquid bubble columns and gas-liquid-solid bubble column
slurry reactors. For gas-liquid bubble columns operating in the
churn-turbulent regime, the &quot;dilute&quot; phase is to be
identified with the fast-rising &quot;large&quot; bubbles.  The
&quot;dense&quot; phase in this case consists of &quot;small&quot;
bubbles entrained in the liquid phase; see Figure 6.  By performing
dynamic gas disengagement experiments the rise velocities of the
&quot;large&quot; bubbles were determined in several columns operated
with several liquids: water, tetradecane and paraffin oil and
paraffin oil slurries. Comparison of the dilute phase rise velocity
in air-FCC and air-paraffin oil systems and paraffin-oil slurries
shows that <I>V</I><SUB>b</SUB> is not only the same for these
different systems but they show the same scale dependence; see
Fig. 8. This conclusion is of great significance in commercial
reactor scale up.  
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna6.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B>Mass transfer from the dilute phase</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna7.gif">
<P>
 It is well known that in a G-S fluid bed operating in the bubbling
regime, there is frequent interaction between the bubbles leading
to a significant enhancement in the mass transfer from the dilute
phase.  We investigated a similar effect for the G-L and G-L-S
systems.  Literature data show that the <I>k</I><FONT SIZE=1>L</FONT><I>a</I>
values for transfer from &quot;large&quot; bubbles is much larger
than what one might expect from bubbles with sizes of about 0.05
to 0.08 m.  Video imaging techniques were used to analyse the
behaviour of the &quot;large&quot; bubbles.  Eight grabbed frames,
at 40 ms intervals, are shown in Figure 9.  What is clear is that
the large bubbles do not have a permanent existence but are constantly
coalescing and splitting.  This leads to an order-of-magnitude
increase in mass transfer enhancement.  These results have just
appeared in <I>Chemical Engineering Science</I> and we believe
that our concepts of mass transfer in G-L dispersions in the turbulent
regime have wider applications.  For example, this could provide
a means for predicting the tray efficiency in a distillation column
operating in the froth regime.
<P>
 The information generated by De Swart has been used in developing
a complete (dynamic) reactor model for a commercial unit.  This
unit has been used to indicate the optimum process conditions.
 Further, the start-up aspects of the Fischer Tropsch reactor
have also been studied.  <BR>
<P>
<B>CFD simulations of fluidized multiphase reactors</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna8.gif">
<P>
 Our unified scale up procedure for multiphase reactors has so
far been largely empirical in character.  We have also started
research in order to put this scale up procedure on a firm fundamental
footing using CFD techniques. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna9.gif">
<P>
 Firstly, Leonard Sagis has focussed on CFD simulations of single
&quot;large&quot; bubbles (larger than 0.02 m in diameter) in
liquid columns.  Figure 10 shows some typical simulations in a
0.1 m diameter column into which a 0.05 m diameter gas bubble
is injected.  These simulations were carried out using the Volume-of-Fluid
technique.   Comparison of the CFD simulations obtained with two
columns of 0.1 and 0.4 m diameter demonstrate the dramatic influence
of scale; see Figure 11.  Bubbles tend to rise faster in a column
of larger diameter.  Furthermore the bubbles appear to be flatter.
 Detailed examination of the velocity profiles reveal that the
differences in the rise velocities are inter alia to be attributed
to significant wall effects. We also performed experiments with
single gas bubbles in columns of 0.1 m and 0.174 m in order to
validate the conclusions of the CFD simulations.  The diameter
influence is evident from the experimental data presented in Figure
12. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna10.gif">
<P>
 Berend van Wachem has undertaken CFD simulation work for a freely
bubbling G-S fluid bed containing Geldart B particles using the
Eulerian-Eulerian approach together with the granular theory.
 Typical simulations of the bed voidage profiles and gas phase
velocity profiles are shown in Figure 13. Interestingly the simulation
of a G-L bubble column operating in the churn-turbulent regime
is a much more difficult exercise than for a G-S fluid bed. 
<P>
<B>(C) MODELLING REACTIVE SEPARATION PROCESSES</B>
<P>
(R. Baur and A. Higler)
<P>
In collaboration with Prof R Taylor
of Clarkson University I have initiated a collaborative research
project on reactive distillation. Arnoud Higler has already begun
his research work at Clarkson University and will be shortly joined
there by Richard Baur.  These two will spend also part of their
time at the University of Amsterdam conducting research.
<P>
At Amsterdam we already have some
experience with reactive distillation.  Some intriguing results
have already been obtained for MTBE synthesis, for which we we
have discovered the phenomenon of multiple steady states; see
Figure 14.  Using the Maxwell-Stefan model to describe the interphase
mass transfer during catalytic distillation for MTBE synthesis
we have observed the increasing the mass transfer coefficient
can, in some situations, decrease the conversion !.  This is counter-intuitive.
<P>
Furthermore, Richard Baur, under
the supervision of Dr Stany Schrans (Shell) has demonstrated that
MTBE synthesis can show oscillatory behaviour, as depicted in
Figure 15.  This work has been presented at ESCAPE6, Rhodos.
<P>
We intend to develop generic design
procedures for reactive distillation columns.  The major focus
of the work at Amsterdam will be: (1) study of counter-current
vapour-liquid hydrodynamics in structured catalytically packed
distillation columns.  Here both experimental and CFD simulation
studies will be undertaken.  (2) determination of capacity limitations
of structured packed columns as a function of the liquid and vapour
properties.  (3) fundmental procedures for estimation of heat
and mass transfer coefficients.
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna11.gif"><BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="krishna12.gif">
<P>
Another associated research area
which will receive our attention concerns counter-current gas
(vapour) - liquid catalytic reactions such as hydrotreating, hydrogenations
and hydrations.  In such examples counter-current contacting is
to be preferred to co-current contacting.  The advantages are
illustrated in Figure 16 for hydration of isobutene to produce
tert butyl alcohol. The development of proper catalyst
configurations in order to be able to handle counter-current contacting
is the issue here.

