<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selectivity enhancement by using Pressure Swing Reactors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=331><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Selectivity enhancement by using Pressure Swing Reactors</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=151>
<P>
<IMG SRC="akodde.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Adriaan Kodde</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Alfred Bliek</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1996 - 2000</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
 The preferential adsorption of one component from a mixture can
be used to remove this component from the gas phase and thus achieve
separation. If a catalyst and adsorbent are combined in a reactor,
reaction and separation will take place simultaneously. In practice
this can be achieved by using a mixture of sorbent and catalyst
in the reactor, or by combining both aspects in one material.
Microporous materials show great potential for this application.
In this communication potential reaction and operation schemes
are discussed and illustrated
<P>
<B>Promising reaction scheme's</B>
<P>
 Selectivity improvement by selective adsorption can be based
on one of the following reaction principles:
<OL>
<LI>Temporal removal of wanted intermediates in consecutive reactions
<P>
<IMG SRC="akodde1.gif">
<P>
<LI>Temporal removal of end products in equilibrium limited reactions
<P>
<IMG SRC="akodde2.gif">
<P>
<LI>Parallel reactions: reactant selectivity by exclusion
<P>
<IMG SRC="akodde3.gif">
</OL>
<P>
<B>Simulation Study</B>
<P>
 The starting point in the search for the optimal pressure swing
operating cycle will be the classic four-step Skarstrom cycle.
Possible alterations on the cycle include: 1) no purge, 2)co-current
depressurization and/or 3) co-current purge. Other key parameters
are the pressure-range, the catalyst/adsorbent ratio and packing,
purge ratio and purge velocity. The simulations are carried out
in <I>gPROMS</I>. 
<P>
In the example shown below selectivity in a consecutive reaction
scheme is shown. It clearly shows that superior performance compared
to steady state operation is possible.
<TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=312>
<P>
<IMG SRC="akodde4.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=312><I><B>Figure 1</B>: PSR performance versus steady state PFR. The PSR unit is operated under four step PSA cycle with pressurization/adsorption/co-current depressu-rization and co-current purge steps. The symbols represent cases with different cycle times, flow rates and pressure ranges</I>.
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-122</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000114-B047-36</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/uva/andreine.html 130.89.50.60 19970216174105 text/html 3486
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:34:28 GMT
