</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Temperature Programmed Reduction of Supported and Unsupported Metal Oxides
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B><FONT SIZE=5>Temperature Programmed Reduction of Supported and Unsupported Metal Oxides</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Researcher:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>A. Andreini</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
 <B>Introduction</B>
<P>
Temperature Programmed Reduction (TPR) is now a routinely applied
technique for the fingerprinting of catalysts. It yields information
over the temperature range where the reduction takes place, the
amount of reducible oxygen, the oxidation state of the metal,
the presence of various surface phases, possible interactions
between the species, interaction with the support, and the factors
that affect dispersion. Criteria for defining ideal conditions
for the application of the technique have been specified lately.
However, the presence of artefacts of various nature has been
demonstrated in some cases, under certain conditions.<BR>
<P>
<B>Objectives</B>
<P>
* The improvement of the experimental and calculation procedures
for minimizing the impact of possible artefacts
<P>
* The evaluation of the Friedman method for the determination
of the activation energy as a function of the conversion, in the
case of unsupported Copper oxide.<BR>
<P>
<B>Background</B>
<P>
Much attention in the literature is still being devoted to Copper.
Copper is a component of catalysts applied in methanol synthesis,
hydrogenolysis of esters, deNO<SUB>x</SUB> ...Copper Oxide samples
from different sources show a great variety of behaviour in TPR.
Some of the observed effects are clearly due to artefacts. This
offers the possibility for gaining insight into their nature and
for studying their impact on the TPR pattern. Improved procedures
are required for eliminating these artefacts or for minimizing
their impact.<BR>
<P>
<B>Experimental</B>
<P>
The catalysts, consisting of various combinations of materials,
are prepared according to a variety of methods and characterized
by various techniques (BET; XRD; COULTER multisizer...). Subsequently
the catalysts are studied under standard TPR conditions in a conventional
TPR set-up. Standard conditions for testing are: atmosferic conditions;
H<SUB>2</SUB>/Ar = 2:1; Flow = 0.307 std cc s<SUP>-1</SUP>. The
set-up is computer operated. <BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
&quot;A priori&quot; assumptions concerning the kinetic model
used in the analysis of the data can lead to the inaccurate determination
of the kinetic parameters or to the wrong selection of the reduction
model. The activation energy as a function of the conversion was
not constant. The Friedman method of analysis also revealed the
presence of an compensation effect. Accordingly, a modification
of the kinetic model was required, leading to the selection of
a reduction model that otherwise would have been rejected. This
conclusion will be further substantiated by future simulation
work.<BR>
<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
