<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microwave heating of solid catalysts
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=331><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Microwave heating of solid catalysts</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=151>
<P>
<IMG SRC="bvos.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Bron Vos</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Alfred Bliek</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1995 - 1999</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>OSPT</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<U><I><B>Introduction</B></I></U><I><B>:</B></I>
<P>
It is well known that some solids can be heated efficiently in
a microwave field as a result of the dielectric relaxation, causing
the microwaves to act as a transfer agent of the electric power.
As a result rapid heating of solids is possible. Interesting aspects
of the use of microwave energy are:
<UL>
<LI>It is possible to create inverse temperature gradients due
to bulk heating by radiation instead of by conduction.
<LI>Rapid heating and cooling is feasible, in contrast to the
(slow) heat transfer in case of conduction. Pulsing of the waves
is possible.
<LI>Heating of solids is selective as gases are transparent to
microwaves.
</UL>
<P>
<BR>
<P>
<U><I><B>The objective</B></I></U><I><B>:</B></I>
<P>
In the present project the objective is to investigate the characteristics
of the solid matter that can be heated in a dielectric field:
<UL>
<LI>Heating of catalyst materials. 
<LI>Calcination and reduction behaviour.
<LI>Seeding: the bulk material itself may have a low dielectric
loss factor and still be made microwave sensitive by the addition
of seed material.
<LI>Develop models describing  the process of heating of a solid
in a microwave field.
</UL>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2"><BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<U><I><B>Experimental work</B></I></U><I><B>:</B></I>
<P>
Literature has shown that alumina and silica are hardly microwave
sensitive. Carbon, on the other hand, can be rapdily heated in
a microwave field. The heating rate of supported and unsupported
catalyst materials in a microwave field will be used to obtain
an overview of the microwave sensitivity of different catalyst
materials.<BR>
<P>
Initially the calcination as well as reduction behaviour of Ni
on alumina in a microwave field will be tested in order to assess
the impact of this heating technique on the catalyst structure
and activity. The analysis of microwave heating, however, is complicated
by the difficulty of temperature measurements and the sample-size
effect.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
