<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Copper Catalysed Hydrogenolysis of Fatty Methyl Esters
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=331><B><FONT SIZE=5>The Copper Catalysed Hydrogenolysis of Fatty Methyl Esters</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=151>
<P>
<IMG SRC="dbrands.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Danny Brands</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Eduard K. Poels/Alfred Bliek</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1993 - 1997</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<I>The hydrogenolysis of fatty methyl esters towards fatty alcohols
is an important step in the production of detergents from natural
fats and oils.<BR>
</I>
<P>
Copper containing catalysts show activity in the hydrogenolysis
of esters towards alcohols:<BR>
<P>
<PRE>R-(C=O)-O-CH<SUB>3</SUB> + 2 H<SUB>2</SUB> --> R-CH<SUB>2</SUB>-OH + CH<SUB>3</SUB>-OH     with: R = C<SUB>11</SUB>-C<SUB>17</SUB></PRE>
<P>
At the department of Chemical Engineering at the University of
Amsterdam, Cu/ZnO/SiO<SUB>2</SUB> catalysts are being tested for
their activity in fatty methyl ester hydrogenolysis. It has been
found that these catalyst can outperform industrial chromium containing
ester hydrogenolysis catalysts on a volume basis.<BR>
<P>
A model, based on epitaxial layers of reduced copper metal on
top of a zinc oxide layer has been developed and is able to describe
the experimental data very well. This model is probably also applicable
for copper based methanol synthesis catalysts.<BR>
<P>
Industrially, the hydrogenolysis of fatty methyl esters is performed
at hydrogen pressures of up to 300 bar. Currently, a liquid phase
process based on inert solvents is being developed that allows
full conversion towards fatty alcohols at hydrogen pressures of
60-80 bar. The main difficulties are the (large) solvent recycle
and the estimation of  thermodynamic properties.<BR>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=281><BR>
Fig. 1: Model of Cu/ZnO/SiO<SUB>2</SUB> catalysts. <BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="dbrands1.gif">
</TD><TD WIDTH=321><BR>
Fig. 2: Flow diagram of an inert solvent based ester hydrogenolysis plant.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="dbrands2.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
