<HEAD>
<TITLE>Forced Oscillations in Heterogeneous Catalysis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=331><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Forced Oscillations in Heterogeneous Catalysis</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=151>
<P>
<IMG SRC="fvneer.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Frank van Neer</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Alfred Bliek</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1993 - 1997</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
 
<P>
 <I>In this research topic we are focused on the use of forced
concentration and temperature oscillations on catalytic systems.
Several purposes of periodic operation are considered on theoretical
as well as experimental basis.</I> <BR>
<P>
 To reveal, a priori, the effect of a periodically change of the
feed of a catalytic reaction first the response of a system towards
transients must be understood. To that end various microkinetic
models were screened on their relaxation and /or transient kinetic
behaviour after imposing subsequent concentration or temperature
steps in time. By following the state variables of the system,
 i.e. the surface occupancies of the catalyst during a period
of oscillation, general conditions could be formulated for the
occurrence of states different from steady state, so called resonance.
The microkinetic models used in simulations differ strongly in
linearity. 
<P>
 In the latter theoretical work numerical as well as semi-analytical
techniques were used to solve the differential equations of the
catalytic system. In case of the semi-analytical approach using
linearisation of the system equations, new requirements were proposed
in terms of rates of the various steps of the catalytic model
for the use of this method.  The linearisation has many advantages
compared to numerical simulation:  only one (relatively less time
consuming) calculation leads to the desired information of the
cycle invariant state during forced oscillations and an analytical
expression for time average rates can be obtained from which influence
of frequency, amplitude etc. can be derived.
<P>
 The use of forced oscillations for elucidation of the microkinetic
mechanism of reactions is demonstrated in a experimental study
towards the kinetics of the re-oxidation of a CuO/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
catalyst. In the oxidation of CO with O<SUB>2</SUB> subsequent
cycles of CO and O<SUB>2</SUB> were imposed on this catalyst.
From the response at various frequencies of oscillation a model
could be proposed for the oxidation in the oxygen half-cycle.
The model includes oxidation of three types of surface sites:
free (reduced) sites, sites occupied with only CO and sites containing
both CO and O. Transient isotopic labelling experiments confirmed
the suggested mechanistic scheme. An interesting phenomenon is
the observation of a net CO dissociation after several cycles
on the CuO catalyst. Transient FTIR experiments were performed
in a flow cell and made us to conclude that carboxylates were
the intermediates in the net CO dissociation. 
<P>
 At the moment CO oxidation on EUROPT-3 (0.3 wt.% Pt/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>)
is the reaction of interest. This highly non-linear system shows
self-oscillations under many conditions. The impact of forced
oscillations on such a system is interesting because the oscillations
in the CO<SUB>2</SUB> production rate might be suppressed by the
periodic operation. This can even coincide with a time average
rate enhancement compared to the optimal steady state rate. A
search to a mechanistic model which can describe the self-oscillations
and the response towards transients is the main goal of the latter
work.<BR>
<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
