<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selection criteria for carbon supported noble metal catalysts in three-phase reaction systems
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B><FONT SIZE=5>Selection criteria for carbon supported noble metal catalysts in three-phase reaction systems</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Monique van der Zon</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Alfred Bliek</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>1995 - 1999</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>IOP Katalyse</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<U><I><B>Introduction</B></I></U><I><B>: </B></I>In a number of
industrial hydrogenation and oxidation reactions transport limitations
occur. Many  authors observe under these conditions a clear effect
of the choice of the catalyst support on conversion. Vinke (Ph.D.
thesis Amsterdam, 1992) showed that during hydrogenation in a
three-phase agitated slurry reactor the gas-absorption is enhanced
if the support of small catalysts particles is chemically modified
resulting in a better particle-to-bubble adhesion. Other experiments
showed that this adhesion behaviour can also be affected by changing
the gas phase. The question now arises whether we can optimise
the chemical environment and catalyst for such reactions in industrial
reactors? To answer this question adhesion and gas-absorption
experiments are performed with gas-liquid systems and a palladium
catalyst on different supports.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="mvdzon1.gif">
<P>
<I><B>Figure 1</B></I> <I>Pick-up needle with gas bubble and adhering
catalyst particles.</I>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83><B>Gas</B></TD><TD WIDTH=66><B>Liquid</B></TD>
<TD WIDTH=76><B>Catalyst</B></TD><TD WIDTH=47><B>a /1<SUP>0</SUP></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>air</TD><TD WIDTH=66>octane</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>0</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>hydrogen</TD><TD WIDTH=66>octane</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>0</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>air</TD><TD WIDTH=66>water</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>112</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>hydrogen</TD><TD WIDTH=66>water</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>0</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>air</TD><TD WIDTH=66>octane</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/C
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>0</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>hydrogen</TD><TD WIDTH=66>octane</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/C
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>0</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>air</TD><TD WIDTH=66>water</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/C
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>88</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=83>hydrogen</TD><TD WIDTH=66>water</TD><TD WIDTH=76>Pd/C
</TD><TD WIDTH=47>180</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<I><B>Table 1:</B> Effect of different three-phase systems on
the bubble-surface coverage angle .</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Results and Discussion</B></I></U><I><B>: </B></I>Experiments
were performed to establish the effect of the liquid phase on
the adhesion of  Pd/C and Pd/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> to air
and hydrogen bubbles under static conditions (fig.1). A comparison
of the obtained values of the bubble-surface coverage angle  for
different three-phase systems is represented in Table 1. It can
be seen that adhesion is influenced by all of the phases involved.
<BR>
<P>
<U><I><B>Future work</B></I></U><I><B>: </B></I>In a joint project
with the Universities of Delft and Utrecht sponsored by the &quot;IOP-Katalyse&quot;,
future research will focus on carbon supported noble metal catalysts.
The relation between catalyst parameters and their performance
in hydrogenation and oxidation reactions will be investigated.

