<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>New methods for the preparation of oleochemicals using solid acid catalysts
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B><FONT SIZE=5>New methods for the preparation of oleochemicals using solid acid catalysts</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Remko Koster</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Alfred Bliek</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>1995 - 1999</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>IOP Katalyse</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<U><I><B>Introduction</B></I></U><I><B>:</B></I> The dimerisation
of unsaturated fatty acids is part of a research investigating
new methods for preparation of oleochemicals using solid acid
catalysts. The objective of this research is to obtain a higher
selectivity in the conversion and synthesis of oleochemicals.
This research should lead to reduction of waste streams and by-products.<BR>
Three major products are made in the dimerisation process: isostearic
acid, dimers and trimers.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="rkoster1.gif">
<P>
All three products have a number of applications, for instance
in cosmetics, coatings, and adhesives. Manipulation of the selectivity
to the three products is desired to be able to respond to market
changes. The three products each consist of numerous different
compounds caused by occurrence of side reactions: especially hydrogen
transfer reactions. 
<P>
Commercially a Montmorillonite clay catalyst is used, but little
is understood of its superiority in catalytic performance<BR>
<P>
<U><I><B>Results and Discussion</B></I></U><I><B>: </B></I>Research
into the catalytic aspects of dimerisation is conspicuously absent
in literature. Therefore, initially this study will focus on the
mechanism behind the existing process. Recent patents describe
the clay catalysed dimerisation reaction, but also thermal, radical
initiated and Lewis acid catalysed dimerisation has industrially
been used. Den Otter proposed a reaction model for the dimerisation
process, in which the dimerisation takes place after a hydrogen
transfer step in a Diels-Alder reaction, leading to the experimentally
found maximum selectivity of 66%. Spiteller et.al. identified
the many different dimer structures, that are formed due to side-
and consecutive reactions as hydrogen transfer and intramolecular
reactions, and showed that the substitution patterns of the structures
do not support a Diels-Alder mechanism. Instead they proposed
a cationic mechanism. <BR>
<P>
<U><I><B>Future work</B></I></U><I><B>: </B></I>In a joint project
with the University of Delft, sponsored by the &quot;IOP-Katalyse&quot;,
future research will focus also on esterification reactions of
fatty acids. The relation between catalyst parameters and their
performance in dimerisation and esterification reactions will
be investigated.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
