Content-length: 4080
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) of NO with NH3 over MnOx/Al2O3 catalysts at low Temperatures
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=331><B><FONT SIZE=5>Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) of NO with NH<SUB>3</SUB> over MnO<SUB>x</SUB>/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> catalysts at low Temperatures</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=151>
<P>
<IMG SRC="skylstra.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>W. Sjoerd Kijlstra</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Alfred Bliek</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1992 - 1996</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>SON, NOVEM</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<I>Alumina supported manganese oxides are studied as catalysts
for the selective catalytic reduction (SCR) of NO with NH<SUB>3</SUB>.
Transient experiments (with labelled reactants), TPD and FTIR
are used to elucidate the complex reaction mechanism. Besides,
the mechanism of inhibition/deactivation by SO<SUB>2</SUB> and
H<SUB>2</SUB>O is evaluated.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><B>Introduction:</B></U> Selective catalytic reduction of NO
with NH<SUB>3</SUB> is one of the most effective ways to remove
NO<SUB>x</SUB> from flue gases emitted by stationary sources:
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><PRE>4 NO + 4 NH<SUB>3</SUB> + O<SUB>2</SUB> ====&gt; 4 N<SUB>2</SUB> + 6 H<SUB>2</SUB>O<BR>
</PRE></CENTER>
<P>
To apply SCR in add-on units, catalysts active and selective at
low temperatures (383-573 K) are required. Alumina supported with
2 wt% MnO<SUB>x</SUB> has appeared to meet these criteria.   
<BR>
<P>
<U><B>Results and discussion:<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
- <B>Transient experiments</B>, combined with<B> TPD</B> revealed
that under reaction conditions the catalyst surface is almost
completely covered by NH<SUB>3</SUB>. However, NO appeared to
react both directly from the gas phase as from an adsorbed state.
Moreover, NO can adsorb in a very stable form, partly deactivating
the catalyst. At the moment, special attention is paid to the
role of surface oxygen and gas phase NO<SUB>2</SUB> in the NO-adsorption.
The possibilities of application of a <B>periodically reversed
flow reactor</B> to use the buffer NH<SUB>3</SUB> in periods of
excess NO<SUB>x</SUB> in stack gases (and avoid NH<SUB>3</SUB>-slip
during excess NH<SUB>3</SUB>!) is under investigation.
<P>
- <B>FTIR</B> studies turned out that the stable form of adsorbed
NO, as established by TPD, has to be a bidentate nitrate. Moreover,
nitrosyls are only detected in the absence of O<SUB>2</SUB>, and
disappear in its presence. As O<SUB>2</SUB> is essential for reaction,
nitrosyls are not likely SCR-intermediates (as argued by other
authors on comparable systems) on this catalyst. NH<SUB>3</SUB>
co-ordinates on both Lewis and Br&oslash;nsted acid sites. Attention
is focused on the type of nitrite that can function as active
intermediate in the catalytic cycle.
<P>
- <B>Water</B> appeared to exhibit a reversible inhibition on
the reaction as well as an irreversible deactivation on the catalyst.
Inhibition is caused by molecular adsorbed H<SUB>2</SUB>O. Deactivation
is probably due to dissociative adsorption of H<SUB>2</SUB>O to
surface hydroxyls, which remain on the surface upon removal of
H<SUB>2</SUB>O from the gas stream (at 383-523 K). This effect
reaches a plateau value, so can be dealt with easily in practical
applications. <B>SO<SUB>2</SUB> </B>can deactivate the catalyst
completely in a very short period due to the formation of MnSO<SUB>4</SUB>.
This formation is almost inevitable, so the application potential
of the catalyst is reduced to sulphur free conditions.<BR>

