<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Phenomena-driven Process Design; a Knowledge-based Approach
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=414><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Phenomena-driven Process Design; a Knowledge-based Approach</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=87>
<P>
<IMG SRC="ioag.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B>
</TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=501><B><FONT>Ioa Silva Gavrila</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B>
</TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=501><B>Piet Iedema</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD>
<TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=501><B>Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<H1><CENTER><FONT SIZE=4>Introduction</FONT></CENTER>
</H1>
<P>
Conceptual process design is the activity of
designing and interconnecting stream processing units, in order
to transform given feed streams into desired product streams.
A design method is proposed in which the necessary phenomena (reactions,
phase changes) to implement the process are taken as starting
point of design, and in which qualitative and numerical design
tasks are alternated. Here only a summary of the qualitative design
entities and tasks is given.
<H1><CENTER><FONT SIZE=4>The Design Method</FONT></CENTER>
</H1>
<P>
<B>Design entities</B>
<P>
Qualitative process designs (flowsheets) may
consist of the following entities:
<P>
<IMG SRC="ioag1.gif">
<P>
<B>Design tasks</B>
<P>
Design tasks that have to be performed to create
a qualitative flowsheet are:
<LI><I><B>Role Assignment</B></I>:
derive desirability of all specified reactions and of phase changes
(gas-liquid) of relevant chemical components. Assigned roles are:
needed, desirable, no-impact, not-desirable, not-tolerable.
<LI><I><B>D<I><B>esign R-QU</B></I></B></I>:
group needed reactions that can occur under same operating conditions
(temperature, pressure) into one unit; determine components that
<I>must</I> enter the unit, and those that are not allowed to
enter; derive by qualitative simulation components that will leave
R-QU based on needed
inputs.
<LI><I><B>C<I><B>onnect R-QUs</B></I></B></I>:
assign feed streams to R-QUs;
if more R-QUs are
needed for all needed reactions to take place, connect them by
intermediate streams; given components in feed streams, derive
components in all process streams.
<LI><I><B>D<I><B>esign S-QU</B></I></B></I>:
if, after the stream assignment, not-allowed components enter
a R-QU, insert a
S-QU before this
R-QU to purify the
stream.
<P>
All tasks in which designs are created contain
the subtasks: generate, select, analyze, evaluate, and modify.
<H1><CENTER><FONT SIZE=4>Example</FONT></CENTER>
</H1>
<P>
A flowsheet after task 'Design S-QU' may look
as follows:
<H1><CENTER><IMG SRC="ioag2.gif"></CENTER></H1>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Reference</B></CENTER>
<P>
I.S. Gavrila and P. Iedema, 1996. <I>Phenomena-driven
design, a knowledge-based approach</I>. Computers in Chemical
Engineering, Pergamonn Press, vol 20, pp. S103-S108.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
