<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Numerical Modeling of Static Mixer Reactors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=350><B><FONT SIZE=5>Numerical Modeling</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>of Static Mixer Reactors</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=132>
<P>
<IMG SRC="davidv.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>D.J.-E. Vidal</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>P.D. Iedema, H.C.J. Hoefsloot</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>March 1996- March 2000</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>SON</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
An important part in the design and scale-up of a polymerization
process is the reactor. The static mixer reactor (SMR) is an interesting
reactor type due to its cooling and mixing capabilities. The polymer
end use properties are directly related to the geometry of the
reactor, the flow, the heat exchange and the mass transfer inside
the reactor which include also rheology, micromixing, macromixing
and polymerization kinetics.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="davidv1.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B>Objective</B>
<P>
The main objective of the study is to simulate the flow phenomena
inside the SMR in order to be able to optimize the SMR geometry
and to predict the polymer end use properties like the molecular
weight distribution.<BR>
<P>
<B>Methodology</B>
<P>
Our methodology is based on non-isothermal, non-Newtonian CFD
simulations achieved by means of a finite element code named POLY3D
from Rheotek Inc. (Montr&eacute;al, Canada). The simulations should
take into account the reaction kinetics and be able to predict
the micromixing from the flow field. To achieve our objective,
we will analyse the pressure drop, the macromixing (residence
time distribution, particle trajectory...) and the micromixing
(striation thickness) inside the reactor.
<P>
Finally, experimental laboratory scale validations on judicious
cases will be performed.<BR>
<P>
<B>Preliminary Results</B>
<P>
Isothermal CFD simulations of Newtonian and non-Newtonian fluids
have been performed for one and two SMX and SMRX elements and
good agreement with literature data has been obtained in terms
of pressure drops and velocity profiles. The trajectory of particles
launched inside the reactor shows also clearly to what extent
the use of two static mixer elements provide enhanced mixing compared
to one.
<P>
<IMG SRC="davidv2.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B>Work to Come</B>
<P>
For the coming year, we intend to implement Ottino's micromixing
model inside the numerical code in cooperation with Rheotek Inc.
As criterion of mixing efficiency, it is also planned to determine
the residence time distribution from the flow field. Finally,
non-isothermal simulations will be performed.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
