<HEAD>
<TITLE>Melting problems during Polymer Processing in a Continuous mixer
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=331><B><FONT SIZE=5>Melting problems during Polymer Processing in a Continuous mixer</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=151>
<P>
<IMG SRC="sanderw.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Sander M. Willemsen</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>H.C.J. Hoefsloot, P. J. Hamersma, P.D. Iedema</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1996-2000</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>DSM</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Introduction</FONT></B>
<P>
Most polymers as produced in a reactor have to undergo a postprocessing
step in a plastification unit, in order to re-adjust end-use properties.
This involves complex phenomena like melting, phase inversion,
mixing with additives, reactions, etc. In this project the plastification
unit is a Farrel Continuous Mixer (see Fig. 1).
<P>
At certain process conditions problems arise; solid aggregates
remain in the polymer melt, that comes out of the Continuous Mixer.
The goal of this research is to find out why these aggregates
remain in the polymer melt.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="sanderw1.gif">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Fig 1. A Farrel Continuous Mixer.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Research Plan</FONT></B>
<P>
To tackle the problem two routes will be followed.
<P>
Firstly, in a laboratory sized plastification machine the forming
of the aggregates will be studied. From these experiments the
structure of the aggregates can be examined (for instance porosity
and strength).<BR>
<P>
Secondly, using Computational Fluid Dynamics the (Non-Newtonian)
flow field in the Continuous Mixer will be examined. For this
purpose we are working with the Finite Element code POLY3D from
Rh&eacute;otek Inc. (Montr&eacute;al, Canada). The CFD-code will
be extended with a mix-melting model. <BR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Near Future</FONT></B>
<P>
This year a start will be made with the investigation of a melting
model. This will be done in an experimental and computational
way. Because the geometry of the Continuous Mixer is quite complicated,
simulations and experiments will performed on the following geometry:
two counterrotating cylinders (see Fig. 2) filled with a fluid
in which a solid particle can be positioned.  With a digital camera
the melting, deformation and movement of the particle will be
filmed.<BR>
<P>
 <IMG SRC="sanderw2.gif">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Fig 2. Set-up for melting experiments.</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
