<HEAD>
<TITLE>Including External Process Variables in Multivariate Calibration of Process Instruments
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B><FONT SIZE=5>Including External Process Variables in Multivariate Calibration of Process Instruments</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Florian Wulfert</B> (<A HREF="mailto:florian@anal.chem.uva.nl">florian@anal.chem.uva.nl</A>)
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Age Smilde, Wim Kok</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>December 1994 - December 1998</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
 In order to control an industrial process, information about
the process has to be obtained and the quality of this information
has to be evaluated. The concentration measurements in process
analysis can be done by near-infrared (NIR) spectroscopy.
<P>
<IMG SRC="wulfert1.gif">
<P>
<I>Process with measurements of process variables (temperature,
pressure, etc.) and spectra<BR>
</I>
<P>
 Multivariate calibration is performed on the measured spectra,
using the absorption data of all wavelengths.
<P>
<IMG SRC="wulfert2.gif">
<P>
<I>Building a PLS model from measured data (e.g. spectra) and
known properties (e.g. concentrations determined by an accurate
off-line technique).<BR>
</I>
<P>
<IMG SRC="wulfert3.gif">
<P>
<I>Predicting the property from on-line
measured data using the model built above.</I>
<P>
<B>Purpose of the research</B>
<P>
 The spectra are modified by &quot;external&quot; variables such
as temperature, viscosity, pressure etc. Fluctuations of the external
variables will therefore result in shift, broadening and intensity
changes for certain absorption bands. 
<P>
 In order to make the instrument robust against such influences,
the effect of the external variables on the measurements has to
be included explicitly in the calibration model.<BR>
<P>
<B>Experiments</B>
<P>
 Different calibration models are evaluated using spectra of ternary
mixtures of water, isopropanol and ethanol. The calibration set
is measured at different temperatures and concentration levels.
<P>
<IMG SRC="wulfert4.gif">
<P>
<B>Further Considerations</B>
<P>
 The measured data in industrial processes is not independent
in time. The model should take into account the correlation between
measurements in the time domain. 
<P>
 Because of the non-linearity of the influences from external
variables it might be necessary to transform the data to a different
domain. 

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
