<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Plant Wide Measurability
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B><FONT SIZE=5>Plant Wide Measurability</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Frans W.J. van den Berg</B> (<A HREF="mailto:fvdberg@anal.chem.uva.nl">fvdberg@anal.chem.uva.nl</A>)
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Age K. Smilde and Huub C.J. Hoefsloot</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>August 1996 - August 2000 </B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>SON</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
   The implementation of in-process analytical instrumentation
for the purpose of obtaining chemical composition information
can strongly improve the control and/or monitoring possibilities
for chemical processes. The introduction of analytical measurements
- compared to more conventional signal transducers (temperature,
pressure, etc.) - requires distinctive understanding. Some of
the specific differences involved are sensor location, instrument
response and precision.<BR>
<P>
<B>Sensor location</B>
<P>
   The cost of purchase and maintenance of analytical instruments
is much higher, so a minimum number of installations is required
providing maximum information per measurement. The choice of instrument
location/sample interfacing is not a simple one as may be judged
from the figure below.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="fvdberg1.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B>Instrument response</B>
<P>
   The information from an in-process instrument becomes available
after a (short ) time delay. This introduces  extra 'death-time'
in the control structures of the process. The sampling/analysis
frequency (speed of analysis) of chemical composition information
is often lower than that of conventional process measurements,
placing constrictions on signal reconstruction (monitoring).<BR>
<P>
<B>Precision</B>
<P>
   All (analytical) instruments have a limited accuracy/precision.
The resulting variance in the response cannot (immediately) be
distinguished from that in the signal under investigation. The
trade-off between variance and sample frequency (as mentioned
under the previous bullet) guides the choice for a particular
in-process instrument or the settings for an individual instrument.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Purpose of the research</B>
<P>
   The goal of this study is to develop mathematical/statistical
methods to assist in the choice of in-process measurements for
monitoring and control purposes. As a starting point, the theory
of P.M.E.M. van der Grinten will be used. The research will be
done in the form of computer simulations. No experimental work
is planned so far.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-135</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000114-B047-213</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/uva/sbijlsma.html 130.89.50.60 19970216174340 text/html 2814
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:37:05 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 06-Nov-96 07:36:25 GMT
Content-length: 2631
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Plant-Wide Instrumentation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=369><B><FONT SIZE=5>Plant-Wide Instrumentation</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=113>
<P>
<IMG SRC="sbijlsma.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Sabina Bijlsma</B> (<A HREF="mailto:sabina@anal.chem.uva.nl">sabina@anal.chem.uva.nl</A>)
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>A.K. Smilde</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1-7-1996/30-6-2000</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B>Introduction<BR>
</B>
<P>
Short wavelength near infrared spectroscopy is very suitable for
monitoring chemical processes. When a kinetic model for such a
chemical process is available, the reaction rate constants of
several reactions can be estimated using curve resolution and
non-linear regression techniques. Figure I shows the estimated
concentration profiles and the estimated pure spectra of the reactant
( A ), intermediant ( B ) and product ( C ) of a simulated batch
process in the absence of any noise:
<P>
<IMG SRC="sbijlsma1.gif">
<P>
<I>Figure I: The calculated concentration
profiles and the pure spectra from a simulated batch process.
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Disadvantages<BR>
</B>
<UL>
<LI>The whole chemical matrix must be known.
<LI>The kinetic model of the several reactions involved in the
process, must be known.
</UL>
<P>
<B></B>
<P>
<B>Strategy<BR>
</B>
<P>
Develop methods, which do not have the disadvantages mentioned
above.<BR>
<P>
<B>Methods to be adapted and developed<BR>
</B>
<UL>
<LI>Tendency modelling for the estimation of the reaction stochiometry.
<LI>Inverse approaches of curve resolution and iterative target
transformation factor analysis that allows for handling the unknown
chemical matrix.
<LI>Multivariate curve resolution for the estimation of reaction
rate constants of several process runs simultaneously.
<LI>Multivariate statistical process control, to decide if the
process is in or out of control with respect to the reaction rate
constants.
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<B>Future<BR>
</B>
<P>
Develop methods using small scale laboratory experiments and computer
simulations.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

