<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Plant-wide Multivariate Statistical Process Control
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=356><B><FONT SIZE=5>Plant-wide Multivariate Statistical Process Control</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=126>
<P>
<IMG SRC="atates.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>TwAIO-student:</B>
<P>
<B>Supervisors :</B>
</TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>A.A. Tates</B>
<P>
<B>A.K. Smilde, P.D. Iedema, C. Georgakis</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B>Philosophy of multivariate statistical process control (MSPC)
<BR>
</B>
<P>
Detecting variation due to special causes. In a process there
are two types of variation: common cause and special cause variation.
The first one is inherent to the process and can only be changed
by optimizing the process and control structure design. The second
type of variation moves the process out of normal operating conditions.
There are three reasons to perform MSPC: detecting if there is
special variation, locating where this special variation starts
in the process and assigning cause(s) of special variation.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="atates1.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<P>
<B>Multivariate Statistical Process Control <BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
Measurements M1, M2 and M3 are measured simultaneously. The results
can be processed in a T<SUP>2</SUP>-chart which shows the behavior
of the 3 measurements in time. Remark that this set up does not
allow to answer the question where the special variation started.
<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="atates2.gif">
<P>
<B>Plant-Wide MSPC <BR>
</B>
<P>
The idea of Plant-wide MSPC is to look at the whole plant simultaneously.
Due to recycle streams and controller structures the measurements
at different locations in a process are not independent. It is
this dependency that should be utilized. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<B>Goal of Plant-Wide MSPC<BR>
</B>
<P>
Plant-wide MSPC aims at developing charts to monitor a complete
process and tries to accomplish three goals: detecting, locating
and assigning causes of special variation anywhere in a process.
<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
