<HEAD>
<TITLE>Radical Polymerisation Reactions
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=312><B><FONT SIZE=5>Simulation of </FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Radical Polymerisation Reactions</FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=170>
<P>
<IMG SRC="lousberg.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Henk Lousberg</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>Peter Hamersma, Piet Iedema and Age Smilde</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1995-1999</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>UvA</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B><P>
In chemical industry the control of polymer
properties by process variables is important to obtain the desired
polymer product composition. Chemical reaction kinetics play an
important role in the conversion process in the reactor. In case
of radical polymerisation kinetics are rather complex. This is
mainly caused by the chain length distribution (CLD) of the polymer
radicals. All radicals with different chain length must be considered
as individual components. The actual number of components may
be more than one thousand. 
<P>
Many researchers have tried to solve this problem with various
mathematical and numerical approximations. <BR>
<P>
<B>Simulation of Polyreactions</B>
<P>
Recently, the software package Predici<SUP>&reg;</SUP> has been
developed, which uses the Galerkin method. This program is able
to calculate CLD's and conversions. It may also be used to obtain
the kinetic rate constants of a reacting system from experimental
data, i.e. number M<SUB>n</SUB> and weight M<SUB>w</SUB> averaged
molecular mass. <BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
In Fig.1 the results are shown of a simulation with Predici<SUP>&reg;</SUP>
of the radical polymerisation of styrene initiated by AIBN. The
dotted lines are simulation results of kinetic constants published
by Villermaux and Blavier. The dots show the corresponding experimental
values. The continuous lines show the results of a fit of reaction
rate constants by Predici<SUP>&reg;</SUP> (See Table 1). The fitted
constants are well in agreement with the experimental data. <BR>
<BR>
<P>
<I>Table 1:</I> Parameter optimisation with Predici<SUP>&reg;</SUP>.
<BR>

<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#808080 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD WIDTH=47></TD><TD WIDTH=94>Villermaux </TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=95>Predici<SUP>&reg;</SUP>
</TD><TD WIDTH=104>SI units</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=47>K<SUB>d</SUB> </TD><TD WIDTH=94>4.94 10<SUP>-5</SUP>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85>5.13 10<SUP>-5</SUP></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=113>s<SUP>-1</SUP>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=47>f</TD><TD WIDTH=94>0.585</TD><TD WIDTH=85>0.62 
</TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=113>dimensionless</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=47>k<SUB>p</SUB></TD><TD WIDTH=94>2.40 10<SUP>2</SUP>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85>2.41 10<SUP>2</SUP></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=113>dm<SUP>3</SUP> mole<SUP>-1</SUP> s<SUP>-1</SUP>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=47>k<SUB>tc</SUB></TD><TD WIDTH=94>9.98 10<SUP>5</SUP>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85>4.38 10<SUP>4</SUP></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=113>dm<SUP>3</SUP> mole<SUP>-1</SUP> s<SUP>-1</SUP>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=47>k<SUB>td</SUB></TD><TD WIDTH=94>1.10 10<SUP>7</SUP>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85>4.76 10<SUP>6</SUP></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=113>dm<SUP>3</SUP> mole<SUP>-1</SUP> s<SUP>-1</SUP>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=47>k<SUB>tm</SUB></TD><TD WIDTH=94>0.152</TD><TD WIDTH=85>0.963
</TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=113>dm<SUP>3</SUP> mole<SUP>-1</SUP> s<SUP>-1</SUP>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
Three constants were modified by Predici<SUP>&reg;</SUP>; k<SUB>tc,
</SUB>k<SUB>td</SUB> and k<SUB>tm</SUB>. Apparently combination
(k<SUB>tc</SUB>)<SUB> </SUB>and disproportionation (k<SUB>td</SUB>)<SUB>
</SUB>termination were overestimated, while transfer to monomer
(k<SUB>tm</SUB>)<SUB> </SUB>seems to be underestimated.
<P>
<IMG SRC="lousberg1.gif">
<P>
<I>Fig 1:</I> Radical polymerisation of styrene with AIBN (0.033
M) and cyclohexane (2.22 M) at 348 K and 0.1 MPa. Literature data
and Predici<SUP>&reg;</SUP> results.<BR>
<P>
<B>Reference</B>
<P>
Villermaux,J and Blavier, L,<I>Chem. Engng Sci</I>. 1984, <B>39</B>,
101-110.<I> </I>

