<HEAD>
<TITLE>Plantwide Controllability and Flowsheet Structure of Complex Continuous Process Plants
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=356><B><FONT SIZE=5>Plantwide Controllability and Flowsheet Structure of Complex Continuous Process Plants </FONT></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=126>
<P>
<IMG SRC="sanderg.gif"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Ph.D. student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>A.J. Groenendijk</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>A.C. Dimian, P.D. Iedema</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>1995 - 1999</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Introduction</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The material balance for main components and impurities
in a complex plant is  closely related with the plantwide control
properties of components' inventory.  This is sharply affected
by interactions between recycles and by connectivity structure.
Keeping the same units but changing their connectivity leads to
flowsheet alternatives possessing different control properties.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Methodology</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>A simulation-based methodology for studying the dynamics
of recycle loops in a complex continuous plant is developed. Steady-state
and dynamic simulation combined with controllability tools enables
to characterise quantitatively interactions between recycles and
to evaluate plantwide control properties of different flowsheet
alternatives. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Case study</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The proposed methodology is illustrated by a case
study: plantwide control and design problem created by the impurities
removal in a balanced VCM process. The controllability properties
of two design alternatives are studied, both in steady-state and
in dynamic conditions.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="sanderg1.gif"><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Results</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Flowsheeting troubles related with the simultaneous
reconciliation of material balance for main components and impurities
are closely related with the plantwide control properties of components'
inventory.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Plantwide controllability of a complex plant is sharply
affected by interactions between recycles and by plant connectivity
structure.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The existence of interactions between recycle loops
may create feasible control structures of some specifications
that are impossible to achieve with stand-alone units. However,
for plantwide control purposes it is desirable to find decoupled
combinations between controlled and manipulated variables.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Conclusions</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Steady-state simulation combined with dynamic simulation
and controllability analysis may be used to evaluate different
alternatives. They enable to get more value from simulation as
the usual sensitivity studies.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Further Work</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>A new challenge is the development of an algorithm
for the design of an optimal flowsheet and control structure were
connectivity between items is a degree of freedom. For this mixed
integer non-linear programming problem we will use optimisation
techniques.</FONT>
<P>
<U><FONT SIZE=2>   </FONT></U>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Dimian, A.C.  A.J. Groenendijk, P.D. Iedema; <I>Systems
Analysis In Handling Impurities</I>, <B>1996</B>,<B> </B>ESCAPE6.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Dimian, A.C.  A.J. Groenendijk, S.R.A. Kersten; <I>Dynamics
of Recycle loops in a complex plant;</I><B> 1996</B>, SIMO96</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
