http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/uva/louwerse.html 130.89.50.60 19970216174440 text/html 3050
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:38:06 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 06-Nov-96 07:36:18 GMT
Content-length: 2867
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Multivariate Statistical Process Control of batch processes using three-way models
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B><FONT SIZE=5>Multivariate Statistical Process Control of batch processes using three-way models</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Post-doc:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Ad Louwerse</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Age K. Smilde</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>Feb. '96 - Feb '98</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=482><B>University of Amsterdam</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
Multivariate statistical process control (MSPC) tries to detect
variation due to special causes. One can define two types of variation
in a process: common cause, variation that can be expected if
the process is running under normal operating conditions (NOC);
and special causes, variation that moves the process out of NOC.
In continuous processes multivariate control charts can be developed
to control the process which are comparable with univariate charts.
MSPC for batch processes is inherently more difficult.
<P>
<IMG SRC="louwerse1.gif"><BR>
<P>
 Yet, batch
processes that are very common in the chemical industry, exhibit
larger variations in their operation. For batch processes the
target values for the different process measurements and output
variables are not clear and constant like in continuous processes.
They depend on time (or conversion factor) and can be described
as &quot;ideal temporal trajectories.&quot; MSPC can then be used
to monitor the deviation from this ideal trajectory for a running
batch.
<P>
<IMG SRC="louwerse2.gif">
<P>
<B>Three way analysis</B>
<P>
<P>
For batch MSPC the data can be arranged in a three-way array,
and analyzed with the batches considered as objects. When a new
batch starts, the available measurements are used to calculate
the position of that batch in the PC1-PC2 plot. If during the
run a batch falls outside the area of NOC (as shown below) than
action has to be undertaken.<BR><P>
<IMG SRC="louwerse3.gif"><BR>
<P>

<BR>
<P>
<B>Tools to handle three-way data</B>
<P>
Several tools to handle three-way data exist. Here a Tucker model
is presented. The advantage of using a Tucker model in batch MSPC
is that specific characteristics for the time- and variable dimensions
can be modelled independently. This can be an advantage in detecting
special variation and in assigning causes.
<P>
<IMG SRC="louwerse4.gif">
<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
