<DOCNO>WT25-B28-141</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000114-B047-291</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/uva/jellema.html 130.89.50.60 19970216174450 text/html 3400
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:38:14 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 13-Nov-96 08:12:52 GMT
Content-length: 3217
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Variance Components in Steel Analysis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Variance Components in Steel Analysis</H1>

Ph.D. student: R.H. Jellema (<A HREF="mailto:renger@anal.chem.uva.nl">renger@anal.chem.uva.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisors: A.K. Smilde (University of Amsterdam), H.F. Pronk (Hoogovens Staal Bv) and M.J.P. Gerritsen (Hoogovens Staal Bv)<BR>
Project term: September 1995 - September 1999<BR>
Sponsor: Hoogovens Steel<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
At the analytical laboratory for process
control of Hoogovens Staal BV, Optical
Emission Spectrometers (OES) are used to
determine the chemical composition of steel
for process and quality control. Measured
concentration levels are disturbed by several
sources of variation. Three main sources of
variation have    to    be    considered:
(i) Fluctuations in the process of steel
production, causing variation between batches
of steel of the same quality. (ii) Sampling
variation, which is introduced because a small
part of the batch is sampled. Sampling
variation also includes heterogeneity of the
sample. (iii) The error of the analytical
method (OES) introduced with the analysis of
a sample.
These three main sources of variation
contribute to the total variation in
concentration levels which should be within
certain specification limits in order to meet
the customer demands.<P>

<B>Purpose of the Research</B><BR>
The initial purpose of this research is to
differentiate the above mentioned main
sources of variation. This will result in a
number of variance components of which the
sizes will be estimated. With this knowledge,
an optimal analysis strategy can be developed
to improve process and quality control.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
In order to assess the size of one of the
variance components, the following
hypothesis is tested: steel slab samples are
more homogeneous than production samples.
Production samples were taken from the steel
bath during the process of steel making and
steel slab samples were taken from steel slabs
(cast steel). Both types of samples belong to
the same steel quality (i.e. the expected
concentration levels are the same.). Analysis
of these samples should give an indication of
the heterogeneity of production samples
compared to steel slab samples. Figures 1a
and 1b show some results for two steel
qualities.
<P>
<IMG SRC="jellema1.gif">
<P>
<I>Figure I: Estimated variances (relative to
variance in production samples) for three
elements in steel quality Q (a) and R (b).</I>
<P>
As can be seen in Figure 1, variations in steel
analysis depend on both
element
concentrations and type of sample.<P>

<B>Further Considerations</B><BR>
The influence of the different variance
components on meeting the specification
limits will be assessed given the interplay
between process variation, sampling variation
and analysis variation. Optimisation of the
total analysis strategy is based on this
assessment.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
