<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PhD-projects Amsterdam 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TD WIDTH=227><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=416><B><FONT SIZE=5>University of Amsterdam</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Department of Chemical Engineering<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Bioprocess Engineering<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=227><B><FONT SIZE=4>Permanent Staff:</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>S.P.P. Ottengraf</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>J.C. van den Heuvel</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>E.P. le Comte</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>P.G. Verschuren</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=416><B><FONT SIZE=4>Research Scientists:</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>E.E. Beuling</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>L. Hellendoorn</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>M.C.J. Smits</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>W.J.H. Okkerse (TUE)</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=2>
<TT><PRE>
University of Amsterdam
Department of Chemical Engineering
Nieuwe Achtergracht 166
NL 1018 WV Amsterdam

telephone: +31 (0)20 525 6517
fax:       +31 (0)20 525 5604
e-mail:    <A HREF="mailto:otteng@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">otteng@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A>
</PRE></TT>
</TD>
</TABLE>
<P>
<P>
Our research is dedicated to exploit the full potential of reactor
systems employing selective retention of immobilised biomass.
To this end the interaction of transport phenomena and kinetics
is studied on the scale of the basic unit itself, i.e. the biofilm.
This objective is realised by the development and use of appropriate
micro&#173;sensors for the measurement of local concentrations
and profiles of substrates and products. The insight obtained
is used for design, scale-up and optimisation of biological conversions,
specifically waste gas treatment systems. Current research topics
include:<BR>
<P>
<B>Acceleration of mass transfer</B>
<P>
Hydrostatic pressure changes in loop reactors will increase mass
transfer in recirculating, gas-producing biofilms. Volume variations
of the entrapped gas phase will be compensated by convective flows
inside sufficiently rigid biofilms. The effect of these fluctuations
is studied on lab-scale by variation of the pressure in a stirred
tank reactor. <BR>
<P>
<B>Co-immobilised mixed culture systems</B>
<P>
Diffusion limited oxygen penetration in biofilms may advantageously
be used for the successive conversion of substrate by co-immobilised
aerobic and anaerobic micro-organisms. Compared to immobilised
pure cultures in series, the intermediate product concentration
in a co-immobilised culture will both be lower for the first organism
at the periphery, and higher for the second organism in the centre.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Transport properties of biofilms</B>
<P>
Literature data on effective diffusion coefficients in immobilisation
matrices are contradictory, and hamper interpretation of observed
kinetics. Research is undertaken to extend classical methods for
the determination of diffusive transport in biofilms with micro-electrode
measurements, to elucidate contributions of molecular diffusion,
cell density, absorption, etc.<BR>
<P>
<B>Waste gas treatment</B>
<P>
The application of biological trickling filters is studied for
the treatment of waste gas streams containing ammonia and chlorinated
hydrocarbons, respectively. The influence of other C-sources,
heterotrophic organisms and inhibitory products is investigated
on a fundamental level. Their effect on operation, design and
economics is studied on a macroscopic scale.<BR>
<P>
<I>Micro-electrodes with tip diameters of 1 - 10 m were developed
for H<SUP>+</SUP>, O<SUB>2</SUB> , NH<SUB>4</SUB><SUP>+</SUP>,
NO<SUB>3</SUB><SUP>-</SUP>, and glucose. Financial support is
received from the UvA, Senter IOP Milieubiotechnologie, Biostar,
and a consortium of several industries and semi-governmental bodies.
Co-operation with other institutes includes TUE, LUW, University
of Hannover, and Max Planck Institute Bremen.</I>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
