<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mass transfer properties of biofilms
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B><FONT SIZE=5>  </FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5> Mass transfer properties of biofilms</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>PhD student:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>Evelien Beuling</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>1992-1996</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>Biotechnological Centre UvA</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Introduction<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
Diffusion of substrates and products through biofilms is often
the rate limiting step in bioreactors utilising immobilised cells.
Therefore, characterisation of the diffusion properties is considered
essential for the modelling and scale-up of microbial conversions
processes. Due to the complex and heterogeneous structure of biofilms
however, experimental determination of dif-fusion coefficients
is difficult. In this project these practical difficulties were
circumvented by the use of well defined model systems. In this
way the influence of different biofilm properties could clearly
be distinguished.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Experimental<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The effective diffusion coefficients of glucose and oxygen were
determined in a classical diffusion cell, which consisted of two
well-mixed compartments that were separated by a 2 mm gel membrane.
<P>
 First, the obstruction effect of cells in a polymer matrix was
studied in a artificial biofilm, consisting of impenetrable particles
with the same size as bacteria, embedded in an agar matrix. Subsequently,
the influence of inactivated bacteria immobilised in the same
agar matrix was determined (See Fig. 1). The obstruction imposed
by the real bacteria on the glucose flux was equivalent to that
of bacteria. The (pseudo) steady-state flux of oxygen, however,
was far less affected by the biomass fraction.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="bpk11.gif">
<P>
<B>Fig. 1</B>. Normalised diffusion coefficients for glucose (triangles)
and oxygen (circles).<BR>
<P>
 This difference indicates that bacteria are somewhat permeable
for oxygen. Additional experiments revealed that oxygen was adsorbed
by the inactivated bacteria, the partition coefficient <I>m</I>
amounted 3.5, while glucose was not adsorbed at all. Due to the
hydrophobic character of oxygen the solubility in water is restricted,
while it probably dissolves easily in the hydrophobic cell wall.
Consequently, some oxygen will be transported through this membrane
resulting in an extra flux.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Conclusion<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The permeability of bacteria for different components is determined
by the diffusional properties of the bacteria, but also by the
partition coefficients. Bacteria appear to be impermeable for
components that are excluded by the biomass.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
