<HEAD>
<TITLE>Removal of ammonia from waste gases with a nitrifying bio-trickling filter: Influence of the pH on biofilm activity
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B><FONT SIZE=5>Removal of ammonia from waste gases with a nitrifying bio-trickling filter: Influence of the pH on biofilm activity</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>PhD student:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>Maarten  Smits</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>1992-1996</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>Senter IOP Milieubiotechnologie</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
Acidification of the environment is a well-known problem in Europe.
Ammonia emissions from, e.g. stable ventilation and composting
facilities, cause about half of the acid rain. Reduction is possible
by direct and controlled microbial oxidation to nitrate. A packed
bed operated as a bio-trickling filter BTF is an attractive system
for nitrification: nitrifying organisms attach easily on a suitable
packing material, and, due to their selective retention, high
conversion rates up to 2.3&nbsp;mol&nbsp;NH<SUB>3</SUB>/m<SUP>3</SUP>.h
can be obtained. Liquid circulation and draining prevent nitrate
and acid accumulation in the biofilm, enabling stable and long-term
operation. Nevertheless, axial and transversal concentration profiles
exist along the reactor and the biofilm, respectively, affecting
the local kinetics. For design purposes, macrokinetic behavior
of the system has to be understood in terms of these local kinetics.
<P>
<IMG SRC="bpk31.gif"><BR>
<P>
The effect of the pH on the activity of nitrifying biofilms was
measured with micro-electrodes for oxygen, at various values of
the pH (Fig. 1). It can be seen that the flux into the biofilm
at pH 7.6, is about a factor two higher than the flux at pH 6.7.
A mathematical model, taking into account the mutual dependence
of pH and reaction rate, was able to calculate both profiles by
changing the pH only. With this model, it is possible to calculate
the flux into the biofilm for various pH and ammonium concentrations.
This is important for macroscopic modeling the BTF. Fig.&nbsp;2
shows the results of these calculations, indicating that the flux
is maximal at relatively high ammonium concentrations (&gt; 3
mol/m<SUP>3</SUP>) and high pH-values.
<P>
<IMG SRC="bpk32.gif">
<P>
The facts that ammonia is the actual substrate, the position of
the ammonia-ammonium equilibrium (pK<SUB>z</SUB>=9.24) which leads
to low ammonia concentrations at low pH values, as well as the
substrate and pH-gradients inside the biofilm, are all responsible
for this behaviour of the flux.
<P>
When the flux is known as function of the pH, it is possible to
model the macrokinetic behaviour of the Bio Trickling Filter,
and the experimental profiles along the height of the reactor.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-146</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000114-B048-8</DOCOLDNO>
