<HEAD>
<TITLE>Acceleration of mass transfer in methanogenic granules
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="uva.gif"></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B><FONT SIZE=5>Acceleration of mass transfer in methanogenic granules</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Researchers:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>Han van den Heuvel, Peter Verschuren</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=501><B>UvA</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
Active methanogenic granules invariably con-tain some internal
gas hold-up, which even may lead to flotation of the sludge. In
a loop reactor, this gas phase will be subjected to alternate
compression and expansion by the hydrostatic pressure differences
experienced during recirculation. In sufficiently rigid and permeable
granules, these volume variations will be compensated by a radial
convective liquid flow inside the particle. Thereby, transport
of substrate from the bulk liquid, and removal of product from
the centre, will be enhanced in excess of diffusion. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="bpk41.gif">
<P>
<B>Fig.1.</B> Experimental set-up of the laboratory scale reactor
system, simulating full scale loop reactor performance.
<P>
A series of fed-batch experiments was done to investigate whether
this 'breathing particle' mechanism was operative in methanogenic
granules. A special 0.6 liter glass reactor system was used both
under atmospheric conditions, and oscillating pressures with an
amplitude of 1&nbsp;bar and a frequency of 1 min<SUP>-1</SUP>
(see Fig.1). For that purpose the closed headspace was connec-ted
to a computer controlled working cylinder, simulating the triangular
pressure changes in a 10&nbsp;m loop reactor with a recirculation
velocity of 0.33 m/s. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="bpk42.gif">
<P>
<B>Fig.2. </B>Overall activity of methanogenic granules in two
series of fed-batch experiments performed alternately under atmospheric
and oscillating pressure.
<P>
The results of two series of batches are summarised in Fig. 2; a distinct enhancement can
be seen during cyclic operation that averages 13%. Furthermore,
a substantial increase of the overall activity is apparent during
both series of experiments. Methanogenic sludge from conven-tional
full scale reactors will exhibit only peri-pheral activity. This
limits the short term activity increase upon penetration of substrate
beyond this zone, and implies that over a longer period the basic
activity may grow due to revival of the inactive centre. In this
way, the (internal) activity of the granules increased some 60%
compared to the original inoculum. The experiments
were terminated when the difference between both operational modes
decreased after 1-2 weeks, due to parasitic activity of suspended
biomass.
<P>
An eventual enhancement of 40% is predicted for loop reactors
after optimisation of the recirculation rate, and the concomitant
develop-ment of biofilm activity to the core. A dramatic improvement
up to 300% is envisaged by the application of specially designed
carrier materials with a central cavity.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
