</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Partial wetting of a structured PVC packing in a biological trickling filter used to purify waste gases
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><P>
<IMG SRC="okkerse.gif"></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=501><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Partial wetting of a structured PVC packing in a biological trickling filter used to purify waste gases</FONT></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>PhD student:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=501><B>Willem-Jan Okkerse</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=501><B>1995-1999</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Sponsor:</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=501><B>Senter IOP Milieubiotechnologie</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=142><B>Location:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=353><B>Eindhoven University of Technology</B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=148><B>Tel. 040 - 2473669</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER>
<P>
Biological trickling filters (BTF's) are packed columns operated
in the trickle flow regime  used to purify industrial waste gases.
After BTF start-up, a biofilm gradually develops upon the inert
plastic packing. This results in an increase
of the specific wetted area of the packing, caused by the alteration
of the surface by the biofilm. For a reliable process design,
knowledge of the specific wetted area of the packing material
is important.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Experimental</B></CENTER>
<P>
A BTF filled with a structured PVC packing
was freely suspended from a load cell, which enabled the continuous
registration of the total weight of the system under both static
and dynamic conditions. <BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Theory</B></CENTER>
<P>
By measuring the change in the liquid hold-up
of the system as a function of time after a sudden cut-off of
the liquid flow, a so-called hold-up curve is obtained (see Fig.
1). These curves contain valuable information on the wetting properties
of the packing. In case of full film flow, for example, disturbances
in the flow will travel with three times the average film velocity.
Cutting-off the liquid supply results in continuity waves travelling
down the packing. The speed of these waves depends on the wetted
area in the filter.
<P>
<IMG SRC="bpk51.gif">
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Fig.
1. </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Hold-up curve of a wetted filter packing
after shutting off the liquid flow instantaneously.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Hold-up curve parameter</B></CENTER>
<P>
After cutting off the liquid flow, the
hold-up will decrease linearly with time, see Fig. 1. The
disturbance time was defined as that time at which the
experimental hold-up curve differs 1% from the initial linear
outflow rate. This parameter can be used conveniently
to investigate the wetting properties of a bare and a biofilm
covered packing.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Future work </B></CENTER>
<P>
After start-up of a BTF, the disturbance time was seen to double
during the first 135 days of operation, indicating a considerable
change in the wetting of the packing and of its surface properties.
Future research will be aimed at quantification of the wetted
packing area by means of the disturbance time, and by using fast
chemical reactions. <BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
