<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Prediction Methods for Nonlinear Dynamic Systems
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Prediction Methods for Nonlinear Dynamic Systems</H2>
PhD-student: 		ir R. Bakker<BR>
Sponsor: 		SON/NWO<BR>
Cooperation:		Prof.dr. F. Takens (RUG), Prof.dr. R. Krishna (UvA)<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="rbakker.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B>
The dynamic behavior of fluidized beds is considered to be chaotic. Chaotic systems are very sensitive for small perturbations. On one hand, this is the reason that future behaviour can be predicted only for a very short period of time. On the other hand, it is possible to drastically change the system behavior applying only small perturbations. This is known as 'chaos-control'. It involves three main steps:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Identify the deterministic mechanism that causes the chaotic behavior.
<LI>Find out what kind of behavior can be stabilized.
<LI>Apply small perturbations to control the selected behavior.
</UL>

<B>Neural networks</B><BR>
Real world chaotic systems are often too complex to describe with models based on first principles. Therefore, neural networks are used to solve the first step of the chaos control problem. Based on a long sequence of measurements, the neural network can learn to predict future behavior from the past.<BR>
The  chaos control strategy has first been applied to a simple experimental system, a chaotic pendulum. The next step is to control the chaotic hydrodynamics of multi-phase chemical reactors, in order to enhance chemical conversion and selectivity.<P>

<B>Experimental pendulum</B><BR>
A neural network model has been trained to predict the state of a driven and damped, chaotic pendulum, based on the measurement of only a single variable, the pendulum's angle. With the aid of the model, a large number of periodic orbits were found. Two of these orbits were stabilized with chaos control to demonstrate that with very small control actions, the original chaotic motion can be changed to a wide variety of periodic motions.<P>

<B>Fluidized bed</B><BR>
As a first step towards chaos control of a fluidized bed, a neural network model has been trained that can reproduce the chaotic hydrodynamic behavior of the reactor. The model is based on ECT (electrical capicitance tomography) timeseries,  measured in a 30 cm diameter fluidized bed.<P>

<IMG SRC="rbakker1.gif" WIDTH=469 HEIGHT=209><P>

Chaos analysis has shown that measured and generated timeseries (Fig. 1) have almost the same chaotic characteristics (entropy, dimension). As a next step, the model will be used to find which kinds of behavior can be stabilized with chaos control.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
The final aim of the project is to apply the prediction models to the real-time control of multi-phase reactors. It involves further improvement of the prediction models and  implementation of a control algorithm that synchronizes the output of a real (noisy) system with a selected orbit of the model.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
