<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Controlling chaos in gas-solids fluidized beds to improve chemical performance
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Controlling chaos in gas-solids fluidized beds to improve chemical performance</H2>
Ph.D.-student	: ir. Sander Kaart	  015 2784343<BR>
Sponsor	: SON (programme "Jonge Chemici")<BR>
Project period	: August 1995 - July 1999<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="sander.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER><P>

Recent studies show that the hydrodynamic behavior of fluidized beds has chaotic features. It is this chaotic behavior that causes the difficulties in scale-up of bench-scale reactors to full size industrial plants.<P>
As was also shown, there is a direct link between the bubble behavior and the chaotic behavior of the fluidized bed. Bubbles are also responsible for a poor conversion if a mass transfer limited (catalytic) reaction is performed in a bubbling gas-solids fluidized bed reactor. Reactant gas present in bubbles has to be transferred across the bubble boundary before it can react at the catalyst particles. This  additional mass transfer resistance, in combination with the high rise velocity of the bubbles, leads to bypass of reactant gas and thus to a lower conversion in a fluidized bed reactor than in a tube reactor with the same contact time. If it is possible to influence the  average bubble size, the bypass can be influenced and preferably be reduced. Since bubbling fluidized beds are chaotic systems, it may be possible to influence the hydrodynamics (average bubble size) of the fluidized bed by using ‘chaos control'.<P>

<CENTER><B>Burnout measurements</B></CENTER><P>

A simple example of a (bubble to emulsion phase) mass transfer limited reaction is the fluidized combustion of coal.  By determining the burnout time of a batch of coal particles an indirect method is found to quantify the bubble to emulsion mass transfer resistance.According to Avedesian & Davidson [1], the burnout time (tburnout) of a batch of coal particles (mbatch) is given by :<P>

<IMG SRC="sander1.gif"><P>

At operating conditions, the first two righthand side contributions are small compared with the third term. The factor ‘E' in the third term is the fluidization efficiency, which is determined by the bubble to emulsion mass transfer and thus by the average bubble size (fig. 1). 

<IMG SRC="sander2.gif"><P>

<CENTER><B>Current Work</B></CENTER><P>

As can be seen in figure 1, changes in bubble size have an effect on the fluidization efficiency. 
The goal of chaos control is to influence the (average) bubble size in the reactor. The current research focusses on applying some simple ‘chaotic' control strategies to the batch combustion of coal (coke) particles and hopefully increase the fluidization efficiency.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>[1] Avedesian, M. M. ,Davidson, J. F., <I>Trans. Instn Chem. Engrs</I>, vol. 51, 121-131, 1973.</FONT><BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
