<HEAD>
<TITLE>Classification of Regimes in Circulating Fluidized Beds using Deterministic Chaos Analysis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Classification of Regimes in Circulating Fluidized Beds using Deterministic Chaos Analysis</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. Robert.C. Zijerveld                              015-2782133<BR>
Sponsors:	NWO, Burgerscentrum, European Union<BR>
Cooperation:	Universities of Naples (dr. A. Marzocchella), Hamburg (prof. J. Werther), Göteborg (dr. F. Johnsson) and Groningen (prof. F. Takens) and Cerchar ( dr. A. Koniuta)<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="robert.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Project background</B><BR>
Fluidized bed reactors are among the most important reactors in chemical industry, because they offer excellent possibilities of dealing with solid reactants in gas/solid exo- and endothermic reaction systems. Especially Ciculating Fluidized Beds (CFBs) are of increasing importance in chemical industry as well as in the energy sector. However, design and scale-up of CFBs are still more an ‘art' than based on ‘knowledge', while also the fluid dynamic regimes that can be distinguished in this reactor are not very well understood yet. It is expected that characterization and classification of these regimes can be enhanced significantly by application of the methods and techniques of deterministic chaos analysis. This would already be of great importance for the design and further development of applications of this type of fluidized bed reactor.<P>

<B>Project objective</B><BR>
Chaos analysis is carried out on time series of pressure that are measured in cold pilot scale CFBs with circular and rectangular shaped riser cross-sections of different size (0.03, 0.083, 0.12, 0.40 m ID, 0.70x0.12 m and 1.20x0.80 m). Furthermore, time series of pressure are obtained in a 12 MWth full scale CFB boiler with 1.47x1.42m riser cross-section. The dependency of the Kolmogorov entropy and dimension on the fluidizing conditions (gas velocity, particle size, riser solids holdup and solids mass flux) is determined in relation to the fluidization regimes, the geometry of the CFB and the riser diameter or width. In this way, a classification of the fluid dynamic regimes will be set up in terms of degree of information loss by means of the chaotic invariant Kolmogorov entropy. <P>

<IMG SRC="robert1.gif"><P>

<B>Project organization</B><BR>
The project is carried out in the framework of a cooperation between Delft University of Technology and Università Federico II (Naples, Italy, dr. A. Marzocchella), Technische Universität Hamburg-Harburg (prof. Werther), the Rijksuniversiteit Groningen (The Netherlands, prof. Takens), Chalmers University of Technology (Göteborg, Sweden, prof. B. Leckner, dr. F. Johnsson) and Cerchar (Mazingarbe, France, dr. A. Koniuta).<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Characterization by means of Kolmogorov entropy shows that the dynamics of the bottom bed in small size risers (Fig. 1) are significantly different from the dynamics of the dense bottom bed in large size risers (Fig. 2), and as a consequence, two types of regimes at circulating conditions are introduced: the circulating exploding bubble bed for large risers and the circulating "slugging" bed for small risers.<P>

<IMG SRC="robert2.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
