<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE><I>in situ</I> Grown Zeolites — Development of a Structured Catalyst System
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2><I><I>in situ</I></I> Grown Zeolites — Development of a Structured Catalyst System</H2>
PhD Student:	<B>Ir. Otto L. Oudshoorn</B> ((015) 2782129)<BR>
Project period:	July 1993 — August 1997<BR>
External Support:	Shell Research and Technology Centre Amsterdam<BR>
Cooperation:	Joint project of the research groups of Van den Bleek and Van Bekkum<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="otto.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Zeolites grown on a Support</B><BR>
The technique of growing zeolite crystals <I>in situ</I> on different supports provides advantages in heterogeneous catalysis not met by other systems. These advantages include: optimal exposure of the catalyst and the possibility for low pressure drop design. In our laboratory, zeolites have been grown on a variety of supports, such as ceramics and stainless steel.<BR>
	The <I>in situ</I> grown zeolite crystals appear to be chemically bonded to the surface, to yield a reliable catalytic system. The carriers can be shaped in any desirable form prior to synthesis, thus providing a powerful reactor design variable.<BR>
	In the present study, different shapes and materials are tested for their usefulness as carriers for <I>in situ</I> grown zeolites. Stainless steel was successfully covered with zeolite Beta and ZSM-5. These stainless steel packings were formed prior to synthesis both as ‘Metal Monolith' structures and as Static Mixer Modules. Advantages of this type of reactor packings are a low pressure drop during operation and an enhanced heat and mass transfer.<BR>

<IMG SRC="otto1.gif" WIDTH=175 HEIGHT=128><P>

	To increase the amount of zeolites present in a reactor system, a carrier with an intrinsic high surface area is preferred. To this end, syntheses on ceramic foams were performed. ZSM-5 was successfully synthesized on different pieces of ceramic foams.<P>

<B>Research Objectives</B><BR>
The objective of this Research Project is to investigate the feasibility of reactor systems based on this new type of Zeolite Packings. Removal of NOx is chosen as one of the model reactions. Selective Catalytic Reduction of NOx with methane as a reductant is a new technology for reducing NOx emission from off-gases:<P>

2NO + CH<SUB>4</SUB> + O<SUB>2</SUB> -> N<SUB>2</SUB> + CO<SUB>2</SUB> + 2 H<SUB>2</SUB>O<P>

	This type of de-NOx-ing is preffered to more common processes using ammonia, which is a pollutant in itself. Besides  methane, other hydrocarbons could be used. This type of reaction is, for example, catalyzed by cobalt exchanged MFI zeolite. Several zeolite types have been successfully grown on a carrier, among others ZSM-5 and zeolite beta. Parameters affecting growth are investigated, such as the concentrations of the components in the synthesis mixture, crystallization temperature, etc. Catalytic tests will initially be conducted using an internal recycle reactor-based set up. In this way gradientless measurement of the catalytic activity of produced packings can be performed.<BR>
	In a later stage other types of reactions will be investigated. Attention will be focussed on reaction systems which benefit by the use of structured packings, i.e., a low pressure drop and/or a strong heat effect (endothermic or exothermic), such as methanol to light olefines (MTLO) process.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
