<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of the PolyLith Reactor (PLR)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Development of the PolyLith Reactor (PLR)</H2>
PhD Student:		Ir. Henk C. IJselendoorn (015-(2)782635)<BR>
Sponsor:		Delfts Stimulus Committee (Committee Beek)<BR>
Cooperation:		Joint project of the research groups of Van den Bleek and Sie<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="ijselen.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The PolyLith Reactor (PLR) is a novel low pressure drop reactor with a structured catalyst packing for heterogeneous catalysis. The catalyst packing consists of catalyst rods. These rods are formed by pressing, extruding or injection moulding suitable catalyst carrier material on (metal) wire structures. The resulting catalyst rod structure is more or less similar to a static  mixture.<P>

<B>Research Topics</B><BR>
At this moment the research is confined to gas-solid systems and consists of 6 parts:<BR>
1.	Pressure drop<BR>
2.	Mass transfer<BR>
3.	Mixing behaviour<BR>
4.	Kinetics of a test reaction<BR>
5.	Manufacture of catalyst  rods<BR>
6.	Development and validation of a reactor 	model.<BR>
From the first four independent research projects a non-fitted reactor model can be derived. Later on the research will also include the hydrodynamics of gas, liquid, solid systems.<BR>
A transparent labscale reactor was build to research the first three points. It can consist different packings of glass rods as model for catalyst rods. The packings differ in diameter of rods (3 - 10 mm), angle of rods (30 - 60 &#176;) and voidage (0.35 - 0.8). For the pressure drop some test experiments were carried out and  the pressure drop is lower than for a packed bed with the same porosity in the higher Re range. It was also tried to press catalyst rods. Square rods were possible, however cylindrical rods gave problems. Later there was contact with a company who delivered extrudated hollow alpha-alumina rods for a catalyst packing. We hope for a further cooperation with this company on research in the manufacture of rods or rod structures. The research plans for 1996 consist of: 1.Pressure drop experiments for 9  different packings and  development of  an engineering-CFD model for pressure drop. 2. Mass transfer experiments with the naphthalene sublimation method. The same packings can be used as for the pressure drop experiments, only position of the naphthalene particle in the reactor is an extra variable. 3. Mixing experiment with NO2 and air. The idea is to measure the lateral concentration gradients with a computer scanner or a digital camera. 3. Growth of zeolite crystals on the catalyst rods, which can be made active for the Selective Catalytic Reduction of NO with NH3 after ion exchange. This reduction will be the test reaction for the PLR. The kinetics of the reaction will be measured in an internal recycle reactor.<P>

<IMG SRC="ijselen1.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><I>Structure of LPR</I></FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

