<HEAD>
<TITLE>Interconnected Fluidized Bed technology for regenerative desulfurization
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Interconnected Fluidized Bed technology for regenerative desulfurization</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. Onno C. Snip; <A HREF="mailto:snip@stm.tudelft.nl">snip@stm.tudelft.nl</A>; 015- 2784753<BR>
Sponsors:		European Communities, DUT<BR>
Cooperation:	Université de Compiègne, IRI, Research groups Grievink and Moulijn (DUT-CPT), NOXSO corporation (USA)<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="onno.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
An Interconnected Fluidized Bed (IFB) reactor system for regenerative sulfur capture during fluidized bed combustion of coal and coal gasification processes is investigated. The main advantages of the IFB system are: (1) compactness and (2) minimal attrition due to effective solids transport. The solids transport is induced and controlled by means of differences in fluidization velocity.<P>

<IMG SRC="onno1.gif" WIDTH=229 HEIGHT=303><P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Testing the IFB concept in a hot facility for continuous sulfur capture and regeneration.
<LI>Further development of a hydrodynamic model for the transport of solids and gas between the compartments.
<LI>Development of rules for design, operation and control of the IFB process.
</UL>

<B>Experimental set-up</B><BR>
The hydrodynamics were studied in cold experimental IFB facilities to reveal driving and resisting forces in solids flow. A high temperature IFB pilot plant facility was used for an experimental study of regenerative 
desulfurization.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
A hydrodynamic model was developed based on a momentum analysis. The model 
appeared to predict the solids flow satisfactory. <BR>
In a final test the IFB pilot plant facility was successfully operated in a continuous five-day period with combined sulfur capture and regeneration with hydrogen. During this continuous experiment step-changes were made in operating parameters. A steady-state sulfur retention of 93% could be obtained. A typical result of a continous regenerative 
desulfurization experiment is shown. The experimental results reveal that the IFB reactor concept does function properly for a 
regenerative process at reaction conditions.<P>

<IMG SRC="onno2.gif" WIDTH=260 HEIGHT=432><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
