<HEAD>
<TITLE>Origin and Propagation of Pressure Waves in Fluidized Beds
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Origin and Propagation of Pressure Waves in Fluidized Beds</H2>
Ph.D-student:	ir.  John van der Schaaf	  (015 - 278 2133, <A HREF="mailto:vdschaaf@stm.tudelft.nl">vdschaaf@stm.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor:	J.M. Burgers Centre for Fluid Mechanics<BR>
Cooperation:	prof. F. Takens (RU Groningen)<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="john.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
At Delft University of Technology, (circulating) fluidized bed dynamics have been characterized using chaos analysis on time series of pressure fluctuations in fluidized beds. Results indicate that fluidized beds do not behave as a temporal chaotic system but more as a spatiotemporal chaotic system. To identify the spatial fluidized bed behaviour and composition of pressure time series, a study was performed on the origin, propagation and attenuation of pressure waves. Experiments presented here were performed with Geldart B particles in a 0.10 m ID bed operated at minimum fluidization in which a gas pulse was injected under the distributor plate.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The initial response of a fluidized bed to a pulse is given in fig. 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="john1.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Fig. 1</B> Initial response of a fluidized bed of polystyrene particles to a gas pulse<P></FONT>

The response in fig. 1 shows the first and second phase of four, 3 and 4 are not shown here. In the first phase the pressure increases to a maximum. The peak height versus distance to bed surface is given in fig.2.<P>

<IMG SRC="john2.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Fig. 2</B> Peak height versus distance to bed surface.</FONT><P>

Clearly, the maximum value is linearly dependent on probe distance to bed surface and has a high propagation speed. These results are explained by an instantaneous rise in gas velocity throughout the whole bed, corresponding to a packed bed response.  In the second phase particles react to the pulse and accelerate upwards, the bed expands, pressure decreases and a bubble is formed at the injection position. The pressure is determined by the difference of particle or bed velocity with gas velocity. Because of gravity the bed decelerates and collapses to an elevated state, the third phase, where the bed level remains at a constant height until the bubble reaches the surface. The pressure remains elevated until the bubble passes the probe. In the fourth phase the bubble disturbs the surface and a wave travels downwards by means of particle collisions. Eventually the bed returns to the undisturbed state.<P>

<B>Conclusions and Future Work</B><BR>
Pressure fluctuations in fluidized beds are  caused by fluctuations in gas and/or particle velocities and by fluctuations of bubbles and bed height, where the intensity of the first are height dependent.  How this connects to the spatiotemporal chaotic nature of the fluidized bed is subject of future investigations. Also the presence of bubbles on wave propagation speed will be investigated.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
