<HEAD>
<TITLE>Catalytic removal of NOx from diesel exhaust gases
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Catalytic removal of NO<SUB>x</SUB> from diesel exhaust gases</H2>
PhD Student:		Ir. Henrike Krijnsen<BR>
Started:		June 1996<BR>
External sponsor:	STW, Stork and Inodes<BR>
Cooperation: 		Stork-Wärtsilä Diesel B.V., Inodes B.V., joint project between the groups of Van den Bleek and Moulijn<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="henrike.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The past twenty years extensive research has been done at DUT studying the selective catalytic reduction (SCR) of NO<SUB>x</SUB> from off-gases. Since 1989 research has been done on the catalytic NO<SUB>x</SUB> removal from diesel exhaust gases.<BR>
A lot of diesel engines are used to ships and local power plants because of their fuel economy, reliability and robustness advantages. Since the introduction of the 3-way catalyst for Otto-engines, however, the exhaust gas of diesel engines is being considered most polluting and therefore the emissions of harmful components (notably soot, NO<SUB>x</SUB> and SO<SUB>x</SUB>)  have to be reduced. The emission of SO<SUB>x</SUB> can be reduced by deep hydrodesulfurisation of the diesel fuel. The emissions of soot and NO<SUB>x</SUB> , both inherently produced in a diesel engine, can (potentially) be reduced through catalytic exhaust gas aftertreatment. <BR>
For safety reasons aqueous urea rather than ammonia is used as reducing agent and injected into the exhaust flow. Urea decomposes into ammonia and CO<SUB>2</SUB>. In turn, ammonia reacts with NO<SUB>x</SUB> over a SCR catalyst.<P>

<B>Research goals</B><BR>
A catalytic system for the removal of NO<SUB>x</SUB> from the exhaust gases of stationary diesel engines will be obtained. The research project will focus on the implementation of commercially available and home made catalysts into a reactor
system. Within this subject the influence of SO<SUB>2</SUB> and water content on the catalyst performance will be monitored. Special attention will be paid to the control system used to dose the aqueous urea in such a way that the NO<SUB>x</SUB>-reduction is high while the ammonia slip in the exhaust gas downstream of the catalyst is as low as possible.<BR>
Final goal of the research project is to obtain an integrated catalytic system for the removal of soot and NO<SUB>x</SUB> from the exhaust gases of stationary diesel engines. The catalytic removal of soot (conversion to CO<SUB>2</SUB>) is being examined  by the group of Moulijn.<P>

<B>Experimental set up</B><BR>
A split stream of the exhaust gas containing the NO<SUB>x</SUB> to be reduced is filtered to remove largest part of the soot.The filtered exhaust gas can be led to two reactors systems. The first system contains about 1 kg of catalyst, the second one contains six parallel reactors with about 10 g of catalyst each. In the first reactor system the SCR catalyst is followed by an oxidation catalyst to prevent the emission of unconverted ammonia. The catalytic system will be tested both on the slipstream of a 10 kW 3-cylinder Lister-Petter test engine and on a 4 MW marine diesel engine at Stork-Wärtsilä.<P>

<B>Recent developments</B><BR>
The construction and automation of the experimental set-up has just been completed.<P>

<IMG SRC="henrike1.gif" WIDTH=550 HEIGHT=119><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
