<HEAD>
<TITLE>Emissions of SO2 and NOx in Circulating Fluidized Bed Combustion of coal
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Emissions of SO<SUB>2</SUB> and NO<SUB>x</SUB> in Circulating Fluidized Bed Combustion of coal</H2>
PhD student:	Geuch Zijlma (015-2784753 / E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:zijlma@stm.tudelft.nl">zijlma@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Project period:	September 1995 - October 1999<BR>
Sponsor:	European Communities<BR>
Cooperation:	CERCHAR (France), EdF (France), Vattenfall (Sweden)<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="geuch.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Circulating Fluidized Bed Combustion (CFBC) is a very promising technology for clean coal combustion. In a Circulating Fluidized Bed (CFB) the emission of SO<SUB>2</SUB> can be lowered by addition of a lime-based sorbent such as limestone. Due to the relatively low temperature in a CFB (850 C), emissions of NO<SUB>x</SUB> from a CFB will be reduced. On the other hand limestone can have a promoting effect on the emission of NO<SUB>x</SUB>. Air staging is applied to decrease the emission of NO<SUB>x</SUB>, dividing the combustion air in primary and secondary air. However, the low oxygen concentration in the lower part may lead to a decreased retention of SO<SUB>2</SUB>.<P>

<B>Experimental set-up</B><P>

<IMG SRC="geuch1.gif" WIDTH=316 HEIGHT=528><P>

At the DUT a laboratory-scale CFB made of quartz, has been built. In this facility, the coal combustion process is simulated, and the interactions between SO<SUB>2</SUB> and NO<SUB>x</SUB> emissions are studied at different staging conditions, O<SUB>2</SUB> concentrations and different sorbents materials. All the relevant components are analyzed by an FT-IR spectrometer at various positions in the riser. The reactor consists of a riser (2 m high, 0.063 m ID), two cyclones, a standpipe and a L-valve to control the solid flow rate.<P>

<B>Preliminary results</B><BR>
The influence of air staging (dividing the combustion air into primary and secondary air) on the hydrodynamics and on the sulfur retention is already being studied.<BR>
The hydrodynamics concerns the axial solids holdup distribution along the riser. The axial solids distribution, deduced from average pressure measurements, was changed only a little when different secondary air ratios were applied. However, these changes were sufficiently large to influence the retention of sulfur dioxide by limestone in the DUT facility. Therefore, air staging seems to have a dual effect, 1) through the oxygen concentration, and 2) through the local concentration of limestone.<P>

<B>Objectives</B>
<UL>
<LI>Determine the influence of air staging on hydrodynamics and SO<SUB>2</SUB>/NO<SUB>x</SUB> emission.
<LI>Perform experiments with addition of SO<SUB>2</SUB>, NH<SUB>3</SUB> and NO.
<LI>Testing of different types of sulfur sorbents
<LI>Mapping the CFB's fluid dynamical behavior by means of pressure measurements.
<LI>Development of a model to describe sulfur retention and NO<SUB>x</SUB> formation in a CFB.
<LI>Optimizing the SO<SUB>2</SUB>/NO<SUB>x</SUB> emission from CFB combustors.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
