<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Controlling the chaotic hydrodynamics of fluidized beds
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Controlling the chaotic hydrodynamics of fluidized beds.</H2>
PhD student	: Ir. R.J. de Korte		  015-2784343<BR>
Sponsors	: STW, Cie. Beek, Setpoint Ipcos, Akzo Nobel, DSM<BR>
Cooperation	: research groups prof. Grievink, prof. De Jong, prof Takens (RUG)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

It is well known that the hydrodynamics of gas solids fluidized beds can affect the chemical performance of the reactor (mass transfer or conversion). Therefore it could be useful to change it. For instance, if the average bubble size of gas bubbles could be reduced, this would mean less bypassing of the solids, resulting in a better reactor performance.
In the past few years, research has shown that the hydrodynamics of fluidized beds are of chaotic nature. Another recent development is the technique of controlling chaos. This has lead to the question whether it is possible to control the hydrodynamics of the bed and improve chemical performance.<P>

The most important characteristic of a chaotic dynamic system is its appearingly random behavior in time. However this is caused by the non-linear deterministic behavior of the system which means it is not random at all, but predictable. Like other deterministic systems, the chaotic system's development in time can also be changed by applying control actions. Normally this would require large control actions to obtain large effects, but because the system is chaotic, it is very sensitive to control actions. In the case of a fluidized bed this means that one should be able to change the hydrodynamics of the bed by injecting small gas pulses.<P>

<B>Chaotic Pendulum</B><P>

In the beginning of the project, a simple experimental chaotic pendulum was studied and a new chaos control algorithm was developed to control the pendulum. This control algorithm has two important characteristics. The first, as mentioned before, is that only very small control actions can change the dynamics completely. The second is the possibility to impose different kinds of behavior.<P>

<B>Experiments</B><P>

The first attempt to control the hydrodynamics of a fluidized bed, was performed in a small slugging bed (4cm ID) with steel balls of one mm diameter. For these conditions, the fluid bed is well in the slugging regime. It was possible to change the slugging frequency by injecting small gas pulses into the bed. Typically, the time averaged injected flow of air was only 10% of the total gas flow through the bed.<P>

<IMG SRC="dekorte1.gif" WIDTH=416 HEIGHT=289><P>

<I>Pressure time series : 1 slugging slowed down by controlling, 2 uncontrolled bed, 3 slugging reduced by controlling</I><P>

Although at lower gas speeds slugging can be changed, it does not work at higher gas speeds so far. Also slugging of Geldart type B particles could not be changed so far.<BR>
Presently better measurement techniques are tested and a new control method is tried out.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
