<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of Zeolite Catalysts for NOx Removal from Diesel Exhaust Gas
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Development of Zeolite Catalysts for NOx Removal from Diesel Exhaust Gas</H2>
Post-doc: Dr. Wijnand E.J. van Kooten<BR>
015-2786733/<A HREF="mailto:W.vanKooten@stm.tudelft.nl">W.vanKooten@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Started: May 1996<BR>
External Support: STW, Stork-Wärtsilä Diesel<BR>
Cooperation: Joint project between the groups of Van Bekkum and Van den Bleek; Stork-Wärtsilä Diesel; Inodes <BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="wijnand.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

Earlier research in our group has shown that Ce exchanged zeolites are very promising catalysts for the selective catalytic reduction (SCR) of NOx using NH<SUB>3</SUB> or urea. These catalysts perform very well over a large temperature range, i.e. 300 to 600 &#176;C. They can be operated with an excess amount of NH<SUB>3</SUB> (upto 30% excess), the excess NH<SUB>3</SUB> being converted to N<SUB>2</SUB> rather than NOx or N<SUB>2</SUB>O. The Ce-zeolites are only slightly active in the oxidation of SO<SUB>2</SUB> to SO<SUB>3</SUB>, which is an advantage in diesel exhaust deNOxing because SO<SUB>3</SUB> adds to the particulate emission.<P>

Regarding the composition of diesel exhaust gases (containing water and SO<SUB>2</SUB>) developing a stable, zeolite-based diesel exhaust deNOx catalyst is a challenging task. Zeolites can show structural and chemical changes under hydrothermal conditions and sulfur can cause deactivation.<P>

Catalysts were prepared by exchanging  Na-ZSM-5, Na-MOR and Na-BEA, with a Ce(Ac)3 solution in water at 80 &#176;C. After ion exchange the zeolites contain between 0.5 and 4 wt % Ce depending on the type of zeolite and the exchange conditions. The zeolites have been tested (as pills or as extrudates) on a small scale test setup as well as on larger scale with diesel exhaust gases. The figure shows the influence of water in the feed on the NOx conversion of CeNa-MOR in two runs up from 200 &#176;C to 600 &#176;C and back to 200 &#176;C. Water has a clear influence on the conversion.
The current research is focussed on both the hydrothermal stability and the influence of SO<SUB>2</SUB> on Ce-ZSM-5, Ce-BEA and Ce-MOR zeolite catalysts.<P>

<IMG SRC="wijnand1.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=282><P>


<I>DeNOx activities of CeNa-MOR with and without water in the feed</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
