<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Simulation and Non-linear Analysis of Fluidized Multiphase Reactors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Simulation and Non-linear Analysis of Fluidized Multiphase Reactors</H2>
<B>Ph.D. student: B.G.M. van Wachem<BR>
Supervisors:	Prof.Dr. R. Krishna and Prof.Ir. C.M. van den Bleek<BR>
Project term:	November 1995 - November 1999<BR>
Sponsor: SON/NWO<BR></B>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B> Introduction</B><BR>
Fluidized multiphase reactors like gas/solid fluidized beds, gas/liquid bubble columns and gas/liquid/solids slurry reactors are of increasing importance in chemical industries. The hydrodynamic analogies(Krishna) between these reactors and their spatiotemporal, chaotic hydrodynamic behaviour(van den Bleek) have already been shown experimentally. This project aims to use CFD modelling to verify and develop tools to study the chaotic hydrodynamic behaviour of fluidized multiphase reactors.<P>

<B>CFD Multiphase Models</B><BR>
The project has started with the implementation of a gas/solids Eulerian-Eulerian model including granular kinetic theory for the solids phase; for both phases the Navier-Stokes equation with additional terms is solved, taking into account solids viscosity and an extra pressure term for the solids phase, calculated from granular kinetic theory.<P>
 
In the near future we will look at Eulerian-Lagrangian models,  where the equation of motion is solved for every particle.<P>

<B>Goals</B><BR>
The simulation results of the CFD models will be used to :<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Compare the results to classical fluid bed characteristics e.g. bubble characteristics, regime transitions, gas holdup, velocity profiles and gas and solids axial dispersion.
<LI>Compare the chaotic behaviour of the results with the chaotic behaviour measured in gas/solid fluidized beds. It has been found that the predictability of a fluid bed, is a function of the superficial gas velocity, reactor diameter and bed height.
<LI>Determine from which physical aspects the chaotic behaviour originates, and how and on which spatiotemporal scale these aspects influence the chaotic behaviour of the system.
</OL>
This project should elucidate which length and time scales are of relevance for the scale-up and the chaotic control of these reactors.("On which time and length scale should one intervene to be able to impose a required hydrodynamic structure ?")<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The Eulerian-Eulerian model has been implemented in an existing CFD software package, CFX from AEA Technology. The model has been tested with simulations of fluidization with a single orifice. Now free bubbling fluidized beds are simulated at different superficial gas velocities and the chaotic hydrodynamic behaviour of these simulations is verified with the measurements done in real fluidized beds<P>

<IMG SRC="berospt1.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><I><U>Free bubbling fluidized bed with glass beads at superficial air velocity U0  = 3·Umf</U></I></FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
