<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bubble Columns at elevated Pressures
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Bubble Columns at elevated Pressures</H2>
Ph. D-student: Ir. H.M. Letzel (015-2786329 / 046-4767628)<BR>
Sponsors: SON/NWO, AKZO NOBEL, DSM<BR>
Cooperation: Prof. Dr. R. Krishna (Uva, joint promotor), DSM<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="martijn.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>
 
<B> Introduction</B><BR>
For scale up purposes, hydrodynamics of (slurry) bubble columns are often studied at ambient conditions, whereas in commercial applications the reactors operate at high temperatures and pressures. System pressure in bubble columns has an important effect on hydrodynamics and therefore on mass transfer. Krishna et al. (1991) showed that the flow regime transition velocity is an important parameter for describing hydrodynamics at high pressures: high pressure shifts the transition to higher gas velocities. <P>

<B>Stability analysis</B><BR>
In gas-solid fluidization, the flow regime transition can be modeled by performing a stability analysis on the one-dimensional continuity and momentum equations of the dispersed phase. We examine whether a similar model, described in gas-liquid flow (Biesheuvel 1995) can explain the gas density effects in a mechanistic way.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
At DSM Research, measurements are done in a 0.15 m ID bubble column, operable at pressures of up to 15 bar. From gas fraction measurements (see figure), the regime transition velocity can be estimated.<P>

<IMG SRC="martijn1.gif"><P>

 
<I>gas fraction as function of gas velocity at elevated pressures</I><P>

<B>Chaos analysis</B><BR>
Chaos analysis of pressure fluctuations gives us more insight in the transition region (Van den Bleek and Schouten 1993, Letzel et al. 1996). There seem to be three regions (see figure): homogeneous flow (I), swirls induced by bubble swarms (II) and coalesced (large) bubbles (III). With this analysis at elevated pressures we hope to find an answer whether the effect of elevated pressure is increased stability or delayed coalescence. If the stability analysis is applicable, our experiments will enable us to determine missing parameters in the theoretical models.<P>

<IMG SRC="martijn2.gif"><P>
 
<I>Entropy and gas fraction as function of gas velocity</I><P>

<B>Future</B><BR>
The next step is to examine the influence of pressure on mass transfer. Insight gained in effects on hydrodynamics should explain our observations.<P>

<B>References</B><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>Biesheuvel, A. 1995 In Waves in Liquid/Gas and Liquid/Vapor Twophase systems (eds. S. Moriaka &  L. van Wijngaarden), pp.1-24. Kluwer<BR>
Bleek, C.M. van den and Schouten, J.C. 1993 Chem. Eng. J. 53, 75-87<BR>
Krishna, R., Wilkinson, P.M. and Van Dierendonck, L.L. 1991 Chem. Eng. Sci. 46, 2491-2496<BR>
Letzel, H.M., Schouten, J.C., Krishna, R. and Van den Bleek, C.M. 1996 submitted for publication<BR></FONT>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
