<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hydrodynamics in Interconnected Fluidized Beds
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Hydrodynamics in Interconnected Fluidized Beds</H2>
PhD student:	ir. Cees S. Stellema	(015-278 1485)<BR>
email: <A HREF="mailto:stellema@iri.tudelft.nl">stellema@iri.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Cooperation:	Radiochemistry at IRI, DUT<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="osptcees.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

      An interconnected fluidized beds (IFB) system consists of a sequence of downcomers and risers. By aerating these beds differently, solids are transported from risers to downcomers via weirs and from downcomers to risers via an orifice. IFB-reactors can be applied in regenerative processes, such as the desulfurisation during fluidized bed coal combustion or the selective oxidation of n-butane. The advantages of the IFB-reactor as comparted to conventional regenerative systems lie in the compactness of the system and the lower solids attrition.<BR>
     Research on the residence time distribution (RTD) in the individual beds of the IFB system, using a single radiotracer particle and two scintillation detectors at a 90 degrees angle (see Figure 1), showed that only at high solids circulation rates the RTD of a riser deviates from that of an ideal mixer. At these circulation rates the horizontal solids dispersion is of the same order of magnitude as the average residence time. The RTD’s then show a bypass.<BR>
     From the residence times in the downcomers the existence of dead zones was demonstrated to be primarely a function of the aeration rate. Increasing the downcomer bed mass (a dependent variable in the overall IFB system) left the dead zone unchanged but increased the plug flow character of the downcomer.<P>

<IMG SRC="osptcees1.gif"><P>
  
<I>Figure 1. "Determination of the RTD’s in an IFB with a single radiotracer particle method"</I><P>

Recently, a positron emission particle tracking (PEPT) setup has become operational (see Figure 2). On opposite sides of the IFB two gamma cameras register the positions of the oppositely directed coincident 511 keV gamma rays coming from a glass bead labelled with Cu-64.<P>

<IMG SRC="osptcees2.gif"><P>
 
<I>Figure 2. "Determination of velocity profiles in an IFB using PEPT"</I><P>

Future research will comprise the development of a radioactive gas (Ar-41, Kr-81m) tracing setup.
Gas residence times and orifice gas cross talk can then be determined.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
