<HEAD>
<TITLE>Three Level Porosity Reactor Concept
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Three Level Porosity Reactor Concept</H2>
Researcher: Ir. Bastiaan W. van Hasselt<BR>
Status: Ph.D. Student<BR>
Started: September 1994<BR>
External support: Onderzoekschool Procestechnologie<BR>
Cooperation: Joint project of the research groups of Sie/Moulijn and Van den Bleek<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>A novel structured reactor packing for countercurrent trickle-flow processes is
being developed. This packing might be a.o. an alternative to the currently used
randomly packedfixed-bed trickle-flow reactor for hydroprocessing of heavy oils.</I><P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>

In many multiphase fixed-bed catalytic
processes, countercurrent operation below
the flooding point is only possible at
unacceptably low lineair velocities, due to
the small size of the catalyst particles.<P>

<IMG SRC="hasselt1.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=339><P>

<I>The TLP concept in G/L countercurrent operation</I><P>

<B>The TLP concept</B><BR>
In conventional hydroprocessing reactors
the G/L mass transfer is relatively fast.
Therefore a novel reactor is conceived in
which a low pressure drop is obtained at
the expense of G/L mass transfer
effectiveness. In this reactor gas and liquid
flow countercurrently through separate
channels with the possibility of periodic
contact.<BR>
The reactor packing has three levels of
porosity: pores in the catalyst particles,
between the catalyst particles packed in a
bed and pores between the various beds.<BR>
Liquid flows down through the beds driven
by gravity; gas flows up, preferentially
around the beds driven by a small pressure
difference. The structured catalyst packing
gives the advantage of easy scale up.<P>

<B>Aim / Experimental / Results</B><BR>
The aim is to characterize hydrodynamics
and mass transfer of the TLP reactor. At the
moment attention is paid to gas-liquid
distribution and improvement of flooding
characteristics.<BR>
A lab-scale reactor module is constructed in
which normal catalyst particles are
contained in beds, formed by horizontal
layers of folded wire gauze.<BR>
Preliminary results indicate that counter-current operation in a small hydrotreater is
possible using the TLP concept.<P>

<IMG SRC="hasselt2.gif" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=294><P>

<I>Flooding lines for the TLP reactor</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
