<HEAD>
<TITLE>The IEA-Model for Circulating Fluidized Bed Combustion
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>The IEA-Model for Circulating Fluidized Bed Combustion</H2>
Ph.D. student: Dipl.-Ing. Jens P. Hannes tel: +49 241 80 5537<BR>
Sponsors: DUT Fellowship, STW, RWTH Aachen (D), EDF (F)<BR>
Cooperation: Joint project of TU Delft and RWTH Aachen (D)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In the framework of
the International
Energy Agency (IEA)
a mathematical modelling group has
been formed to
develop a comprehensive model for circulating fluidized bed
combustion (CFBC).
TU Delft and RWTH
Aachen (Germany)
took over the task to
develop a basic steady
state, one dimensional
model, free to be used
and improved by any
member of the group.<P>

<IMG SRC="hannes1.gif" WIDTH=800 HEIGHT=542><P>

<B>The technology</B><BR>
In a reactor chamber with heat exchanger
walls coal particles are burned in a fluidized
bed of sand and ash. The bed material is
blown out intentionally, separated by a cyclone and returned into the combustor. The
bed buffers temperature peaks during
combustion which suppresses NOx formation. SO2 is captured by limestone particles which are added to the bed material.
Further gas cleaning, besides filtering is not
necessary.<P>

<B>The model</B><BR>
The reactor model was set up one
dimensionally in vertical direction with a
lateral distinction between core and wall
zones to model internal recirculation of
particles. It includes adaptation of geometry
and layout, hydrodynamics of solids and
gas, population balances of the particles,
combustion and chemical reactions as well
as heat transfer.<P>

<B>The plants</B><BR>
To validate the model it was applied to
industrial boilers of 12 to 300 MW of
thermal power. A first fitting was done with
the data of the well documented research
boiler of Chalmers University, Sweden. The
adapted parameters were used to model four
German and one French large scale
industrial boilers of different design made
by different manufacturers.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The Figures above show comparisons of
data and modelling results for variations of
the operational conditions, gained from the
Chalmers boiler. The agreement is
promising since al1 quantities and tendencies
are reproduced correctly. The modelling of
the large plants was done with comparably
satisfying agreement. The proper prediction
of NO keeps problematic since a reliable
modelling approach for the formation
mechanism is still lacking.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
