<HEAD>
<TITLE>Continuous high temperature regenerative H2S removal from coal gas in a rotating monolith reactor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Continuous high temperature regenerative H<SUB>2</SUB>S removal from coal gas in a rotating monolith reactor</H2>
Researcher: <B>Ir. W.J.W. Bakker </B>(Wridzer)<BR>
Status:   A.I.O.<BR>
External  support: Stimuleringsruimte TU-Delft, EU<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="bakker.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
The use of monoliths as structured catalysts in chemical industry
is getting growing attention. Conventional fixed bed reactors
have some obvious disadvantages such as high pressure drop and
maldistributions of various kinds. The composition of a gas outflowing
 from a periodically operated absorber changes in time which is
often considered as a significant drawback. Moreover if a frequent
operation of an acceptor is required the operation becomes troublesome.
<P>
Therefore, the concept of the rotating monolith reactor has been
adopted. In this multi-functional reactor system absorption and
regeneration takes place simultaneously.
<P>
Pressure drop, dust and attrition sensitivity is low and a relatively
small reactor can be applied for moderate rotation speeds. <BR>
<P>
<B>Goal</B>
<P>
The  aim of the project is to develop a rotating monolith reactor
and a sorbent for  continuous, high temperature for continuous,
high temperature  (up to 1173 K)  and regenerative desulfurization
of fuel gas from coal gasification. High temperature removal increases
the thermal efficiency en reduces the complexity of the equipment.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Results<BR>
</B>
<P>
<I>Sorbent</I>
<P>
A regenerable manganese based sorbent for H<SUB>2</SUB>S removal
from hot dry coal gas has been developed. The sorbent has a high
capacity (up to 20 wt % sulfur), reduces H<SUB>2</SUB>S and COS
to concentrations to less then 40 ppm (Shell process) and is very
stable. The optimal  sulfur acceptance capacity is obtained at
1123 K but the sorbent can be applied between 673 and 1273 K.
It consists of two manganese phases: bulk manganese aluminate
which provides the high sulfur uptake capacity and a disperse
manganese oxide phase which provides the desulfurization to a
low H<SUB>2</SUB>S level. The active phase is deposited on to
a monolith which is applied in the rotating reactor. Regeneration
with O<SUB>2</SUB>, H<SUB>2</SUB>O and SO<SUB>2</SUB> is possible.
Regeneration with SO<SUB>2</SUB> under the direct production of
elemental sulfur is the most attractive  option as it makes the
Claus plant which is normally applied to process the regeneration
off-gas superfluous.<BR>
<P>
<I>Reactor design</I>
<P>
A bench-scale rotating (monolith) reactor has been designed and
constructed for continuous desulfurization of coal gas up to very
high temperatures (1273 K). The reactor has been operated up to
923 K without serious problems. The reactor principle can be used
for many other cyclic processes and is therefore very promising.
The reactor and the sorbent has been patented.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
