<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Catalytic removal of soot from diesel exhaust gas
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">


<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Catalytic removal of soot from diesel exhaust gas</H2>

</TD><TD><IMG SRC="jelles.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>
Researcher:  <B>Ir. S.J. Jelles</B> (Sytse)<BR>
Status:   A.I.O.<BR>
Started:  March 1995<BR>
External support: STW<BR>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<I>In this project, the removal of particulates from diesel exhaust
gas is studied. The performance of catalytic diesel fuel additives
is studied and compared with performance in model experiments.
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
 Diesel engines are fuel efficient and have, compared with otto
engines, relatively low emissions of NO<SUB>x</SUB> and unburnt
hydrocarbons. The particulate emission of diesel engines is high
and diesel particulates are considered to be possibly harmful.
The purpose of this project is to develop a system for the removal
of diesel particulates from the exhaust gas.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="jelles1.gif"><BR>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 1. Experimental setup for additive measurements</FONT></I>
<P>
<B>Limitations</B>
<P>
 Straightforward application of a known oxidation catalyst on
a filter for soot removal does not result in sufficient reduction
of particulates. Earlier studies showed that the contact between
particulate and catalyst is of crucial importance. Solid catalysts
cannot make sufficient contact with solid soot particulates.<BR>
<P>
<B>Solutions</B>
<P>
 One way to improve the contact between catalyst and soot, is
the application of a catalytic precursor in diesel fuel. The catalyst
is then incorporated in the particulate. Application of a simple
filter to improve the residence time results in almost complete
removal of the particulates.<BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
 The performance of copper fuel additives was extensively studied,
in this project as well as in earlier work. The influence of different
filter types, additive concentration and operating temperature
on the performance of this system are well established. 
<P>
 Several active metal oxide based catalysts have been found, that
are promising for use as supported liquid phase catalyst. Experiments
using flowreactor equipment and TGA/DTA prove that the concept
of a molten salt catalyst is valid.<BR>
<P>
<B>Further work</B>
<P>
<B> </B>In future work, the performance of a wide range of metals
as catalytic additive will be studied using a three cylinder diesel
engine and compared with results of model experiments. 

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
