<DOCNO>WT25-B28-170</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B002-80</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/lebens.html 130.89.50.60 19970216175110 text/html 3429
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:44:35 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 27-Nov-96 07:40:21 GMT
Content-length: 3246
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of an internally finned monolith reactor (IFMR) for hydrogenation processes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">


<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Development of an internally finned monolith reactor (IFMR) for hydrogenation processes.</H2>
Researcher: <B>Ir. P.J.M. Lebens</B> (Paul)<BR>
Status:  A.I.O.<BR>
Started: November 1994<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="lebens.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>A new concept of a low pressure
drop reactor for countercurrent operation of three-phase hydrogenation
processes is being developed.<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</FONT></B>
<P>
The use of a monolith reactor as
an alternative for a trickle bed reactor is suggested by various
researchers. Mostly, attention is paid to cocurrent gas-liquid
flow in either downward or upward direction. The flow pattern
is dominated by Taylor flow which can enhance mass transfer properties
of the liquid or gas phase under different conditions. However,
processes in which the conversion is determined by equilibrium
or reactant inhibition are preferably operated countercurrently.
The internally finned monolith reactor (IFMR) is a new concept
of a three-phase catalytic reactor in which the gas flows up under
a very low pressure gradient not obstructing the liquid to flow
down as a falling film. Due to its geometry (Figure), catalyst
loading and surface-to-volume ratio can be compared to 3 mm pellets
randomly packed. The decreased mass transfer caused by the laminar
flow of liquid and gas is not being considered as a problem since
the intended applications concern diffusion limited reactions
like dehydrosulfurization, denitrification, and dearomatization.
Another potential application can be found in reactive distillation
processes.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="lebens1.GIF">
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=1>Figure </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=1>Cross sectional view of single channel</FONT>
<P>
<B>Objectives</B>
<P>
The objectives of this project are
to assess the feasibility of the IFMR concept and to optimize
both the channel geometry and the monolith configuration with
respect to its application in hydrotreating processes.<BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
Hydrodynamic studies with decane
and air in a single capillary of 1 m length and a cross section
as depicted in the Figure, have shown that countercurrent flow
of gas and liquid is possible at velocities which are of industrial
interest. It appears that flooding is dominated by instabilities
at the liquid outlet of the capillary. Modifying the geometry
of the outlet can change the flooding limits to higher liquid
and gas velocities. Visual observation demonstrated that the fins
successfully stabilize the flow by confining the liquid between
the fins so that slug formation caused by coalescence of  interfacial
waves only takes place at higher velocities. Pressure drop and
liquid hold-up can be calculated by solving the momentum balance
for both liquid and gas phase. The calculations are in good agreement
with the experimental results.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
