<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Zeolite membranes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Zeolite membranes</H2>
Researcher:  <B>Drs. J.M. van de Graaf </B>(Jolinde)<BR>
e-mail:   <A HREF="mailto:J.vandeGraaf@stm.tudelft.nl">J.vandeGraaf@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Status:   O.I.O.<BR>
Started:  March 1994<BR>
External support: SON/STW<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="graaf.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>T</B>he use of zeolite membranes in separation
or combined reaction and separation processes is very attractive.
Advantages of using such a type of membranes include their ability
to discriminate between molecules based on molecular size, and
their thermal stability. In this study the permeation behaviour
of a stainless steel supported silicalite-1 membrane is investigated.
Experiments include the permeation of hydrocarbons (gases and
vapours) and some permanent gases. It was found that, apart from
molecular size separation using zeolite membranes is governed
by adsorption and/or mobility differences between molecules.<BR>
<P>
<B>T</B>he objective of this study is to
gain insight in the features of zeolite membranes and to develop
a model that is able to describe and predict the permeation behaviour
through these membranes. This, in order to determine the feasibility
of application of this type of membranes in industrial processes.
<BR>
<P>
<B>T</B>he capability of the membrane to
discriminate between molecules based on differences in shape is
illustrated in figure 1. Here the permeation of a 1:1 mixture
of <I>n</I>-butane and <I>i</I>-butane is given as a function
of temperature. The less bulky <I>n-</I>butane molecule is removed
selectively from this mixture. It can be seen that at temperatures
up to 420 K high separation factors are obtained. The separation
of hydrocarbon isomers, is an industrially important process since
isomerisation reactions are equilibrium limited and part of the
product stream has to be recycled. Moreover, the boiling points
of isomers are often close, which makes separation by distillation
difficult and expensive. The initial results presented here show
that the use of zeolite membranes for this type of separation
might be feasible.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="graaf1.gif">
<P>
<I>Figure 1: Mixture permeation of n-butane/i-butane  (1:1) and
selectivity towards n-butane as a function of temperature, P<SUB>tot</SUB>=
101.3 kPa<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>T</B>he above results are being modelled
using the generalised Maxwell-Stefan equations, taking into account
both surface and activated gas phase diffusion through the membrane.
The description of the concentration dependence of the diffusion
coefficient as well as the determination of the adsorbed phase
concentration in the membrane, is  of key importance for further
improvement of this model. This is the subject of current research.


