<HEAD>
<TITLE>A Novel Monolithic Reactor for Three-Phase Hydrogenations for Easy Scale-Up and Improving Selectivities
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>A Novel Monolithic Reactor for Three-Phase Hydrogenations for Easy Scale-Up and Improving Selectivities</H2>
Researcher   Rolf Edvinsson<BR>
Email: <A HREF="mailto:R.Edvinsson@stm.tudelft.nl">R.Edvinsson@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Status: postdoc<BR>
Project term:  March 1995-March 1997<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="edvins.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

Characteristic for many catalytic
reactions is that they involve a gas- and liquid phase reactant
and proceed in the presence of a solid catalyst. The reactor technology
used must be capable of providing adequate contact between all
phases involved reaction. Moreover, there are a number of other
important practical considerations, such as catalyst separation,
hydrodynamics, mixing patterns, pressure drop, internal mass transfer
resistance, and heat transfer.
<P>
The use of monolithic catalysts
is very promising for such processes. A monolithic catalyst consists
of many narrow, parallel channels with the active catalyst material
deposited as a very thin layer (typically 10-30 </FONT><FONT FACE="Symbol">m</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">m)
on the walls. This provides a very large geometrical surface area
(~2500 m<SUP>2</SUP>/m<SUP>3</SUP>) and a very low pressure drop
compared to conventional fixed beds. The use of a thin catalyst
layer is often essential in order to obtain a high selectivity.
<P>
The gas-liquid mixture typically
 passes through a monolith channel as a bubble train (see Fig.).
The bubble is separated from the wall by a thin liquid film acting
as a diffusion barrier for the gas phase reactant. Moreover, it
induces a secondary recirculation in the liquid plug, thereby
improving radial mass transfer.
<P>
The present research is directed
at collecting the knowledge that is necessary for successful scale-up
of a monolithic process. Hydrodynamics is here essential since
it is necessary to
provide a uniform and stable fluid
distribution. It has been shown that in co-current downflow there
exist stable and unstable regions of operation.
<P>
<IMG SRC="edvins1.gif"><P>
Also of great importance is the
modelling of mass transfer. The well defined geometry of the flow
and the channels allows analytical methods to be applied from
first principles.  The models representing the present knowledge
are also used to evaluate the potential of the monolith technology
over conventional ones, primarily slurry and trickle-bed technologies.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
