<HEAD>
<TITLE>Kinetics of Fluid Catalytic Cracking
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Kinetics of Fluid Catalytic Cracking</H2>
Researcher:  <B>Ir. M.A. den Hollander</B> (Marion)<BR>
e-mail:   <A HREF="mailto:M.A.denHollander@stm.tudelft.nl">M.A.denHollander@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Status:   A.I.O.<BR>
Started:  May 1995<BR>
External support: SRTCA <BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="hollande.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>The kinetics of Fluid Catalytic Cracking (FCC) are studied
with the microriser, a laboratory scale entrained flow reactor.
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
Fluid Catalytic Cracking is an important oil conversion process
for the production of gasoline range hydrocarbons. The reactor
used in the process is a riser (entrained flow) reactor. 
<P>
In a riser reactor gas and catalyst flow cocurrently upward. The
catalyst concentration is low (&lt;1 vol%) and the  residence
time is 3-5 seconds. During cracking, the catalyst is deactivated
by coke deposition.<BR>
<P>
<B>Equipment</B>
<P>
The microriser is a laboratory scale entrained flow reactor with
a folded reactor of a variable length. Due to the folded character,
the microriser is a combination of a riser and downer.
<P>
<IMG SRC="hollande1.gif">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2><B>Figure 1</B> Outline of the microriser</FONT>
<P>
<B>Experimental Results</B>
<P>
The microriser has been used to study the cracking of a hydrowax
feedstock with a typical FCC catalyst.
<P>
The contact time of oil and catalyst has been varied by varying
the length of the reactor. Typical results at a catalyst/oil ratio
of 4 are shown in figure 2.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="hollande2.gif">
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2><B>Figure 2</B> Results at a
catalyst/oil ratio of 4; a:<B> </B></FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>conversion
and gasoline yield, b: coke yield<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Conclusions</B>
<P>
Contact times longer than 2 s had no additional effect on both
conversion and gasoline yield.
<P>
No gasoline over-cracking has been observed.
<P>
Increasing the contact time had no effect on the coke yield. Two
possible explanations are: 1) all coke is formed at primary catalyst/oil
contact; 2) the majority of the coke is formed in de hopper of
the disengagement oven. 
<P>
To exclude the second possibility, an on-line stripping section
will be developed.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
