<HEAD>
<TITLE>Positron Emission Profiling of Monolith Catalysts (Applied to exhaust gas catalysis)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">


<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Positron Emission Profiling of Monolith Catalysts (Applied to exhaust gas catalysis)</H2>
Researcher:  <B>Drs. S.C. van der Linde</B> (Simon)<BR>
Status:   O.I.O.<BR>
Started:  May 1994<BR>
External support: SON/NWO<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="linde.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<P>
<I>Delft University of  Technology in conjunction
with Eindhoven University of  Technology have developed a system,
using positron emitters, with which transient kinetics of exhaust
gas catalysis can be studied.<BR>
</I>
<P>
 The use of transient techniques to study the kinetics of catalytic
reactions has become increasing popular in catalysis. Positron
Emission Profiling (PEP), is a recently developed technique with
which the transient behaviour of a catalyst can be followed. The
technique is the one dimensional spin-off of the popular 3D-imaging
technique PET (Positron Emission Tomography) used in nuclear medicine.
With the aid of positron emitting molecules (<SUP>11</SUP>CO and
<SUP>13</SUP>NO), PEP allows <I>in-situ</I> monitoring of gas
and surface concentrations in both time and space. The technique
is currently being used to study the transient response of exhaust
gas catalysts. Figure 1 shows an example of a <SUP>11</SUP>CO
oxidation over a Pt containing catalyst during steady state CO
oxidation. Depending on the experimental conditions, namely the
gas velocity, a PEP image can almost exclusively display the surface
concentration of a reactant. The image shown in figure 1 shows
that during oxidation most of the <SUP>11</SUP>CO pulse is adsorbed
at reactor entrance.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="linde1.gif">
<P>
Information from these profiles , such as surface concentration,
rate constants, can only be obtained by modelling of the reactions
because it is not possible to discriminate between reactants and
products (e.g. <SUP>11</SUP>CO and <SUP>11</SUP>CO<SUB>2</SUB>)
with the detectors. Since the profile is obtained in both time
and space this automatically leads to a system of partial differential
equations (PDEs) which need to be solved. The numerical method
of lines has been employed to solve the PDEs which describe the
reactions taking place on the catalyst surface. The principle
of this method is that the spatial derivatives are approximated
which reduces the PDEs to a set of ODE which may be solved with
existing solvers. To obtain quantitative data the experimental
data has to be fitted. Therefore the PDE solvers have been coupled
to various minimisation routines, such as Simplex, Levenberg-Marquardt.
This technique has successfully been used to determine the dispersion
in a packed reactor. 
<P>
The technique will be further explored by determining reaction
images of the reduction of <SUP>13</SUP>NO by CO over noble metal
catalysts and catalysts containing ion-exchanged  ZSM-5 as the
active phase. 


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
