<HEAD>
<TITLE>A DRIFT spectroscopic study on the catalytic oxidation of soot and diesel exhaust gas cleaning
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">


<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>A DRIFT spectroscopic study on the catalytic oxidation of soot and diesel exhaust gas cleaning</H2>
Researcher: <B>Drs. G. Mul</B> (Guido)<BR>
Status:   O.I.O.
Started:  November 1992
External support: SON/NWO<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="mul.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>A project concerned with the catalytic removal of soot and
other environmentally harmful constituents of diesel exhaust (NO,
CO, hydrocarbons) is carried out at the TU Delft. The aims of
this project are to develop a highly active and stable catalyst
for the oxidation of soot into CO<SUB>2</SUB>, to clarify the
oxidation mechanism, and to evaluate the effects of NO and CO
on the oxidation rate.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
 Although diesel engines are environmentally friendlier than otto
engines regarding the emission of hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides
(NO<SUB>x</SUB>), they are main contributors to the emission of
particulate. Catalytic oxidation is needed to prevent the particulate
from decreasing environmental conditions.<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
</FONT>Within this project two catalytic systems have been investigated:
Cu/K/Mo/Cl catalysts and transition metal oxides. As the former
appeared not to be applicable, because of deactivation due to
evaporation of copper chlorides, research has been mainly focused
on the elucidation of the oxidation mechanism of metal oxides,
the improvement of the activity and the effects of NO and CO on
the performance.
<P>
 
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
<B> </B>DRIFT spectra of partially converted soot in air and ozone,
have revealed that some metal oxides catalyse the formation of
surface oxygen complexes (SOC) on the soot surface, while others
do not. Combined with an <SUP>18</SUP>O<SUB>2</SUB> study, this
has lead to the proposition of the following oxygen species: <I>super</I>
surface oxygen, which can spill-over from the catalyst surface
to the soot surface yielding SOC, <I>sub</I> surface oxygen, present
in the first layer of the oxide, and bulk lattice oxygen. The
amount of each involved in the reaction is dependent on the metal
oxide.
<P>
 The addition of Au to oxidic catalysts was shown to be very effective
in improving the catalytic activity in the oxidation of CO, in
agreement with the literature. Unfortunately, addition of Au was
not beneficial for the activity in soot oxidation. However, <FONT COLOR=#000000>Ag/MnO<SUB>x</SUB>
catalysts, and other Ag promoted oxides, were found to show a
much higher activity in soot oxidation than either MnO<SUB>x</SUB>
(the oxide) or Ag. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000> The presence of NO in the oxidising medium
(10% O<SUB>2</SUB> in Ar) appeared to enhance the oxidation rate.
(Catalytic) formation of NO<SUB>2</SUB> was observed, which subsequently
reacted with soot, yielding NO and CO<SUB>(2)</SUB>. Addition
of CO usually did not effect the oxidation characteristics of
the catalysts, although a strong enhancement of the oxidation
rate in CuO catalysed soot oxidation was observed. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000> The results presented here will be further
evaluated and published in the international journals 'Carbon'
and 'Fuel'.</FONT>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
