<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Design rules for sulfide catalysts. Catalysts for deep hydrodesulfurization of gasoil
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Design rules for sulfide catalysts. Catalysts for deep hydrodesulfurization of gasoil</H2>
Researcher:  <B>Ir. H.R. Reinhoudt</B> (Hank)<BR>
Status:   O.I.O.<BR>
Started:  December 1994<BR>
External support: STW, European Commission<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="reinhoud.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<P>
<I>The aim of the project is to establish catalyst design rules
for the a priori selection of optimal active phase / particle
size / morphology / support combinations for various specific
hydrotreating applications. Part of the project is supported by
the European Union. It focuses on the application of catalysts
for deep hydrodesulfurization of gasoils is a main part of interest.
Catalysts for this field, capable of reaching a sulfur level in
gasoil well below 100 ppm are aimed at to meet future regulations.
<BR>
</I>
<P>
 Catalysts containing mixed sulfides of CoMo, NiMo or NiW are
widely used in hydrotreating processes to produce clean fossil
fuels. Their performance strongly depends on particle size, morphology
and interaction with the support material. In a collaborative
project [TUE (Van Santen / De Beer / Van Veen) and TUD (Moulijn
/ Sie / Van Langeveld)] the effect of preparation and sulfiding
(activation) conditions on these parameters and on the resulting
activity will be studied. Several preparation methods such as
ion exchange, gas phase deposition, sequential and co-impregnation
and pre-treatment procedures, will be used to prepare catalysts
with different particle size and /or morphology of the active
sulfide phase.
<P>
 The E.U. project for development of catalysts for deep HDS of
gasoils was undertaken in co-operation with universities from
Eindhoven, Karlsruhe, London, Madrid/Bilbao and, several industries.
The refractory sulfur compounds in gasoil are mainly alkylated
dibenzothiophenes. CoMo, NiMo and NiW sulfide catalysts, known
for their high sulfur tolerance and Pt, Pd and Ir metal catalysts,
known for their high hydrogenation activity were tested. Results
show that Pt and Pd supported on amorphous silica-alumina (ASA)
are very active for the conversion of 4-ethyl, 6-methyl DBT under
model conditions up to H<SUB>2</SUB>S/H<SUB>2</SUB> ratios 0.2
mol%. In deep HDS of a practical gasoil, NiW supported on -Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
and Pt on ASA showed comparable activity. A sulfur level of less
than 100 ppm can be reached with these catalysts under practical
reaction conditions. 
<P>
 The activity of a series of differently pre-treated NiW--Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
catalysts for both thiophene and dibenzothiophene conversion was
determined. Moreover, the effects of the pre-treatment and sulfiding
procedure on the active phase of these NiW-gamma-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
catalysts were studied using temperature programmed reactions,
infra-red on adsorbed CO and NO spectroscopy and quasi in-situ
XPS.
<P>
 To gain more insight in the kinetic reaction mechanism, for a
number of selected catalysts the kinetics of thiophene and, dibenzothiophene
(DBT) hydrodesulfurization (HDS), chinoline hydrodenitrification
(HDN), toluene hydrogenation will be studied. The activity of
those catalysts will also be studied under industrial conditions.


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
