<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The direct oxidation of propene to propene oxide
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>The direct oxidation of propene to propene oxide</H2>
Researcher:  <B>Ir. T.A. Nijhuis</B> (Xander)<BR>
Status:   A.I.O.<BR>
Started:  August 1993<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="nijhuis.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>At the Delft University of Technology we are working on a project
aiming to find a suitable catalyst for the direct oxidation of
propene to propene oxide. This study is partially performed using
the new Multitrack system.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
 Currently it is impossible to produce propene oxide on a commercial
scale using a direct oxidation. The existing routes for producing
propene oxide either use the chlorohydrin process, producing large
amounts of salts and some chlorinated side products, or use a
hydroperoxide process. The hydroperoxide process produces propene
oxide from a reaction between propene and an organic hydroperoxide,
resulting in stoichiometric amounts of an alcohol as a co-product.
A lot of research has been done on the direct epoxidation of propene,
but so far no viable route has been found. All catalysts used
either have very low activities or low selectivities.<BR>
<P>
<B>The Multitrack system</B>
<P>
 The epoxidation of propene will be studied using the new Multitrack
system. Multitrack is an advanced version of the TAP (Temporal
Analysis of Products) system, used for studying the transient
kinetics of reactions. The concept of Multitrack is giving a small
(100 &#181;s) gas pulse to a reactor and analyzing three masses
simultaneously at very high frequencies (up to 1 MHz). Multitrack
can operate at temperatures from room temperature to 1200 K and
at pressures ranging from vacuum to 300 kPa.<BR>
<P>
<B>The epoxidation of propene</B>
<P>
 Using the Multitrack system we will try to determine the kinetics
of the various oxidation reactions of propene (to carbon dioxide,
propene oxide, and acrolein). As a starting point for the epoxidation
of propene catalysts will be used which show good results in the
easier epoxidation of ethene. The main problem in epoxidizing
propene over a standard silver catalyst used for the epoxidation
of ethene is the reactivity of the <FONT FACE="Symbol">g</FONT>-hydrogen
atoms. When propene reacts with an oxygen atom on the silver surface,
an intermediate is formed which can react to propene oxide. If
the <FONT FACE="Symbol">g</FONT>-hydrogen atoms, however, can
'reach' another adsorbed oxygen atom, the more favourable combustion
will take place. We will try to overcome this problem by using
a catalyst with either very low metal loading or with an atomically
dispersed metal loading, for example using a zeolite. The oxidizing
media to be used will be dioxygen and nitrous oxide. Nitrous oxide
will mainly be used as oxidizing medium to put atomic oxygen on
an isolated site catalyst. The catalysts will be tested both on
the Multitrack system and on a steady-state flow equipment. 

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

