<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selective hydrogenation of benzaldehyde over monolithic catalysts
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Selective hydrogenation of benzaldehyde over monolithic catalysts</H2>
Researcher:  <B>Ir. A.C.J.M van de Riet</B> (Adri&euml;tte)<BR>
Status:   A.I.O.<BR>
Started:  August 1994
External support: NIOK, DSM Research<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="riet.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<I>A multi-purpose reactor for catalyst performance testing has
been developed: the Screw Impeller Stirred Reactor (SISR). The
liquid-phase hydrogenation of benzaldehyde to benzyl alcohol is
used as a test reaction.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
 Monolithic catalysts are widely used for the treatment of exhaust
gases. The monolithic structure provides low pressure drops, large
external surface areas and short diffusion lengths. These features
make monoliths suitable for heterogeneously catalyzed gas/liquid
reactions as well. In this case operation under segmented flow
conditions provides low external mass transfer resistance.
<P>
<P>
<B>Experimental</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="riet1.gif">
<P>
 A reactor for catalyst performance testing has been developed:
the Screw Impeller Stirred Reactor (SISR, see figure). A screw
impeller is used to circulate gas and liquid through the monolith.
The reactor is also suitable for slurry experiments. For this
purpose the inner part of the reactor is replaced by a conventional
stirrer.
<P>
 Nickel monolithic catalysts were tested in the hydrogenation
of benzaldehyde to benzyl alcohol. Benzaldehyde was hydrogenated
with very high selectivity (&gt;99%). When almost all benzaldehyde
was converted, hydrogenolysis of benzyl alcohol to toluene and
water became substantial.<BR>
<P>
<B>Future work</B> 
<P>
 The kinetic parameters for the hydrogenation of benzaldehyde
to benzyl alcohol are determined. The results for monolithic and
slurry catalysts will be compared.
<P>
 Mass transfer characteristics under segmented flow conditions
will be studied in another set-up with an external recirculation
of the liquid phase.


