<HEAD>
<TITLE>Preparation of Monolithic Catalysts for Fine Chemicals Production
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Preparation of Monolithic Catalysts for Fine Chemicals Production</H2>
Researcher:  <B>Ir. T. Vergunst</B> (Theo)<BR>
Status:   A.I.O.<BR>
Started:  March 1995<BR>
External support: IOP Katalyse, IKA94061<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="vergunst.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I> In this project, the preparation and application of monolithic
catalysts is studied. The prepared catalysts are characterized
and will be tested using the selective hydrogenation of benzaldehyde
and cinnamaldehyde.<BR>
</I>
<P>
Monolithic supports are continuous unitary structures, consisting
of many parallel channels, separated by thin walls. A typical
configuration is a square cell geometry, 400 cells per square
inch, a wall thickness of 0.17 mm and an inside edge length of
1.1 mm. A monolithic catalyst consists of three parts (see Figure
1). The first part is the structure which is usually made of cordierite.
The second part is the so called washcoat, a thin layer of alumina,
which is the support of the catalyst. The third part is the catalytically
active component (nickel, or a platinum metal). Both the washcoating
and the metal application are studied in this project.
<P>
 Prepared catalysts are characterized using techniques such as
TPR, XRD, XRF, N<SUB>2</SUB>-adsorption, and H<SUB>2</SUB>-chemi-sorption.
<P>
 The prepared monolithic catalysts will be tested using two reactions.
The nickel catalysts will be tested in the selective hydrogenation
of benzaldehyde into benzyl alcohol (in co-operation with Adri&euml;tte
van de Riet) and the platinum metal catalysts will be tested in
the selective hydrogenation of cinnam-aldehyde into cinnamyl alcohol.
<P>
<IMG SRC="vergunst1.gif">
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 1: A monolithic catalyst consists of three
parts.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<IMG SRC="vergunst2.gif"><BR>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 2: Selective hydrogenation of benzaldehyde
into benzyl alcohol (top) and cinnamaldehyde into cinnamyl alcohol
(bottom).</FONT></I>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
