<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Process and catalyst development for the catalytic hydrogenolysis of CCl2F2 into CH2F2
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Process and catalyst development for the catalytic hydrogenolysis of CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> into CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB></H2>
Researcher: <B>Ir. A. Wiersma</B> (Andr&eacute;)<BR>
Status:   A.I.O.<BR>
Started:  October 1992<BR>
External support: TUDelft, AKZO Nobel B.V., VROM, EC, AlliedSignal B.V., KTI B.V., Johnson Matthey Plc.<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="wiersma.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<P>
<I>At Delft University of Technology a promising catalytic process
has been developed to convert the waste CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>
(CFC-12) into the high value added CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>
(HFC-32). With this process the majority of the CFCs still in
use can be converted into a useful product (HFC-32) using a selected
palladium on activated carbon catalyst.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
 CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> (CFC-12) and CCl<SUB>3</SUB>F (CFC-11)
have been identified as substances which deplete the protective
stratospheric ozone layer, and, therefore, their production and
usage will be prohibited by 1-1-1996 worldwide. However, the depletion
of stratospheric ozone will continue in spite of this prohibition.
This is caused by slow diffusion of CFCs from the troposphere
to the stratosphere and the eventual emission of still banked
and used CFCs. It is, therefore, of utmost importance to prevent
the CFCs which are still in use from being emitted into the atmosphere.
The estimated banked quantities of CFCs are 2.1 million tons worldwide.
The majority (85-90%) of these CFCs are CCl<SUB>3</SUB>F and CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>.
There is no dedicated destruction process available for these
CFCs other than combustion (incineration), with a limited capacity.
<P>
At Delft University of Technology a process is being developed
which not only destructs CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> but at the
same time makes a valuable product (CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>
~ HFC-32) from it. With this process both CCl<SUB>3</SUB>F , which
can be converted into CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> by use of HF,
and CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> can be converted into CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Development of catalyst</B>
<P>
 Different noble metals on an activated carbon support have been
tested as a catalyst for the hydrogenolysis reaction of CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>
into CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>. Palladium on a purified activated
carbon has been selected as a very suitable catalyst. Using this
catalyst, a high selectivity to CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> can
be combined with a high conversion (85% selectivity at 100% CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>
 conversion). The stability of the catalyst looks very promising,
after stabilization of the catalyst no deactivation was observed
for over 1600 hours of operation. A kinetic model based on the
mechanism of the reaction has been developed. Modelling and measurement
of the temperature profiles in an industrial- and pilot-reactor,
respectively, showed that the reaction can be carried out safely
in spite of the very exothermic reaction. <BR>
<P>
<B>Development of process</B>
<P>
 A conceptual process design for a 10 kton/year CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>
conversion plant has been made. This design showed that the conversion
of CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>  into high added value product
CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> is both technically and economically
feasible. 


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
