<HEAD>
<TITLE>Measurements And Modelling of Air Purification in Active Carbon-beds (MAMAPAC)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Measurements And Modelling of Air Purification in Active Carbon-beds (MAMAPAC)</H2>
Researcher:   <B>Ir. M.J.G. Linders</B> (Marco)<BR>
Status:     A.I.O.<BR>
Started:    May 1994<BR>
External support:  Prins Maurits Laboratory (TNO Rijswijk), Bl&uuml;cher GmbH (Germany)<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="linders.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</FONT></B>
<P>
Activated carbon is a relatively cheap material
that can be made very porous and onto which many (organic) compounds
adsorb strongly even at low concentrations. It is frequently used
in filters and clothing materials which serve the protection of
military employees against chemical weapons, and in many civil
applications. The objects of study within the project are:<BR>
<P>
1. kinetics inside carbon particles<BR>
2. modelling of adsorption/diffusion<BR>
3. influence of water vapour<BR>
<P>
<B>Experimental</B>
<P>
A method was developed to measure diffusion coefficients
in activated carbon particles. A specially manufactured epoxy
resin &quot;disk&quot; contains a set of single particles, shown
in Figure 1.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="linders1.gif"><P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 1</FONT></I>
<P>
The cylindrical particles are firmly held and isolated
in polyolefin tubes to prevent the resin from intruding the pores.
These tubes shrink upon heating and enclose the particles very
tightly. The experimental set-up is such that the vapour transport
takes place only through the particles. As convection does not
take place they act as an Activated Carbon Membrane (ACM). The
ACM is placed into a stainless steel module in which permeation
measurements are performed according to the Wicke-Kallenbach method.
Single component experiments have been performed using nitrogen,
methane, ethane, and propane. Also, permeation of binary mixtures
of these components has been studied.
<P>
<IMG SRC="linders2.gif"><BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 2</FONT></I>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
Whereas for nitrogen
and methane hardly any dependence of the feed composition on the
diffusion behaviour was observed, a distinct dependence was found
for ethane and propane. Binary experiments showed an overshoot
of the faster (light) component, that adsorbs less strongly. Figure
2 shows the transient permeation profiles for a mixture of nitrogen
and propane. A clear distinction in the breakthrough times is
observed, indicating that even with a single layer of particles
separation is possible. The solid lines are preliminary modelling
results based upon the one-component diffusion data and the binary
Langmuir model. We see that only the trend is predicted reasonably.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
