<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hydrodynamics of the Down-Flow, Gas-Liquid Monolithic Reactor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Hydrodynamics of the Down-Flow, Gas-Liquid Monolithic Reactor</H2>
Researcher: <B>Eric Grolman</B><BR>
Email:  <A HREF="mailto:grolman@stm.tudelft.nl">grolman@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Status:  post-doc<BR>
Started: August 1995<BR>
Sponsor: DSM Research, Geleen, The Netherlands.<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="grolman.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Scope</B>
<P>
Development of design rules for the gas-liquid monolithic reactor,
in the areas of:
<P>
gas-liquid distribution, scale-up, operating flow rates, start-up
procedures and catalyst configuration (stacking).<BR>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
Monoliths in Chemical Engineering are porous blocks containing
large collections of parallel channels which run all the way through
the material. Typical hydraulic diameters of the channels are
1&nbsp;to 2 mm. Normally, the interior of the channels is covered
with a washcoat and a suitable catalyst.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Monoliths have
been used extensively in catalytic automobile exhaust converters.
In Engineering they provide an interesting alternative to trickle-bed
and slurry-column technologies. Obvious advantages of monolithic
reactors are the absence of on-line solids handling, low pressure
drop and high active surface-to-volume ratios. So far, inexperience
with gas-liquid distribution in this type of reactor has been
a major disadvantage.<BR><P>

<IMG SRC="grolman1.gif" ALIGN=right>

<B>Experiments</B>
<P>
Some 2,500 steady-state measurements of pressure drop and liquid
holdup were performed. A novel way of holdup measurement, using
the weight of the monolith (Fig.), proved highly successful.<BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
A method was devised to obtain homogeneous distribution of gas
and liquid inside the monolith. For homogeneous flow, liquid holdup
and pressure drop were modelled successfully. Problems of maldistribution,
caused by the stacking of subsequent sections, were solved. A
'forbidden' region of intrinsic hydrodynamic instability and maldistribution
was discovered, which is to be well avoided in any actual reactor.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Conclusions</B>
<P>
1) Hydrodynamics are the key to the design of monolithic gas-liquid
reactors.
<P>
2) Unstable regions of operation exist that will destroy even
a  perfect initial liquid distribution.
<P>
3) The channel diameter has a significant effect on both pressure
drop and  stability.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
