<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of a Systematic Design Procedure for Industrial Crystallizers
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Development of a Systematic Design Procedure for Industrial Crystallizers</H2>
Ph.D. Student: Ir. Sean K. Bermingham<BR>
Tel. 015 278 5561<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:bermingham@stm.tudelft.nl">bermingham@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Background</B><BR>
This research work is part of UNIAK3, a multi~
disciplinary research project, of which the ultimate goal
is to improve the performance and controllability of
industrial crystallizers by means of better control and
improved design. The types of crystallization considered
are evaporation and cooling, operated continuously and
batch-wise.<BR>
There are 4 PhD students collaborating within the
UNIAK project, from the following groups: Industrial
Crystallization (Lab. for Process Equipment), Particle
Technology (Chem. Eng. Dpt.), Measurement and
Control (Mech. Eng. Dpt.), and Process Systems
Engineering ( Chem. Eng., Dpt.).<P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The knowledge currently used for design and operation
of crystallizers is generally inadequate. In practice, this
often leads to problems in producing crystals on
specification and/or to unstable process behaviour. This
is probably due to the nature of the design rules,
empirical, as well as their objectives.<BR>
The majority of the design rules mainly focus upon
design specifications such as total production yield and
energy consumption, but not on operability and flexibility
requirements. Furthermore, scale-up rules are generally
unreliable due to the assumption of ideal mixing in
crystallizer vessels.<P>

In general, recent developments in fluid dynamics (e.g.
CFD packages for 2-phase simulations) and in reactor
technology (e.g. compartmental approaches) have led to
a better understanding of processes and scale-up
phenomena. For crystallization, these developments,
combined with improved measurement techniques (e.g.
acoustic techniques for CSD and particle velocities), and
increasing knowledge of the mechanisms involved in
crystallization, should provide the knowledge and tools
necessary for the development of a systematic design
procedure.<P>

<B>Systematic design</B><BR>
Since the mid 80's, a lot of academic research has been
performed in the field of systematic (or conceptual)
design of chemical processes. Since 1988, work in this
field has also included solids processes. With respect to
crystallization, the mentioned work is of direct interest
when considering the overall process flowsheet of a
crystallization process, i.e. mixers. dryers, cyclones, heat-
exchangers and crystallizers. For the design of a single
crystallizer, the primary objective of this study,
combination of the ideas of conceptual design and life
cycle analysis have lead to the design procedure below.<P>

<IMG SRC="921.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=456><P>

<B>Development of Systematic Design Procedure</B><BR>
The first phase of this PhD study focuses on the design
specifications and the synthesis phase.<BR>
<UL>
<LI>An inventory will be made of process and product
related design specifications for a wide variety of
industrial processes, ranging from pharmaceuticals to
bulk products. A lot of attention needs to be given to
the priority of the design specifications
<LI>Empirical and systematic design rules currently
available will be screened for model compatibility and
short-comings.
<LI>Regarding software compatibility, incorporation of
empirical rules and rigorous models in a computer
environment requires an interface between an expert
system for the synthesis of design alternatives and DAE
solvers (such as SpeedUp and gPROMS) which are
used for the analysis of these design alternatives.
</UL>

<B>Acknowledgements</B><BR>
The sponsors of the UNIAK 3 project: Dutch Foundation
of Technology (STW), AKZO-Nobel, BASF, Bayer A.G.,
DOW Chemicals, DSM, DuPont de Nemours, and Purac.<P>

