<HEAD>
<TITLE>Open Loop Design under Uncertainty
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Open Loop Design under Uncertainty</H2>
Ph.D. Student: Ir. Folmer W. de Haan<BR>
Tel.: 015 278 4383<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:F.W.deHaan@stm.tudelft.nl">F.W.deHaan@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In Chemical Engineering, knowledge and
procedures are increasingly captured in
models. These models are used in every
phase of the life cycle. In the design
phase of process synthesis and conceptual
design, the tuning of available
knowledge, model detail and functional
specifications becomes most profound.
Leading questions in this problem area:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>What are the design specifications to be
met? What is the necessary model and
algorithmic detail in relation to the design
phase? How to distinguish between
uncertainty, ignorance and variation?
<LI>How to incorporate statistical,
mathematical programming etc. to obtain
a better i.e. a more robust and cheaper
design?
</UL>

<B>Objectives of the project</B><BR>
The main objective is to extend current
design procedures, amongst wich the
Douglas' hierarchical approach, with a
framework to deal with uncertainties.
That is: classification and quantification
of different kinds of uncertainties and
practical interpretation of improved
design results.<P>

<B>Simple motivating example</B><BR>
Consider a plug flowreactor in which the
following consecutive reactions take
place:<BR>

<IMG SRC="931.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=94><P>

If we were to optimize the length of the
reactor, by maximizing the concentration
of product P. we must include the
uncertainties in the kinetic constants. We
must determine the length of the tube,
given an expression of the uncertainties
in the kinetics in e.g. probability density
functions or upper-and-lower bounds.<P>

<IMG SRC="932.gif" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=202><P>

<UL>
<LI>One way to tackle this problem is to
perform Monte-Carlo simulations,
resulting in a probability density function
(pdf) of the optimal length, L. One could
decide to take the mean or median of
pdfL:<P>

<IMG SRC="933.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=55><P>

<LI>Another way is to set up a stochastic
mathematical programming problem:<P>

<IMG SRC="934.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=106><P>
</UL>
<P>

<B>Activities and further research</B><BR>
We have now investigated the design of
a processing unit to deal with the input
from a highly fluctuating off-gas plant.<BR>
Two main case studies involving complex
unit operations, crystallisation and
fiuidization, will provide necessary
experience to set up a conceptual
framework for model based design under
uncertainty.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
