<HEAD>
<TITLE>Optimization of Heat Exchanger Networks in Retrofit
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Optimization of Heat Exchanger Networks in Retrofit</H2>
Ph.D. Student: lr. Jos L.B. van Reisen RTD<BR>
Tel. 015 278 4348<BR>
co-sponsor: NOVEM<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:j.l.b.vanreisen@stm.TUDeift.nl">j.l.b.vanreisen@stm.TUDeift.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Summary</B><BR>
A new methodology for the retrofit and
debottlenecking design of heat exchanger
networks (HENs) is developed and tested
using industrial case studies. It was found
to give simpler and more practical
improvements of networks than existing
methods and with less effort as well.
Compact and compact multi-stream heat
exchangers (CMSHE) can also be
incorporated<P>

<B>Background</B><BR>
Extensive exchange of heat between
process streams reduces utility usage but
increases investments for heat exchanging
equipment. Besides, the system becomes
more complex. In a retrofit the newer
design must also take maximal advantage
of the existing equipment to minimize
investments. To allow retrofit analysis a
proper representation of the existing
network must be set-up from the available
data.<BR>
To find the most optimal modifications
several systematic approaches have been
developed. The most important ones are
Pinch Technology and Mathematical
Programming
(including Exergetic
Optimisation).<BR>
CMSHE have low area costs and a high
area efficiency. These properties give them
great opportunities in heat integration.<P>

<IMG SRC="941.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=246><P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The project aims are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>A generally applicable analysis and
design method for energy saving retrofits
or capacity increasing debottleneckings;
<LI>A method to trade off the complexity of
the modifications to the profit;
<LI>Design strategies for the use of CMSHE
in retrofit;
<LI>A systematic method to extract the data
from the existing plant;
<LI>Application of the methods to practical
cases.
</UL><P>

<B>Activities</B><BR>
Two industrial case studies have been done
to test the retrofit methodology and the
software implementation that is being
developed. New methodology has been
set-up for data extraction and the
debottlenecking of HENs. The flexibility
of CMSHE has been studied.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
PHITS, the software implementation of the
method, was further developed to handle
the two industrial case studies that have
been completed.<BR>
The case studies showed good potential
compared to the existing methods: simple
modifications could be identified rather
easily. Also restrictions have been encoun-
tered: existing networks that are highly
integrated are still difficult to handle,
especially when MSHE are present.<P>

<B>Cooperation</B><BR>
We have regular contacts with the
University of Manchester Institution of
Science an Technology (UMIST). The
study was originally initiated by the Dutch
Advanced Heat Exchanger Group and
funded by NOVEM.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
