<HEAD>
<TITLE>On-line Use of Dynamic Models to support Plant Operation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>On-line Use of Dynamic Models to support Plant Operation</H2>
Ph.D. Student: Ir. Bert. J. Vos
Tel.: 015 278 4383<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:b.j.vos@stm.tudelft.nl">b.j.vos@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The increasing requirements with respect to
environmental care, product quality and cost
efficiency set stringent demands on plant
performance. Currently, approximately 90
percent of the improvements in plant
performance can be subscribed to optimization
of existing equipment. Models, based on
rigorous knowledge of the process, play a key
role in this, by providing a reference with
respect to the plant's (optimal) performance. In
the past, models were often used off-line.
Currently a shift takes place from off- to on-line
use. <I>Real Time Optimization</I> is an example of
this. The RTO-models are equal to sets of
nonlinear algebraic equations and consequently,
RTO is limited to steady state optimization.
Driven by the stringent demands, there is also a
shift taking place <I>from steady state to dynamic</I>
models. However, due to the complexity, the
on-line use of dynamic models is currently
often limited to linear systems.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The objective of this research is to extend the
on-line use of dynamic models, to models that
are nonlinear Differential and Algebraic
Equations. The DAE-structure allows the
rigorous modeling of the dynamics of a large
number of existing plants. In potential, the
expansion toward DAE's enables us to support
and optimize plant operation under both steady
and transient conditions.<BR>
The tools needed to monitor process
performance under dynamic conditions through
DAE-models in an on-line environment are
subject of this research.<P>

<B>Problem description</B><BR>
Measured and unmeasured disturbances
influence the process. Consequently, the model
needs to be tuned frequently. This on-line
tuning is complicated by many factors. An
example is the limited number of measured data
which are in addition subjected to errors and
different or even irregular sampling rates.
Finally, one has to deal with the limited domain
of validity of the model.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
A robust strategy is designed for the on-line
tuning and validation of DAE models. The
strategy can cope with the complications
mentioned above. It is based on a parameter and
state estimation scheme using a moving horizon
approach. The nummerical condition of the
problem is monitored through sensitivity
information. In case the data contains
insufficient information, use will be made of
prior information which is obtained from
preceding horizons. The weighing factor
between the prior information and the
information kept by the data will be deduced by
minimizing the approximated joined confidence
interval of the parameters. The DAE model and
validation scheme are structured in a way that
they allow for multiple applications with the
validated model output. However, in this
research the emphasis is on performance
monitoring.<P>

<IMG SRC="951.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=254><P>

<B>Future Research</B><BR>
This research is in it's final year. It will be
completed by two case studies. The case studies
will be used to test the practical value of the
deduced strategies.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
