<HEAD>
<TITLE>Process Design Studies
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Process Design Studies</H2>
TwAIO's<BR>
Tel. 015 278 4351<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:Grievink@stm.TUDelft.nl">Grievink@stm.TUDelft.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

The <I>TwAIO opleiding Proces- en
Apparaatontwerpen</I> at the TUDelft has the
requirement that each candidate
participates in a team project and in an
individual design project. In the first case,
the emphasis lies on innovative approaches
with respect to alternative process routes.
In the latter case, the design study
complements research projects in the
university or, especially, in industry. The
research group Process Systems and
Control supervises (or has supervised this
year) a number of projects:<P>

<B>Chloroformation</B><BR>
Methylene chloride and chloroform are
produced from methyl chloride by thermal
chlorination. This process of AKZO
NOBEL was studied with respect to its
potential for increased capacity and
preferred product ratios. To this end, the
existing process was designed as a
reference (base) case, bottlenecks were
indicated and alternatives were developed
for reactor, product recovery and product
purification. If compared with the base
case, some alternatives showed to be
attractive technologically as well as
economically.<P>

<B>Catalytic Conversion of CFCs</B><BR>
Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) were
developed around 1930 as refrigerants.
Nowadays, CFCs are strongly related to
the depletion of the ozone layer in the
stratosphere.<P>

Due to these harmful characteristics, the
production of dichlorodifluoromethane
(R12) is banned in the European
Community. However, a satisfactory
solution for the destruction of the large
inventory of R12 still present in the
refrigeration systems is not yet available.
At the moment, the most common
destruction method is incineration of the
CFCs, followed by off-gas treatment. This
destruction process is expensive, and does
not produce valuable products.<P>

An alternative option, the catalytic
hydrogenolysis of R12, is currently being
developed by the group of Industrial
Catalysis of the Delft University of
Technology. This process converts R12
selectively into R32 (difluoromethane).
Just like RI2, R32 is applicable as a
refrigerant, but it is environmentally safer
than R12 due to the lack of chlorine
atoms. Apart from its practical uses, R32
is a compound with an appreciable
economical value. This makes the process
an attractive alternative to incineration.<P>

Within the scope of the collective design
project, a group of TwAIOs developed an
industrial process design for the catalytic
conversion of RI2. Key features of the
design are the reaction unit, comprising
two multi-tubular fixed bed reactors,
subsequently followed by a series of
purification steps. After selective removal
of both HF and HCI to yield the valuable
by-products HBF4 and hydrochloric acid,
pressure-swing distillation is used to break
the complex azeotrope between the
product, R32, and reactant R12.<P>

An economic evaluation has revealed great
economic potentials for the process.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
