<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>The Design of Chemical Processes in their Environment</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>The Design of Chemical Processes in their Environment
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Ph.D. Student: Ir. Paulien M. Herder
<P>
Tel.: +31 15 278 2823
<P>
Email:<A HREF="mailto:p.m.herder@sepa.tudelft.nl"> p.m.herder@sepa.tudelft.nl </A><BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
A wide range of hierarchical, optimization based and knowledge
based design methods is available for the conceptual design of
processes in the chemical industry. The most advanced methods
are those for the &quot;classic&quot; continuously operating processes
in the oil-refining and petrochemical industry (e.g. see the work
of Douglas). A disadvantage of these existing methods is that
the processes are more or less designed as stand-alone systems.
The possibilities for process integration and other forms of synergy
with the plant's environment are only considered after the process
configuration is established.
<P>
In the research project we concentrate on the influence of <I>external
factors</I> on the design process and on the final plant design.
External factors are defined as those factors that influence the
design and the design process of a plant, but cannot be manipulated
by the process designer. Examples can be found in the physical
(heat integration, site infrastructure), economic (market dynamics,
product revenues) and social (legislation, public concern) environment.
We assume that earlier incorporation of external factors into
the design process of the plant will improve:
<UL>
<LI>the design process (due to less iteration loops), 
<LI>the final design (the plant better fits in its environment),
<LI>and the operation of the plant (less retrofits due to a more
flexible design),
</UL>
<P>
thereby reducing the &quot;<I>total cost of ownership</I>&quot;
of a plant instead of cost-minimizing each stage in the plant's
life time separately.
<P>
<B>Objectives</B>
<P>
The main objective of the research project is:
<P>
<I><B>Improving the design process and the final plant design
by early incorporation of external factors,<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
by:
<UL>
<LI>Identification and classification of the influential external
factors. 
<LI>Development of an adjusted hierarchical method (&quot;parallel
hierarchical method&quot;) for the conceptual design of chemical
processes. The area of application of the design method should
if possible be extended to batch processes, to solids handling
processes, and to processes with a strongly fluctuating raw material
composition.
<LI>Development of a system or tool to support the process designer
with the incorporation of external factors. 
</UL>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
Two industrial case studies have been done at two different (in-house)
engineering companies, yielding an extensive list of external
factors. Furthermore, the current design processes in the two
companies have been evaluated by studying the available handbooks,
and through a large number of interviews with process designers,
managers, etc. 
<P>
It can be concluded from the case studies that a need for early
incorporation of external factors exists, but that the currently
available tools and design methods are not able to support the
designer in that particular way. 
<P>
<B>Future research</B>
<P>
The functional specifications for a supporting tool are now being
formulated. The tool should be able to support a process designer
in incorporating all relevant external factors in all stages of
the design process. It will also show the interaction between
different external factors. The specifications will be tested
and improved in three ways:
<UL>
<LI>industrial case study(-ies) in an engineering contractor company;
<LI>a board of experts (from the industry as well as from the
academic world);
<LI>two groups of students, one working with and the other one
without the tool.
</UL>
<P>
The results will be used to improve the functional specifications
of the tool and a prototype of the tool will probably be built.
<P>
<B>Information</B>
<P>
This research project is done at the Faculty of Systems Engineering,
Policy Analysis and Management of the Delft University of Technology
and is supervised by Prof. dr. ir. M.P.C. Weijnen (SEPA) and Prof.
ir. J. Grievink of the Faculty of Chemical Engineering, Delft
University of Technology. The research project started in September
1994 and is expected to be finished in September 1998. <BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 21/01/97</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
