<HEAD>
<TITLE>New Single Particle Strength Test for Aspherical Granules with Large Size Distribution
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>New Single Particle Strength Test for Aspherical Granules with Large Size Distribution</H2>
Ph.D.-Student: Ir. W.J. Beekman<BR>
Particle Technology Group,<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
Genencor International B.V., Delft<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

A new particle strength test has been
developed with which granule (or
agglomerate) impact strength can be
measured, even for aspherical particles with a
wide particle size distribution. Both
information about fragmentation and attrition
strength is measured.<P>

Current impact velocities approach 10 m/s.
The currently investigated type of granules
are water solvable and in size between 300
micro-m and 1000 micro-m. Due to the high number of
repetitions of the impact experiments
(typically several thousands for each granule)
nice statistics are obtained.<P>

For different types of granules a relation has
been found between compression strength
distribution and impact strength distribution
by aid of material constants such as Young's'
modules. Stress strain curves are shown to be
a limiting case of the fatigue phenomenon.<P>

When percentage damage is plotted as a
function of fatigue (damage on the Z-axis)
versus repetitions (X-axis) and expected
impact force (Y-axis), different types of
granules appear as certain three dimensional
planes (in Fig. 1, one of those planes is
shown). Distance between the planes is a
good measure of overall granules strength.<P>

The experimental basis has been provided for
a much better understanding of granule
strength of current granulation techniques.<P>

<IMG SRC="1001.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=322><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
