<HEAD>
<TITLE>Production of a submicrometer, dense ceramic powder using the spray pyrolysis process
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Production of a submicrometer, dense ceramic powder using the spray pyrolysis process</H2>
OIO : Ir D. Camelot<BR>
-- 31 (0)15 278 43 72<BR>
Sponsor: SON\STW<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

For the production of advance ceramic
materials, high purity, dense,
homogeneous and submicron particles
are required. Moreover the size
distribution of the powder should be
quite narrow in order to allow the
formation of a dense and fracture free
ceramic body during the sintering
process.<BR>
The spray pyrolysis process consists
basically on the atomization of a
precursor solution into droplets which
are driven by a carrier gas through an
oven. Inside the oven the solvent
evaporates and intraparticle reactions
occurs that lead to the product material.
This process exhibits many advantages
for ceramic powder production. The
control of the homogeneity is achieved
(in case of multicomponent powders)
on a particle scale, the purity is only
dependent on the precursor purity (no
contamination by grinding), the amount
of by-product is very low, the size
distribution of the final powder is easily
controlled by the atomization process.
But this process as been reported [1] to
often lead to hollow (non-dense)
particle formation. This hollow shape
being the result of the quick
evaporation of the solvent which
generate a concentration gradient in the
droplet which in turn creates surface
precipitation.<BR>
In this work, we are investigating a route
to produce dense particles with this
process. In order to do so we induce a
polymerization reaction in the precursor
droplet while it is evaporating and we
subsequently calcinate the polymer
formed in order to obtain the desired
metal oxide.<BR>
In order to achieve such reaction in
droplet a new droplet generator was
developed in our lab [2]. Its principle is
based on the mixing of droplet through
electrical forces. Practically, two
electrosprays are set beside one another
and they are set to opposite polarities so
that the droplets produce by one spray
are attracted by the droplets produce by
the other spray. In one spray an alcoholic
solution of a metal organic compound is
fed in the system while on the other
spray a mixture of water and alcohol is
sprayed. When the droplets meet the
water reacts with the metal organic
leading to an instantaneous hydrolysis
reaction giving a metal hydroxide. The
hydroxides react between them via
oxolation and olation to give an oxide or
a precursor of an oxide. The so-formed
particles are then carried through an
oven where they are calcined leading to
the formation of oxide submicrometric
particles.<BR>
So far our effort have been concentrated
on the production of SnO2 and TiO2 but
we are now moving to multicomponent
oxide production as BaTiO3.
Beside this work an investigation on the
particle morphology in function of the
different parameters of the Spray
Pyrolysis Process is on its way through
the study of ultrasonically levirated
single drops.<P>

<B>REFERENCES<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>[1] Messing G.L. et al. <I>J. Am. Ceram. Soc.</I> Vol
76 No 11 (1993) 2707<BR>
[2] Borra J-P et al. <I>J. Aerosol Sci.</I> Vol 27 suppl
1, pp 181-182, 1996.</B></FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
