<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Energy Reduction in jet milling processes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Energy Reduction in jet milling processes</H2>
AIO: ir. H.J.C.Gommeren<BR>
<A HREF="http://dutw1283.wbmt.tudelft nl/hpages/gomm/erik.htm">http://dutw1283.wbmt.tudelft nl/hpages/gomm/erik.htm</A><BR>
Sponsors: Novem/Wedco/TU-Delft<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In today's process industry there is
an increasing need for fine polymer
powders with a narrow, well defined
particle size distribution. Several types of
jet mills are used on a semi large scale,
though their energy efficiency is very
poor. The research project aims at a 50%
energy reduction of the jetmilling process
by developing a control system and
improved design of the grinding plant.
One of the topics of this project is the
dynamic modelling of a fluid energy
driven mill, namely the opposed type.<P>

<B>Grinding plant</B><BR>
In a jet mill high pressure air is
injected in the grinding chamber of the
mill.. Particles in the highly turbulent air
flows collide and break. Solid feed is
brought into the mill chamber by a
screwfeeder. A rotary valve serves as a
pressure lock. The end product is
collected in a bagfilter.<P>

<IMG SRC="1021.gif" WIDTH=697 HEIGHT=477><P>

<I><B>Figure 1:</B> Opposed jet mill plant</I><P>

<B>Experiments</B><BR>
The experiments have been carried
out with several opposed jet mills.<P>

<IMG SRC="1022.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=298><P>

<I><B>Figure 2:</B> Opposed jet mill plant</I><P>

Experimental data from jet mills of
different scales and configurations is used
to verify and optimize the population
balance model. The purpose of this model
is to predict optimal setpoints of the solid
feedrate, air supply and rotorspeed such
that the required specification of the end
product is achieved at minimum energy
consumption. Furthermore it serves as a
tool for plant design and scale-up.<P>

<B>Joint program</B><BR>
The project that started in November
1992 is carried out jointly by the Delft
University of Technology, Particle
Technology Group and the Process
Control Group.<P>
If you are interested in this project, please
contact our homepage (internet address,
see beading).<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
