<HEAD>
<TITLE>Electro hydrodynamic atomization in the cone-jet mode
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Electro hydrodynamic atomization in the cone-jet mode</H2>
Ph.D. Student: ir. R. Hartman<BR>
Tel --31 15 2783874<BR>
Laboratory of Particle Technology<BR>
Department of Chemical Engineering and Material Science<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER><BR>
Electro Hydrodynamic atomization in the Cone-Jet mode can be used to produce highly
monodisperse aerosols. In this process the shape of a liquid droplet is transformed by electrical
forces into a conical shape. At the cone apex, a jet with a high charge density occurs which can
break up into main droplets with a narrow size distribution, and smaller satellites.<BR>
This phenomena is of interest, since the uni-polar droplet charge reduces coagulation (e.g.
combustion), increases deposition (e.g. paint spraying) and allows for controllable trajectories
(e.g. non-impact printing). In other applications where solutions are sprayed in order to produce
a monosized powder, (e.g. medicines, toner powder), the high particle charge creates a technical
problem. Evaporating charged particles can exceed the Rayleigh charge limit and 'explode',
creating a spray with a much wider size distribution. Another problem is to allow the particles
time to dry before collection. Both problems can be solved by discharging the particles.<P>

<CENTER><B>Research Topics</B></CENTER><BR>
At this moment three different topics are under investigation. First is the fundamental
research of the phenomenon itself. The produced droplet size only depends on the liquid flow rate
and the liquid properties like viscosity, conductivity, electrical permittivity and surface tension.
A physical numerical model has been developed in order to investigate the influence of these
liquid properties and the liquid flow rate on the droplet size and droplet charge.<BR>

The second area under investigation is the electrical interaction between the highly
charged droplets just after production. This interaction causes a size segregation effect. Small
droplets will be found at the edge of the spray while large droplets will be found near the spray
centre, Ganan-Calvo (1994). This size segregation effect has
been simulated and measured in order to investigate the
droplet production mechanism, and the segregation mechanism
itself. If we are able to control the size segregation effect
taking place in the spray shortly after production, then the
main droplets can be separated from the smaller satellites. It
was found that air velocities of several metres per second
influence strongly the dispersion of the droplets and a charge
relation between main droplets and satellites could be
established.<P>

<IMG SRC="1031.gif" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=278><P>

Disadvantage of Electro Hydrodynamic Atomization is the low liquid flow rate which
makes it more complicated to produce at industrial production rates. For instance the maximum
liquid flow rate for ethanol is 5 ml/h for a produced droplet size of 20 micro-m. The third area under
investigation is the scaling-up of the process by putting a number of nozzles close to each other.
Due to the electric fields, neighbouring nozzles will have an influence on each other, which
might disturb the droplet production process. Of further interest is the influence of discharging
the aerosol on the droplet production and the aerosol collection.<BR>
Ganan-Calvo, A.M. Lasheras, J.C. Davila, J. Barrero, A. (1994) <I>J. Aerosol Sci.</I> <B>25</B>, 1121.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-195</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B003-113</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/104.html 130.89.50.60 19970216175618 text/html 2851
