<HEAD>
<TITLE>Particle Shape and Size Characterisation by Light Scattering
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Particle Shape and Size Characterisation by Light Scattering</H2>
Sponsor: NOVEM<BR>
Postdoc.: Drs. J.G.A.E. de Smet<BR>
tel :--031(0)15 2783570<BR>
TUDelft<BR>
Department of Chemical Process Technology<BR>
Section particle technology<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER><P>

A vast number of products from chemical
processes appear in particulate form. The
particles appear in different size and shape.
In a vast number of industrial processes the
size and shape of the particles can influence
the process considerably.<BR>
Thus knowledge of the shape and size of
the particles is highly desirable. An on4ine
sensor which can measure both the size and
shape of the particles is therefore needed. A
promising technique by which information
about the size and shape of the particles can
be obtained is forward light scattering. The
former can be measured by a lot devices,
already available on the market.<BR>
Excellent work in this direction is already
been done by C. Heftels [1].<P>

<CENTER><B>ASPECTS</B></CENTER><P>

In our project we want to extend his work
to identify as much different shapes as
possible. To identify shapes of particles
from experimental data we have to solve
inverse problems and have to rely on
regularization methods.<BR>
The angular distribution of the intensity of
the scattered light is related to the size
shape and optical properties of the material.
Approximate models for scattering can be
used such as fraunhofer diffraction.
Numerical computations show the
dependence of the angular distribution of
the intensity distribution for a square and a
sphere [l](see fig 1). There is a distinct
difference between the two.<P>

<IMG SRC="1051.gif" WIDTH=575 HEIGHT=340><P>

<CENTER><B>FUTURE WORK</B></CENTER><P>

In the near future we will perform
numerical investigations to identify a broad
class of different shapes. Experiments will
be performed on ensembles of particles of
different shapes.<BR>
A physical-mathematical model on
diffraction and scattering will be applied
and" modified" to be used for an on4ine
sensor.<BR>
We want to extend the measurement range
to systems were the concentration of the
particles in the gas and/or liquid phase is
high.<P>

[1] C. Heftels, On4ine particle size and shape
characterisation by narrow angle light scattering<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
