<HEAD>
<TITLE>Laser Synthesis and Hot Isostatic Pressing of Silicon Nitride Powder
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Laser Synthesis and Hot Isostatic Pressing of Silicon Nitride Powder</H2>
I.L. Tuinman: AIO<BR>
B. Scarlett, J. Schoonman<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>1. Introduction</B><BR>
The most common route to produce
advanced technical ceramics such as
silicon nitride is by powder processing.
This processing involves among others
powder production, milling, compaction
and sintering. Silicon nitride is notorious
for its difficult handling and sintering due
to the lack of a liquid silicon nitride phase.
During the past ten years much effort
has been
devoted at the TUDelft to
producing
silicon nitride powder
with
improved
handling properties
and
especially
improved sinterability.
The
powder is
produced in a CO2-1aser driven
aerosol reactor shown in fig. 1.<P>

<B>2. Experiments and Results</B><BR>

Nanosized silicon nitride powders were
synthesized in the laser driven aerosol
reactor from silane and ammonia. The
product powders were subsequently dry
pressed mechanically, encapsulated in
quartz, and sintered in a hot isostatic press
at 1950 °C and 1950 bar for up to 1 hour.
Powders that were exposed to air prior to
sintering were densified to up to 96.5% of
theoretical density. Their final density was
dependent on the initial BET surface area.
Unexposed powders were densified to
circa 90%. Their final density seems to
depend mainly on the percentage of
amorphous phase in the original powder.<P>

<IMG SRC="1061.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=375><P>

fig. I Schematic side view of the reactor<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-198</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B015-94</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/107.html 130.89.50.60 19970216175649 text/html 3062
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:50:14 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Monday, 16-Dec-96 08:19:41 GMT
Content-length: 2882
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Powder Agglomeration Using a Lodige High Shear Mixer
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Powder Agglomeration Using a L&ouml;dige High Shear Mixer</H2>
Ph.D-Student: P.A.L. Wauters, M.Sc.<BR>
Particle Technology Group,<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
Genencor International B.V., Delft<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

INTRODUCTION:<BR>
Granulation is a general term for size
enlargement processes. Particle size
enlargement can offer many advantages such
as: improved dusting behaviour, better
product appearance, improved flow
characteristics and better solubility, to name
but a few. Granulation can be performed in
a large number of different pieces of
equipment, e.g. fluidized bed, high shear
mixer, rotating drum, prilling tower,
extruder, etc. This research deals with
granulation in a high shear mixer.<P>

THEORY:<BR>
In a high shear mixer (see Fig. 1), granules
are formed by adding a binder to an agitated
powder. The binder will form liquid layers
on the powder particles which allows them
to stick together after collision, causing the
particles to grow. Due to the complexity of
the system most research on granulation is
more of an empirical nature. In the first
stage of this research, factorial design was
used as a tool, to determine the influence of
the binder liquid content, binder liquid
viscosity, ploughshare speed and the initial
particle size distribution.<P>

<IMG SRC="1071.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=330><P>

RESULTS:<BR>
In order to qualify the influence of certain
parameters, the course of the mass diameter
in time for all the experiments was plotted
(see for example Fig. 2, which present the
results of the experiments carried out at a
high binder liquid viscosity).<P>

<IMG SRC="1072.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=311><P>

From Fig. 2 it is clear that both binder
liquid amount has a profound influence on
particle growth. More binder liquid causes
faster, more extended growth. A higher
binder liquid viscosity has the same effect,
but to a lesser extent. This is in accordance
with both theory as well as earlier findings.<P>

OUTLOOK:<BR>
The next step in the project will be using
population balance modeling in order to
describe and predict the evolution of the
whole particle size distribution in time
during granulation. Apart from this,
experiments on a large scale continuous
granulator will be performed. The goal of
the project is to find a way to control a
continuous granulator. Apart from having a
good model, it is also necessary to have
good measurements and thus on-line particle
size analysis will also be looked at.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

