<HEAD>
<TITLE>On-line chemical analysis of single particles
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>On-line chemical analysis of single particles</H2>
AIO: M. Weiss<BR>
Sponsors: Stichting voor Scheikundig Onderzoek Nederland (SON) / Stichting voor Technische Wetenschappen (STW)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<H3>Introduction</H3>
It is often useful to know the size and
the chemical composition of small par-
ticles. The Particle Technology Group
at Delft, University of Technology has
developed such an instrument.<P>

<H3>Experimental Setup</H3>
Particles are sampled into the vacuum
chamber of a TOF inass spectrometer by a differentially pumped nozzle
system. Tim aerosol beam intersects
with two beams of a helium-neon laser
whereby the particles are scattering
light. The scattered light is detected
by a photo-multiplier. The time between the two scatter signals is proportional to the speed of the particles,
which is particle size dependent. At
the same time a second laser (excilner
at 308 nm) is triggered which vaporizes
the particles and ionizes the fragments.<P>

<IMG SRC="1081.gif" WIDTH=510 HEIGHT=389><P>

The generated ions are accelerated into
the flight tube of the TOF mass spectrometer. The mass spectrum detected
with the aid of multi channel plates
gives information on the chemical composition of the particle.<P>

<H3>Results and Conclusions</H3>
A potential application of the instrument is the detection of soot and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH)
on the soot. Two soot types were analyzed: Printex U, a soot produced
by Degussa AG, Germany, via a flame
route, and Norit SX2, a pulverized,
activated coal. The following figures
shows inass spectra of the two soot
types. They can clearly be Discriminated. A PAH (anthraeene) absorbed
on the soot can be detected.<P>

<IMG SRC="1082.gif" WIDTH=553 HEIGHT=885><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
