<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fiber Deposition in Lower Parts of the Lung
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Fiber Deposition in Lower Parts of the Lung</H2>
Ph.D Student: Y. Zhou, M.Sc.<BR>
Tel: 31-15-2785501<BR>
Laboratory of Particle Technology<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER><P>

In order to investigate fiber deposition
behaviour in the lower part of the lung, a
granular bed filter was developed as a
model for these parts of the lung with the
granular size varying per layer. The
spherical particle deposition in the lower
parts of the lung during inspiration has
been compared with that in the granular
bed filter with the similar physical dimen-
sions and equal flow rate. The results are
in good agreement with the calculating
model. For investigating fiber deposition in
lungs, the length, diameter and orientation
of the fibers should be considered.<P>

<CENTER><B>FIBER ORIENTATION</B></CENTER><P>

For fully developed laminar flow, the
orientation of fibers has been variously
described by different authors as aligned
parallel to the direction of the streamlines,
or as exhibiting a periodic end-over-end
rotation. In our research, the Reynolds
number in the experimental system is small
(max. 60). The fiber flow in the system is
therefore assumed to be aligned with
streamlines.<P>

<CENTER><B>EXPERIMENT AND RESULTS</B></CENTER><P>

Polydispersed glass fibers and a kind of
monodispersed fibers were used in the
experiments. In our experiment, fibers
were dispersed by a fluidized bed aerosol
generator or a nebulizer. The dispersed
fibers were then neutralized by a
radioactive source (Kr 85) before
introducing them into the granular bed
filter. There are two sampling probes
located before and after the granular bed
filter for measurement.<P>

The empirical model for fiber deposition in
a granular bed filter are obtained by the
experimental data. This model was also
compared with the model of Asgharian
(1988) who developed his model for fiber
deposition both in human lungs and rat
lungs. He also compared it with several
mathematical models for human lung
deposition and experimental data for rat
lung deposition. He proved it to be in good
agreement with the data of rat lung
deposition. Our model is in very good
agreement with the Asgharian model for
alveolar deposition as shown in the figure.<P>

<IMG SRC="1091.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=410><P>

<CENTER><B>REFERENCE</B></CENTER><P>

Asgharian, B. (1988), <I>The deposition of
fibrous particles in the respiratory tract
using a mathematical model</I>, PhD thesis,
SUNY Buffalo, NY<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
