<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Laboratory for Physical Technology<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Department of Chemical Technology and Material Science
Julianalaan 136
NL 2628 BL Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 5180
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 4135
e-mail:    <A HREF="mailto:g.frens@stm.tudelft.nl">g.frens@stm.tudelft.nl</A>
internet:  <A HREF="http://www.cpt.stm.tudelft.nl/cpt/ph/ph_home.html">http://www.cpt.stm.tudelft.nl/cpt/ph/ph_home.html</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<H2>Laboratorium voor Fysische Chemie</H2>
<B>(vakgroep Chemische ProcesTechnologie)</B><P>

Secretariaat: Anke Stoker, tel. 2633

<TABLE>
<TR><TD>Prof.dr. G. Frens</TD><TD> Colloids, Suspensions, Interfaces
<TR><TD>Dr.ir. M. Peereboom</TD><TD> Process Kinetics and Thermodynamics
<TR><TD>Dr.ing. M.C. van der Leeden</TD><TD> Adhesion Technology, Precepitation
<TR><TD>Ir. M. Trijssenaar</TD><TD> Extreme Control in Lubrication
<TR><TD>Drs. S. Shulepov</TD><TD> Coagulation Kinetics
<TR><TD>Ir. E. Margarita</TD><TD> Activation of Metal Surfaces
<TR><TD>Drs. S.G.O. de Haas</TD><TD> Polymer Adsorption and Adhesion
<TR><TD>Ir. L. Evers</TD><TD> Thin Liquid Films
<TR><TD>Drs. M.V. ten Kortenaar</TD><TD> Autocatalytic reactions
<TR><TD>Ir. A.M.D.E. Timmerman</TD><TD> Supersaturation in flow
<TR><TD>Ir. A.A.C.M. Rutten</TD><TD> Whey Protein adsorption
<TR><TD>N. van Westen</TD><TD> Sorbent Preparation Facilities
</TABLE><P>

Secretariaat Fysische Chemie:<BR>
Sue van de Giessen,<BR>
tst. 2633, fax. 4135<BR>
<P>
The Laboratory of Physical Chemistry studies static and dynamic properties of interfaces,
colloids and thin layers. Equilibrium at an interface is determining for properties of
disperse systems and of products which are made out of those, like paper, magnetic tape,
food, detergents and cosmetics. Dynamic effects at interfaces (e.g. during heat- or mass-
transfer) are decisive in the outcome and the effectivity of chemical reactions and physical
separation- or compounding processes which involve disperse systems.<P>

In process technology our investigations aim at the development of "Extreme Control"
strategies as a method for self regulation in industrial processes. The idea is to locally
control the conversions everywhere in a reactor, in such a way that they proceed with
optimum selectivity and yield. This is effected by coupling physical or chemical
transformation processes, through the interface as an anisotropic medium, with the
transport of heat and matter of reactants and products. This coupling gives the possibility
for cyclic mechanisms like in heterogeneous catalysis, which keep boundary conditions
for the desired processes at their optimum value.<P>

Together with groups from the Faculties for Civil Engineering and for Aerospace
Technology the Laboratory studies fundamental and chemical aspects of adhesion and the
durability of adhesive bonds in the "Hechtingsinstituut TUD". In this institute the
participants have joined their expertise in the field of adhesion technology to study
applications of this modern bonding method in advanced metal/polymer composites, in
medicine (surgery), in building and airplane-, automobile- and other metal constructions.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 16/12/96</CENTER></H6>

