<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Instabilities in Supersaturated Soap Surfaces
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Instabilities in Supersaturated Soap Surfaces</H2>
V.A. Nierstrasz, G. Frens, L.J. Evers<BR>
Laboratorium voor Fysische Chemie, TU Delft, 2628 BL Delft, Julianalaan 136, The Netherlands.<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<IMG SRC="1121.gif" ALIGN=left WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=606>

<H3>The aureole around the hole in a bursting soap film is
an area of increased surface coverage with surfactant.</H3>
In this supersaturated surface the film is kept in its shape by a gradient in
the surface tension. The stability of the film ends abruptly at the rim of
the hole. There, the unbalance of forces leads to a shock-wave which
propagates into the film.<P>

<H3>In a Newton-black film the material of the rim is a
supersaturated soap solution. It becomes unstable, and
assumes a scalloped appearance.</H3>
Visco-elasticity of the film around the hole causes retardation of the hole
expansion. The instabilities demonstrate a disproportion of the toroidal
rim into sections with different elastic and dissipative properties, joined
together by surface tension gradients.<P>

<H3>Marginal regeneration is an
instability along the perimeters
(Plateau borders) of vertical soap
films.</H3>
The drainage of film into the lower Plateau
border creates supersaturated line of film
elements. The surfactant has to be retumed to
the film surfaces. This leads to the instability
known as marginal regeneration.<P>

<IMG SRC="1122.gif" ALIGN=right WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=448>

The classical explanation of marginal regeneration is in terms of thermal thickness
fluctuations and exchange of film elements along the borders due to the Laplace
pressure difference between film and Plateau border.<P>

Experimental observations on<BR>
- the effect of the drainage rate on the periodicity;<BR>
- the rate of marginal regeneration as the film expands and contracts;<BR>
- the effect of viscosity and surface tension
prove that marginal regeneration is due to surface tension
gradient between the film and its supersaturated perimeters.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
