<HEAD>
<TITLE>Effectivity of the washing process
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Effectivity of the washing process</H2>
AI0: A.M.D.E. Timmerman (015-2782638 / <A HREF="mailto:A.Timmerman@stm.tudelt.nl">A.Timmerman@stm.tudelt.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor: IR-TN0<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

In the detergency industry the washing process
is characterised by the 'Sinner-factors':
energy, temperature, chemistry and time.
Departing from these factors the washing
process can be optimalized. If, however, the
backgrounds of the Sinner factors are known,
it will be possible to optimize the washing
process from a more fundamental point of
view. From earlier research it was concluded
that a soiled textile could never be cleaned in
a normal washing process if the most
important mechanism governing the mass
transfer from fabric to detergent solution were
diffusion. Therefore, in this research it is
supposed that there is a flow both along the
fabric-surfactant solution interface and in the
fabric yarns.<P>

<B>Theory</B><P>

During the washing process fabrics are moved
and deformed continuously. Through the
stretching of the fabric, liquid (particularly a
surfactant solution) is squeezed from pores in
the yarns. Our first hypothesis is that the
deformation of the fabric and the flow in the
yarns causes, in case of a very concentrated
surfactant solution, a local surfactant
supersaturation at the fabric-surfactant
solution interface. This local supersaturation in
turn, could cause instabilities, which might
cause a change of the velocity profile in the
textile pores (figure (1). In this case the
surfactant molecules flow along the fabric-
liquid interface. This flow along the interface
may be advantageous for the effectivity of the
washing process.<P>

<IMG SRC="1131.gif" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=295><P>

<B>Figure 1</B><P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

It is our objective to find evidence for flow
along the liquid-fabric interface. In order to do
so the following experiment will be carried
out: surfactant solutions of different
concentrations are pushed through a narrow
capillary. The flow through the capillary is
measured It is envisaged that highly
concentrated solutions, particularly 3 times the
critical micelie concentration, where a
maximum cleaning activity is achieved, will
reach a maximum increase in flow rate with
increasing pressure. We will measure the flow
of various surfactant solutions from the
capillary as function of the pressure. If a
sudden non-inear increase in flow is measured
at a certain pressure this indicates that there is
slip at the wall of the capillary.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-204</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B015-186</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/114.html 130.89.50.60 19970216175817 text/html 3130
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
