<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Adsorption of reducing agents on metals
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Adsorption of reducing agents on metals</H2>
AIO : Mamix ten Kortenaar (015-2781485)<BR>
Sponsor: TUD<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I><B>Objective</B></I><P>

Electroless plating is an autocatalytic process
in which metals are deposited on a substrate by
a reducing agent. The reducing agent is
oxidized on the catalytic substrate and released
electrons are consumed by metal ions present at
the interface. The deposited metal layer
propagates the catalytic oxidation of the
reducing agent resulting in an autocatalytic
growth of the metal film. Electroless plating is
applied in the manufacture of printed circuit
boards and is a cheap and attractive way to
metallize various substrates. However, the
detailed mechanism of electroless metallization
has still not been elucidated and this often
makes it an empirical matter. An enhanced
understanding may improve kinetic control of
selective microscale metallization processes.<P>

<I><B>Methods</B></I><P>

The adsorption and exchange of formaldehyde
(reducing agent) is studied on various catalytic
metals. This is done by using radioactive
labeled formaldehyde molecules and
equipment, currently built at the Interfaculty
Reactor Institute. The equipment enables to
study adsorption (in-situ) at the liquid-solid
boundary down to 1% of a monolayer.
Adsorption rate, adsorption isotherms as well
as exchange rates can be measured as a
function ofpH, potential, time, temperature and
concentration.    Any    adsorbate-adsorbent
combination can be studied, provided that a
convenient tracer molecule is available. The
method is based on a 'press down' procedure
as shown in the next column. By pressing down
a smooth electrode with adsorbed (radioactive)
molecules on a flat glass scmtillator, most of
the solution entrapped in the gap is squeezed
out. The glass scintillator converts detected beta-
particles into light pulses, which are sent to a
photomultiplier tube. The quantity of adsorbed
molecules is obtained rapidly by subtractmg
background signals, obtained when the
electrode is in the upward position.<P>

<I><B>Data Processing and Prospects</B></I><P>

The rate of exhange is measured and simulated
by compartimental analysis, yielding an
appropriate physical model which describes the
different 'kinetic compartments' in the entire
adsorption process. The model yields the time
of residence of formaldehyde molecules
adsorbed on the metal electrode. These times
are supposed to be characteristic of the
(electro)catalytic activity of the metal and
eventually serve kinetic control of selective
deposition    processess.    In    addition,
electrochemical as well as spectrosopical
techniques are used in order to verify the model
postulated.<P>

<B>THIN-CAP METHOD</B><P>

<IMG SRC="1171.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=282><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
