<HEAD>
<TITLE>Emulsion Lubrication in cold rolling
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Emulsion Lubrication in cold rolling</H2>
AIO: Ir. M Trijssenaar (015-2786181 / <A HREF="mailto:m.trijssenaar@stm.tudelft.nl">m.trijssenaar@stm.tudelft.nl</A>)
Sponsor: Hoogovens<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction.</B><P>

Cold rolling is the process in which steel
sheet is reduced in thickness from hot rolling
exit thickness (order 1 mm) to its final
thickness (order 0.2 mm) In order to cool the
rolls and steel sheet, to lower the friction and
to decrease the wear rate, the contact
between rolls and sheet is lubricated with an
oil-in-water emulsion. The emulsion is
sprayed onto the steel and a lubricating layer
of fluid is sheared into the roll bite by the
velocity of the surfaces.<P>

Contrary to the lubrication with pure oil, the
mechanism of lubrication with emulsions is
not quite understood. In existing models of
cold rolling lubrication [1] the lubricating
fluid is always assumed to be one phase (the
oil phase). This is not a correct assumption.
The composition and thickness of a
lubricating film formed by an emulsion, and
the mechanism by which this film is formed,
is not known.<P>

<B>Experimental.</B><P>

Experiments were performed on the pilot
s'tze cold rolling stand of Hoogovens. Rolling
force and roll velocity are kept constant,
while the reduction factor r (1-ratio of outlet
and inlet thickness of the sheet) is varied by
adjusting the inlet and outlet tensions on the
sheet. As also the lubricating film on the sheet
is reduced in thickness during each pass, in
order to not deplete this film, the lubricating
film on the surface must be replenished from
the emulsion. Measured oil film thicknesses
on the sheet after each pass are shown to be
fairly constant. The amount of replenished oil
during a pass is shown to be a function of
reduction factor. A higher reduction leads to
larger amounts of replenished oil.<P>

<B>Mechanism of oil fdm building from O/W
emulsions.</B><P>

The mechanism of lubricant film
replenishment can take place either in the
work zone between roll and sheet, or just
before this zone, in the entry zone.
Experiments have been carried out on the
spreading of an emulsion droplet during a roll
pass, which showed that though the lubricant
film thicknesses were much larger than
expected from existing hydrodynamic
lubrication theory, the experimentally
determined replenishment of the lubricant
film cannot take place in the work zone as the
film thicknesses in the work zone are too
small for this effect.<P>

The replenishment of the lubricant film has
to take place in the entry zone. In order to
explain the sensitivity of the replenishment of
the film thickness for reduction, in the entry
zone some mechanism must occur which is
itself dependent on the reduction. It appears
the velocity profile in the entry zone is
reduction-dependent. The velocity gradients,
influenced by the reduction, change
themselves the coalescence of oil droplets
from the emulsion with the existing oil film.<P>

[1] Wilson, W. R. D., Walowit, J.A (1971)
<I>Trib. Conv., Instn Mech Engrs</I><I>, 164-172</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
