<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ageing of 'active' aluminium oxide layers.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Ageing of 'active' aluminium oxide layers.</H2>
AIO: Ir. E. Margarita (015-787345 / <A HREF="mailto:E.Margarita@lr.tudelft.nl">E.Margarita@lr.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Project term: March 1993 - March 1997<BR>
Sponsor: IOP-Coating / Delft Adhesive Institute / Delft University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The characterization of aluminJure oxide
layers after specific surface treatment
obviously is of the greatest importance in
understanding the levels of joint strength and
potential joint durability that may be archieyed
in adhesive bonding of these surfaces
Characterization of the aluminium surface
includes a wide variety of techniques This
forms the aim of this study The aim is to
study the role of the created 'active' oxide
layer after different pretreatments on the
adhesive bonding to aluminium. One of the
usefull pretreatments used in the aerospace
manufacturing is chromic acid anodizing.<P>

However, even when provided surface
pretreatment has been carried out properly,
variations in adhesion quality have been
observed as a function of the elapsed time
between the end of pretreating and applying
the primer This time is called the "SET"
(Surface Exposure Time)<P>

<B>Characterization of the oxide layers</B><P>

The techniques used for characterization of
the changes of the created oxide layer as
function of the SET are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>contact angle (CA) measurements
CA = f (Temperature, Rel Humidity)
<LI>XPS measurements
<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

<LI>The polar part of the surface energy
appears to be a function of the RH and
the temperature

<LI>The XPS- measurements indicate a
dehydratation of the oxidelayer.
The Gibbsite', aluminium trihydroxide.
layer converts into a 'Boehmite/
pseudoboehmite',
aluminium oxide
hydroxide, layer.
</UL>

