<HEAD>
<TITLE>PhD-projects Delft 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<PRE>Delft University of Technology
Department of Chemical Technology and Material Science
Julianalaan 136
NL 2628 BL Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 2667
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 8047
internet:  <A HREF="http://www.stm.tudelft.nl/ttf/ttfhome.htm">http://www.stm.tudelft.nl/ttf/ttfhome.htm</A></PRE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<IMG SRC="lat961.gif" ALIGN=left><CENTER><H1>Delft University of Technology<BR>
Laboratory of Applied Thermodynamics<BR>
		and Phase Equilibria<BR></H1></CENTER>

<B>Permanent staff</B><BR>
Prof.Dr.Ir. J. de Swaan Arons<BR>
Dr.Ir. H.J. van der Kooi<BR>
Dr.Ir. Th.W. de Loos	<BR>
Dr.Ir. C.J. Peters<P>

<B>Laboratory Assistants</B><BR>
L.J. Florusse<BR>
J.H.F. Grondel<BR>
W. Poot<P>

<B>Research theme</B><BR>
The study, theoretically and experimentally, of thermodynamic models for processes with or without chemical conversion, normally at high pressures (up to 4000 bar and 400 °C).<BR>
The task of applied thermodynamics is to provide maximum information on required thermodynamic properties for application in a wide range of pressure, temperature and composition. The challenge is to accomplish this from a minimum number of experimental data and from a thermodynamic model which contains essential information on the molecular properties of the system and which relies on the sound principles of molecular and statistical thermodynamics.<P>

<B>Research topics</B><BR>
<B>Phase and interfacial behaviour of gas condensates</B><BR>
Many reservoir fluids have characteristics between natural gas and oil. This research focuses on the observation, modelling and prediction of phase behaviour and, whenever possible, interfacial tensions and concentration profiles in representative model systems.<P>

<B>Hyperbaric reservoir fluids</B><BR>
Experimental investigation and modelling of vapour-liquid, solid (wax)-liquid and solid (wax)-vapour equilibria of asymmetric model systems for high pressure reservoir fluids (p > 500 bar).<P>

<B>Near-critical processing</B><BR>
Studies are made of enhanced volatility and solubility of low volatile solutes and their mixtures in near-critical gases and of crystallization based on the gas-antisolvent phenomenon.<P>

<B>Enhanced oil recovery</B><BR>
Investigation and modelling of high pressure vapour-liquid equilibria of systems interesting for enhanced oil recovery. Development of a model for the description of the pressure influence on liquid-liquid equilibria in oil-water-surfactant systems which is of interest for enhanced oil recovery by surfactant flooding.<P>

<B>Polymer solutions</B><BR>
Determination and modelling of phase equilibria and stability limits (with pressure-pulse-induced critical-scattering, PPICS) of fluid phases composed of polymers and near critical solvents.<P>

<B>Supercritical water</B><BR>
Experimental investigation and modelling of the phase behaviour of binary and ternary systems comprising water, salts and alternative refrigerants in the near-critical region of water.<P>

<B>Enzymatic reactions</B><BR>
Enzyme catalyzed reactions are performed in near-critical fluids. In this project three fields in research are integrated: thermodynamics, enzymology and reactor engineering. The influence of reactor type, reactants, pressure, temperature and water on the enzyme's behaviour is investigated.<P>

<B>Thermodynamic analysis of processes</B><BR>
Analyzing processes on their driving forces (temperature, concentration and velocity gradients) and lost work and, where possible, making suggestions for the reduction of these losses. The research content of these studies relates closely to the process' design.<P>

<B>Lactic acid study</B><BR>
The design of a thermodynamic model, partly based on experiments, partly on predictions, allowing the routine use of established flowsheeting programs for processing lactic acid and its derivatives.<P>

Computer aided design of technical fluids
Environmental, safety and health restrictions impose limitations on the choice of fluids for separation and energy processes. Based on group contribution methods computers can assist in the design of the desired compounds or compound mixtures.<P>

<B>Phase behaviour in bioseparation processes</B><BR>
Models will be developed to predict the phase behaviour of biopolymers of practical interest in aqueous solutions of varying acidity and salt content. The predictions will be verified experimentally.<P>

<B>Water-electrolyte-solvent systems</B><BR>
A model will be developed for the description of liquid-liquid equilibria of these systems based on own experimental and literature data. This model has to be used in the design of extraction columns for the caprolactam production.<P>

<B>Fundamental studies</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Research on the classification of complex fluid phase equilibria;
<LI>Study of improvements in the performance of equations of state of practical importance;
<LI>Simultaneous description of interfacial and bulk phase behaviour of binary and multi-component mixtures.
</UL>

<B>Research scientists</B><BR>
<B>PhD students</B><BR>
P. Cornelisse (2)<BR>
