<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fluid Three-Phase Behaviour in Certain Ternary Mixtures
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Fluid Three-Phase Behaviour in Certain Ternary Mixtures</H2>
Ph.D-student:	Dipl.-Ing. Kerstin Gauter (<A HREF="mailto:K.Gauter@STM.TUDelft.nl">K.Gauter@STM.TUDelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor:	Delft University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="kg.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B> Introduction</B><BR>
Fluid multiphase behaviour of binary systems and its classification has been a subject of study by many authors, and it is therefore relatively well known. However, systems in nature and industrial processes are very often not binary, but have three components or more. For processes where two phases or more are involved, as for example in supercritical extraction, knowledge of fluid multiphase behaviour of multicomponent mixtures is a prerequisite. <P>

<B>Outline and systems measured</B><BR>
This project concentrates on ternary systems with two heavy components (solutes) and CO2  (solvent). Various series of mixtures have been examined for regions of fluid three-phase behaviour and the critical end-points (CEP). Experiments have been done with the so-called Cailletet-apparatus, where phase transitions are observed visually. Temperature and pressure of phase transitions can be measured for samples with fixed compositions. The mole fraction of CO2 is kept constant at a value where three-phase behaviour occurs for every mixture measured. It is therefore possible to plot the critical end-point (CEP) data in two-dimensional diagrams, such as temperature versus x* and pressure versus x*. The modified mole fraction x* represents the mole fraction of the heaviest component on a CO2-free basis. The values x*=0 and x*=1 represent binary systems, and intermediate values represent all possible ternary mixtures. <P>

<IMG SRC="kg1.gif" WIDTH=385 HEIGHT=259><P>

The observation of the development of CEP-lines with x* helps in understanding the fluid phase behaviour of ternary systems. CEPs are characteristics of three-phase boundaries.<P>

<IMG SRC="kg2.gif" WIDTH=393 HEIGHT=257><P>
 
Examples of series of systems measured are CO<SUB>2</SUB> - n-alkane - nitrophenol, with n-alkanes from pentanol to octanol, and CO<SUB>2</SUB> - 1-alkanol - n-alkane, with various alkanols from pentanol to octanol and the alkanes dodecane, tridecane and tetradecane.<BR>
It can be seen that CEP-lines are originating in a CEP of a binary system. When two lines of different nature merge, a tricritical point occurs.  <P>

<B>Current and future aspects</B><BR>
In order to be able to generalize the experimentally obtained information, correlation and prediction of the data with a suitable model will be attempted.<BR>
All mole fractions referred to here are overall compositions. However, in an industrial separation process for example, the mole fractions of the coexisting phases has to be known. <P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-213</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B015-322</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/ospt96ps.html 130.89.50.60 19970216180014 text/html 3137
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:53:37 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Tuesday, 03-Dec-96 07:35:25 GMT
Content-length: 2956
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Phase Behaviour and Modelling of Aqueous Electrolyte Systems at Near-Critical Conditions
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>The Phase Behaviour and Modelling of Aqueous Electrolyte Systems at Near-Critical Conditions</H2>
PhD Student	: ir Peter Jan Smits	(Phone	: +31 15 278 2118)<BR>
Fax: +31 15 278 8047      E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:P.J.Smits@stm.tudelft.nl">P.J.Smits@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor	: NWO/SON<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="ps.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B> Introduction</B><BR>
 The phase behaviour of near- and supercritical aqueous systems is of importance in various engineering applications, such as supercritical water oxidation (SCWO) processes for the destruction of hazardous wastes, and hydrothermal conversion of biomass for power generation purposes.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Experimental investigation of the fluid phase behaviour of model systems for SCWO processes.
<LI>Modelling of experimental data using advanced EoS (APACT,SAFT)
</UL>

<B>Previous Work</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>APACT EoS modelling of properties of pure H<SUB>2</SUB>O
<LI>APACT EoS fluid phase equilibrium calcutations for H<SUB>2</SUB>O/CH<SUB>4</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>O/C<SUB>2</SUB>H<SUB>8</SUB> at high temperatures and pressures
<LI>Measurement of high-pressure-high-temperature fluid phase equilibria of the systems H<SUB>2</SUB>O/CF<SUB>4</SUB> and H2O/CF4/NaCl
</UL>

<B>Present Work</B><BR>
<UL><LI>Measurement of high-pressure-high-temperature fluid phase equilibria of the systems H<SUB>2</SUB>O/CHF<SUB>3</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>O/CHF<SUB>3</SUB>/NaCl is currently in progress
</UL>

<B>Future Work</B><BR>
<UL><LI>Modelling of experimental results with APACT and SAFT
</UL>

<B>Experiments</B><BR>
(Gas+gas) equilibria for the above mentioned systems have been measured in a high-pressure autoclave with sapphire windows and magnetic stirring. The temperature range was 580&lt;T/K&lt;673 and the pressure range 20&lt;p/MPa&lt;200. Isopleths for the system H<SUB>2</SUB>O/CF<SUB>4</SUB> are presented as an example in figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="ps1.gif" WIDTH=398 HEIGHT=411><P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
From the experimental results it can be concluded that the binary system CF<SUB>4</SUB> + H<SUB>2</SUB>O exhibits type-III fluid phase behaviour according to the classification of Van Konynenburg and Scott. Although only two critical points could be measured in the binary system, the course of the critical locus suggests that this system exhibits (gas + gas) immiscibility of the second kind. Addition of NaCl shifts the immiscibility region towards higher temperatures (salting-out phenomenon). Barotropy was observed in both the binary and ternary systems.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
