</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gas-Anti-Solvent Process
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Gas-Anti-Solvent Process</H2>
PostDoc:			Dr. Juan C. de la Fuente B. (<A HREF="mailto:J.delaFuente@STM.TUDelft.nl">J.delaFuente@STM.TUDelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor:			Delft University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="jf.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B> Introduction</B><BR>
The addition of a third component to an organic solvent, in which a solid has been dissolved, to assure crystallization of this solid, is an attractive route to produce pure solid organic materials with a prescribed particle size distribution and morphology. The component that is added is typically a dense gas near its critical point. This process, called Gas-Anti-Solvent Process, (GAS-Process), exploits the ability of gases to dissolve in organic liquids and to lower the solvent power of the liquid for the compounds in solution, which causes the solids to precipitate. If an organic liquid (which is a solvent for the solid to be recrystallized) and a gas are at least partially miscible, introduction of the gas into the liquid solution will result in expansion of the liquid phase, reducing its solvent power for the solid, and the solid will precipitate.  The size and morphology of the crystal can be changed by variation of the process parameters.<P>

<B>Thermodynamic Modeling</B><BR>
The antisolvent-solvent-solute ternary system, exhibits three phase solid-liquid-vapor (SLV) equilibria. For the description of this system the Peng-Robinson equation of state has been selected. Knowing the interaction coefficients used in the Van der Waals mixing rules, the Peng-Robinson EOS has proved that it is capable to describe the SLV phase equilibria of the system like as; carbon dioxide (antisolvent) + toluene (solvent) + naphthalene (solute). It can thus assumed that the fluid phase behavior of systems, can be reasonably well described, even if no experimental data are available. For the GAS process, the expansion of solvent is responsible for the crystallization of solute. However, for a given antisolvent and a given mole fraction, all expansions are similar, which would imply that the solubility of the solid in the solvent is the limiting factor for a successful crystallization process [Kordikowki et al., 1995].<P>

<IMG SRC="jf1.gif" WIDTH=343 HEIGHT=378><P>

<B>Future Works</B><BR>
Considering the presented information about the phase behavior of the antisolvent-solvent-solute ternary system, the goal of this work is to find a way to select the "best conditions" for the production of the crystals. More specifically, a correlation is needed that computes the mole fraction of the solute in the liquid phase at given equilibrium pressure and temperature from the pure component parameters of the components present in the mixture. With this correlation the "best combination" antisolvent-solvent for a given solute will be suggested. If necessary, extra information of the fluid phase equilibria will be obtained experimentally.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Kordikowski, A., Schenk A.P., Van Niellen R.M., and Peters C.J. The J. of Supercritical Fluids. 1995, 8(3), 205.</FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
