<HEAD>
<TITLE>Enzymatic Reactions in Near-Critical Fluids
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Enzymatic Reactions in Near-Critical Fluids</H2>
Ph.D.-student:	Ir Rob M.M. Stevens (<A HREF="mailto:R.Stevens@STM.TUDelft.nl">R.Stevens@STM.TUDelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor:		Delft University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="rs.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The influence of pressure and water activity on the enzyme is of main importance in enzymatic reactions under near-critical conditions. For better understanding both the phase behaviour of the reactants with the near-critical carbon dioxide as the water adsorption isotherms of the enzyme  are investigated.<P>

<B>VLE measurements and modelling</B><BR>
The phase behaviour of the binary systems consisting of the reactants vinyl acetate, 2-butyl acetate, and 2-butanol, + the solvent carbon dioxide has been measured and modelled. As can be seen e.g. the experimental data for 2-butanol + CO<SUB>2</SUB> have been fitted with the PRSV/WS EOS, which gave very good results.<P>

<IMG SRC="rs1.gif" WIDTH=380 HEIGHT=276><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Fig 1.: P, x bubble point curves for five temperatures (283, 303, 313, 353 and 413 K) . Symbols: experimental data; solid lines: temperature dependent interaction coefficient; dashed lines: tempt independent; dotted: prediction with 313 K parameters.</FONT><P>

<B>Solubilities and EOS predictions</B><BR>
For determining the phase behaviour at low concentrations of reactants a new apparatus for determining the mutual solubilities has been designed. All three above mentioned systems are measured and an example is given for 2-butanol + carbon dioxide. The EOS parameters determined from the VLE measurements are used to predict the solubilities. As shown the PRSV/WS gave better results compared to the purely predictive LCVM model.<P>

<IMG SRC="rs2.gif" WIDTH=389 HEIGHT=264><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Fig 2.: Solubility isotherms (303, 313, 333 K) of 2-butanol in CO<SUB>2</SUB>. Symbols: experimental data; solid lines: LCVM-prediction; dashed lines: PRSV/WS prediction</FONT><P>

<IMG SRC="rs2.gif" WIDTH=389 HEIGHT=264><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Fig.3: Water adsorption isotherms of PcL(+), im PcL(o) and Celite(triangle). Symbols: experimental data; lines: BETisotherms</FONT> <P>

In order to get an idea of the amount of water present on the Pseudomonas cepacia lipase as a function of water activity, the adsorption isotherms are measured above saturated salt solutions for the enzyme and carrier. It appeared that the BET adsorption theory describes this behaviour satisfactory.<P>

<B>Future aspects</B><BR>
Adsorption isotherms are determined in NCCO<SUB>2</SUB> and the phase behaviour is modelled in order to perform the model reaction in NCCO<SUB>2</SUB>.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
