<HEAD>
<TITLE>Interfacial Tensions and Fluid Phase Behaviour for Near-Critical Gas Condensates
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Interfacial Tensions and Fluid Phase Behaviour for Near-Critical Gas Condensates</H2>
Researcher:	ir P.M.W. Cornelisse (<A HREF="mailto:P.J.Cornelisse@STM.TUDelft.nl">P.J.Cornelisse@STM.TUDelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor:	EC<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="pc.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The project performed at the Delft University of Technology is part of a larger research project, which is sponsored by the EC. The objective of this research project is to improve the modelling of the gas and oil flow processes that occur in near-critical hydrocarbon fields. The task carried out by  the Delft University of Technology mainly concerns the proper description of the fluid phase equilibria and the behaviour of interfacial tensions.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Modelling of near-critical phase behaviour in multicomponent mixtures.
<LI>Modelling of the interfacial tensions between fluid phases at near-critical conditions.
<LI>Description of wetting behaviour at solid surfaces and oil/water interfaces.
</UL>

<B>Research plan</B><BR>
To fulfill the just mentioned objectives, a model fluid was selected composed of five hydrocarbons ranging from methane to tetradecane. For this mixture the phase behaviour will be studied at near-critical conditions.<P>

In addition the liquid-vapour interfacial tensions of the mixture are examined by means of the square gradient approximation of van der Waals. Additionally, an attempt is made to study the wetting transitions of this mixture when it is in contact with a solid surface or with a water interface. Because it is expected that these transitions are difficult to be described, first a pure fluid is brought into contact with a solid or water interface. For this purpose hexane has been selected.<P>


<B>Results</B><BR>
It was found so far that the liquid-vapour interfacial tensions of multicomponent mixtures can be modeled accurately, although only mixtures with less than three components can be dealt with. The description of the near-critical area has been successful only for pure fluids.<P>

In addition it was found from computations with the square gradient theory that the wetting transitions that take place at hexane/water interfaces are strongly influenced by the values of the gradient parameters and the model that is used to describe the phase behaviour. A typical wetted hexane/water interface is presented in the figure below.<P>

<IMG SRC="pc1.gif" WIDTH=340 HEIGHT=273><P>

Study of hexane in contact with a solid surface by means of Cahn's theory shows that several different types of transition may take place. These transitions are subject of further research.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
In the next months the study will concentrate on extension of the results to mixtures with more than one component present. The goal is that calculations can be performed for mixtures with five or more components present.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
