<HEAD>
<TITLE>Modeling and Predicting Liquid-Liquid Equilibria   of Water-Electrolyte-Solvent Systems
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Modeling and Predicting Liquid-Liquid Equilibria   of Water-Electrolyte-Solvent Systems</H2>
Ph.. D.-student:	 Mark Wijtkamp (<A HREF="mailto:M.Wijtkamp@STM.TUDelft.nl">M.Wijtkamp@STM.TUDelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor:		DSM Research/ Delft University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="mw.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Caprolactam is the monomer of NYLON-6 and specifications for such material are extremely stringent, requiring extensive purification. The production of caprolactam is realized in a multi step process with coproduction of many by-products. The main starting materials for the caprolactam production are benzene or toluene, where the first step involves the production of cyclohexanone. This intermediate  is converted into cyclohexanone oxim, using hydroxylamine. Caprolactam is obtained after rearranging the oxim in the so-called Backman rearrangement. By neutralizing the  acid rearrangement mixture, two aqueous phases are obtained, where both coexisting phases are subjected to several extraction units, yielding pure caprolactam (figure 1).<BR>
In modeling the extraction process, the thermodynamic modeling of the liquid-liquid equilibria, occurring in the extraction units, is necessary.<P>

<IMG SRC="mw1.gif" WIDTH=544 HEIGHT=494><P>

Figure 1. Caprolactam production (Lo et al., 1991).<P>

<B>Goals</B><BR>
Modeling and predicting the liquid-liquid equilibria of water-electrolyte-solvent systems is still difficult, from a thermodynamic point of view. In describing the phase equilibria of  the system water-caprolactam-ammonium sulphate-  organic solvents, it will be aimed to develop a dedicated model.<BR>
Because of the unavailability or lack of development of reliable models, testing and further development of existing models is essential. <BR>
The development of a dedicated model requires experiments, where the influence of the organic solvents and ammonium sulphate on the phase equilibria is investigated.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
Before the development of a dedicated model can be achieved, an experimental program will be carried out. This program consists of measuring liquid-liquid, and liquid-liquid-liquid equilibria of the systems water-caprolactam-ammonium sulphate-organic solvents. The experiments will be performed at 1 atm and temperatures equal or higher than room temperature. The organic solvents that will be investigated are benzene, toluene, and a mixture of cyclohexane/second component (e.g. alcohol, ketone). <BR>
After acquisition of the experimental data, modeling of the phase equilibria will be performed. This will be done by using existing or adjusted models. Examples of models which can be used for the calculation of thermodynamic properties of electrolyte solutions are the NRTL, UNIFAC or the Zerres & Prausnitz model (Zerres and Prausnitz, 1994). <P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Lo, T.C., Baird, M.H.I., and Hanson, C., <I>Handbook of Solvent Extraction</I>, Krieger, Malabar, 1991.<BR>
Zerres, H., and Prausnitz J.M., 1994, AIChE J, 40, 676.<BR></FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
