<HEAD>
<TITLE>Phase behaviour in aqueous two-phase systems of (bio)polymers
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Phase behaviour in aqueous two-phase systems of (bio)polymers</H2>
Ph.D.-student:	Ir. F. Roos (<A HREF="mailto:F.Roos@STM.TUDelft.nl">F.Roos@STM.TUDelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor:		ABON<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="fr.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
At present there is a growing interest in the use of aqueous two-phase systems (ATPS) as a powerful, but mild separation technique for mixtures of biomolecules. As it is important in industry to properly design appropriate separation equipment the knowledge of phase equilibria is a prerequisite. As not many data on these ATPS is available the main objective of this project is to acquire fundamental thermodynamic information and develop a correlative, and if possible predictive, model.<P>

<IMG SRC="fr1.gif" WIDTH=337 HEIGHT=184><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><I><B>Figure 1.</B> General set-up of the project</I><P></FONT>

<B>Set-up of the project</B><BR>
As is schematically represented in figure 1 the project focusses on three different approaches to relate the (bio)polymers to be used to the requested phase equilibria. The first approach will be using a kind of group contribution method (GCM) which is hoped to  yield an entirely predictive model based on the structures of the components present in the ATPS. In this approach attention is also given to ideas concerning changing water structures as a result of different solutes <SUP>(1)</SUP>.The second idea is related to the so-called corresponding state principle (CSP) and is assumed to allow predictions of the phase behaviour based on a very limited number of simple experiments <SUP>(2)</SUP>.<BR>
Finally it is also possible, although extremely time consuming, to determine the phase behaviour by means of an entirely experimental program.<P>

<B>Present interest</B><BR>
As can be seen in figure 1 the virial coefficient is considered a main parameter in  relation to the predictive models. Therefore it is essential to acquire a thorough knowledge about how the (osmotic) virial coefficients relates to the phase behaviour. However with respect to the CSP  it is even more important to determine the relation between the experimentally determined osmotic pressures and the osmotic virial equation, especially the consideration about the truncation of the equation after the second or the third osmotic virial coefficient is taken into consideration. Another point of interest is the interactions between the different components in the solutions. It is known that these interactions are the basis of the second and higher virial coefficients, so getting a feeling for their magnitude and for the sensitivity of the model towards (small) deviations is of great importance for future modelling.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
Regarding the lack of relevant data concerning  the ATPS the first objective will be to perform osmotic pressure experiments on these systems. The experiments will be conducted on systems containing mixtures of (bio)polymers as well as on aqueous solutions of each of the compounds of these mixtures. Later on these experimental data will be used in the modelling of the phase behaviour of the aqueous two-phase systems of interest. Also a sensitivity study will be carried out on the (cross) interaction coefficients within these systems.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>(1) Zaslavsky, B.Y., Aqueous Two-Phase Partitioning, 1995<BR>
(2) Wang, L., Bloomfield, V.A., Macromolecules 23, 1990, 194<BR></FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
