<HEAD>
<TITLE>PhD-projects Delft 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H1>Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology</H1>
<H2>Research group Bioprocess Design</H2>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="tud.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

In the research group Bioprocess Design the attention is focused on the integration of bioconversion, downstream processing and control in the development of the total (bio)process. Research is subdivided in three main themes:<P>

<OL>
<LI><B>Biokinetics and Biocatalysis</B><BR>
Emphasis is placed on the modelling of the kinetics of biological systems for application in processes with an increased return. Chiral compounds and the analytical-chemical techniques used to separate them play an important part in this work. 

<LI><B>Metabolic Modelling, Monitoring and Process Control</B><BR>
The stricter demands concerning product quality, environment, safety regulations and profitability of fermentation processes increase the need for good control. Mechanistic and black box models (Artificial Neural Networks) are being exploited for model based control. Also, attention is given to state estimation ("software sensors"), fault diagnosis and data reconciliation.

<LI><B>Bioreactor Design and Downstream Processing</B><BR>
This research is concerned with the technological aspects of biotechnological production processes and environmental processes. Special attention is given to methodology (regime analysis and scale-up) and hydrodynamics. Process integration and process intensification have been driving forces for innovative projects on downstream processing.
</OL>

<H3>Research team</H3><BR>

