<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Control of waste water treatment plants
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Control of waste water treatment plants</H2>
Researcher:	Ir. C. Hellinga   ((015) 278 50 25)<BR>
Promotor:		Prof.dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen, Prof.ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Supervisor:	Dr.ir. M.C.M. van Loosdrecht   (015) 278 16 18, Prof.ir. H.B. Verbruggen (Fac. of Electrical Engineering, DUT)<BR>
Institute:		Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Project term:	April 1995  - April 1999<BR>
Financed by:	DUT<BR>
BSDL-sector:	Environmental Biotechnology - control<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="ch.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The main objectives for controlling municipal waste water treatment plants are 1) to get maximum purification at minimum costs  -energy and/or chemical additions-  (short term goal) and 2) maintaining the relevant microbial  populations as activated sludge inside the plant (long term goal).  Increasingly stricter legislations for the effluent composition, new investments for plant extensions, or better measurement and control strategies are becoming necessary. Because improved control will often be the cheaper alternative, there is an emerging interest for new approaches in this area.<P>

This project focuses on several items:<BR>
improving the observability of the dynamical behaviour waste water treatment plants by using off-gas analyses,<BR>
developing new control strategies based on modern modelling and control techniques (Artificial Neural Networks, Fuzzy Control, Model Based Predictive Control)<BR>
Developing control strategics for the SHARON process<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><P>

The in our laboratory newly developed SHARON process (biological nitrogen removal without sludge retention) will be built on full scale at the Rotterdam Waste Water Treatment Plant (WWTP) Dokhaven.<P>

A strategy for pH control was evaluated in simulation with practical influent data. The process turned out to be very robust with respect to influent disturbances. <BR>
Off-gas analyses (CO<SUB>2</SUB>, O<SUB>2</SUB>) are proceeeding in the underground Dokhaven plant (A/B process). First results show that these data are not only indicative for the plant load but also for the influent composition. In the same plant, an experimental program runs to study the dynamic behaviour of intermediate settling tanks.<P>

<B>Research Plans</B><P>

Results of the experimental programs at Dokhaven (off-gas and intermediate settling tanks) will become available in autumn 1996. If possible, the obtained insight will be used to evaluate in simulation new opportunities for improving overall plant performance, especially with respect to N-removal. A new experimental program will be carried out at Genemuiden WWTP for evaluating the usefulness for monitoring and control of a new NADH probe. The start-up procedure of the SHARON process will be studied in simulation.<P>

