<HEAD>
<TITLE>Kinetic resolution in organic solvents
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Kinetic resolution in organic solvents</H2>
PhD student:	A. Wolff, M.Sc.   (+31 - 15 - 278 23 30)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof.dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
Supervisor: 	Dr.ir. A.J.J. Straathof   (015 278 23 30)<BR>
Project term:	January 1993 - January 1997<BR>
Financed by:	SON - Process Technology <BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="aw.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Enzymatic kinetic resolution reactions is one of the most important methods to obtain pharmaceuticals and agrochemicals that are not contaminated with the "wrong" enantiomer. <BR>
The performance of such processes are to a large extent determined by the solvent system used. In this project kinetic models of enzymatic reactions in (organic) solvents will be set up and applied to optimize kinetic resolution processes.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to develop kinetic models for enantioselective enzymatic reactions in (organic) solvents and to use these models for process development.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
A theory, which relates the enzymatic activity and enantioselectivity to the thermodynamic activity of the solute in different solvents, correctly explains the experimental data that have been obtained so far: With increasing amounts of cosolvent, the solubility of the substrate increased up to 20-fold. However, this was counteracted by a 20-fold increase in K<SUB>m</SUB> for both enantiomers R and S (Fig. 1). The net rate went down upon addition of organic solvents, because Vmax decreased. The enantioselectivity remained constant in any solvent type, thus pure water appeared to be the best environment for an efficient reaction in this case. Because there seem to be no clear advantages in the addition of cosolvents for the asymmetric hydrolysis of particular esters with a low water-solubility, we heave studied a suspension process.<P>

<IMG SRC="aw1.gif" WIDTH=435 HEIGHT=256><P>

We have developed a simple model that incorporates the kinetics of substrate dissolution and the kinetics of enzymatic reaction (Fig 2). <P>

<IMG SRC="aw2.gif" WIDTH=421 HEIGHT=284><P>

The model predicted and the experiments confirmed that increasing the reaction temperature was more beneficial to the productivity than the addition of water-miscible solvents.  The advantages of using substrate suspended in water are that the enzymatic conversion rate is higher than in organic solvent, the amount of substrate per reactor volume can be extremely high (despite the low solubility of the substrate), and no organic solvent is needed.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
