<HEAD>
<TITLE>Enzymatic hydrolysis in organic solvent
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Enzymatic hydrolysis in organic solvent</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. M.J.J. Litjens   (+31 15 278 23 30)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof.dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
Supervisor: 	Dr.ir. A.J.J. Straathof   (+31 15 278 23 30)<BR>
Project term:	October 1995 - October 1999<BR>
Financed by:	ABON<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Enzymatic ester hydrolysis is widely applied, a.o. in the production of fatty acids and chiral compounds. Esters are often poorly soluble in water, therefore these processes are usually carried out in a water/organic solvent biphasic system.
One can think of several cases where an aqueous phase is undesirable: for instance when the substrate or the product is not stable in water, or when the desired product is hard to isolate from an aqueous environment. In these cases it can be advantageous to perform the process in an organic solvent, in the absence of a water phase. The reaction water that is needed for hydrolysis, can be added by saturating the solvent with water, e.g.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to demonstrate that ester hydrolysis without a separate water phase is a feasible process. Because the reaction equilibrium in organic solvents is unfavourable, one of the products must  be  removed  from  the reaction mixture.<P>

<IMG SRC="ml1.gif" WIDTH=427 HEIGHT=282><P>

Figure 1. Model system: kinetic resolution of racemic ethyl-2-chloropropionic acid using <I>Candida rugosa</I> lipase in dichloromethane<P>

For this reason ammonium bicarbonate is added, causing the carboxylic acid to form a  precipitating ion pair with ammonium ions. After removing the precipitated ion pair from the reaction mixture, pure carboxylic acid and ammonia should be recoverable upon heating (see <B>Figure 1</B>).<P>


<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
Experiments confirmed that the addition of ammonium bicarbonate improved the reaction yield, complete conversion was obtained with a ten-fold overdose of ammonium bicarbonate (See <B>Figure 2</B>). The enantioselectivity of the reaction is comparable with other solvent systems<SUP>1</SUP>.<P>

<IMG SRC="ml2.gif" WIDTH=455 HEIGHT=261><P>

Figure 2. Kinetic resolution with (+) and without (-) ammonium bicarbonate<P>

Presently, we are studying the hydrolysis of glycidyl butyrate by Pig Pancreas Lipase, also in the presence of ammonium bicarbonate. The equilibria of reaction and precipitation of this  reaction system will be investigated in detail.<P>

<B>Reference</B><BR>
<SUP>1</SUP>Rakels et al. (1994), <I>Tetrahedron: Asym.</I>, 5, 93-100<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
