<HEAD>
<TITLE>Enzymatic processes for  B-lactam antibiotics
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Enzymatic processes for  B-lactam antibiotics</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. M. Diender  (+31-15-278 51 23)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof.dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
Supervisor: 	Dr.ir. A.J.J. Straathof   (+31-15-278 23 30)<BR>
Project term:	August 1996 - August 2000<BR>
Institute:		T.U. Delft, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Financed by:	Chemferm- Clusterproject Min. EZ <BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="md.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The fine chemical industry is one of the industry segments where the impact of bio-catalysis is felt most profoundly. Possible explanations are:
<UL>
<LI>	the need to replace traditional, stoichio-metric processes in order to improve the product to waste ratio,
<LI>	the failure to translate chemocatalytic processes from petrochemicals to fine chemicals,
<LI>	the ready acceptance of enzymes by theorganic chemist as part of his toolbox, whereas organic chemistry is still the dominating discipline in fine chemical industry,
<LI>	the low entry barrier, i.e. low investments, for new technologies in this small scale industry, facilitated by the fact that fine chemical companies become increasingly part of larger industrial conglomerates.
</UL>

<B>Synthesis of semi-synthetic antibiotics</B><BR>
The industrial production of semi-synthetic antibiotics, with a history of some 30 years, is an outstanding example of the development of biocatalysis. The original synthesis of semi-synthetic antibiotics, <I>e.g.</I> cefalexin starting from benzaldehyde and fermentation of  penicillin G is a ten-step process employing stoichiometric chemistry only and causing a waste stream of 30-40 kg per kg of end product. In the <I>Chemferm</I> process only six steps are needed, whereby biocatalysis is involved in three of  them.However, when it comes to the design of  the production plant for the final coupling step, the engineers are faced with an equilibrium process requiring recycle of starting materials and handling of many solids:
<UL>
<LI>	crystallisation and isolation of the desiredsemi-synthetic antibiotic,
<LI>	crystallisation and recovery of excess starting materials,
<LI>	crystallisation and isolation of  by-products from undesired hydrolysis  of  both end product and side-chain precursor.
</UL>

<B>Plans</B><BR>
Integration of  biocatalysis in the synthesis of semi-synthetic  B-lactam antibiotics, <I>e.g.</I> amoxycillin or ampicillin, greatly reduces the number of steps and is of considerable benefit to the environment by eliminating organic waste. The overall production process, how-ever, is more complicated, because of several recycle streams and a large number of solids to be handled. 
A better understanding of enzyme action and a rational design of  improved biocatalysts (including immobilisation) are needed to reach more ideal processes where recycles are eliminated. Also, optimal process conditions, <I>e.g</I> in a sieve bottom reactor, are required to achieve feasible processes at plant scale.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
This project has only recently started.<P>

<B>Reference</B><BR>
A. Bruggink, Chimia <B>50</B> (1996) 431-432.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
