<HEAD>
<TITLE>Enantioselective reductions by yeast
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Enantioselective reductions by yeast</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. W.F.H. Sybesma   (+31- 15 - 278 53 07)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof.dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
Supervisor: 	Dr.ir. A.J.J. Straathof   (+31 - 15 278 23 30)<BR>
Institute:		Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology<BR>
University:	Delft University of Technology<BR>
Project term:	August 1996 - August 2000<BR>
Financed by:	IOP-catalysis<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="ws.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Since several decades it is well-known that Baker's yeast (<I>Saccharomyces cerevisiae</I>) can be applied as redox-biocatalyst. Recently new interest in the catalytic potential of this microorganism has been shown because of the importance of enantioselective catalysis.<P>

<B>Advantages are:</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>	The active cell mass is extremely cheap and is available in unlimited quantities. Dried baker's yeast can be stored easily.
<LI>	Handling of baker's yeast is simple. Most conversions can be performed in conventional apparatus, and with cheap, harmless ingredients. No special microbial or fermentation expertise is required, and aseptic procedures are not necessary.
<LI>	Baker's yeast is neither toxic nor pathogenic.
<LI>	A huge number of yeast-catalyzed biotransformations is known. For example, for hundreds of ketones, hydroxyketones, ketoacids, ketoesters and alkenes, reductions have been performed at a high level of enantio- or regioselectivity.
</UL>
<B>Disadvantages are:</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>	The productivity is low, so large amounts of yeast are required. This hampers the product isolation and leads to waste problems.
<LI>	Often low substrate concentrations are used, which is disadvantageous for the downstream processing.
<LI>	Usually the enantiomeric purity of the product is too low, because several oxidoreductases with different enantioselec-tivities are active in the yeast, e.g.
</UL>

On a laboratory scale, reductions with yeast are carried out conveniently, and kg-productions have been accomplished. However, on a production scale the aforementioned disadvantages usually prevail. The purpose of this project is to find ways to make the reductions considerably more efficient. Therefore commercially available baker's yeast cell mass will be studied with respect to selective redox-conversions of alcohols/ketones that are commercially relevant. The model system of choice is the enantioselective reduction of a ketoacid ester to the corresponding hydroxyacid ester.<BR>
The goal is a procedure that leads to an enantiomeric excess of 99%, with a high yield, a high productivity, that is easily carried out, reproducible, can be scaled up and has a low environmental burden.<BR>
By a collaboration on enzymological, microbiological and technological areas the required improvements should be obtained. Enzymological studies will be performed to determine the presence and activity of the relevant enzymes. Subsequently, using knowledge of the physiology of yeasts and the technological aspects of bioconversions, the model system will be optimized with respect to (enantiomeric) purity, product yield and isolation, and economical use of the biocatalyst. Optimization may be performed by induction of the required enzymes, by specific adjustments of the redox balance, by immobilization of the yeast and by fed-batch processing.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
This project has only recently started.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

