<HEAD>
<TITLE>Enzymatic synthesis of hydroxynitriles
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Enzymatic synthesis of hydroxynitriles</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. A.A. Boogert   (+31- 15 - 278 51 23)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof.dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
Supervisor: 	Dr.ir. A.J.J. Straathof   (+31- 15 - 278 23 30)<BR>
Project term:	September 1996 - September 2000<BR>
Financed by:	IOP-catalysis<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Enantiomerically pure hydroxynitriles are versatile building blocks for the synthesis of pharmaceuticals, crop protection agents and liquid crystals. Homochiral hydroxynitriles can be produced with the use of a biocatalyst like the enzyme R-oxynitrilase from almonds. This enzyme catalyses the addition of hydrogen cyanide to an aldehyde to form  R-hydroxynitrile. The major advantages of R-oxynitrilase are its low cost price, broad substrate range, high atom efficiency and enantiomeric specificity.  Although much research has been done on the production of hydroxynitriles on a lab scale, there is no successful application on an industrial scale.
Some problems in the enzymatic production of hydroxynitriles are the occurence of the competing, nonspecific chemical addition of cyanide to aldehydes, low enzyme stability and the production of a waste stream containing hydrogen cyanide. <P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

The aim of this project is to develop an industrial process for the enzymatic production of enantiomerically enriched hydroxynitriles. The process will be optimized by looking at enzyme kinetics, reactor type,  immobilization and stability of the enzyme and downstream processing.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

This project has only recently started.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

