<HEAD>
<TITLE>Combining Neural Networks with Deterministic Models
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Combining Neural Networks with Deterministic Models</H2>
Ph.D. student:	Eric van Can<BR>
Promotors:	Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben, Prof. dr.ir. Heijnen<BR>
Supervisor:	Ir. C. Hellinga<BR>
Institute:	Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Project term:	October 1992 - October 1996<BR>
Financed by: 	Delft University of Technology<BR>
OSPT:	BSDL sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="evc.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Mathematical models are very useful tools for optimisation and control of (bio)chemical processes. Unfortunately, accurate dynamic models are not directly available for a given process. Different modelling approaches exist:<P>

<IMG SRC="evc1.gif" WIDTH=511 HEIGHT=149><P>

The aim of this research is to develop methods to obtain accurate models with good extrapolation properties for optimisation and control of (bio)chemical processes.<P>

<B>Grey Box Modelling Approach </B><BR>
Dynamic models in (bio)chemical engineering are always based on macroscopic balances. These balances contain accurately known terms (e.g. diffusive transport) and inaccurately known terms (e.g. kinetics of conversion). The inaccurately known terms can be modelled by a neural network, which is an easy to use non-linear black box modelling technique. The identification data only have to cover the input-output space of the inaccurately known terms and the accurately known terms can be used for extrapolation. As a result one obtains an accurate model with a limited experimental effort and without the need to develop a rigorous deterministic model. Furthermore , the model can be extrapolated reliable outside the domain of the identification data.<P>
Main research topics concern:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>relation between domain of the identification data and the application domain of the model
<LI>fast identification of neural networks
<LI>choice of identification experiments
<LI>thorough validation of interpolation and extrapolation properties
</UL>

<B>Test Cases</B><BR>
The grey box modelling approach has successfully been applied to the real time modelling and control of  a pressure vessel. Currently, the approach is tested on the modelling of the enzymatic conversion of penicillin G including temperature and pH effects.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-227</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B016-185</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/mj.html 130.89.50.60 19970216180314 text/html 3439
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:56:39 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
