<HEAD>
<TITLE>Three Phase Suspension Reactors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Three Phase Suspension Reactors</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. Marc H. van der Jagt  ((015) 278 10 06)<BR>
Promotor:		Prof ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Supervisor:	dr.ir. R.G.J.M. van der Lans   ((015) 278 10 06)<BR>
Institute:		Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Project term:	1992 - 1996<BR>
Financed by:	Ministry of Economic Affairs (IOP-MBT)<BR>
OSPT		BSDL-sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess design<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="mj.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

The background of the research was the successful development of a wet soil cleaning reactor picture. Basically the tapered formed reactor integrates a classification of coarse relatively slightly polluted fractions like sand and fines as well as biological treatment of the fines.<BR>
Essential for the process economics at full scale is the energy which is needed to attain a state of suspension. Suspending particles is the limiting part of the process.<P>

The research aims at the development of a model which relates the power necessary to establish a suspension in pneumatically agitated multiphase systems and the characteristics of a suspension such as particle concentration and concentration distributions. The reactor is a model validation tool.<P>

<IMG SRC="mj1.gif" WIDTH=320 HEIGHT=309><P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
In our view three mechanisms play a role in the particles distribution. Sedimentation on one hand is counteracted by particle entrainment by the liquid flow and turbulent dispersion due to the same flow on the other. In very densely concentrated systems there is not really a separate liquid and solids phase but one pseudo monophase with its hydrodynamic properties determined by the relevant solids fraction. As a result in such a system dispersion is dominating and determines the phases concentration profiles.<P>

<B>Present state of the research and future</B><BR>
Recently hydrodynamic models have been developed decribing liquid and slurry flow in aerated vessels including the dits reactor. A discrete compartment model is constructed as well as a continuous version predicting the flow profiles very reasonably. For the rest an elegant flow based model is used to simulate measured concentration profiles and further turbulent dispersion now is being integrated into the model.<BR>
Since the model parameters are flows and particle concentrations verification is done by reasonably simple physical measurements with electromagnetic and optical probes. Besides the experiments carried out in the described reactor multiphase behaviour is investigated in bubble columns. For that purpose a bubble column was constructed with variable air and recirculation water injection possibilities. Yet polydisperse measurements with basalt and sand in the column equipped with a conical sparger are done and next on the programme are air lift draught tube measurements.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-228</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B016-205</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/cui.html 130.89.50.60 19970216180326 text/html 3194
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 17:56:51 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Thursday, 05-Dec-96 07:52:59 GMT
Content-length: 3012
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Regime analysis of fungal fermentations
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Regime analysis of fungal fermentations</H2>
PhD student:	Cui Yi Qing, MSc   (015 278 2363)<BR>
Supervisor:	Dr.Ir. Rob G.J.M. van der Lans   (015 278 1006)<BR>
Project term:	September 1992 - September 1996<BR>
Financed by:	Unilever<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="cui.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Fungal fermentation is a complex process in which numerous problems arise. The scale up and optimization of this process still rely on empiricism and tradition. One of the reasons is the diverse fungal morphologies. The hydrodynamic conditions in a bioreactor, fungal morphology and growth, broth rheology, and formation and secretion of the products interact with each other and all these parameters are very sensitive for scaling up and down.<P>

<IMG SRC="cui1.gif" WIDTH=332 HEIGHT=95><P>

<B>Aim, scope and set-up of research</B><BR>
The objective of this project is to study the scale-up of fungal fermentation processes from laboratory or pilot plant scale to production scale, concerning both the physical aspects of the bioreactor and the physiological aspects of fungal growth and morphology. Submerged fermentation of <I>Aspergillus awamori </I>with both synthetic medium and complex medium of wheat bran were used as the model system.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The results obtained are the following:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>	Numerous fungal fermentations have been carried out in 2 L, 15 L and 100 L fermenters. The information on morphology, growth, yield, maintenance and respiration with different substrate such as glucose, sucrose and wheat bran were obtained.


<LI>	When wheat bran is used, fungi may grow on its surface. We call this attachment or adhesion. 
	Factors which influence adhesion are studied.
<LI>	Agitation is normally used for mass and heat transfer, gas dispersion and certain homogenization in fermenters. How this agitation influences the morphology of the fungi was investigated.
<LI>	The effect of the dissolved oxygen tension on fungal morphology was studied in a parallel fermentation mode.
<LI>	A model of fungal fermentation in stirred bioreactors was developed, in which pellet size, biomass, fraction of filamentous mycelia in the total biomass, mass transfer in both pellets and in bulk, and mechanical damage were incorporated.
<LI>	Both the development of a compartment model and the measurement in 30 m<SUP>3</SUP> stirred vessel with various geometries and at different operation conditions were done.
<LI>	Correlations for the local power uptake of Rushton turbines in multi--impeller systems were obtained through a study of a large number of literature data.
</OL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="cui2.gif" WIDTH=342 HEIGHT=228><P>

