<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gradient elution in Centrifugal Partition Chromatography
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Gradient elution in Centrifugal Partition Chromatography</H2>
PhD student: Jr. M.J. van Buel (tel. 015-2782361, Email: <A HREF="mailto:M.Buel@stm.tudelft.nl">M.Buel@stm.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Promotor: Prof. lr. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Supervisor: ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen (tel. 015-2782361)<BR>
Institute: Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Project Term: August 1992-August 1996<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction:</B> Selectivity and capacity are
the key parameters in large scale
hromatographic processes. Conventional
large scale chromatographic processes
have some limitations that do not make
them optimal for all cases. One of the
bottlenecks is the limited sorbent
capacity, whereas one would like to
operate at the solubility limit. In
Centrifugal Partition Chromatography
(CPC), two liquid phases are used as the
mobile and the stationary phase. A
tortuous designed inner geometry of the
column in combination with a centrifugal
field retains one of the liquids in the
colunto (stationary phase), while the other
liquid phase (mobile phase) flows through the
stationary phase. Any combination of immiscible
liquids can be utilised and careful selection of the
two-phase system can fine-tune the system for a
particular separation. CPC has been shown to be a
valuable technique for the purification of
pharmaceutical and biotechnological products from
complex mixtures. Various elution modes are
possible, of which gradient elution has shown to be
a valuable tool to separate mixtures of components
with a wide range of partition coefficients e.g. plant
extracts and peptides. However, detailed
understanding of the underlying fundamentals of a
CPC separation which govern the
separation
efficiency, such as thermodynamics
and mass
transfer, is scarce. This makes
prediction,
optimisation and scale-up of CPC (gradient elution)
separations a difficult task.<P>

<B>Modelling:</B> Recent studies have shown that normal
mode effluent concentration profiles can be
predicted if the partition coefficients and mass
transfer coefficients of the components are known
(Van Buel <I>et al</I>., 1996). The model was modified to
make it suitable for prediction of gradient elution
separations. Parameters needed for the prediction of
effluent concentration profiles are the experimental
conditions (flow rate, stationary phase hold-up and
rotational frequency), and the partition coefficients
and the mass transfer coefficients as a function of
the gradient.<P>

<IMG SRC="mjb1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1:</B> Gradient elution separation. Dashed line is model
prediction, solid line is experimental data<P>

<B>Preliminary Results:</B> The model predictions were
compared to experimental effluent concentration
profiles of a gradient elution experiments for the
separation of chloro-methyl-phenols in the
heptane/methanol/water (HMW) system. The HMW
is extremely useful for gradient elution. The top
phase consists almost completely of heptane,
independent of the composition of the bottom
phase. By changing the composition of the mobile
phase (bottom phase) during a separation,
components with large differences in partition
coefficients can be separated. The result is shown in
Figure 1.<P>

<B>References</B><BR>
Van Buel, M.J., Van der Wielen, L.A.M., Luyben,
K.Ch.A.M., (1996). Effluent concentration profiles
in Centrifugal Partition Chromatography, <I>AIChE.
accepted for publication</I>.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
