<HEAD>
<TITLE>Centrifugal Adsorption Technology
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Centrifugal Adsorption Technology</H2>
PhD-student:	ir. M. Bisschops (+31-15-278 2151 / <A HREF="mailto:M.Bisschops@STM.TUDelft.NL">M.Bisschops@STM.TUDelft.NL</A>)<BR>
Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
Sponsor:	IOP Milieutechnologie-Preventie<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="mb.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Background</B><BR>
Adsorption and Ion Exchange are well established techniques for separating diluted components from large aqueous streams. These techniques are therefore applied in waste water treatment as well as in downstream processing of biotechnological products.
Conventional adsorption processes, however, suffer from being rather voluminous. Moreover, too high pressure drops and fouling are often a problem.<BR>
An enormous increase in separation efficiency can be obtained by using very small adsorbent particles. This will lead to very low mass transfer resistance and high interfacial area. However, countercurrent flow can only be obtained if a large force on the adsorbent particles can be applied. In this project we use the centrifugal force.<P>

<B>Equipment Development</B><BR>
An experimental setup has been constructed to demonstrate the concept of Centrifugal Adsorption Technology (CAT) and to identify bottlenecks is in the technology. This setup operated at low-g conditions and was therefore not appropriate for relevant experiments.<BR>
Based on the experiences with this machine, an experimental setup for high-g conditions (up to 1000 g) has been constructed as well. This allows application of small adsorbent particles (typical particle diameter 30 &#181;m).<BR>
Afther having demonstrated the feasibility of the technology, the concept has been patented (Bisschops et al., 1996).<P>

<B>Experimental program</B><BR>
Essentially, there are a few phenomena that will determine the operation of CAT-equipment:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> 	Hydrodynamic capacity
<LI> 	Solids holdup in the column
<LI> 	Degree of backmixing
</UL>
These are therefore be investigated in the experimental setup. Other topics that are being studied are the swelling behavior of resin materials and ion exchange isotherms.<P>

<IMG SRC="mb1.gif" WIDTH=281 HEIGHT=147><P>

Drawing of the High-g rotor<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
Calculations show that a decrease in equipment volume of several orders of magnitude can be obtained. This yield the following advantages:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> 	Compact equipment allows the use on sites with lack of space,
<LI> 	Short contact times allow the processing of sensitive (biotechnological) products,
<LI> 	Low adsorbent inventory allows the use of more selective materials.
M/UL>

<B>References</B><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>M.A.T. Bisschops, L.A.M. van der Wielen and K.Ch.A.M. Luyben, Dutch Patent NL 52483 (1996)</FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
