<HEAD>
<TITLE>Volatile acids and salts as clean auxiliary materials in protein precipitation processes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Volatile acids and salts as clean auxiliary materials in protein precipitation processes</H2>
PhD student: ir. G.W. Hofiand (015-278 6372) (email: <A HREF="mailto:G.W.HofLand@WbMt.TUDelfT.NL">G.W.HofLand@WbMt.TUDelfT.NL</A>)<BR>
Promotor: prof. dr.ir. G.M. van Rosmalen/ prof. it. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Supervisor: dr. G.J. Witkamp (15-278 3602) / ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen (015-278 2361)<BR>
Institute: Delft University of Technology, Laboratory for Process Equipment<BR>
Project term: December 1995-December 1999<BR>
Financed by: Onderzoeksstimuleringsruimte (Comm. Beek)<BR>
BSDL-sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Intro</B><BR>
It is estimated that 80 % of all industrially produced proteins are recovered from fermentation
broths or natural source by means of one or more precipitation steps. Often auxiliary
compounds like salts or acids/bases are used to recover the protein by salting-out or
isoelectric precipitation, respectively. Since recovery of these compounds is economcally
unattractive they form a large environmental problem now and in future.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
In this project alternative precipitation processes are under consideration that use salts or
acids whichcan be recycled more easily than their conventional counterparts due to a high
volatility such as carbon dioxide and ammonia or combinations of these. The objectives are
to develop the process and design equipment for the precipitation or possibly crystallisation
of proteins with volatile acids and bases.<P>

<IMG SRC="gwh1.gif" WIDTH=750 HEIGHT=222><P>

<B>Current research</B><BR>
The research is primarily directed towards proteins that are produced in relatively large
amounts (bulk proteins). Proteins from natural sources, which are used primarily in the food
industry, as well as proteins from biotechnological sources, like industrial enzymes, are
investigated. Currently a pilot-installation is being built for precipitation experiments under
pressure. Both kinetics and technological aspects will be studied with this installation.<P>

The research is performed in close collaboration with the Department of Biochemical
Engineering (it. M. van Berlo, ir. F.E.D. van Halsema) and the Department of Applied
Thermodynamics (ir. F. Roos), both of the Delft University of Technology. Moreover,
collaboration with some Dutch industries has been established.<P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
