<HEAD>
<TITLE>More Efficient Process Chromatography
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>More Efficient Process Chromatography</H2>
PhD student:	Drs. ir. J. Houwing    (+31- 15 - 278 51 23)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof.ir. K.Ch.A.M Luyben<BR>
Supervisor: 	Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen   (015 278 23 61)<BR>
Project term:	April 1995 - April 1999<BR>
Financed by:	IOP-milieutechnologie<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="jh.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Chromatography is an important unit operation used in the production of biotechnological products. However, conventional chromatography has some disadvantages, of which production of large eluent and salt wastes and dilution of the product are the most important. In this project, a collaboration with the group of Wesselingh (RuG), we seek ways to improve chromatographic processes on these points. Recently, we have studied the effect of use of Simulated Moving Bed (SMB) technology on eluent consumption in production of recombinant Human Serum Albumin (HSA).<P>

<B>SMB-technology</B><P>

In a Simulated Moving Bed system, a countercurrent contact between a sorbent and a liquid stream is established, usually resulting in a binary separation of the feed. Thus, a ternary separation such as in purification of rHSA from a feed that also contains less strongly binding components (A, typically coloured substances, salts) and more strongly binding contaminants (B, typically yeast proteins), requires a cascade of two SMB-systems, as depicted in Fig. 1.  In SMB1, fraction A is removed from the HSA containing stream, in SMB2, HSA is separated from fraction B.<P>

In such systems, movement of components is regulated by adjustment of the salt concentration, pH and the ratio of liquid to sorbent flow in the sections. The dimensions of the system can be calculated from mass balances and partition coefficients.<P>

<IMG SRC="jh1.gif" WIDTH=346 HEIGHT=211><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Fig.1.: Set-up of a cascade of SMB systems for HSA purification</FONT><P>

<B>Results and conclusion</B><P>

Partition coefficients of BSA (used as a model for rHSA) were measured, those of components A and B were estimated (see Fig. 2.). <P>

<IMG SRC="jh2.gif" WIDTH=255 HEIGHT=203><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Fig. 2.: Partition coefficients of BSA, A and B on Q-Sepharose FF.</FONT><P>

Using these partition coefficients, eluent and salt consumption in conventional and SMB chromatography were calculated. It could be shown that eluent consumption can be reduced by a factor two by use of SMB technology, whilst salt consumption is similar to the conventional separation.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-233</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B017-42</DOCOLDNO>
