<HEAD>
<TITLE>Use of volatile salts in protein extraction and precipitation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Use of volatile salts in protein extraction and precipitation</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. M. van Berlo   (015 278 5123)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof.ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Supervisor: 	Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen   (015 278 2361)<BR>
Project term:	July 1995 - July 1999<BR>
Financed by:	Strategic Programme ABON/Min Economic Affairs<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="mvb.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Huge amounts of salts are being used in separation processes in downstream processing of bioproducts, for example in aqueous two-phase extraction (ATPS) and in precipitation. Because of technical and economical reasons these salts can hardly be recycled and thus form a considerable waste stream. The use of regainable volatile salts can accomplish a large reduction of this environmental burden. <P>

<B>Volatile salts</B><BR>
Some gases behave like an acid or a base when dissolved in water. Due to dissociation reactions these gases, for example CO<SUB>2</SUB> (acid) and NH<SUB>3</SUB> (base), form a multitude of ions  (fig. 1).<P>

<IMG SRC="mvb1.gif" WIDTH=269 HEIGHT=225><P>

<I>Figure 1: Compounds in the gas-liquid system H<SUB>2</SUB>O + CO<SUB>2</SUB> + NH<SUB>3</SUB>.</I><P>

The desired ionic strength and pH can be created by adjusting the pressure and the ratio of the two gases. Ionic strengths and pH's at various pressures and gas ratios can be calculated using dissociation constants and Henry coefficients determined by Kawazuishi and Prausnitz (1987). Figure 2 shows some results of such calculations performed with MATLAB. It shows that a higher pressure leads to higher ionic strengths at all gas ratios. It is evident that even at 1 bar quite high ionic strengths can be accomplished. Typical ionic strengths necessary for performing extraction and precipitation processes are 0.1-0.4. <P>

<IMG SRC="mvb2.gif" WIDTH=430 HEIGHT=348><P>

<I>Figure 2: Influence of relative fractions of NH<SUB>3</SUB> and CO<SUB>2</SUB> on ionic strength and pH (ideal behavior).</I><P>

<B>Research aims</B><BR>
General:<BR>
Description of ATPS and precipitation processes for protein purification with use of volatile salts by experimenting	and modelling.<BR>
Topics:<BR>
- Thermodynamic equilibria<BR>
- Mass transfer<BR>
- Separation of water and volatile salts<BR>
- Design of continuous protein extraction processes<BR><P>

<B>Reference</B><BR>
Kawazuishi K., Prausnitz, J.M. (1987), Ind.Eng.Chem.Res. 26, 1482.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
