<HEAD>
<TITLE>Design of a biofilm airlift suspension reactor for integrated nitrification and denitrification
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Design of a biofilm airlift suspension reactor for integrated nitrification and denitrification</H2>
PhD-student: it. Wim A.J. van Benthum (015-2781551)<BR>
Supervisor: dr.ir. Mark C.M. van Loosdrecht and prof. dr.ir. Sef J. Heijnen<BR>
Project term: November 1993 - November 1997    Financial support: IOP-MT and TU Delft<BR>
Delft University of Technology, Department of Biochemical Engineering, BSDL<BR>
Environmental Biotechnology<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In the near future complete nitrogen
elimination from wastewaters will be
required. Complete nitrogen removal
requires the circulation of the wastewater
through aerobic and anaerobic zones. For
the oxydation of ammonium (nitrification)
a reactor has been developed based on
biofilms formed on small carriers
(d=0.3 mm). These carriers are kept in
suspension in an airlift reactor. This
process has several advantages over the
conventional fiocculated sludge process:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>low sludge (biomass) production;
<LI>high volumetric conversion capacity
due to high active biomass concentration
(up to 30 g/l);
<LI>small area requirement (10% of
conventional process);
<LI>sludge has a low growth rate, leading to
good nitrification, even at low
temperatures.</UL>

<B>Objectives of the project</B><BR>
This project is aimed at integrating the
denitrification process in a biofilm airlift
suspension reactor. Therefore an anoxic
compartment has to be created in the
reactor, with a large exchange flow of
wastewater and biofilm particles between
aerobic and anaerobic compartments. An
example (BASE reactor) is given in the
figure below. This reactor has been built
on pilot scale (6 metres high)<P>

<B>Research topics</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Choice of an optimal reactor geometry.
The central aspect will be a controllable
and reliable circulation between the
compartments, with the possibility of
upscaling.
<LI>Hydrodynamic characterization of the
BASE reactor (two and three phases).
<LI>Study of the effect of fluctuating
aerobic/anoxic conditions on the
(de)nitrification in biofilms. This study
must support the design of the residence
time in and exchange rate between both
reactor compartments.
<LI>Setting-up a process and reactor model
for the treatment process, with special
emphasis on scale-up and control of the
reactor.
<LI>Testing of the designed system for the
nitrogen elimination capacity.</UL>

<IMG SRC="wajb1.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=272><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

