<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Compartment model approach
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Compartment model approach</H2>
Post-doc:   	Dr.Ing. P. Vrábel   (+31-15 278 2363)<BR>
Supervisor:	Dr.Ir. Rob G.J.M. van der Lans <BR>
Project term:	September 1996 - December 1998<BR>
Financed by:	Project "Bioprocess Scale-up Strategy" of the EU Biotechnology Programme of Framework IV<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="pv.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The occurrence of inhomogeneity in large scale bioreactors is well known with respect to the chemical and physical environment. To predict the conversion, models have been developed<BR>
<UL><LI>from a single ideal mixed compartment to multi-compartments (CMA)
<LI>from  equations using simplifying submodels of turbulent flow (CFD)</UL>

CMA does not simulate detailed local characteristics (turbulence) but is based on global flow characteristics. The orientation in space is based on the assumed knowledge of the flow of the dominating phase. <BR>
In spite of the restrictions characteristic for CMA in comparison to CFD, such as low resolution and a priori needed knowledge on global flow patterns, there is much experience with compartment modelling and because global characteristics are more easily measured this approach has a power to result in an easy to use computer programs in a short time.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The present project aims are:<BR>
Writing a powerful but good accessible computer code<BR>
<UL><LI>Model extension from single phase multiple turbine impeller system to/with other types of stirrer
	<UL><LI> aeration
	<LI> mass transfer
	<LI> kinetics</UL></UL>
Experimental verification in large scale experiments (30 m<SUP>3</SUP>)<BR>
Validation and comparison with CFD<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
The work on the project started in September 1996. A single phase multi-compartment model was already developed in Delft (Cui et al., <I>Compartment mixing model for stirred reactors with multiple impellers</I>, Trans IChemE, Vol 74, 1996) assuming a parallel flow pattern and using equal sized ideal mixed compartments. Currently, the possibilities of extension of the model for two phase system is being studied together with rewriting the existing simulation program into a more powerful code.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

