<HEAD>
<TITLE>Thermodynamics of antibiotics in separation processes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Thermodynamics of antibiotics in separation processes</H2>
Post-doc: Dr. S. Rudolph (015-2782361)<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:s.rudolph@stm.tudelft.nl">s.rudolph@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Supervisor: 		Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen (015 - 2782361)<BR>
Promotor: 		Prof. Ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Project Term: 	January 1997 - April 2000<BR>
Institute: 		T.U. Delft, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology<BR>
			Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Sponsor: 		DSM, Gist-brocades via Cluster Project Chemferm, Min. EZ<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction and Objectives</B><BR>
Antibiotics are still a major weapon in the continuing defence of the human body against bacterial invasions. Flexible adaptation of bacterial resistance against particular antibiotics requires a continuous development of new antibiotics. A well known, large class of (semi-synthetic) antibiotics are the "penicillins". These are composed of the antibiotic nucleus such as 6-aminopenicillanic acid, which is responsible for the antibacterial action, and a side chain molecule which is often a non-natural chiral amino acid, coupled via an inverse hydrolysis. The side chain molecule is responsible for the specificity of the antibacterial action. In biopharmaceutical science, a large number of quantitative techniques has been developed to characterize the physico-chemical properties (Log P, QSAR, molecular modelling). Most of these techniques are usually quite remote from the sort of thermodynamic models that process engineers use to evaluate various process options. Bridging this gap and making the huge body of pharmaceutical knowledge available for process development is one of the aims of this project.<P>

Current processes use fine chemical means (organic solvent environment, protective groups) for the large scale production of semi-synthetic antibiotics (SSA-typically 100-1000 ton per year). However, process economy and environmental restrictions force companies to develop alternative, biotechnology based process routes, without solvents and protective groups. Biotechnology implies operation in a mainly aqueous environment, and this leads to a number of problems: (1) the yield of the inverse hydrolysis in pathologically low in water, (2) separation of unconverted reactants and degradation products from the desired products is troublesome as all components are fairly similar in structure and (3) the large number of different SSA does most likely not lead to one single technological solution for all processes. In this respect, we aim at developing a unifying thermodynamic framework for quantification of phase behavior of SSA in a number of separation processes (extraction, crystallization, sorption) in a broad variety of "other" solutes (salts, cosolvents).<P>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
This framework will extend earlier findings for the phase behaviour of amino acids in aqueous-cosolvent systems (Gude et al, 1995) and amino acids+salt+water systems (Khoskbarchi and Vera, 1996). In this case, thermodynamic formulations were developed using a simple excess Gibbs energy expression which makes use of readily available binary information.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Gude, M.T., L.A.M. van der Wielen and K.Ch.A.M. Luyben. <I>Fluid Phase Equilibria </I>116:110-117, 1995<BR>
Khoskbarchi, M., an J.H. Vera.  <I>A.I.Ch.E. Jl.</I> 42(8):2354-2364, 1996</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
