<HEAD>
<TITLE>Integrated reaction and separation in centrifugal partitioning chromatography
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Integrated reaction and separation in centrifugal partitioning chromatography</H2>
PhD student:	vacancy   (+31 - 15 - 278 23 61)<BR>
Promotor: 	Prof. I.r.  K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Supervisor: 	Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen (+31 - 278 23 61)<BR>
Project term:	autumn 1996 - autumn 2000<BR>
Institute:		T.U. Delft, Kluyverlaboratory for Biotechnology<BR>
Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Sponsor:		Research School Process Technology (OSPT)/Min. Econ. Affairs<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Potential advantages of integration of reaction and separation are: (a) improved yields for equilibrium limited conversions, (b) simulataneous purification and thereby (c) decreased number of units of operation in the process and possibly (d) smallere total equipment volume. Centrifugal Partition Chromatography (CPC) is a novel chromatographic method which has promising prospectives in performing integrated reaction and separation. In a CPC two immiscible liquids, a mobile and a stationary phase, are brought into contact. Due to the special internal geometry of the CPC-device, a theoretical number of plates can be achieved varying from several hundreds to thousands in a relative modest volume (< 1 Liter). The objective of this project is to demonstrate the capability of CPC as a unit operation (CPCr - Centrifugal Partition Chromatographic Reactor) in the field of integrated reaction and separation.<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
Attention is drawn towards the use of aqueous two phase systems (ATPS) as reaction media because of the Bio-compatibility of these systems. The concept of CPCr was successfully demonstrated in a bench scale (100 mL) CPC. The model system was a PEG-phosphate aqueous two-phase system and the model reaction was the enzymatic chiral resolution of racemic N-acetylmethionine to yield L-methionine, acetic acid and unconverted N-acetyl-D-methionine.<BR>
The physico-chemical properties of the biphasic reaction system of the biphasic system where determined separately and inputted in an predictive model. Calculations gave a reasonable description of experimental effluent profiles. The thermodynamics of this complex reaction-separation system will be studied more in detail to provide a better description of chromatographic reactor, to increase concentrations of reactants and, finally, to investigate the potentials of replacing some of the phase forming components by reactants and products.<P>

A pilot scale CPC-apparatus is constructed and is operational since may 1996. This apparatus is a twenty-fold scaled-up version of the bench scale machine. Physical characterization in the sense of dispersion and mass transfer studies in aqueous-organic solvent systems are on-going, but preliminary results indicate positive scale-aspects (better mass transfer characteristics at the larger scale). Conversion-separation experiments will also be performed at this larger scale. In addition, a number of other potentially interesting conversions is under investigation.<P>

This project is performed in close collaboration with the section Pharmacognosy (group Verpoorte) of Leiden University and with various industrial partners. <P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
