<HEAD>
<TITLE>Separation processes for Semi-Synthetic Antibiotics
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Separation processes for Semi-Synthetic Antibiotics</H2>
Post-doc:		vacancy<BR>
Supervisor: 		Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen (015 - 2782361)<BR>
Promotor: 		Prof. Ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
Project Term: 	Spring 1997 - Spring 1999<BR>
Institute: 		T.U. Delft, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology<BR>
			Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
Sponsor: 		DSM, Gist-brocades via Cluster Project Chemferm, Min. EZ<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>


<B>Introduction and Objectives</B><P>

B-Lactam antibiotics comprise a class of multifunctional chemicals with weak electrolyte groups and with polar as well as hydrophobic moieties. A typical example is 6-aminopenicillanic acid (6-APA, shown in Figure), which is the key intermediate for the production of most semi-synthetic antibiotics (SSA).<P>

Separation processes for these species from a mixtures of structurally very similar molecules is a troublesome task, which is usually accompanied by frequent changes in pH and the use of organic solvents. Developing one optimal technological solution for the whole class of SSA is unrealistic, giving the multitude of SSA's produced. Hence, development of an "optimal" process from a broad variety of possible process alternatives probably remains a case-to-case analysis.<P>

<B>Approach</B><P>

This problem will be approached at two levels: (1) unit operations and (2) process devlopment. Some unit operations (crystallization and chromatographic operations) are capable of separating fairly similar components with a good yield and to a good degree of purity. Some promising, flexible systems will be evaluated with respect to their applicability for the field of SSA-purification.<P>

The second level is that of the development of integrated processes. Experimental evaluation of large numbers of process alternatives is impossible, hence computer-aided process evaluation techniques should be used. Various tools are available ranging from expert system driving selection of cascades of equipment towards rigorous flowsheeting. In both extremes, a good (thermodynamic) data base is indispensable. Conventional thermodynamic data bases and models (e.g. UNIFAC) are (still) insufficient, but these are being developed in a companion project. The use of auxiliary materials such as acids, bases, salts and (co) solvents will remain most likely inevitable and such strategies must be chosen that most of this materials are recycled within process boundaries.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
