<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Section Heat transfer<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Faculty of Applied Physics
Heat Transfer Section
Lorentzweg 1
P.O. Box 5046
NL 2600 GA Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 1448
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 1204
internet:  <A HREF="http://duttwte.tn.tudelft.nl:8080/trwthome.html">http://duttwte.tn.tudelft.nl:8080/trwthome.html</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=center>Delft University of  Technology</H2>

<H2 ALIGN=center>Research Group 'Heat Transfer'</H2>

<B>Permanent Staff</B><BR>
prof.dr.dipl.-ing. K. Hanjalic<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
prof.ir. C,J, Hoogendoorn<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
prof.dr. D.J.E.M. Roekaerts<BR>
dr.ir. C.C.J. Bart<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
dr. J.J.Ph. Elich<BR>
dr.ir. Th.H. van der Meer<BR>
dr.ir. T.W.J. Peeters<P>

<B>Research Scientists</B><BR>
ir. H.S. Doi<BR>
dipl.-ing. I. Hadzic<BR>
dipl.-ing. S. Kenjeres<BR>
ir. E. Meinders<BR>
ir P. Nooren<BR>
dr. A.M. Versluis<BR>
ir. R. Verweij<BR>
ir. H.A. Wouters<P>

<SUP>*</SUP> participating in OSPT<P>

<B>Research Themes</B><P>

<B>Convection, diffusion, radiation and turbulent flames</B><BR>
Turbulent combustion and flames and associated convective heat and mass transport are
studied by numerical simulation and experimental investigations using laser diagnostics
and other techniques. The emphasis in on combustion of natural gas. One of the points of
interest is the NO-formation. Applications are related to burners and furnaces for special
high temperature processes.<BR>
Research is also pursued in thermal radiation, focussed on soot formation and radiative
properties of flames in furnaces.<P>

<B>Natural convection</B><BR>
Natural convection phenomena occur in many different fields of science. Examples
are atmospheric flows, crystal growth, space heating and building physics, heaters and
burners, heat exchangers, distillation columns, chemical and nuclear reactors etc. etc..
Experimental research is performed by laser Doppler anemometer techniques in a large
rectangular enclosure with adjustable boundary conditions. The measured data on the
turbulent flow field and temperature field should serve for a better understanding of flow
structure and laminar-turbulent transition under the influence of buoyancy, as well as
a benchmark for the numerical simulation with various turbulence models. Numerical
studies focus on the development of advanced turbulence closure models for fluid flow,
forced and natural convection. The ultimate goal is to obtain new industrial standards
for turbulence modelling that can have a much wider application than the standard two-
equations model.<P>

<B>Miscellaneous</B><BR>
Experimental and numerical study on cooling of electronics. Underground coal gasi-
fication. Heat conduction studies. Improvement of thermodynamic processes by e.g.
compact burners and robust expanders. Mathematical modelling and numerical simula-
tion of turbulence and heat transfer in flows with destabilization and modulation aimed at
heat transfer augmentation. Experimental study on modulated impinging jets.<P>

<B>Experimental facilities/expertise</B><BR>
Computational research covers fundamentals of flow and chemistry modelling in non-
reacting and reacting turbulent flows, as well as model application to complex industrial
problems. The experimental programme includes advanced flow measuring techniques
(laser Doppler anemometry, laser interferometry), techniques for flame diagnostics (LIF
and CARS), measurements of conductivity and radiative properties (infrared thermogra-
phy), surface temperature (liquid crystals) and heat flux.<P>

<B>Industrial Research</B><BR>
Industrial research is going on in all of the above mentioned fields. Software for large
computational fluid dynamics and heat and mass transfer studies has been developed and
is available. Also radiative heat transfer codes are in use. For industrial research these
codes are available for practical problems in technology.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 05/12/96</CENTER></H6>

