<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of an oxy-acetylene combustion torch reactor for chemical vapour deposition of centimeter-size diamond plates.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Development of an oxy-acetylene combustion torch reactor for chemical vapour deposition of centimeter-size diamond plates.</H1>

Researcher: Ria Okkerse-Ruitenberg<BR>
Status:  PhD-student<BR>
Cooperation: Joint project between the department of Chemical Technology in Eindhoven and the Kramers Laboratory for Physical
Technology in Delft.<BR>
Telephone nr: 040-2474959 / 015-2781400<BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<I>By combining an extensive combustion mechanism and a surface-phase
mechanism derived from first principles with flow simulation software,
a 2D model can be obtained for the torch reactor that does not
contain any fitting-parameters.<BR>
</I>
<P>

<IMG SRC="okkerse1.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The optical properties of monocrystalline diamond makes it an
attractive material for applications in the optical industry.
However, monocrystalline diamond in the sizes needed by the optical
and electronic industry is not readily available on the market.`
<P>
With combustion flame chemical vapour deposition (CVD) of diamond
single-crystal diamond films can be produced at relatively low
costs. The set-up consists of an ordinary welding torch and a
water cooled block of copper used as a mount for substrates (see
figure 1)
<P>
 
<P>
<B>Research topics</B><BR>
In this project a simulation model for the torch reactor will
be developed. This will include:
<P>
a) equations for hydrodynamics<BR>
b) a gas-phase chemistry model<BR>
c) a surface chemistry model based on quantum mechanical calculations
of surface rate parameters<BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B><BR>
The full 48 components combustion chemistry has been reduced to
a mechanism sufficient for the description of acetylene combustion.
The results obtained with the reduced mechanism do not differ
significantly from those obtained with the original mechanism.
A surface mechanism has been derived for the growth of diamond
on the basis of data of Skokov et al. [1]. Figure 2 gives preliminary
results.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
1. Skokov, S., Weiner, B., Frenklach, M., J. Phys. Chem., <B>98</B>,
7073 (1994), Skokov, S., Weiner, B., Frenklach, M., J. Phys. Chem.,
<B>99</B>, 5616 (1995)</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-243</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B017-166</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tud/groen.html 130.89.50.60 19970216180705 text/html 3522
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 18:00:30 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
