</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Scaling up two-phase reactors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Scaling up two-phase reactors</H2>
<H3>hydrodynamics of bubble columns and bubbling fluidized beds</H3>
AiO: ir. Joost S. Groen<BR>
Kramers Laboratorium voor Fysische Technologie<BR>
Telephone: 015-2787084; e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:joost@klft.tn.tude1ft.nl">joost@klft.tn.tude1ft.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: DUT (commissie Beek stimuleringsruimte)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

The subject of the present research is the non-
stationary behaviour of bubble columns and
bubbling fluidized beds of various sizes. The
behaviour of bubbles and of bubble swarms is the
major subject of detailed research.<P>

With the help of Laser Doppler Anemometry
(LDA) the liquid flow in bubble columns is
studied. Time-averaged liquid velocity profiles,
turbulence intensities, Reynolds stresses and
coherent structures are being determined. In
Figure 1 a typical example of a fluctuating axial
velocity time signal is shown.<P>

<IMG SRC="groen1.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=218><P>

Although the averaged liquid flow field is
continuous, it appears to be dominated by distinct
velocities that appear in an alternating sequence
both in upward and
downward direction as
depicted in Figure 2. The
flow field should be seen to
be determined by the time-
averaged presence of either
upward or downward flow.
These dominating velocities are called typical
velocities that can be an order of magnitude larger
than the average velocities.<P>

<IMG SRC="groen2.gif" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=216><P>

Reynolds stress and turbulence intensity profiles
are much flatter than predicted by literature
models. An explicit distinction is made between
high-frequency fluctuations (i.e. turbulence) and
low-frequency oscillations induced by bubble
swarms. Two-phase turbulent flow can to a large
extent be described by single-phase theory such as
the -5/3 law for fully developped turbulence.<P>

Glass fibre probes are used to study the bubble
(swarm) behaviour. Gas fraction fluctations and
oscillations have been studied. A simple model
describing bubble swarms in terms of measured
covariance parameters has been developped from
which it follows that swarms axially extend no
further than the column diameter.<P>

From these findings a phenomenological model for
axial dispersion in bubble columns has been
presented. Considering axial dispersion as
transport with a typical velocity over a typical
distance, it follows that the axial dispersion
coefficient can be modelled as the product of the
typical velocities and the column diameter. The
predictions of this model are compared (in Figure
3) with existing literature data and a frequently
used correlation and given the simplicity of the
model the agreement is striking.<P>

<IMG SRC="groen3.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=311><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>J.S. Groen, R.G.C. Oldeman, R.F. Mudde and H.E.A. van
den Akker, 1996, <I>Chem. EngngSci.</I> 51(10), 2511-2520<BR>
J.S. Groen, R.F. Mudde and H.E.A. van den Akker, 1997,
<I>Exp. in Fluids</I>, submitted.<P>
</FONT>
<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
