Ir. A.F.M. Paijens<BR>
<P>
<I>Research scientists:</I><BR>
Ir. A.M. Berends<BR>
Ir. G.R.M. Breembroek<BR>
Ir. A.M. Diederen<BR>
Ir. P.J. Diepen<BR>
Ir. Fakhri<BR>
Ir. H.J.C. Gommeren<BR>
Drs. M. van der Gun<BR>
Ir. G.W. Hofland<BR>
Ir. J.H. ter Horst<BR>
Ir. C. Koopman<BR>
Ir. M.L.J. van Leeuwen<BR>
Ir. J.P. Muusze<BR>
Dipl.-Ing. A. Neumann<BR>
Ir. L. van Oord<BR>
Ir. H. Oosterhof<BR>
Ir. F.E. Wubbolts<BR>
Ir. T. Zijlema<P>

<B>Research Domain</B><P>

The research activities of the Laboratory for Process Equipment are aimed at developing better separation processes and equipment and improving systematic design knowledge and generic tools, with particular emphasis on advancing the state of the art of scale-up and scale down. The ultimate goal of our research effort is to contribute to the development of a process technology that will meet more stringent social requirements with respect to safety and environmental protection.<BR>
Most of our research projects are devoted to the development of mathematical models that can be used for optimization, design and control of separation processes and equipment. This requires integration of our engineering/technological approach with fundamental and other related applied disciplines which occurs through close collaboration with TU Delft laboratories for aero- and hydrodynamics, particle technology, process integration and process control, as well as trough joint research ventures with laboratories from other Dutch and foreign universities and research institutions. Nearly all of our projects are carried out in close cooperation and with financial support of national and international process industries and equipment manufacturers.<P>

<B>Research activities</B><P>

A short summary is given of the research topics and targets.<P>

<UL>
<I><B>A Industrial Crystallization and Precipitation</B></I>
<LI>Optimization of the separation efficiency, i.e. purity and
yield
<LI>Improvement of particulate product properties, i.e. crystal
size distribution
<LI>Production of particles with specific shapes and sizes 
<LI>Modeling of crystallizers and precipitators
<LI>Reduction of the energy consumption and solid wastes
<LI>Control of the crystal quality
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<I><B>B Supercritical Fluid Technology</B></I>
<LI>Assessment of the hydraulic limits of operation in supercritical
fluid (SF) extraction.
<LI>Optimization of SF-processes, i.e. minimization of consumption
of supercritical fluid and energy
<LI>Development of reliable design rules
<LI>Advocate the introduction of this novel technology in process
industry
<LI>Application of supercritical solvents as reaction media
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<I><B>C Novel separation processes</B></I>
<LI>Development of extractive crystallization: water binding as
alternative for distillation
<LI>Exploration of the application of distillation in combination
with vapor permeation
<LI>Investigation of liquid membrane extraction processes
<LI>Development of equipment for a continuous fiber sorption process
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<I><B>D Distillation, absorption and extraction</B></I>
<LI>Scaling-up rules in boiler feed water de-aeration
<LI>Development of new packing geometries and a mass transfer
model for structured packings
<LI>Development of high performance droplet separators
<LI>Establishing design rules for spray columns
</UL>

