<HEAD>
<TITLE>Liquid membrane extraction of heavy metal ions from solid-containing process streams II
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Liquid membrane extraction of heavy metal ions from solid-containing process streams II.</H2>

<TABLE><TR>
<TD>
Ph.D.-student: Ir. Anke Berends (<A HREF="mailto:A.M.Berends@WbMT.TUDelft.NL">A.M.Berends@WbMT.TUDelft.NL</A>)<BR>
Phone: 015 - 2786372<BR>
Sponsors: Senter, Onderzoeksstimuleringsruimte (comm. Beek)<BR>
</TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="berends.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Liquid membrane extraction is
a technique that can be used to remove trace amounts of contaminants
from process streams. A liquid membrane is a thin layer of an
organic phase containing a selective extractant. The extractant
forms a complex with the contaminant, e.g. a heavy metal ion,
and transports the ion from the process stream, located at one
side of the membrane, to the strip phase, located at the other
side. Ideally the extractant will only transport the ion to be
removed, while other ions remain in the process stream. By choosing
an appropriate chemical composition for the strip phase, a lasting
high driving force for transport can be realized. The required
amount of organic phase in the system is low, enabling the use
of highly selective (often expensive) extractants.<BR>
In order to supply the necessary
stability to the membrane, it can be absorbed into a porous solid
support, yielding the so called Supported Liquid Membrane (SLM)
technique. The process stream flows at one side of the impregnated
support and the strip phase at the other. Due to the presence
of the porous solid, the physical separation of the process stream
and the strip phase is good and this technique is suitable for
application in solid containing process streams. An example is
the extraction of contaminants during the recrystallization step
of a solid, thus yielding purer crystals. Currently, no such technique
is available for industrial application.<P>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
Aim of the project is to develop
the SLM technology and to describe the transfer phenomena taking
place. Ultimate goal is to develop a process that is ready for
application in the industry for the removal of heavy metal ions
from solid containing process streams.<P>

<B>Experimental set up</B><BR>
Experiments are conducted in
a transverse flow hollow fiber module from Twente University.
The organic phase is absorbed into the pores of the fibers, while
the feed and strip phase flow on the shell and lumen side respectively.<P>

<IMG SRC="berends1.gif"><P>

The figure shows a schematic representation of the module. With
this set up, extractions of cadmium from an acidic, chloride containing
solution and extraction of copper from a neutral solution have
been established. In order to clarify the extraction mechanism,
a flat sheet membrane set up is available. Furthermore, a single
fiber set up is available to study the effects of trans membrane
pressure and flow rate on the stability of the liquid membrane.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
Research will focus on increasing
the stability of the membrane for model systems which approach
actual industrial conditions. To be able to treat slurries, the
effect of solid particles on the membrane will be studied. The
optimum process module design will be determined as a function
of the slurry characteristics, such as the particle size distribution.
Finally, a model describing the process will be developed.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
