<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of a Systematic Design Procedure for Industrial Crystallizers
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of a Systematic Design Procedure for Industrial Crystallizers</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
Ph.D. Student: S.K. Bermingham (<A HREF="mailto:bermingham@stm.tudelft.nl">bermingham@stm.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsors: Dutch Foundation of Technology (STW), AKZO-Nobel, BASF, Bayer A.G., DOW Chemicals, DSM, DuPont de Nemours, and Purac<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="bermingham.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Background</B><BR>
This research work is part of UNIAK3, a multi-disciplinary research
project, of which the ultimate goal is to improve the performance
and controllability of industrial crystallizers by means of better
control and improved design. The types of crystallization considered
are evaporation and cooling, operated continuously and batch-wise.<BR>
There are 4 Ph.D. students collaborating within the UNIAK project,
from the following groups: Industrial Crystallization <I>(Lab.
for Process Equipment)</I>, Particle Technology <I>(Chem. Eng.
Dpt.)</I>, Measurement and Control <I>(Mech. Eng. Dpt.)</I>, and
Process Systems Engineering <I>(Chem. Eng., Dpt.)</I>.
<P>
<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The knowledge currently used for design and operation of crystallizers
is generally inadequate. In practice, this often leads to problems
in producing crystals on specification and/or to unstable process
behavior. This is probably due to the nature of the design rules,
empirical, as well as their objectives.<BR>
The majority of the design rules mainly focus upon design specifications
such as total production yield and energy consumption, but not
on operability and flexibility requirements. Furthermore, scale-up
rules are generally unreliable due to the assumption of ideal
mixing in crystallizer vessels.
<P>
In general, recent developments in fluid dynamics (e.g. CFD packages
for 2-phase simulations) and in reactor technology (e.g. compartmental
approaches) have led to a better understanding of processes and
scale-up phenomena. For crystallization, these developments, combined
with improved measurement techniques (e.g. acoustic techniques
for CSD and particle velocities), and increasing knowledge of
the mechanisms involved in crystallization, should provide the
knowledge and tools necessary for the development of a systematic
design procedure.<BR>
<P>
<B>Systematic design</B><BR>
Since the mid 80's, a lot of academic research has been performed
in the field of systematic (or conceptual) design of chemical
processes. Since 1988, work in this field has also included solids
processes. With respect to crystallization, the mentioned work
is of direct interest when considering the overall process flowsheet
of a crystallization process, i.e. mixers, dryers, cyclones, heat-exchangers and crystallizers. For the design of a single crystallizer, the primary objective
of this study, combination of the ideas of conceptual design and
life cycle analysis have lead to the design procedure below.
<P>
<IMG SRC="bermingham1.gif"><BR>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Fig. 1: Possible Structure of a Systematic Design
Procedure for Industrial Crystallizers</FONT></I>
<P>
<B>Development of Systematic Design Procedure</B><BR>
The first phase of this Ph.D. study focuses on the design specifications
and the synthesis phase.
<UL>
<LI>An inventory will be made of process and product related design
specifications for a wide variety of industrial processes, ranging
from pharmaceuticals to bulk products. A lot of attention needs
to be given to the priority of the design specifications
<LI>Empirical and systematic design rules currently available
will be screened for <U>model</U> compatibility and short-comings.
<LI>Regarding <U>software</U> compatibility, incorporation of
empirical rules and rigorous models in a computer environment
requires an interface between an expert system (probably CLIPS)
for the synthesis of design alternatives and DAE solvers (SpeedUp
and gPROMS are currently used) which are used for the analysis
of these design alternatives.
</UL>

