<HEAD>
<TITLE>Compact separation equipment using sorption by fibers

</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Compact separation equipment using sorption by fibers</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
Ph.D. Student : Ir. A.M. Diederen, (<A HREF="mailto:a.m.diederen@wbmt.tudelft.nl">a.m.diederen@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Phone: ../31/15 278 6628 or 6678<BR>
Sponsor: Ministerie van Economische Zaken<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="diederen.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction.</B><BR>
In theory, the application of highly porous fibrous sorbents instead
of granular sorbents in a moving instead of a fixed or fluidized
bed can reduce the equipment size considerably. For the separation
of dissolved volatile organic compounds (VOCs) from water, elastomers have been identified as materials with suitable sorption properties.<P>

<B>Research aim</B><BR>
Development of a compact pilot scale unit for continuous and countercurrent
removal of VOCs from water using fibrous sorbent materials.<P>

<B>Applications</B><BR>
Industrial wastewater (chemical, petro-chemical
and oil- and gas industries), groundwater (former gasworks,
former paint factories, gasoline tanks,
produced water with natural gas production.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Thin
silicone rubber fibers have been produced successfully, but large
axial dispersion in packed beds prohibits meaningful application
of these fibers.

<LI>Research
is now focused on open-cell elastomeric foam.

<LI>Countercurrent
operation of the demo separation unit using reticulated PUR foam
shows a removal efficiency of more than 90%.

<LI>Operation
of the countercurrent demo equipment gives &quot;proof of principle&quot;.

<LI>Predictive
mass transfer model for fibrous sorbents in countercurrent operation
gives satisfactory results.

<LI>Preliminary
scale-up study shows a reduction in equipment-size for liquid
VOC-removal with open-cell elastomeric foam to 1/10th relative
to traditional techniques.
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="diederen1.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<B>Current research program</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Determination
of properties of cellular silicone (resistant to steam regeneration),
evaluation of the applicability of this open-cell foam.

<LI>Scaled-up
and improved design for countercurrent equipment using fibrous
sorbents, economic evaluation for liquid VOC-removal.
</UL>

<B>Further reading</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Zee, G. van, <I>Counter current
sorption using fiber sorbents, </I>Ph.D.-thesis, Delft University
Press, 1996, ISBN 90-407-1328-6

<LI><A HREF="http://www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl/WERKGR/novelsep/fibers/fibers.htm">http://www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl/WERKGR/novelsep/fibers/fibers.htm</A>
</UL>

