<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fractional Suspension Cooling Crystallization
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Fractional Suspension Cooling Crystallization</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
PhD-student: Ir. Paul Diepen (31 15 2783647)<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:P.J.Diepen@wbmt.tudelft.nl">P.J.Diepen@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Sponsors: STW, TNO, GMF, DSM, Cindu Chemicals<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="diepen.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Fractional Suspension Cooling Crystallization (FSCC) can be used
for large scale separation and ultrapurification of organic compounds.
The energy consumption of  FSCC-processes is low, because of the
high selectivity of crystallization. Furthermore, the use of solvents
can be avoided.
<P>
<B>Aim</B><BR>
The aim of this project is to establish
design rules for FSCC-processes. Optimization is aimed at improvement
of the purity and the crystal size distribution of the product,
which determine the separation efficiency.
<P>
<B>Results</B><BR>
Currently the project focuses on impurity uptake. Phenol and some
industrial relevant impurities were used as a model system. For
most of the end products produced from phenol, a phenol purity
of over 99.95 wt% is required.<BR>
The two major phenol processes, the cumene and the toluene/benzoic
acid process, yield different impurities (Fig.1). Conventionally,
separation is obtained by several distillation towers. To attain
the required product purity, large reflux ratios and an extraction
solvent are needed.
<P>
<IMG SRC="diepen1.gif">
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Fig.1. Impurities produced in the phenol processes.</FONT></I>
<P>
FSCC is an interesting separation alternative, because of its
high selectivity. To determine the feasibility of FSCC, the distribution
coefficients of the impurities need to be known, which are determined
by thermodynamics and kinetics (growth and mass transfer rate).
<P>
Thermodynamically, the impurity uptake rate will be determined
by a competition between a phenol and a impurity molecule for
a vacancy in the crystal lattice. Therefore, the thermodynamic
distribution coefficient equals:<P>
<IMG SRC="diepen2.gif"> 
<P>
The difference in Gibbs free energy change consists of a enthalpy
and a entropy contribution:<P>
<IMG SRC="diepen3.gif">
<P>
The enthalpy contribution is determined using molecular modeling.
The entropy contribution can be approximated by the difference
in melting entropy between the impurity and phenol. <BR>
In Molecular Modeling (MM), a phenol crystal is build. Then,
a phenol molecule in the center of the crystal is replaced by
an impurity molecule and the energy differences are calculated.
This yields a bulk property, whereas the uptake is at the interface.
This can be accounted for using a surface correction factor.<BR>
The thermodynamic distribution coefficients were also determined
experimentally. In Table 1, the experimental and calculated values
are given.<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Table 1. Experimental and calculated values.</FONT></I>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=78></TD><TD WIDTH=57><FONT SIZE=2>impurity</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=57><FONT SIZE=2>MM<SUB>bulk</SUB></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>(kg/kg)</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=55><FONT SIZE=2>exp. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>(kg/kg)</FONT>
</TD><TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=58><FONT SIZE=2>MM<SUB>surface</SUB></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>(kg/kg)</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=78><FONT SIZE=2>cumene</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=57><FONT SIZE=2>AMS</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=57><FONT SIZE=2>1.2E-06</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=55><FONT SIZE=2>4.0E-04</FONT>
