<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>An integrated distillation / vapour permeation process using a hollow fibre membrane module for solvents dehydration
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>An integrated distillation / vapour permeation process using a hollow fibre membrane module for solvents dehydration</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
Ph.D. Student : Ir. Fakhri (E-mail : <A HREF="mailto:Fakhri@wbmt.tudelft.nl">Fakhri@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsors  : SON and AQUILO B.V<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="fakhri.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Integration of distillation with pervaporation proved to be a
good alternative process for the dehydration of solvents especially
the dehydration of alcohol's. For instance, the dehydration of
ethanol using a hybrid distillation/pervapora-tion process can
have the advantage of saving about 25 % of the energy consumption
compared to the dehydration using an azeotropic distillation process.
<BR>
From energy point of view, combination of distillation with pervaporation
is not optimal because of the condensation of overhead vapour
of the column and again evaporation in the membrane unit. The
energy efficient character of the membrane process can be maximum
utilised when the vapour from the distillation column is send
directly to the permeator. The membrane process where the feed
enters as saturated vapour is called as a vapour permeation process.
<P>
<B>Objective</B><BR>
The objective of this project is to develop a viable hybrid distillation/
vapour permeation system for solvents dehydration using a hollow
fibre membrane module.<P>

<B>Research approach</B><BR>
For process development and design purposes, a model for a hybrid
distillation/vapour permea-tion process has been developed. A
user subroutine for the vapour permeation process using a hollow
fibre membrane module has been developed and implemented in ASPEN.
The parameters used in the subroutine are taken from the experiments
in a laboratory scale test unit.
<BR>
 A demonstration pilot plant of the integrated distillation/vapour
permeation is designed and constructed. The pilot plant will be
used to validate the model developed and to show the technical
feasibility of the hybrid process.
<BR>
 The conceptual design study for the commercial dehydration process
of isopropyl alcohol and ethanol has been performed. The membrane
can be used only to break the azeotrope or to purify the azeotropic
mixture. The design results have been compared  to the dehydration
process using azeotropic distillation.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

