<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Pastille Purification in a Gravity Wash Column
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Pastille Purification in a Gravity Wash Column</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
PhD-student: MSc. M.A. van der Gun<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:m.a.vandergun@wbmt.tudelft.nl">m.a.vandergun@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
phone: +31-(0)152783647<BR>
Sponsors: NOVEM, European Commission (JOU3-CT95-0032)<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="gun.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
A Gravity Wash Column (GWC) can not only be used to wash the impure
liquid from the crystal surface but also for purification of crystals
by adiabatic recrystallisation and sweating. These last two processes
can occur if the residence time in the purification column is
long enough (approximately 1.5 hrs.). In the Granupure project
pastilles (solid particles) in stead of crystals have to be purified.
The pastilles are produced by Sandvik Process Systems GMBH which
is the co-ordinator of the project. Other parties involved in
the Granupure project are: TNO (Institute of environmental sciences,
energy research and process innovation), University of Bremen,
University of Rome and the University of Moscow.
<P>
<B>Aim</B><BR>
The aim of the project as a whole is to develop a purification
process by means of the treatment of pastilles. At the Delft University
of Technology the feasibility of the Gravity Wash Column has to
be determined. If the GWC is suitable for this purpose design
rules for an optimum operation will be established.<BR>
<P>
<B>Working principle</B><BR>
In the process to be developed the advantages of both layer-based
and suspension-based methods will be used. This combination deals
with the difficulties related to the demands of a wash column
(e.g. no plate-like crystals, low viscosity of the melt). The
pastilles are fed to the column at the top, then they settle to
form a loosely packed bed. Via the pastille size the settling
velocity and thus the mass flux can be controlled. The stirrer
is operated at low speed to minimise axial dispersion in the column.
At the bottom of the column a rotating knife is used to control
the bed level in the column. Part of the molten product is recycled
back into the column to provide an upward counter-current liquid
flow.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="gun1.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>fig. 1.  A Gravity Wash Column</CENTER>
<P>
<B>Strategy</B><BR>
As mentioned before the pastilles are purified by sweating, washing
and adiabatic recrystallisation. To be able to develop a design
and control strategy for this type of purification column several
processes have to be described: mass and heat transfer, particle
behaviour (i.e. bed voidage, settling velocity), hydrodynamics
(i.e. mixing), maximum temperature gradient for stable bed transport,
production capacity and flexibility.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
