<HEAD>
<TITLE>Volatile acids and salts as clean auxiliary compounds in protein precipitation processes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Volatile acids and salts as clean auxiliary compounds in protein precipitation processes</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
Ph.D. Student : Ir. G.W. Hofland, e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:G.W.Hofland@WbMt.TUDelft.Nl">G.W.Hofland@WbMt.TUDelft.Nl</A><BR>
Sponsors: Onderzoekstimuleringsruimte(comm. Beek), NOVEM, Campina-Melkunie<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="hofland.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction.</B><BR>
It is estimated that 80 % of all industrially produced proteins
are recovered from fermentation broths or natural source by means
of one or more precipitation steps. Often auxiliary compounds
like salts or acids/bases are used to recover the protein by salting-out
or isoelectric precipitation, respectively. Since recovery of
these compounds is economically unattractive, they make up a large
environmental problem now and in future.
<P>
<B>Research aim</B><BR>
In this project alternative precipitation processes are under
consideration that use salts or acids/bases which can be recycled
more easily than their conventional counterparts due to a high
volatility. Particularly carbon dioxide, ammonia or combinations
of these are under consideration. The aim is to develop the process
and design equipment for the precipitation or possibly crystallization
of proteins with volatile acids and bases.<BR>
<P>
<I>Current process</I>
<P>
<IMG SRC="hofland1.gif"><BR>
<P>
<I>Alternative process</I>
<P>
<IMG SRC="hofland2.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B>Applications</B><BR>
Applications are expected for proteins that are produced in relatively
large amounts (bulk proteins). These comprise food proteins, 
industrial enzymes, and  some pharmaceutical proteins<BR>
<P>
<B>Current research</B><BR>
Two research areas have been determined.
<UL>
<LI>Isoelectric precipitation using CO<SUB>2</SUB> 
<LI>Salting-out precipitation using combina-tions of NH<SUB>3</SUB>
and CO<SUB>2</SUB>.
</UL>
<P>
Currently  installations are under construction for precipitation
experiments under pressure. Both kinetics and technological aspects
will be studied with these installations.<BR>
The project is carried out in close collaboration with the Department
of Biochemical Engineering and the Department of Applied Thermodynamics,
both from the Delft University of Technology. Moreover, collaboration
with some Dutch industries has been established among which Campina-Melkunie.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
