<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cooling Crystallization of Explosive Compounds
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Cooling Crystallization of Explosive Compounds</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
Ph.D. student: Ir J.H. ter Horst<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:J.H.terHorst@wbmt.tudelft.nl">J.H.terHorst@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>, internet: <A HREF="http://www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl">www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: TNO, DYNO Industrier<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="horst.gif"></A></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
An unintentional initiation of explosives can be prevented by
lowering the sensitivity of the explosive towards sudden shocks.
It has been shown that the crystal quality of the high explosive
RDX influences its sensitivity. A shock wave moving through a
crystal can form hotspots at the defects like inclusions and dislocations,
after which initiation and detonation takes place.
<P>
<B>Aim</B><BR>
It is the objective of this research project to control and improve
the RDX product characteristics like crystal quality, crystal
size distribution (CSD) and purity by varying the operating conditions
during batch cooling crystallization. This means that batches
of RDX crystals with a given mean crystal size, purity, CSD and
defect content should be produced in a reproducible way.
<P>
<B>Research intention</B><BR>
To improve the quality of RDX crystals the relation between internal
perfection and morphology of the RDX crystals on the one hand
and the crystallization process on the other has to be fundamentally
understood. Small scale (10ml) crystallization
experiments at well defined conditions in stagnant RDX solutions
are used to determine the morphology and growth rate of the crystals.
From this the influence of the solvents and impurities on morphology
are deduced. Also the conditions at which growth induced defects
like inclusions appear are investigated.<BR>
Computer calculations with aid of the computer program Cerius<SUP>2</SUP>
are used to explain the influence on the morphology of the solvents
and the impurities present in the system.<BR>
On a larger scale the crystallization process is optimized with
aid of the results of the small scale experiments and the computer
calculations.  Here the hydrodynamics in the crystallizer and
related to this the attrition of crystals has a strong influence
on the produced crystals. With crystals from these experiments
the influence of the defect content on the sensitivity can be
investigated.
<P>
<B>Results</B><BR>
It is found that the crystallization solvent has a large influence
on the crystal morphology. Solvent influenced morphologies, predicted
by Monte Carlo adsorption calculations show a large resemblance
with the experimental morphologies.<BR>
Due to an impurity, crystal faces are blocked in growth. At higher
supersaturations macrosteps appear on the RDX crystal surface
when the crystallization is taking place from stagnant cyclohexanone.
The effect of the impurity is eliminated when the crystallization
takes place from water saturated cyclohexanone. <P>

<TABLE><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="horst1.gif"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>RDX crystal grown
from butyrolactone</FONT></CENTER></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="horst2.gif"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>RDX  crystal grown
from cyclohexanone</FONT></CENTER></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
