<HEAD>
<TITLE>Removal of heavy metals, lanthanides and radium from phosphogypsum
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Removal of heavy metals, lanthanides and radium from phosphogypsum.</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
PhD-student : Ir. C. Koopman (<A HREF="mailto:C.Koopman@wbmt.tudelft.nl">C.Koopman@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Tel.  : 015-2786372<BR>
Sponsor : Kemira Agro, Hydro Agri<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="koopman.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Phosphoric acid is produced from phosphate ore and concentrated
sulfuric acid. Besides  phosphoric acid also a large amount of
gypsum is formed. With the phosphate ore and sulfuric acid a certain
amount of impurities is introduced in the process. Some of these
impurities have affinity for the phosphoric acid. Others such
as lead, mercury, lanthanides and radium are mainly built in the
gypsum crystals. The concentrations of these impurities are very
low (10<SUP>-12</SUP>-10<SUP>-6</SUP>kg/kg), but yearly kilograms
of these impurities are disposed. Aim of the project is to find
techniques to reduce the concentration impurities in the gypsum.
By lowering the concentration radium the gypsum might become a
useful product in the building industry. The technology to be
developed should be able to remove the impurities in-line from
slurry streams.<BR>
The techniques investigated to lower the concentration impurities
are solvent extraction, liquid membrane extraction and ion exchange.
<P>
<B>Experimental</B><BR>
Solvent extraction experiments are conducted in a transverse flow
hollow fibre module to investigate the possibility of extraction
from recrystallisation acid solutions with and without the presence
of gypsum crystals (see fig.1).<BR>
Also flat sheet membrane experiments are conducted to investigate
the possibility of liquid membrane extraction. With this technique
extraction and stripping are realised in one apparatus.
<P>
<IMG SRC="koopman1.gif">
<P>
<U><FONT SIZE=2>Fig.1: Experimental set-up for the extraction
with hollow fibre module.</U><BR></FONT>
<P>
<B>Results</B><BR>
The extraction of mercury, lead and cadmium is possible with 0,2
M Cyanex 302 in kerosene. This is shown in fig.2.
<P>
<IMG SRC="koopman2.gif">
<P>
<U><FONT SIZE=2>Fig.2: Results of the extraction from industrial
phosphoric acid with Cyanex 302 in a hollow fibre module.<BR>
</FONT></U>
<P>
The presence of gypsum crystals did not affect the extraction.
The stripping with 25% sulfuric acid was not very effective. Liquid
membrane extraction did not decrease the concentration any further.
Lanthanides were not extracted with Cyanex 302.
<P>
<B>Future work</B><BR>
Other extractants and also ion exchange materials will be investigated.
Also research on the membrane stability and transverse flow hollow
fibre module will be conducted

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
