<HEAD>
<TITLE>Control and Design of industrial crystallizers (UNIAK III)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Control and Design of industrial crystallizers (UNIAK III)</H2>

AIO's: 5 (1 vacancies)<BR>
Supervisor: Herman. J.M. Kramer<BR>
Sponsors: Akzo-Nobel, BAYER, BASF, DOW, DSM, DuPont, PURAC and STW.<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Crystallization is a separation methods frequently used in industry.
The knowledge necessary for an optimal operation of the crystallization
process is, however, inadequate for automatic control and mainly
based on experience. In practice this often leads to problems
in producing crystals on specification and to unstable process
behaviour. Also the design of industrial crystallizers is mainly
based on experience which leads to conservatism and to long periods
of troubles shooting during the start-up of a new plant.<BR>

In the Laboratory for Process Equipment it has been shown, that
the crystallization process of a 1000 l, ammonium sulphate producing,
evaporative, draft tube baffled crystallizer can be monitored
by an on-line measurement of the Crystal Size Distribution (CSD),
that the process can be described by a dynamic model based on
first principles and that the process can be stabilised and controlled.<BR>

For this new project two main objectives have been formulated.
The <B>first</B> is the improvement and generalisation of the
observation and control systems for crystallization processes,
which is necessary for the implementation of automatic control
systems in industrial plants. Generalisation of the control strategy
involves the stabilisation and optimisation  in <B>batch</B> and
<B>continuous</B> crystallizers of the product quality, which
includes not only the crystal size distribution, but also the
filterability and purity of the product. For this purpose the
crystallization models must be refined and generalised with respect
to different materials, crystallizer geometry and scale of operation
 The <B>second</B> objective for the project is to improve the
performance and the controllability of industrial crystallizers
by a better <B>design</B>. The intention is to come to a systematic
procedure for the conceptual design of industrial crystallizers
in which plant specifications, empirical knowledge, and generalised
process models will be combined.<BR>

Four Departments of Delft University of Technology, will work
together in this project in close cooperation with the industrial
sponsors to form a multi-disciplinary team perceiving the objectives
of the project  The main research items will be:

<UL>

<LI>the development of fundamental crystallization models, generalised
for material properties, process conditions and hydrodynamics.

<LI>the characterisation of the product quality of a crystal suspension
in terms of CSD, morphology, uptake of mother liquor inclusions
and their relation to filtration, breakage and caking

<LI>the extension of the on-line measurement technique to obtain more
detailed knowledge of the product quality.

<LI>the development of compartment and overall process models based
on knowledge of the hydrodynamics inside the crystallizer

<LI>the development of efficient process actuators for batch and continuous
processes.

<LI>the exploration of the techniques for a conceptual design and
analysis for industrial crystallizers.

</UL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
