<HEAD>
<TITLE>Precipitation and mixing
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Precipitation and mixing</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
Ph.D. Student : Ir.M.L.J.van Leeuwen, <A HREF="mailto:M.J.L.vanLeeuwen@wbmt.tudelft.nl">M.J.L.vanLeeuwen@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
tel: ../31/15 278 6605 or 6678, fax: ../31/15 278 6975<BR>
Sponsor : Akzo Nobel Chemicals bv<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="leeuwen.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction.</B>
Precipitation (reactive crystallization) has very fast reaction
kinetics and because of this there can be a significantly influence
of mixing. In practical applications mixing is not never instantaneous
and therefore local differences in species concentration will
occur throughout the reactor. When the reaction kinetics are highly
non linear (as in precipitation) these differences can have a
large influence on the final product properties.
<P>
<B>Research aim</B><BR>
In this research tools to model the influence of mixing on precipitation
are studied. One of the most important question is to what detail
the hydrodynamics need to be modeled in order to get an accurate
description of the precipitation process. Therefore an inventory
of mixing models from literature has been made and four levels
of detail are recognized:
<OL>
<LI>Classical models of ideal mixing (CISTR)
<LI>Compartment models
<LI>Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD)(statistical turbulence models)
<LI>Vortex descriptive models (deterministic turbulence models)
</OL>
<P>
For all four levels of detail models including precipitation kinetics
are being studied and barium and strontium sulfate are used as
model systems. <BR>
<P>
<B>Results.</B><BR>
For precipitation of barium sulfate in a stirred tank reactor
the influence of the impeller speed on the mean particle size
is shown in Figure 1 both for experiments as from a number of compartment
models. The compartment models used in Figure 1 need a <BR>

<P>
<IMG SRC="leeuwen1.gif">
<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>Figure 1. Mean particle size of barium sulfate as
a function of impeller speed in a stirred tank reactor.</FONT>
<P>
lot of empirical input regarding the flow pattern. When this is
not available or when more information on properties locally in
the reactor are needed a CFD model can be used. This will significantly
increase the computational effort, but the number of needed parameters
is reduced. <BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="leeuwen2.gif">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Figure 2. CFD calculation
for barium sulfate precipitation in a stirred tank reactor. Supersaturation
(left) and nucleation rate (right)</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
