<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ultrapurification with Hydraulic Wash Columns
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Ultrapurification with Hydraulic Wash Columns</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
PhD-student: Ir. Lianne van Oord   (015-2783647)<BR>
Sponsors: TNO-MEP, DSM, Cindu Chemicals B.V., NOVEM   <BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:L.vanOord@wbmt.tudelft.nl">L.vanOord@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="oord.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>The TNO-Thijssen hydraulic wash column</B>
<P>
Melt suspension crystallization can be used for large-scale separation
and ultrapurification of organic compounds. In the down-stream
processing of melt suspension crystallization, wash columns are
particularly appropriate for the solid-liquid separation of pure
crystals and impure mother liquor. A product purity of 99.9% and
higher can be obtained.
<P>
<IMG SRC="oord1.gif">
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 1</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>: The TNO Thijssen
hydraulic wash column.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The hydraulic wash column combines a continuous solid-liquid separation
with a counter-current washing action. The slurry is pumped into
the column and the crystals form a dense bed, which is transported
through the column. The mother liquor flows through the bed and
leaves the wash column via filters located halfway down the wash
column in filter tubes. At the bottom of the column the crystals
are scraped off by a rotating knife and caught by a circulating
stream of molten crystals, the product. Due to an excess pressure
in the reslurry chamber, a small amount of the product is forced
upwards into the crystal bed, where it acts as a washing liquid.
<P>
<B>Objectives</B>
<P>
At the moment it is not possible to predict the wash column behavior
for a given slurry on the basis of first principles. The aim of
the project is to develop an overall model so that the pilot hydraulic
wash column can be scaled up to industrial dimensions. With this
model the wash column design (number of filter tubes, position
of the filters, height of the column) can be optimised for a new
product. Development of a control strategy and automation of the
wash column will also be part of the project.
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="oord2.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 2</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>: Porosity gradient
in the filtration section.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
In current wash column models a constant porosity in the filtration
section is assumed. Measurements of the crystal velocity in the
wash column show that there is a porosity gradient in the filtration
section of the wash column (Figure 2).<BR>
As this porosity gradient influences the permeability and the
transport forces needed, this phenomenon, called consolidation,
is included in the wash column model.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
