</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Antisolvent Crystallization of Na2CO3
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Antisolvent Crystallization of Na<SUB>2</SUB>CO<SUB>3</SUB></H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
Harald Oosterhof (E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:H.Oosterhof@wbmt.tudelft.nl">H.Oosterhof@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsors: NOVEM, Akzo Nobel<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="oosterhof.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In industry well soluble salts are crystallized by means of cooling
or evaporative crystallization, the latter being very energy intensive.
In order to reduce these energy costs another process is presented:
antisolvent crystallization. Instead of evaporating the solvent
the solubility of the salt in the brine is decreased by adding
a third component: the antisolvent binds the water and the salt
is forced to crystallize. After crystallization mother liquor
and antisolvent have to be separated at little energy cost and
recycled within the project; see the figure below.
<P>
<IMG SRC="oosterhof1.gif">
<P>
<B>Field of research</B><BR>
In the project that is sponsored by NOVEM and Akzo Nobel, the
antisolvent crystallization of Na<SUB>2</SUB>CO<SUB>3</SUB> and
NaNO<SUB>3</SUB> is studied. Commonly used antisolvents are ethanole,
PEG and butanole. Growth rate, growth mechanism and crystal quality
are investigated by means of a automated microscopic setup: under
very well defined process conditions the behaviour of a single
crystal can be observed. Molecular modelling is used to predict
and/or explane the morphology of the crystals and the influence
of the several antisolvents. Continuous crystallization under
extreme conditions (from -20 to 200&#176;C and upto 20 bar) of
the salts can be performed in a fully automated hastelloy setup.
Samples of the crystal product can be taken and analyzed for size
(CSD), shape and antisolvent uptake with various analytical techniques.
Regeneration of the antisolvent is also done: the possible use
of pervaporation or nanofiltration is studied in a bench scale
membrane unit.
<P>
<B>More information?</B><BR>
Visit our site on Internet: <A HREF="http://www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl/werkgr/novelsep/extract/exk.htm">http://www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl/werkgr/novelsep/extract/exk.htm</A>.


