<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Precipitation with a Volatile Anti-Solvent: the continuous GAS process
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Precipitation with a Volatile Anti-Solvent: the continuous GAS process</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
PhD: Ir. F.E. Wubbolts (<A HREF="mailto:F.E.Wubbolts@wbmt.tudelft.nl">F.E.Wubbolts@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsors: NWO/SON, Delft university<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="wubbolts.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
At high pressures a considerable amount of a gas can be dissolved
in a liquid solution. Once dissolved in the liquid phase it may
act as an anti solvent. This new process for drowning out is often
referred to as the Gas Anti-Solvent (GAS) process. On the basis
of our experience with the batch-wise GAS process a pilot plant
has been constructed, to investigate different continuous modes
of operation and to gain experience with a number of model compounds.
A very suitable anti-solvent to use in the GAS process is carbon
dioxide, because is non-toxic and because it has a relatively
low critical pressure and temperature.
<P>
The carbon dioxide can be added to the solution either as a liquid
or as a vapour. This opens new opportunities to control the level
of supersaturation in an anti-solvent crystallisation processes.
Also the viscosity of the mother liquor in the GAS process is
5 to 10 times lower, compared to a process that uses a conventional
liquid anti-solvent. Enhanced conditions for mass transfer at
the growing crystal surface are thus to be expected.
<P>
<B>Aim</B><BR>
The aim of the project is to establish the process conditions
of the GAS process and to study the influence of the unusual properties
of the mother liquor on the composition and appearance of the
product. The precipitation of both organic compounds and polymers
will be studied in different precipitators. For organic compounds
the attention will focus on their separation and purification.
For polymers the objective is to produce particles with a specific
size, shape and structure.
<P>
<B>Approach</B><BR>
The first series of experiments will focus on the mixing of a
solution with liquid carbon dioxide in a &#189; liter stirred
autoclave. It is expected that the conditions for mixing the solution
with the anti-solvent will dominate the behaviour of the crystalliser
and determine the size of the crystals that are formed. These
studies will therefore investigate the influence of the low viscosity
on the degree of mixing in stirred vessels and the effect of the
position of the inlets relative to the stirrer on the particles'
size and size distribution. Later a different mode of operation
will be investigated where the anti-solvent is added as a vapour.
The behaviour of the crystalliser and hence the composition and
structure of the precipitate is expected to be different. For
both modes of operation suitable engineering models will be developped
and verified by experiments.
<P>
<IMG SRC="wubbolts1.gif"><BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
