<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Crystallization of NaCl with Amines as Antisolvents
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Crystallization of NaCl with Amines as Antisolvents</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
PhD-student : Ir. Tjakko G. Zijlema<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:t.zijlema@wbmt.tudelft.nl">t.zijlema@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>, tel. 015-2786661<BR>
Sponsors :  Novem B.V., Akzo Nobel<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="zijlema.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>

<IMG SRC="zijlema1.gif">
<P>
In industry well soluble inorganic salts with a small solubility
temperature dependency like NaCl, are often separated from water
by evaporative crystallization. The evaporation of water in these
processes is rather energy consuming. To reduce energy costs in
the production of such inorganic salts crystallization with an
organic antisolvent could be an interesting alternative, because
the energy intensive water evaporation step is substituted by
the addition of an antisolvent. The application of antisolvent
crystallization however, introduces an additional separation step
in which the antisolvent has to be recovered from the remaining
mother liquor after crystallization. The antisolvent recovery
must be carried out with little energy consumption in order to
make the crystallization process economically feasible. With respect
to this the amines diisopropylamine and dimethylisopropylamine
could serve as suitable antisolvents, because they can be separated
from the water phase by a temperature induced liquid-liquid phase
split.
<P>
<B>Experimental</B><BR>
In continuous antisolvent crystallization experiments the influence
of the amine fraction, residence time, solid state percentage
and mixing on crystal size, shape and purity is investigated.
Furthermore single crystal growth experiments are carried out
to study inclusion formation and crystal growth rates as a function
of supersaturation and temperature in antisolvent water mixtures.
<BR>
Parallel to the crystallization experiments the recoverability
of the amines from water/salt/amine mixtures is investigated.
Liquid-liquid equilibria experiments are carried out to determine
to what extent the amines can be separated from the mother liquor
after crystallization by a temperature induced liquid-liquid phase
split.
<P>
<B>Results</B><BR>
The NaCl product from the continuous crystallization experiments
generally consists of relatively small agglomerated crystals with
amine uptakes of up to 1000 ppm. Current research concentrates
on improving the quality of the NaCl product formed in continuous
crystallization experiments (increase crystal size, suppress agglomeration
and reduce amine uptakes).<BR>
The liquid-liquid equilibria experiments showed that the amine
recovery by a temperature induced liquid-liquid phase split is
not sufficient. Therefore the applicability of organophilic pervaporation
is tested for the purification of amine containing water streams.
<P>
<B>More information?</B><BR>
Visit our site on Internet:
<A HREF="http://www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl/werkgr/novelsep/extract/exk.htm">http://www-api.wbmt.tudelft.nl/werkgr/novelsep/extract/exk.htm</A>

