<HEAD>
<TITLE>Influence of spray drying on FCC catalyst properties
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Influence of spray drying on FCC catalyst properties</H2>
Ph.D.-student: ir. Stefan C.T. van der Sanden	(X-31-40-247-2359)<BR>
Laboratory of Separation Technology<BR>
Eindhoven University of Technology<BR>
Sponsored by: Akzo-Nobel Chemicals B.V. Amsterdam<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="ss1.gif" WIDTH=126 HEIGHT=60><IMG SRC="ss.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Fluid Catalytic Cracking (FCC) is a major refinery process for the production of gasoline and fuel oil. Environmental regulations, feedstock quality and market demands require continuous improvement of FCC catalysts. The major active component of  a FCC catalyst is a type Y zeolite, which is  dispersed in a relative inactive matrix. This matrix moderates the strong activity of the zeolite and consists usually of three components: an active component, a densifier and a binder material. Generally the production of FCC catalysts can be divided into four primary operations:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Mixing
<LI>Spray drying
<LI>Ion exchange
<LI>Final drying
</UL>
Of these operations spray drying is the most complex and has large influence on the FCC catalyst properties.<P>

<B>Project summary</B><BR>
The drying process and the formation of the particles during drying is investigated fundamentally in order to understand relations between FCC catalyst properties and process conditions. The final goal is to optimise existing processes and/or to develop new ones, based on rules from models and experiments.<P>

<B>Aspects</B><BR>
During the spray drying operation the FCC catalyst particles are both shaped and dried. The formed particles are spherical and highly porous. Not only shrinkage and deformation but also segregation of the components in the particles influence the final chemical and physical properties of the FCC catalyst. A drying model will be developed which describes the microscopic transport phenomena in the porous medium and emphasis will be laid on particle morphology and strength.
Because many different components can be used, a choice is made for standard materials.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
A start will be made with the investigation of the drying behaviour of the components with special emphasis on the binder material. The water vapour isotherm of these materials and of several compositions will be determined at various temperature levels. Furthermore the drying kinetics and segregation during drying will be examined.
Because the project has just started no experimental data are yet available.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
