<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ultrafiltration of multicomponent mixtures (Modeling Mass Transfer)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Ultrafiltration of multicomponent mixtures (Modeling Mass Transfer)</H2>
Ph.D. student:	Ir. P.G.W.F. Pijpers<BR>
Supervisor:	Prof. Dr. Ir. P.J.A.M. Kerkhof<BR>
Phone:	040 247 23 59<BR>
E-mail:	<A HREF="mailto:tgtcfp@tc0.chem.tue.nl">tgtcfp@tc0.chem.tue.nl</A><BR>
Sponsors:	Gist–brocades, X–Flow, Unilever, Akzo–Nobel, Stork–Wafilin<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Ultrafiltration is a pressure driven separation process used for concentration of solutions and size–selective separations of macromolecules and colloidal particles from low molecular weight species.<BR>
Research efforts are concentrated on modeling mass transfer during ultrafiltration of aqueous multicomponent systems.
As a model situation for multicomponent mixtures a ternary system consisting of dextran, polyethylene glycol and water is used.<P>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
Roughly two different mass transfer regions can be distinguished: the polarization layer just outside the membrane and the membrane itself.<BR>
For modeling mass transfer in the polarization layer we use a multicomponent boundary layer model with in which turbulent diffusivities are incorporated to account for turbulence effects [Kerkhof, 1995].<BR>
For modeling mass transfer inside the membrane we have chosen to use the ‘standard’ Maxwell–Stefan equations where the membrane–component diffusivity accounts for the friction between the components and the membrane, without distinguishing between viscous and diffusive contributions as is customary [Kerkhof, 1995].<BR>
Two aspects can be distinguished in experimental work: the determination of parameters (e.g. activities) and validation of the mass transfer models. For the latter we have built a fully computer controlled tubular crossflow module in which ceramic Carbosep® membranes are applied.<P>

<B>Progress</B><BR>
A computer model has been developed (CFlow) for simulation with, and validation of the used mass transfer models.<P>

<IMG SRC="fp1.gif" WIDTH=381 HEIGHT=308><P>
 
<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Figure 1 – Example result</B></FONT>

The thermodynamic properties (i.e. activity coefficients) are determined with a membrane osmometer. <P>

<B>Future</B><BR>
Further adoption of mass transfer models, determination of thermodynamic and physical properties.<P>

<B>Literature</B><BR>
Kerkhof P.J.A.M., A modified Maxwell–Stefan model for transport through inert membranes: The Binary Friction Model; accepted for publication in the Chemical Engineering Journal.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
