<HEAD>
<TITLE>Drying Behaviour of Deformable Porous Media (a Mechanistic Approach)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Drying Behaviour of Deformable Porous Media (a Mechanistic Approach)</H2>
Ph.D-student: ir. Bas Kroes (tel --31 40 247 3660 / fax --31 40 244 6104)<BR>
email:	<A HREF="mailto:TGTCBK@CHEM.TUE.NL">TGTCBK@CHEM.TUE.NL</A><BR>
Laboratory of Separation Processes and Transport Phenomena<BR>
Eindhoven University of Technology<BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="bk.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>


<B> 	INTRODUCTION</B><BR>
Drying of porous materials is often accompanied by shrinkage. Shrinkage and deformation depend on moisture concentration gradients in the medium. The concentration gradients can be predicted when drying kinetics are known. To work out a good drying kinetics model the diffusity of the medium has to be known as a function of moisture content. To attain this it is important to give a fundamental description of microscopic transport phenomena in the porous medium. The ultimate goal of this project will be a good prediction of the apparent diffusity based on material properties and micro structure. This will result in a fundamental description of micro and macro behaviour of a large number of porous deformable media during a drying process. <P>

<B>	ASPECTS</B><BR>
Many porous media exist. In this study three types of clays will be used, because extensive information about these clays is available [1]. By mixing up these clays it is possible to vary material properties and structure in a controlled way.
A fundamental physical-mathematical model, which predicts drying behaviour ofvarious structured media i.e. various mixtures has been developed [2]. The model is being verified with NMR-imaging experiments which provide moisture profiles during a drying experiment. An example of these profiles is given in      figure 1. <P>

<IMG SRC="bk1.gif" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=198><P>

<B> Figure 1</B> Drying profiles from clay<P>

Temperature effects have been studied by means of drying curves (water loss as a function of time)<P>

<B>	EXPERIMENTAL: INPUT PARAMETERS</B><BR>
Input parameters for the model, i.e. gaspermeability, sorption isotherms, capillary pressure, bound water diffusion coefficient  and heat conductivity as a function of temperature and moisture content have been determined. <P>

<B>	RELATIONSHIP PARAMETERS</B><BR>
Since the moisture dependency of the liquid permeability is hard to obtain from experiments, a porous structure network model has been  developed to calculate this material characteristic [3]. Mercury porosimetry and sorption experiments are used to characterize the network.	 <P>

<HR SIZE=0>

<FONT SIZE=-1>[1] Ketelaars, A.A.J., Drying Deformable Media; Kinetics, Shrinkage and Stresses, Ph.D-thesis, Eindhoven University of Technology, 1992<BR>
[2] Hommes, J.P.L., Modelling Drying Kinetics of Porous Materials, Graduate Report, Eindhoven University of Technology, 1996 <BR>
[3] Aarden, F.B., Influence of Structure on Transport Phenomena in Porous Materials, Graduate Report, Eindhoven University of Technology, 1996  <BR></FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
