<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Modelling Quality in Spray Drying</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Modelling Quality in Spray Drying</FONT></B>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=151><B>PhD. student:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=638>ir. Frank Kieviet      040-2472359
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=151><B>Supervisor:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=638>prof.dr.ir. Piet J.A.M. Kerkhof
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=151><B>Project term:</B></TD><TD WIDTH=638>1992-1996
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=151><B>Sponsor</B></TD><TD WIDTH=638>Unilever</TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=151><B>E-mail</B></TD><TD WIDTH=638><A HREF="mailto:tgtcfk@chem.tue.nl">tgtcfk@chem.tue.nl</A>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=151><B>WWW</B></TD><TD WIDTH=638> <A HREF="http://www.tcp.chem.tue.nl/~tgtcfk"> http://www.tcp.chem.tue.nl/~tgtcfk</A>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
Spray drying is a process in which a liquid feed containing a
solid (dissolved or suspended) is sprayed into hot air. The solvent
evaporates and a dry solid (a powder) remains.
<P>
The objective of this research project is to develop a fundamental
model that can be used to predict the quality of the dried product.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Approach</B>
<P>
Product quality parameters are moisture content, thermal degradation,
aroma retention and such. These parameters depend solely on the
temperature and moisture history of the particles. In turn, these
histories depend on  the air temperature and humidity a particle
experiences on its way through the tower.
<P>
These histories can be calculated using computational fluid dynamics
(CFD): starting from the air flow pattern, the particle trajectories
are calculated. Interactions (heat, mass and momentum) between
particles and air are calculated and are added to the source terms
in the flow field calculations. After some of these iterations,
a two way coupled air flow pattern, temperature and humidity pattern
is obtained.
<P>
For calculating the mass transfer from the particles to the air
(evaporation rate) in the CFD program, it was necessary to develop
a fast algorithm based on the so-called short-cut methods.<BR>
<P>
<B>Experimental validation and results</B>
<P>
Magnitudes of the velocities at various locations in the spray
drying chamber were measured using a hot-wire anemometer. Despite
large fluctuations in the velocity, the agreement between measurements
and the CFD airflow pattern was reasonable.
<P>
To measure temperatures and humidities in the spray drying chamber,
a novel device had to be developed to prevent the probe from being
wetted by the particles. Using this instrument (micro-separator)
the temperature and humidity pattern was measured. Measurements
agreed quite well with the CFD predictions.
<P>
By calculating particle tracks taking turbulent dispersion into
account, particle residence time distributions can be calculated
with the CFD program. The calculated distributions differed enormously
from the distributions that were measured. This is caused by the
fact that most particles are deposited on the wall of the cone.
They slide slowly towards the outlet. The sliding of the particles
-promoted by two electrical hammers hitting the wall of the cone
every second- can not be modelled very well.
<P>
An enzyme (-amylase) was added to the feed of the spray dryer.
This enzyme slowly degrades at high temperatures. The percentage
of degraded enzyme at the outlet was measured.  The percentage
was also modelled using the temperature and humidity histories
as predicted by the CFD model. There was a large discrepancy between
model predictions and measurement results. This is probably caused
by the inaccurate residence time predictions.<BR>
<P>
<B>Conclusion</B>
<P>
The term of the project came to an end in October and I am currently
working on the project report / PhD thesis.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 21/01/97</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
