</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Diffusion coefficients in liquid systems</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Times">Diffusion coefficients in liquid
systems<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times">AIO:  Ir I.M.J.J. van de Ven - Lucassen</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times">Sponsor:  SON</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>______________________________________________________________________________________________
<BR>
</FONT><TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=409><B>Introduction</B>
<P>
The measurement of diffusion coefficients in liquid systems is difficult and time consuming; the scarcely available data are not very accurate.<P>
In literature many equations have been proposed relating the diffusion coefficient in a liquid mixture to other properties of the mixture.<BR>
<P>
<B>Objectives</B>
<P>
The purpose of our work is:<UL>
<LI>to develop a model based on molecular interactions, predicting the diffusion coefficient in a liquid mixture as a function of composition and temperature
<LI>to develop an automated instrument for the measurement of diffusion coefficients in liquid mixtures over a wide range of conditions (temperature, concentration)
<LI>to test the accuracy of the model on experimental data
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<B>Apparatus</B>
<P>
The instrument employs the principle of Taylor dispersion. The experimental setup of the standard HPLC equipment has been fully automated. The implementation of a second (UV)detector enables us to measure the concentration/time curves of two solute components in ternary systems almost independently.<P>
<IMG SRC="iv1.GIF">
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 1</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>: Experimental setup: SV: selection valve; A: autosampler; D: degasser; RI: refractive index detector </FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=409><B>Results</B>
<P>
<I>Measurement of diffusion coefficients</I>
<P>
Experiments on the methanol + water system (25<SUP>o</SUP>C, 35<SUP>o</SUP>C) and the ethanol + water system (25<SUP>o</SUP>C, 40<SUP>o</SUP>C) show an accuracy of 0.5 to 1.5%.
<P>
Experiments were performed on the ternary systems ethylbenzene + acetone + water, glucose + acetone + water, methanol + acetone + water (25<SUP>o</SUP>C).<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="iv2.GIF"><BR>
<P>
<B>Figure 2</B>: Diffusion coefficients of the system methanol + acetone + water (25<SUP>o</SUP>C) ; x Methanol &lt; 0.4: D<SUB>12,tern.</SUB> is very inaccurate <BR>
<P>
<I>Modeling</I>
<P>
The modeling of molecular diffusion in liquid systems is based on the use of the GROMOS package for Molecular Dynamics. A subroutine has been developed for simulating diffusion. MD simulations have been done for the binary systems glucose + water and methanol + water.<BR>
<P>
<B>Literature</B>
<P>
Van de Ven-Lucassen, I.M.J.J.; Kieviet, F.G.; Kerkhof, P.J.A.M. <I>Fast and Convenient Implementation of the Taylor Dispersion Method, </I>J.Chem.Eng.Data, <B>1995</B>, <I>40</I>, 407-411
<P>
Van Gunsteren, W.F.; Berendsen, H.J.C. Biomos b.v. Groningen<BR>

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>

