<HEAD>
<TITLE>Noble metal catalysis for the selective treatment of waste water
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Noble metal catalysis for the selective treatment of waste water</H1>

Researcher:  P. J. M. van Andel-Scheffer<BR>
Status:   Post-doc researcher<BR>
Started:  November 1993<BR>
External support: IOP-Milieu Preventie<BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>

Up till now, the application of noble metal catalysts for the
(selective) removal of organic pollutants or heavy metals from
waste waters is very limited. The lack of stability and high catalyst
price may be pointed out as major reason. The catalytic performance
of noble metal catalysts is strongly affected by heavy metals,
either in a negative way (poisoning) or in a positive way (promotion).
So, for a successful use of these catalysts in waste water treatment
processes fundamental and quantitative knowledge about the reactivity
towards organic pollutants and about the noble metal/heavy metal
interactions is necessary.
<P>
 The catalytic activity of active carbon supported platinum (lead/tin)
catalysts towards the total oxidation of phenol in the liquid
phase was investigated, batchwise as well as in a Continuous Stirred
Tank Reactor (CSTR). A simplified reaction scheme is pictured
in Figure 1. The influence of several process parameters (temperature,
pH, concentrations) was studied. Phenol was totally oxidized at
413 K and 0.1 MPa O<SUB>2</SUB> (0.6 MPa total pressure) using
a Pt/C catalyst, with carbon dioxide as major product. Phenolic
polymers and benzoquinone were found as side products.
<P>
 For the investigation of noble metal/heavy metal interactions,
a liquid phase pulse chemisorption technique was developed. By
means of a HPLC system, a solution containing the adsorbant is
pulsed over a small amount of the adsorbent/catalyst. Using this
technique adsorption/desorption processes can be studied in situ
in the liquid phase. During the adsorption of lead onto platinum,
approximately 11% adsorbs irreversibly onto the platinum, while
89% interacts with the support. The Pt<SUB>exposed</SUB>/Pb<SUB>adsorbed</SUB>
stoichometry has been determined and equals 2.
<P>
 A feasibility study showed that the application of Pt/C catalysts
as active material for waste water treatment in case of heavy
metal removal is very limited. Other techniques show more advantages.
The application of platinum for selective phenol removal is more
promising.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="pia1.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>Figure 1. Simplified phenol oxidation scheme<BR>
</CENTER>

