<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Partial Oxidation of Methane to Synthesis Gas over Noble Metal Catalysts
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>The Partial Oxidation of Methane to Synthesis Gas over Noble Metal Catalysts</H1>
Researcher: Joop C. Slaa<BR>
Status:   Post-doc researcher<BR>
Started:  February 1994<BR>
External support: European Commission<BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<I>Catalytic partial oxidation of
methane to synthesis gas is currently being studied in a fixed
bed reactor using a Rh/alpha-Al<I><SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
catalyst. The main points of interest are (i) the reaction network
and (ii) the intrinsic kinetics.</I><BR>
</I>
<P>
The Catalytic Partial Oxidation
(CPO) of  methane to synthesis gas, represented by the following reaction,
<P>
CH<SUB>4</SUB>  +  1/2 O<SUB>2</SUB> --&gt; CO  + 2H<SUB>2</SUB>,<P>

is an energy-efficient alternative
to steam-reforming of methane, as it is a slightly exothermic
reaction (H<SUB>1300 K</SUB>= -22 kJ mol<SUP>-1</SUP> for CPO
vs. +228 kJ mol<SUP>-1</SUP> for steam reforming). CPO may, however,
be built up from a sequence in which a strongly exothermic complete
combustion of methane is followed by the strongly endothermic
reforming of the residual methane.Thus the type of reaction network
has consequences for reactor design on an industrial scale. In
order to investigate the reaction mechanism and the kinetics of
this reaction, experiments are being carried out over Rh/alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
in a tubular fixed bed reactor.
<P>
The reaction conditions have been
chosen such that intrinsically kinetic data are obtained. Because
strongly exothermic and endothermic reactions may be involved,
several precautions, such as dilution of the catalyst bed with
inert material, are necessary to be able to obtain intrinsically
kinetic data. Furthermore, a reaction temperature higher than
1274 K is used in order to avoid the deposition of carbon on the
catalyst; such a high temperature is also favourable for the selectivities
to CO and H<SUB>2</SUB>. In order to minimize gas phase reactions
and wall effects, a sintered Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> reactor
tube is used, and the empty space is filled with sintered Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>.
The reactor is surrounded by a fluidized bed in order to improve
the heat transport between furnace and reactor. The set-up is
being operated at temperatures up to 1500 K and pressures up to
2 MPa.
<P>
Rh/alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
is stable and gives good selectivities to CO and H<SUB>2</SUB>.
Experiments in which the space time, W/F<SUB>CH4,0</SUB>, is varied,
result in oxygen conversions from 0 to 1, which allows analysis
of the reaction network. A complicated network appears to be needed
in order to be able to describe the results adequately. Although
at oxygen conversions below 1 significant selectivities to CO
and H<SUB>2</SUB> were obtained, the primary products are CO<SUB>2</SUB>,
C<SUB>2</SUB>H<SUB>6</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>O. The catalyst appears
to be present in two states, the transition being at an oxygen
conversion of 0.5 under the condtions used. When all oxygen has
been consumed, CO and H<SUB>2</SUB> are formed via reforming of
CH<SUB>4</SUB> by CO<SUB>2</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>O. The support
as such behaves similarly to the catalyst at low oxygen conversions,
but shows no reforming activity. The support probably enhances
oxidation reactions by reverse spillover of oxygen or hydroxyl
species onto rhodium.
<P>
A kinetic model is currently under
development.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
