<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reactor design for the Partial Oxidation of Methane to Synthesis Gas
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<P>
<H1>Reactor design for the Partial Oxidation of Methane to Synthesis Gas</H1>

Researcher :  Marc A.W. van Dijk<BR>
Status :  AIO-2<BR>
Started :  January 1996<BR>
External support : European Commission<BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<I> The aim of this project is the design of alternative industrial
reactors for the production of synthesis gas from natural gas
by means of modelling and simulation<BR>
</I>
<P>
 Steam reforming of methane is economically still the most attractive
process for the production of synthesis gas. Partial oxidation
of methane is an interesting alternative for this process, since
it may improve the energy efficiency and decrease the capital
investment. Aim of this work is to investigate and design alternative
reactor configurations on industrial scale for both the catalytic
as the non-catalytic partial oxidation of methane to synthesis
gas. For this purpose these reactor configurations are simulated
using advanced computer models, which use literature correlations
for heat and mass transport phenomena. The data concerning reaction
kinetics are whenever available obtained from experimental work
carried out within our group.
<P>
 The first reactor configuration being investigated consists of
two zones. The feed enters a homogeneous zone in which methane
and oxygen are partially combusted in a turbulent flame to yield
a mixture of hydrogen, steam, methane, carbon monoxide, carbon
dioxide and higher hydrocarbons; this mixture subsequently enters
a heterogeneous catalyst bed where the mixture is equilibrated
by steam reforming. The computer model incorporates axial dispersion,
diffusion limitation inside the catalyst pellet and effects due
to external heat and mass transfer. The applied reaction kinetics
consist of gas phase reactions in the homogeneous zone and catalytic
reforming reactions in the heterogeneous zone. The computer model
is currently validated using industrial data for a secondary reformer.
<P>
 The second reactor being investigated is a reactor in which partial
oxidation and steam reforming take place in one catalyst bed.
The effect of gas phase reactions occurring in the voids of the
catalyst bed is incorporated into the simulation model.<BR>
<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
