<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Direct Catalytic Partial Oxidation of Methane in Oxygen to Synthesis Gas
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>The Direct Catalytic Partial Oxidation of Methane in Oxygen to Synthesis Gas</H1>
Researcher:  Carlo R.H. de Smet<BR>
Status:   AIO-4<BR>
Started:  April 1995<BR>
External support: -<BR>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="cds961.gif" ALIGN=right>

 The project is concerned with the investigation of the intrinsic
kinetics of reactions occurring during the direct catalytic partial
oxidation of methane in oxygen to synthesis gas. In this direct
oxidation process, catalysed by noble metal catalysts such as
platinum and/or rhodium, methane is converted into carbon mono-xide
and hydrogen, thereby minimising the formation of the total combustion
pro-ducts, carbon dioxide and water. 
<P>
Experiments are carried out in a fully automated setup, containing
a single Pt or Pt-10%Rh gauze catalyst (Figure 1). Gas phase and
catalyst surface temperature  are measured both. The catalyst
tempe-rature is determined by means of optical pyrometry and a
surface thermocouple, constructed by spotwelding a thin Pt or
Pt-10%Rh wire to the gauze. High linear gas velocities, up to
40 m s<SUP>-1</SUP>, are applied in the gauze reactor setup to
allow for intrinsic kinetic measurements. The gauze reactor can
be operated at temperatures up to 1423 K and pressures from 0.1
to 0.3 MPa.
<P>
 Both Pt and Pt-10%Rh gauzes have been tested at various conditions.
The Pt catalyst appeared to be stable at low temperatures only
(T<SUB>gauze</SUB> &lt; 1173 K). At these conditions the main
products are carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide and water. Hydrogen
is produced at high temperatures only. The Pt-10%Rh gauze can
be operated at higher temperatures (T<SUB>gauze</SUB> &lt;1273
K) without significant metal evaporation. With the Pt-10%Rh catalyst,
CO and hydrogen selectivities are slightly higher.
<P>
 The experimental results will be used to estimate kinetic parameters
of important elementary steps and to model the gauze reactor on
an industrial scale. Reactor models will include heat and mass
transport phenomena, since these are of primary importance during
reactor operation.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

