<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Non-linear phenomena in automotive exhaust catalysis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Non-linear phenomena in automotive exhaust catalysis</H1>

Researcher: Rob H. Nibbelke<BR>
Status:   AIO-4<BR>
Started:  January 1994<BR>
External support: <BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<I>The kinetics of reactions concerning
automotive exhaust catalysis for vehicles powered by Otto engines
are investigated. Special attention is paid to so-called non-linear
phenomena, such as multiplicity of steady states and autonomous
oscillations.<BR>
</I>
<P>
The aim of automotive exhaust catalysis
for vehicles powered by Otto engines is the simultaneous treatment
of three types of pollutants, i.e. carbon monoxide, uncombusted
hydrocarbons and oxides of nitrogen. For this purpose, the so-called
three-way converter was developed. An effective use of the catalyst
is only possible if the air/fuel ratio is controlled very precisely.
Therefore, the three-way catalyst is combined with an electronic
control system to keep the exhaust gas composition near the stoichiometric
ratio. For a further optimisation of the exhaust gas converter,
a full understanding of the processes taking place is necessary.
Therefore, a kinetic model consisting of elementary reaction steps
is being constructed for the reactions between the various components
present in exhaust gas. <BR>
<P>
Experiments concerning the oxidation
of CO by O<SUB>2</SUB> over a commercially available Pt/Rh/CeO<SUB>2</SUB>/gamma-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
catalyst in the presence of CO<SUB>2</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>O
were carried out. An adequate kinetic model for the description
of the latter experiments was developed, involving both the noble
metals and ceria. Also experiments concerning the oxidation of
ethene by O<SUB>2</SUB> in the presence of CO<SUB>2</SUB> and
H<SUB>2</SUB>O were carried out using the same catalyst. The experiments
could be descibed adequately with a kinetic model involving the
noble metal only.<BR>
<P>
Special attention is paid to so-called
non-linear phenomena, such as multiplicity of steady states and
autonomous oscillations. Numerical simulations of kinetically
induced multiplicity in 1-dimensional heterogeneous reactors were
carried out for the noble metal catalysed oxidation of CO by O<SUB>2</SUB>.
For certain conditions, an infinite number of steady states was
predicted for an ideal plug flow reactor. As this feature is not
supported experimentally, a special type of feedback mechanism
was incorporated in the reactor model to reduce the infinite number
of steady states to a finite number, i.e. 3 or 5. The latter feedback
mechanism was called 'effective axial diffusion of adsorbates
via the solid phase'.<BR>
<P>
An experimental investigation of
steady state multiplicity and/or autonomous oscillations will
be attempted. Moreover, the interaction between forced oscillations
and autonomous non-linear behaviour will be studied both experimentally
and numerically.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
