<HEAD>
<TITLE>Aqueous phase oxidation of alcohols using carbon supported platinum catalysts
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">
<H1>Aqueous phase oxidation of alcohols using carbon supported platinum catalysts</H1>
<B>Researcher:  A. Peter Markusse</B><BR>
Status:   AIO-4<BR>
Started:  March 1996<BR>
External support: -<BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
Selective oxidation of alcohols and carbohydrates can lead to
valuable products and useful feedstocks for the chemical industry.
Noble metal catalysed aqueous phase oxidation with oxygen is an
environmentally clean option, in contrast to present methods involving
large amounts of inorganic waste or severe reaction conditions.
In our laboratory several alcohols and carbohydrates have been
studied, notably alkyl glucosides, ethanol, ethylene glycol and
propylene glycol. In these investigations platinum, supported
by activated carbon, graphite or carbon fibrils, has been used
as the catalyst. <BR>
<P>
The products to be expected from these oxidations depend on the
configuration of the alcoholic function. Primary alcohols give
aldehydes and carboxylic acids, whereas secondary alcohols give
ketones. Besides these mild conversions also carbon chain rupture
may occur. <BR>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="peterm961.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
A big drawback in the use of platinum is the fast deactivation
of the catalyst. Several causes for this have been proposed, but
the major cause seems to be platinum overoxidation. The approach
chosen to study this phenomenon is measurement and modelling of
changes in the kinetics of a simple system. For this purpose a
secondary alcohol will be chosen. <BR>
<P>
Better understanding of overoxidation phenomena is expected from
characterisation of deactivating catalysts. Extended X-ray Absorption
Fine Structure (EXAFS) will be used for <I>in situ</I> determination
of platinum-oxygen interaction during an oxidation reaction. 

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
