<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">
<H1>Quantitative Analysis of Transient Kinetic Experiments: Modelling of TAP pulse experiments over supported catalysts</H1>
Researcher :  Andr&eacute; H.J. Colaris<BR>
Status :  OIO<BR>
Started :  April 1996<BR>
External support : SON / NWO<BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<I>Pulse experiments, using Temporal Analysis of Products (TAP)
performed over beds of porous catalysts, and the pulse responses
are modelled to extract quantitative kinetic information.<BR>
</I>
<P>
Transient kinetic experiments form an advanced approach for assessing
reaction kinetics. Instead of operating the reactor at (quasi-)steady
state one makes use of the dynamic regime of the reaction, i.e.
the time scale of a forced perturbation in the inlet flow of a
reactant is of the order of the time scale of the reaction itself.
By observing the response at the outlet, this relaxation technique
provides extra information, leading to more accurate rate coefficients,
identification of individual coefficients, and a better model
discrimination. 
<P>
Transients or perturbations are introduced in a TAP reactor by
admission of small and narrow pulses of reactants over the catalyst
bed. Time-resolved responses are measured via mass spectrometry
(see the schematic representation below). 
<P>
<IMG SRC="colarisa1.GIF"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>Schematic representation of the TAP setup</FONT>
<P>
A single pulse may contain roughly between 10<SUP>14</SUP> and
10<SUP>18</SUP><SUB> </SUB>molecules, and the pulse width is about
200 s. The modes of gas transport in the reactor may include Knudsen
diffusion, molecular diffusion and viscous flow, but in order
to simplify the interpretations of the pulse responses the experiments
will be executed in the Knudsen regime.
<P>
When examining kinetics over porous catalysts, one would like
to avoid effects due to a limited diffusion path and non-uniform
accumulation in the pores of the pellets by choosing proper experimental
conditions. Otherwise, the above-mentioned effects should be incorporated
in the modelling / interpretation of the TAP results.
<P>
Pulse intensity and number of active sites are playing a mayor
role in the interpretation and their influence will be investigated
in detail. Typical reactants and catalysts to be studied deal
with automotive exhaust gas treatment. 

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
