<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Partial Oxidation of Methane to Synthesis Gas over Noble Metal Catalysts</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">
<H1>The Partial Oxidation of Methane to Synthesis Gas over Noble Metal Catalysts</H1>
Researcher :  Rob. J. Berger<BR>
Status :  Post-doc researcher<BR>
Started :  May 1993<BR>
External support : European Commission<BR>
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
The work is performed in the framework of the Joule-Thermie project
JOF3-CT95-0026 &quot;Catalytic partial oxidation of methane to
synthesis gas (syn-gas) : compact, energy-efficient reforming
technology with reduced environmental impact&quot;, in which five
companies, three universities and one research organization cooperate
and which is financed by the European Commission. In Eindhoven,
the emphasis is on catalytic partial oxidation of methane by oxygen
to synthesis gas over noble metal catalysts at temperatures above
1273 K and pressures up to 2 MPa. The main goal of the project
is to determine the intrinsic reaction kinetics, to derive a kinetic
model including all the reactions of importance and to develop
reactor designs for reactors for the process on industrial scale.
<P>
 Catalytic experiments using Rh supported on -Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>
are performed in a tubular fixed-bed reactor. It was found that
the reaction kinetics change drastically if the oxygen conversion
reaches 50%, and this is attributed to a reduction of the active
metal. The experimental results are fitted in order to develop
a model that can describe the performance of the reactor over
a wide range of conditions. The effect of gas-phase reactions
will be included in the model.
<P>
 Further, catalytic experiments on a single Pt and Pt/Rh gauze
in a new fully automated setup are carried out. By using both
a pyrometer and a Pt/Rh wire spotwelded to the gauze, the gauze
temperature can be measured accurately at conditions where a large
temperature difference of several hundreds degrees exists between
the gauze and the gas. CO selectivities up to 80% have been found
experimentally. During operation, however, a roughening of the
surface and a slow evaporation of the platinum takes place. The
next step is to develop a detailed kinetic model describing the
performance of the gauze.
<P>
 The interaction between heterogeneous (catalytic) and homogeneous
(gas phase) reactions and the possibility of multiple steady states
in the reactor, i.e. the occurrence of hysteresis and ignition/extinction
phenomena is investigated by combining the results of the items
mentioned above and by using Laser-induced fluorescence (LIF),
a technique that analyzes the concentrations of radicals in the
gas phase.
<P>
 Both reactor types mentioned are also being designed on industrial
scale by means of advanced computers models, using literature
correlations for heat and mass transport phenomena and kinetic
data derived from the experiments. These models cover both the
pellet scale and the reactor scale and also include the, at industrial
scale very important, effects of gas-phase reactions.<BR>
<P>
Berger acts as project leader of the Eindhoven group which actually
includes : Dr.&nbsp;Ir.&nbsp;J.C. Slaa, Ir. C.R.H. de Smet, Ir.
M. van Dijk and several students.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
