<HEAD>
<TITLE>Aspects of scaling up (semi) batch reactors for emulsion (co)polymerization
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Aspects of scaling up (semi) batch reactors for emulsion (co)polymerization</H2>
Ph.D. student: ir. M.F. Kemmere<BR>
Phone: 040 247 36 73<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:tgtcmk@chem.tue.nl">tgtcmk3@chem.tue.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: Foundation of Emulsion Polymerization (SEP)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER><BR>

Since the rate of stirring influences the
degree of mixing and therefore the out-
come of emulsion polymerization, the
process is sensitive to the scale of op-
eration. In those cases the rate of mix-
ing is of the same order of magnitude
or lower than the intrinsic rates of phe-
nomena like:<BR>
· nucleation<BR>
· coagulation and coalescence<BR>
· polymerization<BR>
The ratio of rates of these phenomena
and the mixing rate is important for
scaling-up emulsion polymerization
reactors.<P>

<CENTER><B>Objective</B></CENTER><BR>
The final aim of this project is to find
recommendations for the scale-up and
the way of operation of industrial
emulsion polymerization reactors, par-
ticularly for (semi)-batch processes.
The influence of mixing on product
properties in terms of particle size dis-
tribution, chemical composition distri-
bution and rheology of the latex will be
studied.<P>

<CENTER><B>Approach</B></CENTER><BR>
To achieve insights into scaling-up
emulsion polymerization reactors, the
following aspects will be investigated:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>
Coagulation: Batch experiments
with the same recipe but with dif-
ferent impeller types and speeds
will be carried out to investigate
the coagulation behavior of latex
particles in the reaction mixture[1 ].
<LI>
Secondary Nucleation: First, sec-
ondary nucleation effects will be
studied by adding extra emulsifier
to prevent coagulation during
seeded polymerization. Secondly,
the influence of the rate of stirring
on the secondary nucleation by
means of the particle size distribu-
tion will be tested.
<LI>
Mixing: The flow pattern of differ-
ent impeller types will be investi-
gated with flow visualization tech-
niques and Laser Doppler Veloci-
metry [2]. The influence of mixing
on product properties like PSD,
MMCCD and rheology will be
studied.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Experimental setup</B></CENTER><BR>
The following system will be used for
the (semi) batch emulsion polymeriza-
tion reactions:<P>

<IMG SRC="2011.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=301><P>

1. M.J.J. Mayer, J. Meuldijk, D. Thoenes, J.
Appl. Pol. Sci., 56, (1995), 119<BR>
2. F. Jeurissen, J. Wijers, D. Thoenes, I. Chem.
Engng. Syrup. Series, 136, (1994), 235<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B28-280</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B019-177</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/tue/202.html 130.89.50.60 19970216181445 text/html 2339
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 18:08:08 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 11-Dec-96 07:32:12 GMT
Content-length: 2156
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Continuous Emulsion Copolymerisation Reactors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Continuous Emulsion Copolymerisation Reactors</H2>
Ph.D. Student: Frank van den Boomen<BR>
Sponsor: European Union, IntelPol Bre2-CT 93-0523/Project No. BE-7009<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
During a batch emulsion copolymerisation,
composition drift occurs because of the
difference in reactivity of both monomers
and the difference of partition of the mono-
mers between the polymer and the water
phase. To produce copolymers with a homo-
geneous composition, i.e. a narrow chemical
composition distribution, a semi-empirical
semi-batch procedures can be used.<P>

From an economical point of view it may be
attractable to produce homogeneous copol-
ymers continuously. Experiments in a single
CSTR revealed that very homogeneous
copolymers are formed, but at low conver-
sions. The conversion was raised by employ-
ing a series of three CSTRs. Copolymer
produced in this reactor system exhibited a
three modal chemical composition distribu-
tion.<P>

In principle it should be possible to avoid
composition drift by adding additional
monomer to CSTR 2 and 3. The flow rates are
calculated with a model.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Figure 1 shows the conversions-time curves.
The conversion starts at 100% because a seed
latex is used. After an initial decrease of the
conversion steady states are reached in all
reactors. The average chemical composition
has been measured with 1H NMR. Assuming
that a copolymer with a specific composition
has been formed in each reactor the average
chemical composition can be recalculated to
actual compositions.<P>

<IMG SRC="2021.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=79><P>

Although the model calculations are not in
very good agreement a homogeneous copoly-
mer has been produced.<P>

<IMG SRC="2022.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=769><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

