<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cleaner Technology Options in Tanzania (the consequences for engineering education)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Cleaner Technology Options in Tanzania (the consequences for engineering education)</H2>
Ph.D.-student: ir. P. van Schijndel (-31 40 2 47 34 98)<BR>
Centre for Environmental Technology, CMT<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Development countries, like Tanzania,
are striving to reach te levels of
economic well being which the
developed countries have achieved.
However the industrial development as
was undertaken by the developed
countries would be catastrophic for the
environment. To combine economic
growth with sustainable development,
the primary focus of environmental
protection must be preventive
measures, and an ideal stage of these
measures is at the design of processes.
With the help of cleaner production
design methodologies engineers may
be in a position of in-cooperating
measures to minimise the pollution eg.
by introducing recycling loops, by
changing raw materials or by changing
the operating condition of the process,
or in-cooperating treatment options.<P>

<B>Aim of the research</B><BR>
The research aims at the identification
of the possibilities of cleaner
production methods in Tanzania and
the adaptation of educational
programmes for engineers in such a
way that they conform with the
requirement that graduated engineers
should be tailored to design for cleaner
production. This research started in
august 1996.<P>

<B>Methodology</B><BR>
<I>Possibilities,for cleaner production in
development countries</I><BR>
In the explorative part rapid assessment
based on production, pollution, and
energy use figures will be used to make
a priority listing. For selected process-
industries a life cycle assessment will
be made for the products
manufactured. Major problem areas,
with respect to environment and energy
use, will be identified.
In the engineering design part of this
research step retrofitting possibilities
for the plants will be made for a
cleaner production process, assuming
that a new plant will be erected. Exergy
analysis and life cycle analysis of the
processes will be the main tools in the
design part.<BR>
In the socio-economic assessment the
feasibility of the (technical)
improvements will bc checked. This
part of the research could lead to
practical suggestions on retrofitting of
the selected industries and
considerations which should be taken
into account when designing similar
production methods.<BR><P>

<I>Education in cleaner production
engineering</I><BR>

Knowledge gathered in the first part of
this research is to be used for the
adaptation of the existing
environmental engineering M.Sc.-
programme and global suggestions for
other engineering programmes at the
University of Dar es Salaam.<P>



<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
