<HEAD>
<TITLE>Recycling of Chlorine Containing Polymer Waste Streams
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Recycling of Chlorine Containing Polymer Waste Streams</H2>
Ph.D.-student: ir. M.J.P. Slapak (-31 402474956)<BR>
Centre for Environmental Technology, CMT<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Thermal recycling is a very useful tool
for conversion of heterogeneous and
polluted PVC-rich polymer waste. The
formation of dioxins, chlorinated
hydrocarbons and HC1 is a big
problem. Hydrothermal recycling in a
bubbling fluidised bed is an option to
convert chlorine containing polymer
waste in a one-reactor-concept and to
avoid the mentioned problems.<P>

<B>Aim of the research</B><P>

The development of a conversion
process for PVC containing waste
using existing cleanup processes as
being used in chemical and
petrochemical industries.<P>

<B>Methodology</B><P>

The research has been carried out
according to three projects.<BR>
<UL>
<LI>The selective removal of HCI is
carried out a pilot plant.
Optimisation of the process is
studied.
<LI>The break down kinetics.
<LI>A reactor model has been developed
for reactor design.
</UL>
The projects started December 1994.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Labscale test system is developed,
constructed and tested. In 1996 first
qualitative and quantitative
measurements are being expected.
Kinetics of the break down of pure
PVC in both inert and steam
environment are finished successfully.
The research is continued with PVC
containing additives and PVC waste.<P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
