<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reduction of Ferric Ions in Dilute Solution in a Semi-Technical Scale GBC reactor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Reduction of Ferric Ions in Dilute Solution in a Semi-Technical Scale GBC reactor</H2>
Ph.D. student: K.N. Njau, MSc. (tel. * 31 40 247 3784)<BR>
Lab. Instrumental Analysis, subgroup Electrochemical Technology<BR>
Sponsor: Centre for International Cooperation Activities (CICA).<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>
Electrochemical reduction of metal ions in
dilute solution is of much interest for
purification of waste waters. Conventional
methods of addition of reductants into an
effluent stream are becoming less interesting
as environmental concerns become more
stringent, and requirements for even cleaner
technologies for effluent treatment become
necessary.<BR>
GBC (Gas diffusion electrode packed Bed
electrode Cell) process is providing an
alternative cleaner technology which utilizes
hydrogen gas to reduce metal ions. Coupling
of a gas diffusion electrode and a packed bed
provides a strong tool for treatment of metal
ions in dilute solutions.<BR>
The undivided GBC-cell consists of a gas
diffusion electrode (2) in direct contact with
a packed bed of carbon particles (3). The
hydrogen gas flows through the gas chamber
(1). The packed bed electrode offers a large
electrode/electrolyte contact area. This mode
of operation enables reactions with dG < 0
to proceed spontaneously, i.e. external
power souce is not necessary. The system of
Fe<SUP>3+</SUP>/Fe<SUP>2+</SUP> in sulphuric acid solution is used
as a model to study the behaviour of the
reactor. The reactor consists of an activated
carbon bed with a thickness of 1 cm and
height of 20 cm. A 20 x 20 cm gas diffusion
electrode catalyzed with platinum is used.<P>

Experinlents have been conducted in a flow-
by single pass mode with low to medium
ferric concentrations. The effects of
temperature, acid concentration, reactor
height and velocity in the bed on the
performance of the reactor are being
investigated. Current efficiencies will be
determined.<P>

The reactor conversion can be described by
an empirical equation [1]:<P>

-ln (l-X) = A<SUB>e</SUB> k<SUB>ov</SUB> tau<P>

where:<BR>
X = fractional conversion<BR>
tau = residence time in the reactor<BR>
k<SUB>ov</SUB> = the overall reaction rate constant<BR>
A<SUB>e</SUB> = geometric surface area of gas diffusion electrode<BR>
<P>
The k<SUB>ov</SUB> has been found to increase with
increasing acid concentration, volumetric
rate of solution, temperature and decreasing
feed concentration of Fe<SUP>3+</SUP>.<BR>
Estimation of potential distributions in the
bed has indicated that for some electrolysis
conditions the reactor is partially under
diffusion control.<P>

<IMG SRC="2101.gif" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=259><P>

[1] K.N. Njau, W.-J. van der Knaap and L.J.J.
Janssen, Proc. 4th Eur. Symp. on Electrochemical
Engineering, Prague, 1996, pp. 311-317.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
