<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Phd-projects Enschede</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Department of Chemical Reaction Engineering<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
University of Twente
Department of Chemical Engineering
P.O. Box 217
NL 7500 AE Enschede

telephone: +31 (0)53 489 2880/4798
fax:       +31 (0)53 489 4774
internet:  <A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/">http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/</A>
</PRE></TT>

<B>Permanent Staff:</B><BR>
Prof. dr.ir. W.P.M. van Swaaij<BR>
Prof. dr.ir. G. Versteeg<BR>
Ir. D.W.F. Brilman<BR>
Dr.ir. A.B.M. Heesink<BR>
Dr.ir. JAM. Kuipers<BR>
Dr.ir. W. Prins<BR>
Ing. H.A. Akse<BR>
<P>
<B>Ph.D.-students:</B><BR>
Ir. M. Biesheuvel<BR>
Mevr. Ir. P.J. Boon<BR>
Ir. D.W.F. Brilman<BR>
Ir. E. Delnoij<BR>
Ir. B.P.B. Hoomans<BR>
Ir. P. Huizenga<BR>
Ir. A.M.C. Janse<BR>
Ir. H.W.JP. Neomagus<BR>
Ir. G.Rexwinkel<BR>
Ir. M. van St. Annaland<BR>
Ir. R.D. Vas Bhat<BR>
Ir. R.H. Venderbosch<BR>
Ir. R.W.J. Westerhout<BR>
<P>

Chemical Reaction Engineering may be described as the basis of process technology. Physical transport
phenomena are of primary importance, under which come fluid flow phenomena, heat and mass transfer.
These subjects underpin process technology, equipment engineering, physical separation, scaling-up methods,
modeling, etc. Chemical reactions are added to chemical engineering science by the discipline kinetics and
catalysis of chemical reaction engineering.<BR>
In tt~is way elements of physical science, as well as chemical kinetics and thermodynamics provide a
fundamental package through which numerous problems arising from aspects of process design, development,
evaluation and operation can be solved. Furtherefore the subjects of chemical reaction engineering and
physical transport phenomena are of great importance for material sciences.<BR>
The efforts of the Chemical Reaction Engineering group are on the development and understanding of new
reactors and subsequent application of those reactors in the process industry. Specific research areas are:<P>

<B>Gas-Liquid (Solid) reactors</B><P>

The main research topic within this section is studying the interactions and mutual influencing of mass transfer
processes and complex (reversible) chemical reactions. By manipulating mass transfer parameters the yields
and sclectivity's obtained in multiphase processes can be increased significantly.<BR>
All rcsearch items use an industrial process as model system to develop the know-how. This enables an
intensive cooperation with industry, leading to more application-related research.<P>

Within the section a subdivision is made: gas-liquid, gas-liquid-solid and multiple phase systems.<BR>
In the gas-liquid subsection current topics are: Removal of hydrogencyanide (HCN) from industrial gas
streams using a reactive absorption liquid. Main goal is the development of a solvent which selectively (and
regenerative) absorbs HCN. In another project the production of mono-chloroacetic acid (MCA) is studied. In
this process a number of consecutivc and parallel reactions occurs, thus making the selectivity obtained a
major item<BR>
In the subdivision gas-liquid-solid currently a new reactor concept is studied. The slurry, containing very fine
catalyst particles, is fined within the reactor, while the liquid phase products are removed from the reactor
through the porous wall (membrane).<BR>
In the multiple phase systems section a start was made studying these processes and developing theory.
Examples of these multiple phase systems can be found in hydroformulation and the production of tertiary
carboxylic acids. Charactcristic for these processes is the presence of two liquid phases. Attractive aspects of
these processes are the possibilities to remove selectively intermediary products and enabling the recycle of a
homogeneous catalyst through simple phase separation.<P>

<B>Gas Solid reactors</B><P>

Within the Chemical Reaction Engineering group gas-solid reactors have been studied for a long time. Within
the research program two directions can be recognized. The first one is focused on a better understanding of
the fundamentals in existing, widely used reactor types as (circulating) fluidized beds and packed beds. Next to
this, new reactor types are being developed.<BR>
(Fast) fluidized beds were studied in relation with energy-conversion processes (pyrolysis, gasification and
combustion) and gas-cleaning technologies.<BR>
Examples of newly developed gas-solid reactors involve the Trickle Flow Reactor, the Floating Bed Reactor,
the Rotating Cone Reactor and the Membrane Reactor.<BR>
In the future this strategy of fundamentals and new reactor types will be continued. Especially the
(hydrodynamic) modeling using powerful computers will be used to study the influence of mixing and
heat/mass transfer on chemical reaction. The rapid development of micro-electronics will be important for the
development of new reactor types.<P>

<B>Membrane reactors</B><P>

In this section the possible applications of ceramic and polymeric membranes in new reactor concepts are
studied. In these concepts the membranes are not selected for their permselectivity or transport-abilities. The
membranes used enable selective (stoechiometric) feed of reactants or selective removal of products. Avoiding
hazardous operation (explosion limits !) by feeding reactants separately and keeping them separated in a
membrane reactor, while the reaction front is located within the membrane is one example.<P>

Currently, catalytic partial oxidation reactions are studied, using the concept ofa non-permselective membrane
reactor. Main objective is to demonstrate that manipulation of the reactant feed strategy influences the
selectivity obtained.<P>

<B>Liquid-Solid reactors</B><P>

Within this section the removal of traces of halogenated hydrocarbons and heavy metals from waste water
using (regenerative) hydrophobic particles is studied. Traditionally, activated carbon is used for these
applications. However, the use of hydrophobic particles offers some very interesting advantages. Since the
particles are filled with air no internal diffusion limitation occurs, since the transport within the particles
occurs through the gas phase. Therefore, external mass transfer resistance completely dominated the
adsorption process. For this reason liquid-solid contact efficiency in a packed bed reactor is studied. E.g.
effects of maldistribution are being studied using a packed bed with hydrophilic and hydrophobic particles,
some of which containing a water dissolving compound which can be traced at the reactor outlet. Results are
general applicable for describing liquid-solid packed bed reactors.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 17/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
