<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mass transfer with chemical reaction in a G-L-L system
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Mass transfer with chemical reaction in a G-L-L system</H2>
Ir. D.W.F. Brilman (053-4894479 / <A HREF="mailto:d.w.f.brilman@ct.utwente.nl">d.w.f.brilman@ct.utwente.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: SHELL (SRTCA) / Twente University<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Multiphase reaction systems are frequently encountered in chemical reaction engineering
practice. Among them, gas-liquid-liquid (GLL) systems have not received much attention up
till now, although some important applications are involved with this type of operation.
such as hydroformylation, SHOP and hydrocarboxylation (Koch synthesis). These processes
are all commercialized succesfully. However, the fundamentals of the processes of mass
transfer and chemical reaction in these systems are not fully understood.<P>

<I><B>Scope</B></I> of this project is to gain more insight in the processes of mass transfer with complex
chemical reaction in a gas-liquid-liquid system. The Koch reaction { alkene (org.) + CO (g) +
H<SUB>2</SUB>0 (aq) --> carboxylic acid } is chosen as an industrial relevant demonstration system.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Determination of the reaction kinetics and -mechanism of the demonstration system
<LI>Study of mass transfer and mixing in a G-L-L system
<LI>Modeling mass transfer and mass transfer with chemical reaction in a GLL system
</UL><P>

<B>Experimental work</B><BR>
The kinetics of the model system chosen are being studied. Preliminary results show that
formation of the carbocat ion is rate determining, especially when loaded catalyst solutions are
used. Experiments and modeling showed that reaction kinetics should be described using an
activity based rate expression.<BR>
From experiments with the Koch reaction systems it is clear that micromixing phenomena
determine selectivity to a large extent. This will be studied in the near future.<BR>
Experiments concerning the mass transfer mechanism from gas to liquid-liquid dispersion
revealed that, next to the generally accepted shuttle mechanism, a second mechanism may be
important. Coalescence of an organic phase droplet and a gasbubble in water was observed
under conditions of forced and free interaction, thereby forming a gasbubble with a skin of
organic phase. These coalescences were found to be independent of the initial spreading
coefficient of the system under consideration. The extent of this transport mechanism in some
applications will be studied.<P>

<B>Modeling</B><BR>
A true heterogeneous fluxmodel for describing mass transfer in a GLL system (esp. with
respect to the shuttle mechanism) is being developed, using a <I>Overture</I> (being developed at
LANL, USA). The software package uses overlapping grids and enables 2-D and 3-D
calculations. Pseudo-Homogeneous models can be verified and e.g. the influence of particle
size, geometric effects (shielding) and bulk phase flow near interphases can be studied.
Reactor modeling will start in 1997.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
