<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mass Transfer with Complex Chemical Reaction in Gas - Liquid Systems
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Mass Transfer with Complex Chemical Reaction in Gas - Liquid Systems</H2>
Ph.D. Student: Rahul D. Vas Bhat (+31-53-4892405 / <A HREF="mailto:r.d.vasbhat@ct.utwente.nl">r.d.vasbhat@ct.utwente.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Previous research on gas-liquid mass
transfer with multiple reactions in the
liquid phase is limited by assumptions of
irreversibility, equal diffusivity of the
chemical species and isothermal
absorption. It is the aim of this project to
overcome these constraints and to
understand their importance to the overall
mass transfer. Fundamental models of
mass transfer with reversible consecutive
and two-step reactions of general orders
have been prepared. Additionally, the flux
model has been extended to understand an
industrial system. The chlorination of
acetic acid has been chosen for this.<P>

<B>Present Results</B><P>

<I>1. Consecutive Reactions</I><BR>
The influence of reversibility, unequal
diffusivity of the reactants and solute
loading has been investigated. K<SUB>1</SUB> and K<SUB>2</SUB>
are the equilibrium constants of the first
and second reaction, respectively. Here the
mobility of the gas phase component is ten
times higher than the other species present.<P>

<IMG SRC="2351.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=234><P>

<I>Figure 1: Effect of K<SUB>1</SUB> on enhancement for
high mobility of gas component; K<SUB>2</SUB> = 100</I><P>

<I>2.     Chlorination of Acetic Acid</I><BR>
The overall reaction mechanism can be
reduced to a set of three consecutive
reactions. The intermediate product,
monochloroacetic acid (MCA) is the
desired product while a part of the acetic
acid is converted to dichloroacetic acid
(DCA). The reaction is catalysed by acetyl
chloride, which acts as a homogeneous
catalyst.<BR>
The original flux model has been modified
to take into account the MCA reaction
mechanism. The model has been integrated
into an overall description of a bubble
column. Figure 2 shows the effect of
catalyst concentration on the yield and
selectivity towards MCA.<P>

<IMG SRC="2352.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=244><P>

<I>Figure 2: Effect of catalyst concentration
on MCA yield and selectivity</I><P>

<B>Future Direction</B><P>

<OL>
<LI>
Experimental validation of the two-
step reaction system using the
absorption of CO<SUB>2</SUB> in NaOH solutions.
<LI>
Modification of the existing flux model
to account for non-isothermal
absorption behaviour.
<LI>
Determination of physico-chemical
parameters such as solubility, diffusion
coefficients, vapour liquid equilibria
and chemical equilibrium constants for
the MCA system.
<LI>
Experimental validation of selectivity
and yield as predicted by the model for
MCA manufacture.
</OL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
