<HEAD>
<TITLE>Removal of Hydrogen Cyanide from Gaseous Streams by means of Gas/Liquid Processes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Removal of Hydrogen Cyanide from Gaseous Streams by means of Gas/Liquid Processes</H2>
PhD student: Ir. P.J. Boon (053-4892881 / <A HREF="mailto:p.j.boon@ct.utwente.nl">p.j.boon@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Project term: 11-1994 to 11-1998<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The removal of HCN from gaseous streams
is necessary in processes dealing with coal
and petroleum handling. The HCN
production takes place by the pyrolysis
reaction of nitrogen containing organic
substances found in natural fuel products
like pyridines and pyrroles.<BR>
By processing coal and petroleum feed, a
gaseous stream is formed which contains
besides HCN, impurities like H<SUB>2</SUB>S, CO<SUB>2</SUB> and
NH<SUB>3</SUB>. For the removal of H<SUB>2</SUB>S there are
several industrial processes available. In
most cases HCN is removed simultaneously.
Sometimes, however, the presence of HCN
complicates the removal of H<SUB>2</SUB>S and causes
corrosion. In these cases, it is necessary to
remove HCN, preferably before H<SUB>2</SUB>S.<P>

<B>Scope</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to
develop a gas/liquid absorption process
suited for the (selective) removal of HCN
from a gaseous stream.<P>

<B>Research activities</B><BR>
The gas/liquid absorption processes that
have been selected for further research are:<BR>

1. <I>Absorption of HCN in water</I>: The
solubility of HCN in water is very high. The
solubilities are comparable to that of NH3 in
water. This would make water a favourable
solvent for HCN removal. The
concentrations in the gas phase should be
reduced to ca. 10 ppm, it has been shown,
however, that the use of water only is not
sufficient.<BR>
<I>2. Absorption of HCN in an aldehyde/ketone
solution</I>: In this case the liquid phase
contains a yet unspecified aidehyde or
ketone. The reaction of aldehydes and
ketones with HCN is as follows:<BR>

HCN + R<SUB>1</SUB>R<SUB>2</SUB>CO = R<SUB>1</SUB>R<SUB>2</SUB>C(OH)(CN)<BR>

The reaction is reversible. A disadvantage of
the use of aidehyde is the occurrence of side
reactions. NH<SUB>3</SUB> as well as H<SUB>2</SUB>S seem to react
with the aidehyde. Other reactions that
occur are the hydration of the aldehyde and
aldol condensation. The latter group of
reactions are particularly important in
alkaline media.<BR>
<I>3. Absorption of HCN in a polysulphide
solution</I>: The application of a polysulphide
solution for the removal of HCN makes use
of the fact that HCN is readily oxidized to
thiocyanates (HSCN) in the presence of
sulfur:<BR>

Na<SUB>2</SUB>S<SUB>x+1</SUB> + CN = NaSCN + Na<SUB>2</SUB>S<SUB>x</SUB><BR>

This is a fast and irreversible reaction. The
advantage of polysulphides is that they do
not react with the other components present
in the gas stream. Polysulphides are,
however, very unstable depending on
temperature and pH. A thermodynamic
study will, therefore, be carried out.<P>

For the theoretical description of the above
processes a flux model has been written for
electrolytic solutions. The diffusion of all
the ionic species have been coupled in order
to maintain electro-neutrality.<P>

<B>Future direction</B><BR>
Kinetic studies on the reaction of HCN, NH<SUB>3</SUB>
and H<SUB>2</SUB>S with aldehydes will be carried out.
A homogenous system will be used for HCN
while for the other two components a
heterogeneous system (stirred cell) will be
employed. The aldehydes selected are
propanal and n-butanal.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
