<HEAD>
<TITLE>Contacting in gas solids reactors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Contacting in gas solids reactors</H2>
Ph.D.-student	: ir. R.H.Venderbosch (053-4893028)<BR>
Sponsor: Netherlands Energy Research Foundation ECN<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:venderbs@utct.ct.utwente.nl">venderbs@utct.ct.utwente.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B> INTRODUCTION</B><BR>
Turbulent fluidized beds or risers of circulating fluid beds are favourable reactors for rapid, exothermal reactions because of the large specific surface area available for reaction and short residence times for gas and/or solids. One of the most promising claims of these types of reactors is the excellent contacting between the solids and the gas. In this PhD project the contacting in these type of reactors is investigated from a hydrodynamic as well as from a kinetic and/or mass-transfer point of view.<P>

<B>EXPERIMENTAL PROGRAMME</B><BR>
This study can be separated into four parts, viz. the experimental determination of<BR>
<OL>
<LI>mass transfer resistances and kinetics of a model reaction in a fixed bed,
<LI>the hydrodynamic behaviour of turbulent fluidized beds and risers,
<LI>the performance of the absorption of H<SUB>2</SUB>S on a Fe/Mo-sorbent and its regeneration in the high-velocity fluid bed regime, and
<LI>gas-solids mass-transfer coefficients in several types of gas-solids reactors by means of proper model reactions.
</UL>

<B>RESULTS</B><BR>
<OL> 
<LI>In a 7 mm ID fixed bed reactor the kinetics of the CO-oxidation reaction over a Pt/gamma-alumina catalyst (70 micro-m) were determined. At high temperatures (> 725 K) mass transfer controlled reaction rates were obtained. An important variable in these latter experiments was the degree in which the catalyst was diluted with inert gamma-alumina particles. Results showed that contacting is maximal at infinite dilution, while it decreased with decreasing degree of dilution. The experiments could be interpreted with a simple model, which accounts for clustering of particles.
<LI>Solids hold-up measurements were carried out in the turbulent fluid bed regime and in a riser of a circulating fluidized bed by different techniques: i) pressure gradients,  ii) quick-closing valves and iii) direct measurement of the solids velocity by a new contactless  method based on the characteristic luminescence of phosphorous material. It was demonstrated that solids-wall friction is only partially (Geldart's type B) or not at all (type A)  responsible for the deviation between the terminal falling velocities and the evaluated slip velocities. Results obtained by this newly developed technique were completely consistent with those derived by the quick-closing valves, which provided strong evidence in favour of the cluster instead of single-particle concept for the flow of solids.
<LI>Due to the high bed-to-wall heat transfer coefficients, the turbulent fluidized bed is expected to be an excellent reactor for highly exothermic reactions. The absorption of H<SUB>2</SUB>S on a Fe/Mo sorbent, and its regeneration in (un)diluted air were investigated in this high-velocity fluid bed regime. Despite the high gas velocities and the severe regeneration conditions applied, high H<SUB>2</SUB>S-removal efficiencies (up to 99.9%) were observed over more than 40 cycles. 
<LI>Measurement of mass transfer numbers were carried out in a turbulent fluid bed and in the riser of a circulating fluidized bed using both model reactions: the CO-oxidation over a Pt/gamma-alumina catalyst and the absorption reaction of H<SUB>2</SUB>S over a Fe/Mo catalyst. From the results it could be concluded that the assumption of excellent gas-solids contacting in these types of beds is not valid. Observed mass transfer numbers per unit volume of active catalyst (represented by the Sherwood number) as a function of the particle Reynolds number, showed the same trend as for a packed bed. In figure 1 it is shown that its values decrease at a higher solids hold-up and lower dilution ratios nd (defined as m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>inert</SUB>/m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>cat</SUB>), which can be attributed to the shielding of particles due to formation of clusters or strands of particles. This was confirmed by the dependency of gas-solids contacting on 
the kinetic rate constant per unit volume of reactor.
</OL>

<IMG SRC="2381.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=437><P>

Figure 1. 	Experimental Sherwood number on basis of the active
		catalyst versus the solids hold-up in  a fast fluidized bed.
		Indicated is the dilution ratio, nd, defined as m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>inert</SUB>/m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>cat</SUB>.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
