<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Modular Membrane Slurry Reactor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Modular Membrane Slurry Reactor</H2>
PhD Student: ir. P. Huizenga (053-4892890)<BR>
Supervisor: dr. ir. J.A.M. Kuipers (053-4893039)<BR>
Project Term:		November 1993-November 1997<BR>
Sponsor:		OSPT<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I><B>General Project Description</B></I><P>

Slurry reactors have found widespread application for gas/liquid/solids contacting operations in the chemical industries. The most important advantages of this reactor type are its excellent heat transfer characteristics and the possibility of using relatively small particles. Further application is mainly hampered by difficulties encountered in scale-up and particle separation from the liquid.<P>
 
<IMG SRC="2391.gif" ALIGN=right WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=260>

The main goal of the research project is the development and description of a novel kind of reactor. This type of reactor is expected to circumvent the problems mentioned before. The crux of the concept is a modular configuration in which reaction and separation are performed simultaneously. Of the vast number of configurations that could be envisaged, there is one which seems very attractive. In this configuration, each unit is box-shaped and possesses two permeable walls, which retain the particles. Gas is fed to the bottom, while liquid passes the unit in cross-flow. The configuration developed allows countercurrent operation of the fluid phases and easy plug flow approximation (tanks in series). In first instance the project focuses on the description of a single unit. This approach fits well into one of the central research themes of the OSPT; small scale development of industrial scale reactors.<P>

<I><B>Progress </B></I><BR>
<I>* Hydrodynamics:</I><BR>
Two models have been developed describing the distribution of the solid phase between the cake layer on the membrane and the slurry bulk. One model is based on a combination of penetration theory, viscous resuspension theory and Kolmogoroff’s theory of isotropic turbulence. The other model is based on a force balance using an analogy with slurry flow in horizontal pipes. Both models result in the same dimensionless number uniquely describing the equilibrium solids holdup in the slurry bulk. Experiments have been performed in which the cake resistance is determined as an indirect measure of solids holdup. These experiments have proven the novel dimensionless number to describe the simultaneous influence of permeate flux, gas velocity, particle diameter and kinematic liquid viscosity. The independence of filter cake build-up on gas phase density has been demonstrated as well by varying the molar mass of the injected gas (He, N<SUB>2</SUB>, SF<SUB>6</SUB>). This result is also predicted by both models developed. A novel measurement technique for solids holdups less than 15 v% in a gas/liquid/solids system is also being developed. This technique, based on fluorescence, has been validated for a liquid/solid system. After demonstration of the technique for a three phase system, direct validation of the filtration models developed will be possible.<BR>
<I>* Chemical Reaction:</I><BR>
An inventarisation and characterisation of relevant industrial processes has been made. This involves a.o. applicability of a membrane slurry reactor to the various processes. Also, a number of potentially interesting reactor concepts have been generated. A small scale reactor has been constructed to demonstrate the operability of a filtering slurry reactor using the hydrogenation of alpha-methylstyrene.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
