<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Discrete Particle Simulation of Fluidised Beds
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Discrete Particle Simulation of Fluidised Beds</H2>
Ph.D. student: Ir. Bob Hoomans (+31 -(0)53-4892948 / <A HREF="mailto:b.p.b.hoomans@ct.utwente.nl">b.p.b.hoomans@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
project duration: 1-6-1995 / 1-6-1999<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/hoomans.html">http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/hoomans.html</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

A discrete particle model of a two-
dimensional gas-fluidised bed has been
developed. The motion of the particles is
directly calculated from the forces acting
on them whilst particle interactions are
taken into account. The particles are
assumed to interact through instantaneous,
binary, inelastic collisions with friction.
Simulation techniques from hard-sphere
simulations, which are commonly
encountered in Molecular Dynamics, are
used to process a sequence of collisions.
The gas phase is modeled by instationary
conservation laws of mass and momentum
for      two-phase      flows.      This
Eulerian/Lagrangian simulation technique
offers a unique possibility to study the
influence of the particle characteristics on
the bed-hydrodynamics in great detail.<P>

<B>Objective</B><P>

This project is a cooperation with the
Chemical Physics group of Dr. W.J. Briels
at Twente University. The objective is to
study the influence of particle properties on
the fluidisation behaviour.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Simulations with the two-dimensional
model have shown a strong dependency of
the fluidisation behaviour with respect to
the impact properties [1] (i.e. coefficients
of restitution and friction). Animations of
these simulations are available at the
project's homepage (<I>see above</I>).<P>

Furthermore the two-dimensional model
has been extended to take a particle size
distribution into account. Segregation has
been successfully simulated for both
polydisperse and polydense mixtures. A
snapshot of a simulation with a binary size
distribution is presented below.<P>

<IMG SRC="2401.gif" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=406><P>

At present the code is extended in order to
study riser flow.<P>

Experimental validation of the models is of
crucial importance and will be part of the
project as well.<P>

[1] B.P.B. Hoomans, J.A.M. Kuipers, W.J.Briels &
W.P.M. van Swaaij, 1996, Discrete Particle
Simulation of Bubble and Slug Formation in a Two-
Dimensional Gas-Fluidised Bed: a Hard-Sphere
Approach,<I>Chem. Engng Sci.</I>, Vol. <B>51</B>, pp 99-118.


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

