<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of an Integrated Pilot Plant for the Flash Pyrolysis of Biomass
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Development of an Integrated Pilot Plant for the Flash Pyrolysis of Biomass</H2>
PhD student: ir. Arthur M.C. Janse (053-892935)<BR>
Supervisor: dr.ir. W.Prins (053-892891)<BR>
Project term: November 1993-November 1996<BR>
Financial support: CEC (Air Program), Novera, "de Schelde"<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

A continuous pilot plant for the flash pyrolysis of
biomass to bio-oil with a design throughput of 10
kg/hr wood is being developed. This integrated unit
combines the flash pyrolysis process with the
combustion of the produced char to operate the
plant autothermally.<P>

<IMG SRC="2411.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=300><P>

<I>Figure 1: Scheme (left) and 3D-view (righ0 of the
continuous pyrolysis pilot plant</I><P>

The core of the pilot plant (see figure 1) consists of
a rotating cone reactor. Sand and biomass particles
are fed to the bottom of the reactor and move
upwards in a spiral way along the cone wall due to
the centrifugal force. Eventually, the solids leave
the reactor by passing the upper edge of the cone
wall. The sand particles are added to prevent
fouling of the cone wall and improve the heat
transfer to the biomass particles. A disadvantage of
this first generation cone reactor is that the sand
particles must be recycled continuously to the
bottom of the cone.<BR>
A new type of cone has been developed in which
the cone bottom plate is missing. By inserting the
cone into a fluidized bed, the sand particles are
soaked up automatically into the rotating cone,
move along the cone wall, and fall over the wall
back into the fluidized bed. In this way an internal
recirculation is realized.<BR>
A specific feature of this new cone type is the
possibility to recycle also partly converted biomass
particles. In this way, single pass conversion is not
necessary and somewhat coarser biomass feed can
be processed.<BR>
A second fluidized bed, called the combustor is
positioned around the cone reactor and its
belonging (first) fluid bed. This second fluid bed is
meant for the combustion of produced char. Sand
and char particles are transported from the inner
fluid bed to the combustor bed through an orifice.
The transport of hot sand from the combustor to
the cone vessel is realized with a riser, partly
submerged into the combustor bed. Additional
advantages of this pilot plant configuration are its
compactness and integrated character.<P>

<IMG SRC="2412.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=354><P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Cold flow experiments with cones of several scales
showed very high sand transport capacities without
the use of much carrier gas, up to 1.5 kg/s for a
pilot scale cone (height 60 cm, cone angle 60°).
Also the heat transfer characteristics of the rotating
cone reactor have been investigated, using the
newly developed fluoroptic measurement
technique. The cone reactor exhibits higher external
heat transfer coefficients (in the order of 500-1500
W/m<SUP>2</SUP>/K), than normally encountered in fluidized
beds. Other cold flow experiments in a cold full
scale version of the pilot plant revealed the
possibility to realize a constant sand recirculation
between the two reactor vessels and the easiness of
this operation.<BR>
The first experiments with the hot version of the
pilot plant have been carried out successfully.
Substantial amounts of bio-oil have been produced
already and also the possibility to transport char
from the rotating cone bed to the combustor bed
has been proven.<BR>
Future work will concentrate on enhancing the
biomass throughput of the pilot plant and on the
addition of catalyst particles to improve the quality
of the produced bio-oil.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
