<HEAD>
<TITLE>Rapid Cycling Reactor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Rapid Cycling Reactor</H2>
PhD-student: Ir. Martin van Sint Annaland (053-4892881 / <A HREF="mailto:sintanna@ct.utwente.nl">sintanna@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Promotor: Prof. dr.ir. W.P.M. van Swaaij<BR>
Supervisor: Dr.ir. J.A.M. Kuipers<BR>
Project term: August 1996 - August 1999<BR>
Sponsor: SON<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>


Heterogeneously catalysed gas phase reactions
with very rapid catalyst deactivation form an
industrially important class of chemical
transformations. An example of this type of
reactions is the dehydrogenation of lower
paraffin's to the corresponding olefins. During
the endothermic dehydrogenation the catalyst
is deactivated by coke formation. After a short
time on stream the catalyst has to be
regenerated. The heat supplied by the
exothermic regeneration is used for the
endothermic dehydrogenation.<BR>
Processes that are currently being applied in
industry for this type of reactions are based on
the packed bed reactor technology or the
fluidised bed reactor technology. The main
disadvantages of packed bed reactors are
possible plugging of the catalyst bed and
temperature control during the exothermic
regeneration. The main drawback of fluidised
bed reactors is the large catalyst flow between
the dehydrogenation reactor and the
regeneration reactor.<P>

<B>Scope</B><BR>
The main objectives of the project are the
development and description of a reactor
system for alternately heterogeneously
catalysed endothermic gas phase reactions
with very rapid catalyst deactivation and in
situ exothermic catalyst regeneration in order
to achieve a high conversion rate per unit
reactor volume and a good heat integration of
the endothermic main reaction(s) and the
exothermic regeneration reaction(s).<P>

<B>Concept</B><BR>
As a possible reactor configuration a
multitubular or monolith type reactor will be
studied, where the catalyst is deposited at the
tube walls. For this type of reactor scale-up or
scale-down procedures may be facilitated by
the use of the concept of parallelism. The tube
walls serve as an energy repository. During the
phase when endothermic reactions proceed
heat is withdrawn from the tube walls and
during the regeneration phase heat is supplied
to the tube walls. Because of the limited heat
capacity of the tube walls and the rapid
catalyst deactivation, the switching times
between the main and regeneration reactions
will be very short. This will put special
demands on the micro-switches controlling the
feed flow to a single tube or a group of tubes.
Within the present concept also periodic flow
reversal will be studied. Beside other benefits
of reverse flow reactors, this type of operation
enables very high temperatures in the center of
the reactor, despite the fact that low
temperatures prevail at the reactor inlet and
outlet. This allows the micro-switches to be
operated at lower temperatures. The fast
switching between the main reaction(s) and
the regeneration reaction(s) on the one hand
and the flow direction on the other hand
explains the name given to this project: Rapid
Cycling Reactor (RCR).<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL><LI>
Development of an advanced model to
simulate the dynamic behaviour of the
various processes occurring in the RCR.
Using this model an optimal reactor
configuration and reactor dimensions, as
well as optimal reaction conditions and
cycling times can be determined.
<LI>
After selecting an appropriate reaction
system, the concept of the RCR will be
tested in an experimental set-up.
</UL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
