<HEAD>
<TITLE>A Catalytic Membrane Reactor for Partial Oxidation Reactions
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>A Catalytic Membrane Reactor for Partial Oxidation Reactions</H2>
Ph.D. Student: Ir. Hein Neomagus (053-4894338)<BR>
Supervisor : Prof. dr. ir. Geert Versteeg (053-4893027)<BR>
Project term: March 1994 - March 1998<BR>
Sponsor     : GASTEC NV Apeldoorn<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

In the past years, a new type of membrane reactor has been developed. This reactor
is largely made up of two chambers, separated by a (catalytic active) membrane.
The reactants are introduced into the reactor on opposite sides of this membrane,
and will diffuse into the membrane, where they meet and will react. Besides the
partial pressures of the components in both compartments, the reaction plane in the
membrane can also be shifted with the applied pressure difference over the
membrane.<BR>
A new application of this type of reactor is to perform a partial oxidation in which
the intermediate is the desired product (B):<P>

<IMG SRC="2431.gif" WIDTH=328 HEIGHT=50><P>

It may be possible to influence the selectivity of the reaction, by inducting a
pressure difference between the two chambers. A higher pressure on the 'oxidation-
side' of the membrane causes the already produced (and desired) products to be
driven away from the oxidation zone and therefore to be protected against further
oxidation into undesired products. After a kinetic research the partial oxidation of
isobutene to methacrolein and methacrylic acid is chosen as a model reaction to
prove this principle:<P>

<IMG SRC="2432.gif" WIDTH=540 HEIGHT=50><P>

The membrane reactor has also proven to be a successful catalytic burner for
methane and a deep investigation will now be done to clarify whether this reactor is
also a possible alternative for performing the catalytic partial oxidation (cPo) of
methane to syngas, which is another interesting way of converting methane.<P>

<IMG SRC="2433.gif" WIDTH=271 HEIGHT=50><P>

Also new types of this reactor are studied; a membrane reactor based on sintered
stainless steel for the oxidation of H<SUB>2</SUB>S to S0<SUB>2</SUB>, is investigated as an alternative for
the use of ceramic membranes.<BR>
The CPO of methane is also studied in a reactor where a conventional packed bed
is the physical barrier between the two reactants.<P>

The flux model based on the Dusty Gas Model (Veldsink 1993) has been extended
for non-isothermal conditions and an inhomogeneous distribution of the catalyst.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
