<HEAD>
<TITLE>Application of hydrophobic particles for the removal of halogenated hydrocarbons and heavy metals from waste water
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Application of hydrophobic particles for the removal of halogenated hydrocarbons and heavy metals from waste water</H2>
Ph.D.-student: Ir. G. Rexwinkel (053-4894338)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr. Ir. A.B.M. Heesink (053-4893024)<BR>
Project term: October 1993-October 1997<BR>
Sponsor: IOP Preventie, AKZO Nobel<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Instead of activated carbon, which has bad
regeneration    characteristics,    porous
polymer particles can be used for the
reinoval of halogenated hydrocarbons from
waste water. Adsorption at the surface of
these polymers is highly reversible
allowing smooth regeneration.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The main objectives of this project are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Model development of the processes
that occur in the particles.
<LI>Model development of the processes
that occur during desorption with steam.
<LI>Model development of the processes
that occur in the contactor.
<LI>Revealing the dominating mechanisms
for mass transfer in packed beds.
</UL>
<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The adsorption equilibrium of a mixture of
1,1,l-trichloroethane and nitrogen gas on
Amberlite XAD-4 particles was examined
in a thermogravimetric analyser at various
temperatures. At various partial pressures
the sorbent particles were allowed to reach
equilibrium at 20°C, subsequently the
temperature of the sorbent particles was
raised up to 120°C, using a heating rate of
6°C/hour. The weight of the sorbent
sample was continuously monitored. A
model has been developed that describes
the uptake of halogenated hydrocarbons as
a function of partial pressure or
concentration and temperature. Freundlich
type adsorption has been assumed where
the heat of adsorption is taken to be
proportional with the logarithm of the
uptake of halogenated hydrocarbons:<P>

<IMG SRC="2451.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=32><P>

Using the above mentioned assumptions
the van 't Hoff equation can be integrated,
resulting in the following equation:<P>

<IMG SRC="2452.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=252><P>

In figure 1 a parity-plot of the measured
and calculated uptake is shown.<P>

<IMG SRC="2453.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=370><P>

<I><B>figure 1:</B></I> parity-plot of calculated and measured uptake<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
The developed model is capable of
describing the experiments quite accurate.
The average relative deviation between
experiment and model is 3%.<P>

