<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Pressure Profiles in RPSA
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Pressure Profiles in RPSA</H2>
PhD. Student: ir. Frank Foeth (<A HREF="mailto:f.foeth@ct.utwente.nl">f.foeth@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisor: dr. Ir. H. Bosch (<A HREF="mailto:hansbosch@ct.utwente.nl">hansbosch@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Project term: 1 June 1991 - 1 June 1996<BR>
Sponsor: eerste geldstroom<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Rapid Pressure Swing Adsorption (RPSA)
takes place in a single column with a large flow
resistance. Therefore not only composition
waves but also pressure and temperature waves
occur thoughout a cycle. An RPSA cycle comprises three steps:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>high pressure feed step
<LI>redistribution of pressure in delay step
<LI>regeneration in exhaust step
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="2481.gif"><P>

<I>Fig. I Pressure profiles during feed, delay
and exhaust step</I><P>

Short cycle times (typically less than 10s), continuous product generation and high adsorbent.
productivity are
characteristic
for
RPSA
processes.<P>

<B>Goal</B><BR>
Calculation of pressure response without any
parameter fitting.<BR>
Accurate model calculations are necessary to
facilitate optimisation of the many process para-
meters that determine product purity and reco-
very.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
We studied the separation of methane from
CO<SUB>2</SUB>-CH<SUB>4</SUB> mixtures at 40 °C in a lm column
with 10 mm ID filled with .25 mm activated
carbon particles and provided with pressure and
temperature sensors along the column length.<P>

<B>RPSA Model</B><BR>
Continuity equation for each component:<P>

<IMG SRC="2482.gif"><P>

The (quadratic) Ergun equation relates the
superficial velocity u and the total pressure
gradient.<BR>
Our RPSA model takes into account volumes of
vessels and flow resistances in valves. The
numerical method of lines is used to solve the
resulting system of partial differential equations. Special features, e.g., sigmoid curves to
simulate the opening and closing of the valves
and bi-directionai difference procedures were
incorporated to improve the stability of the calculation.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR><P>

<IMG SRC="2483.gif"><P>

<I>Fig. 2 Measured (dotted lines) and calculated
(symbols) pressure response as a 
function of time</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
