</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Coated Adsorbents for Pressure Swing Adorption
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Coated Adsorbents for Pressure Swing Adorption</H2>
Ph.D. student: Drs Rick van der Vaart (0534892876)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr Ir Hans Bosch (0534892826)<BR>
Project term: December '92-December '96<BR>
Sponsor: SON/STW<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The last two decades have seen a tremendous growth in
research activities in the field of adsorptive gas separation.
One of the main topics is the development of more selective
adsorbents.<BR>
In the present research, the selectivity is enhanced by the
combination of the adsorbent with a selective membrane. As a
first stage in the development of those coated adsorbents we
here present experimental results on cellulose acetate coated
activated carbon. We focused on a l-dimensional tablet
geometry to facilitate sample preparation.<P>

<IMG SRC="2491.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=194><P>

<B>Model</B><BR>
The tablet is only accessible through the membrane as shown
in Figure 1. Instantaneous equilibrium powder particles
(Langmuir), Laminar flow and dispersion:<P>

<IMG SRC="2492.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=101><P>

with boundary conditions:<P>

<IMG SRC="2493.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=113><P>

and initial conditions:<P>

<IMG SRC="2494.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=39><P>

<B>Membrane preparation and characterisation</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Dipping technique using a 14% cellulose acetate (Kodak
Eastman) solution in DMF (Merck, zur synthese) while the
pores were blocked with a filler.
<LI>Gas permeation measurements of CO<SUB>2</SUB> and CH<SUB>4</SUB>.
</UL>

<B>Uptake measurements</B><BR>
gravimetrical (Hiden Analytical Gravimetric Analyser):<BR>
pressure step of 1000-2000 mbar CO<SUB>2</SUB><BR>
pressure step of 5-3000 mbar CH<SUB>4</SUB><BR>
<P>
<B>Experimental results</B><BR>

<IMG SRC="2495.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=804><P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>A dip-coating technique turns out to be suitable to coat an
activated carbon tablet with a defect-free cellulose acetate
membrane.
<LI>The model predicts the experimental uptake reasonably well
without any parameter fitting.
<LI>The use of a selective coating results in a gain in selectivity
<LI>Accumulation of the poor permeating component improves
selectivity.
<LI>Coated adsorbents may be feasible; However, the
development of a method to apply very thin coatings to
adsorbent particles is essential.
</UL>

