<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Adsorption Isotherms from Temperature - Programmed Desorption experiments
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Adsorption Isotherms from Temperature - Programmed Desorption experiments</H2>
PhD Student: Ir. Jose Mugge (053-4892876 / <A HREF="mailto:J.M.Mugge@ct.utwente.nl">J.M.Mugge@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr.ir. Hans Bosch<BR>
Project term: May 1996 - May 2000<BR>
Sponsor: SON<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
A new TPD method to determine a series of
adsorption isotherms from a limited number of
experiments is investigated. It combines two older
methods:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>a flow measurement of adsorption
isotherms, and
<LI>temperature-programmed reduction for the
evaluation of activation energies.
</UL>
The basic idea is to calculate the adsorption
isotherm parameters from exit concentration
profiles, which result from a continuous rise at a
constant feed composition.<P>

Previous work for a system of one adsorbing
component has shown that it is possible to obtain
accurate values for the adsorption parameters from
TPD: the calculated isotherms agreed well with
reference adsorption data obtained from other
techniques.<P>

At the moment the method is expanded for a system
of one strong and one weak adsorbing component.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
The adsorption of CO<SUB>2</SUB>/N<SUB>2</SUB> mixtures on an activated
carbon (RB1, courtesy Norit) was studied in a
packed bed. Prior to a TPD run the isothermal
breakthrough was used to determine the quantity
adsorbed at the starting temperature. During a TPD
run the exit concentration was continuously
monitored as a function of a linear increase in
temperature, the feed composition was kept
constant.<P>

<B>Model</B><BR>
The TPD response curves were modelled using a
differential mole balance equation:<P>

<IMG SRC="2501.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=257><P>

The assumptions underlying the model are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>no radial gradients
<LI>no axial temperature gradients
<LI>ideal gases
<LI>constant pressure
<LI>Langmuir adsorption:<BR>
<IMG SRC="2502.gif" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=90>
<LI>local adsorption equilibrium between the
solid and the surroundig gas phase is
established.
</UL>
<P>

<B>Preliminary Results</B><BR>
During the experiments heating rate, total flow and
feed concentration were varied. The modelled TPD
curves were fitted to the experimental data to
obtain values for the adsorption parameters.<P>

<IMG SRC="2503.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=670><P>

<B>Further Research</B><BR>
Further work include experiments to investigate
in more detail the parameters influencing heat
and mass transfer in TPD measurements.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
