<HEAD>
<TITLE>Modelling and Measurements of Protein Adsorption Kinetics under Shear Flow using Ellipsometry
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Modelling and Measurements of Protein Adsorption Kinetics under Shear Flow using Ellipsometry</H2>
PhD student: Ir. Sander Rekveld (+31-53-4892930 / <A HREF="mailto:S.Rekveld@ct.utwente.nl">S.Rekveld@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr. ir. Imre G. Racz(+31-53-4893019)<BR>
Project term: October 1992 - January 1997<BR>
Sponsor: Unilever Research Vlaardingen<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The adsorption of proteins and subsequent removal of
the resulting layer presents a major problem in industry.
Rate determining step(s) of removal have not yet been
identified as a function of process parameters.
Unfortunately, most experimental studies have been
carried out under undefined mass transport conditions.
However, to extract the intrinsic kinetics experimental
studies of adsorption/desorption kinetics under defined
flow are necessary. Therefore. to increase the
understanding of removal processes in general, and of the
effect of aqueous flow on adsorption and removal in
particular, experiments providing measurements of
removal of protein under defined hydrodynamic
conditions have been carried out.<BR>
The effect of surfactants on the removal is also
investigated.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
To find the rate determining step(s) in protein
adsorption/desorption from comparison between model-
ling of diffusion/convection and adsorption/desorption
and in situ measurements of the protein layer in a
parallel plate flow cell.<P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
The adsorption and desorption of proteins is modelled as
a pseudo reaction of the protein molecules with the
surface, using Langmuir kinetics:<P>

<IMG SRC="2511.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=291><P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
<I>Materials</I><BR>
Fibrinogen a blood protein is used at concentrations
from 50 - 1000 mg/l solutions.<BR>
Surfaces consist of chromium layers prepared by thermal
evaporation onto glass substrates.<P>

<I>Methods</I><BR>
A sensitive optical technique, dynamic in situ ellipso-
merry is used to monitor the removal of soil layers on
the molecular level.<P>

<IMG SRC="2512.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=238><P>

Total reflection ellipsometry is used to monitor the
adsorption and removal of fibrinogen from the surfaces.
The preparation of the surfaces is critical in obtaining
reproducible results. Therefore, after cleaning the
surfaces are characterised using both ellipsometry to
determine the optical properties and by contact angle
measurements.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Time resolved in situ experiments during adsorption and
desorption of protein show Langmuir type of adsorption
kinetics at low concentrations of protein (<50 mg/l).
At higher concentrations an overshoot in adsorbed
amount is found that cannot be described by Langmuir
kinetics.<BR>
Measurements show only complete removal of the
fibrinogen layer by C<SUB>12</SUB>EO<SUB>5</SUB> (2. c.m.c.) from chromium
surfaces in parallel plate flow at low concentrations.
By comparing measurements with numerical
calculations of convection and diffusion, mass transport
limitations where shown to be absent at the
concentrations and shear flow velocity used.<BR>
Therefore the rate determining step in fibrinogen
adsorption to chromium surfaces at the shear velocity
(3500 s<SUP>-1</SUP>) studied where shown to be determined by the
kinetics of adsorption and desorption. Mass transport
limitations where absent for all concentrations studied.<P>

<B>Acknowledgments</B><BR>
This project in sponsored and supported by Unilever
Research Vlaardingen.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
