<HEAD>
<TITLE>Application of membrane technology for industrial waste water
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Application of membrane technology for industrial waste water</H2>
PhD student: Ir. J.P. van 't Hul (053-4892930 / <A HREF="mailto:J.P.vantHul@ct.utwente.nl">J.P.vantHul@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr. Ir. I.G. Racz<BR>
Project term: March 1994 - March 1998<BR>
Sponsor: Ministry of Economic Affairs (IOP-prevention)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<IMG SRC="2521.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=330><P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In the textile industry a large amount of
water and chemicals are used in order to
meet the desired product qualities. This
causes waste water, which is now usually
treated in a municipal water purification.
In the future this will be confronted with
cost increment and restrictions.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The overall objective of this IOP
prevention programme is to show how
membranes can be used to minimise the
use of chemicals, water and energy.
Membranes can be used for two purposes.
Firstly process water and its energy can be
recycled. Secondly waste can be
concentrated for further treatment.
Unfortunatelly a membrane process shows
an unwanted flux decline in time. This
complicates the design of such processes.
The special objective of this research is to
study this flux decline.<P>

<B>Preliminary results</B><BR>
The washing process after the textile
dyeing process, where unfixed dyes are
washed out has been chosen as topic of
study. Calculations on a modified
washing-process by using membranes
showed a possible water saving of 70
percent compared to the original process.
An experimental unit has been constructed
for testing membrane modules.<P>

<B>Further research on membranes</B><BR>
Waste water of textile washing ranges
consists of dyes and auxiliary chemicals.
These auxiliary chemicals differ from the
sort of washing process used. Firstly
experiments with real waste water will be
done to investigate flux decline. After that
experiments with artificial waste water
will be done to investigate which
(combination of ) components are responsible for this flux decline.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
