<HEAD>
<TITLE>Flux enhancement in ultrafiltration by secondary flows in curved channels
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Flux enhancement in ultrafiltration by secondary flows in curved channels</H2>
PhD student: ir. Jan Ophoff (+ 31(0)53 489 29 30 / <A HREF="mailto:J.Ophoff@ct.utwente.nl">J.Ophoff@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisor: dr. ir. Imre G. Racz (+ 31(0)53 489 30 19)<BR>
Project term: November 1993 - February 1998<BR>
Sponsors: NWO/STW, Stork Friesland B.V.<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Membrane separation processes are widely
used in many industrial applications for
concentrating and fractionating. Advantages of
membrane applications are direct separation
without the use of additives and no phase
change in the process. However, in pressure-
driven membrane processes the most severe
limitations are concentration polarisation and
fouling due to limited back transport. The result
of concentration polarisation is a considerably
lower flux than the pure water flux.<P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
In membrane separation processes
concentration polarisation and fouling limit the
flux through the membrane. Concentration<P>

<IMG SRC="2531.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=173><P>

<I>figure 1</I> Secondary streamlines in a curved tube<P>

polarisation occurs as result of the limited back
transport rate of the rejected molecules. This
back transport can be enhanced by eddies that
occur in turbulent flow or in baffled flow
channels or in pulsating flow. In other recently
developed membrane modules vortices are
created by a rotating tube (Taylor flow) or by
centrifugal forces caused by the curvature of
the membrane itself (Dean flow). The last
method seems very promising: easy to scale-up
and energetically attractive. We are
investigating the application of this concept in
membrane modules. In <I>figure 1</I>, the

characteristic secondary flow behaviour is
showed. The secondary flow field in curved
channels yields the same back mixing under
laminar flow conditions as turbulent flow
causes in straight flow channels.<P>

<B>Research program</B><BR>
Based on the above considerations, we have
developed a new membrane module. In <I>figure 2</I>
an example of a curved tube membrane module
is shown.<P>

<IMG SRC="2532.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=158><P>

<I>figure 2</I> preliminary module design for a curved tubular membrane module<P>

<B>Conclusion</B><BR>
Curved channel membrane modules have a
very high potential. Under laminar flow
conditions relatively high fluxes can be
reached. Research has to be done on the
modelling of the mass transfer in coiled tubes
for example as a function of the curvature. The
model will be validated by measurements. The
design of curved channel membrane modules
has to be optimised to enhance the membrane
surface area per module volume.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
