<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Phd-projects Enschede</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Department of Industrial Processes and Products<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
University of Twente
Department of Chemical Engineering
P.O. Box 217
NL 7500 AE Enschede

telephone: +31 (0)53 489 2877
fax:       +31 (0)53 489 4821
e-mail:    <A HREF="mailto:K.R.Westerterp@ct.utwente.nl">K.R.Westerterp@ct.utwente.nl</A>
internet:  <A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/vakgr/weste.html">http://www.ct.utwente.nl/vakgr/weste.html</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<CENTER>Twente University of Technology</CENTER><P>

<H2><CENTER>Research Group 'Industrial Processes and Products'</CENTER></H2>

<B>Permanent staff</B><BR>
Prof.dr.ir. K.R. Westerterp<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
Dr. M.S.A. Vrijland<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
Prof.dr. G. Weickert<BR>
Dr. A.E. Kronberg<BR>
Ir. H. van den Beld<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
Dr.ir. A.G.J. van der Ham<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
Ing. G.H. Banis<SUP>*</SUP><P>

<SUP>*</SUP> participating in OSPT<P>

<B>Research Fellows</B><BR>
Dr. K. M&uuml;ndlein<P>

<B>Research Scientists</B><BR>
Ir. J. van den Beld<BR>
Ir. A. Benneker<BR>
Ir. J.W. Bolk<BR>
Ir. J. Kulman<BR>
Ir. G. Meier<BR>
Ir. J.J. Samson<BR>
Ir. P. Roos<BR>
Ir. A. Westenbroek<BR>
Ir. B. van Woezik<BR>
Ing. F. Strozzi<P>

<H4>Research Themes</H4>

The research themes are directed towards applications in the chemical industry. Based on chemical and mechanical engineering, physics, chemistry, economics, mathematics, modelling and biotechnology several important areas in process development are exercised, for the development of both individual processes as well as particular tools to be generally applied in this area of science.<P>

<I>Development of processes with high heat effects</I><P>

The most dangerous aspects of chemical reactors is the evolution of heat during a reaction. The problems are moreover multiplied if the process is executed under pressure. Therefore the research in this field is directed towards better understanding of equipment used and towards the development of safety procedures. For highly exothermic and catalytic processes often a wall cooled tube filled with catalyst is used. Much work is being done to better understand this equipment, so that eventually it can be designed on the basis of kinetic measurements alone and also runaway cam be prevented. Also the flow reversal reactor is being developed to clean air polluted with volatile organic compounds by catalytic oxidation and without any additional energy supply. Also explosion limits in flowing gases in pipe lines are studied. Runaways (Seveso) in chemical industry can have disastrous consequences. To prevent runaways in (semi) batch reactors special safety procedures are developed theoretically and experimentally. Start-up of chemical plant and major changes of operating conditions always are critical from a safety and environmental protection point of view; therefore start-up procedures are developed and tested in industrial plants. Oxidation, nitration, esterfication and combustion reactions are used in this research.<P>

<I>Development of three phase processes</I><P>

Investigation of catalytic hydrogenation reactors for the fine chemicals industry where a single reactor is used for multitude of hydrogenation reactions. The influence of pressure on the hydrodynamics in (packed) bubble columns, agitated gas-liquid slurry and trickle flow reactors is being studied using e.g. CO<SUB>2</SUB>-amine reactions.<P>

<I>Polymerization Reactor Engineering</I><P>

The set-up of the Polymerization Reaction Engineering group (PRE) started 3 years ago, specialised equipment has been purchased and new projects for bulk polymerization have been started.<P>

<OL TYPE=i>
Major research items are:
<LI>Ziegler Natta propylene polymerization
   <UL>
   <LI>experimental research and modelling of the polymerization of propylene in solution-, slurry- and fluidized bed reactors.
   <LI>Scale-up of fluidized bed reactors for Ziegler-Natta (Kaminsky) catalyzed propylene polymerization.
   </UL>
<LI>Mathematical modelling of bulk polymerization reactors with the focus on high temperature, high conversion and high viscosity polymerization. Styrene polymerization is chosen as a model system.
<LI>Runaway studies and reactor safety in polymerization.
</OL>

<I>Fundamental research on (axial) dispersion in packed bed reactors</I><P>

The theoretical development and experimental confirmation of a new general one-dimensional model for longitudinal dispersion in various chemical reactors, the so called 'wave model', to replace the Danckwerts model.<P>

<I>Exploratory chemical process development</I><P>

Development of new processes for methanol production, e.g. the reactor section with interstage product removal concept and carbonylation.<P>

<I>Process Economics</I><P>

Process economics are used as a tool to evaluate research results but also to screen industrial processes, and to determine the major cost factors and to obtain eventually better cost estimation methods for (new) processes.<P>

<I>Biotechnology and environmental protection</I><P>

The skills of reaction engineering, mathematical modelling and microbiology are combined to develop new processes. A process for biological soil decontamination and a membrane bioreactor process have ben developed and are being introduced into industrial practice.<P>

<I>Computer applications in chemical technology</I><P>

All the process development and evaluation work is accompanied by active mathematical modelling (Speedup, gPROMS), flowsheeting (Aspen, Hysim) and optimization of process conditions (SimuSolv).<P>

<I>Automation and measurement</I><P>

Due to demands for safety, accuracy, reproducibility and also the large amount of measurements, remote control of most of the experimental plants in the High Pressure Laboratory is very essential. By automation a set-up a different type of experimental procedure is obtained and also continuous operation and long time testing catalysts becomes feasible. Over the past years, much special knowledge has been obtained concerning mass flow and pressure measurements and especially accurate temperature measurement.<P>

<B>Industrial Research</B><P>

Many projects received and receive support from industry: Akzo, DOW, DSM, Shell, etc. Further, support was received from NWO/STW.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 17/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
