<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Flexible Low Density Polymeric Foams With CO2 Used as an Environmentally Friendly Blowing Agent
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Flexible Low Density Polymeric Foams With CO<SUB>2</SUB> Used as an Environmentally Friendly Blowing Agent</H2>
PhD student: Ir. Warner J. Nauta (+31-53-489 2869 / <A HREF="mailto:w.j.nauta@ct.utwente.nl">w.j.nauta@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr. ir. Th. van den Boomgaard (+31-53-489 2965)<BR>
Fax: +31-53-489 4611<BR>
Internet: <A HREF="http://utct1029.ct.utwente.nl/people/w.j.nauta">http://utct1029.ct.utwente.nl/people/w.j.nauta</A><BR>
Project term: March 1996 - February 2000<BR>
Sponsor: DSM Research<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Motivation</B><BR>
Low density polymeric foams (p<50
kg/m<SUP>3</SUP>) can be produced by dissolving a low
boiling liquid or an easy condensable gas
(<I>blowing agent</I>) under high pressure in the
polymer melt. Extrusion to atmospheric
conditions induces nucleation of bubbles,
reshiring in a cellular structure. Traditionally,
blowing agents like chlorofluorocarbons and
aliphatic hydi'ocarbons have been used in the
production of low density foams. However,
environmental concerns make the use of these
blowing agents questionable. Carbon dioxide
might be a promising substitute: it is inert, non
toxic, easy available and has a very low global
warming potential.<P>

<B>Research objectives</B><BR>
The dimensions of foams produced from
low modulus materials like polethylene and
polypropylene are not stable in time. After
production carbon dioxide present inside the
cells of the foam permeates out of the cells
into the surrounding; simultaneously air
permeates from the surrounding into the cells.
However, due to a discrepancy in these fluxes
- carbon dioxide permeates faster out then air
into the foam - an subambient pressure will bc
created inside the foam, resulting in a collapse
due to the low modulus of the material.<BR>
In this project we try to find out the
mechanism of the exchange of blowing agent
by air and how to influence this. This can be
done by the introduction of components which
reduce blowing agent permeability. Further-
more the dimensional stability of the foam will
be quantitatively related to polymer
permeability by means of gas transport
modeling.<P>

<B>Gas Transport Modeling</B><BR>
Preliminary results indicate that the
dimensional stability of a low density foam
can be quantitatively related to the permeation
properties of the polymer. In Figure 1 the
relative volume change of a foam piece is
shown as a function of time.<P>

<IMG SRC="2601.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=267><P>

In numerical simulations the exchange of
blowing agent by air is assumed to be 1-
dimensional. The closed-cell foam is
approximated by parallel polymer layers. The
amount of gas in the foam is calculated as
function of the time (Figure 2)<P>

<IMG SRC="2602.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=266><P>

As can be seen experimental results are in
good agreement with the numerical results.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
