<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Water diffusion limitation in bipolar membranes at high current density
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Water diffusion limitation in bipolar membranes at high current density</H2>
PhD student: Ir. John Krol (053-4892961)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr. Ir. Matthias Wessling (053-4892962)<BR>
Project term: May 1993- May 1997<BR>
Sponsor: University of Twente<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Bipolar membranes are membranes that
contain on one side positive fixed charges and
on the other side negative fixed charges.
When placed in an electric field bipolar
membranes are capable to perform accele-
rated water dissociation i.e. water is split into
protons and hydroxyl ions. In combination
with monopolar ion exchange membranes,
bipolar membranes can thus be used to
produce acid and base solutions from the
corresponding salt solution. Figure I shows
the schematics of this process in the case of
NaC1 as the starting salt solution.<P>

<IMG SRC="2611.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=273><P>

<I><B>Figure 1:</B></I> Production of HCI and NaOH from
a NaC1 solution using a bipolar membrane
which splits water into protons and hydroxyl
ions (aem = anion exchange, cem = cation
exchange, bm = bipolar membrane).<P>

The process using bipolar membranes is
economically very attractive and has a
multitude of interesting applications. Salt
solutions, for example, are often encountered
as waste water streams in industry. With
bipolar membranes, these streams can be
converted into acid and base streams thereby
not only increasing the value of the chemicals
but also reducing the amount of waste water
to be disposed of, an important factor with
regard to environmental problems and the
environmental regulations that become more
and more stringent nowadays.<P>

<B>Water diffusion limitation</B><P>

The prime function of a bipolar membrane is
the splitting of water into protons and hydro-
xyl ions. Water that is split at the bipolar
membrane interphase is replenished by
diffusion from the bulk solutions through
both layers of the membrane. Increasing the
current density through the membrane
increases the water splitting rate and hence
the consumption of water necessary for the
reaction. Hence it is to be expected that at a
certain current density the diffusion of water
into the bipolar membrane limits the water
splitting rate.<BR>
Figure 2 shows a measured current - voltage
curve of a bipolar membrane. At high current
(about 480 mA/cm^2) an inflection point is
observed showing a drastic increase in
resistance caused by drying out of the bipolar
membrane interphase.<P>

<IMG SRC="2612.gif"><P>

<I><B>Figure 2:</B></I> Voltage drop (dv) across bipolar
membrane as a function of applied current
density i.<P>

The increase in resistance is found to be ir-
reversible. At the moment research is carried
out to establish the chemical nature of these
irreversible changes occurring with a bipolar
membrane when it is submitted to current
densities exceeding the inflection point.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
