<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Development and Application of Bipolar Membrane Technology
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>The Development and Application of Bipolar Membrane Technology</H2>
PhD student: Dipl.-Ing. Friedrich G. Wilhelm (M.S.) (+31-53-489 3474 / <A HREF="mailto:f.g.wilhelm@ct.utwente.nl">f.g.wilhelm@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Supervisor: Dr. ir. Matthias Wessling (+31-53-489 2962)<BR>
Fax: +31-53-489 4611<BR>
Internet: <A HREF="http://utct1029.ct.utwente.nl/people/f.g.wilhelm">http://utct1029.ct.utwente.nl/people/f.g.wilhelm</A><BR>
Project term: August 1996 - July 2000<BR>
Sponsor: NWO (SON & STW)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Motivation</B><BR>
Electrodialysis with bipolar membranes has
recently gained increasing attention for the
production of acids and bases from the
corresponding salt solutions. The process is
very energy-efficient and has a multitude of
interesting applications.<BR>
Today, however, the process is affected in
many applications by unsatisfactory membrane
properties, inadequate process design, and
particularly by lack of application know-how.
Membranes available today were developed
mainly to be used for the production of
inorganic bases and acids such as NaOH or
KOH and HC1 or H<SUB>2</SUB>SO<SUB>4</SUB> from the
corresponding aqueous salt solutions. In these
applications the membrane are not exposed to
elevated temperatures or highly aggressive
chemicals.<BR>
There are a multitude of commercially very
interesting applications in the chemical industry
or the treatment of certain industrial effluents
containing highly oxidizing or chemically
aggressive components or require operation at
elevated temperatures. Thus, the development
of "better" bipolar as well as monopolar
membranes is the key-issue of the project.<P>

<B>Membrane Preparation Parameters</B><BR>
In preparing and developing better ion
exchange membranes, the underlying issues of
permselectivity, stability, and, especially for
bipolar membranes, water splitting have to be
addressed.<BR>
Chemical stability is manily influenced by
choosing the matrix polymer, the functional
fixed ionic groups and also the surface
treatment. A support layer, as well as the
spacer in the module provide the mechanical
stability. Thermal stability is mainly a property
of the matrix polymer itself; the performance at
elevated temperatures, however, is also
influenced by the functional groups and the
degree of crosslinking.<BR>
<P>

<IMG SRC="2621.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=335><P>

<I><B>Figure:</B></I> Electrodialysis cell arrangement with bipolar
membranes for the production of an acid and a base fi'om
the corresponding salt. The numbers refer to the text.<P>

High permselectivity for the counter-ions in
the (monolayer) ion exchange membranes
(IEM) and the water splitting feature in the
bipolar membrane (BPM) are the desired
properties, as shown in the <B>Figure</B>, line (1).
The parallel transport of co-ions trough the
IEM (3), also occuring in the BPM (2), limits
the purity of the achieved acid and base as well
as the current eff'lciency of the process. The
co-ion transport and the diffusion of
undissociated acid and base (4) occur mainly at
higher product concentrations. Increasing the
permselectivity and the current efficiency can
be achieved by increasing the fixed ion density
and changing the structure of the membranes,
e.g. by employing assymetric membrane layers
or composite membranes.<BR>
After testing and characterizing the obtained
membranes and comparing them to
commercially available membranes, their
performance in relevant industrial applications
will be investigated in simulation and
experiment.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 15/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
