</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dynamics and Control of Processes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Dynamics and Control of Processes</H2>
Projectleader: Prof.dr.ir. B. Roffel<BR>
Address: University of Twente, Chemical Technology Department, P.O. Box 217, 7500 AE Enschede, Netherlands<BR>
Phone: 053- 489 3596<BR>
Fax: 053- 489 3849<BR>
E mail: <A HREF="mailto:B.H.L.Betlem@utwente.ct.nl">B.H.L.Betlem@utwente.ct.nl</A><BR>
Project team: Ir. R. van Aggele, R. Azink, Ir. B.H.L. Betlem<BR>
Cooperation with:AKZO-Systems (Ede); Dow Chemical (Terneuzen); ITP TNO
(Delft); Faculty Computer Science UT, KEMA (Arnhem), Badger
(Den Haag)<BR>
Keywords: process control, quality control, neural network control, multivari-
able control, fuzzy control, dynamic optimization, object oriented
software, batch distillation<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Brief description</B><P>

In order to improve of a process and to produce better products at reduced costs,
improved process control is imperative. Techniques and methods how to achieve impro-
ved control is the central research theme of the group. This theme can be subdivided
into a number of smaller areas, namely:<P>
<UL>
<LI>advanced modelling and control of continuous processes
<LI>integration of process design and process control
<LI>dynamic optimization of batch operation
</UL>

<B>Advanced Modelling and Control</B><P>

In order to develop better control schemes for control of processes, a good knowledge
of the dynamics of the process is necessary. Some processes are relatively easy to
model, starting from first principles, such as basic energy, mass and partial mass balan-
ces. Other processes, e.g. polymerization processes are more difficult to model, since
reaction kinetics are often complicated and traces of impurities may have a large impact
on the model. Consequently, a robust model cannot so easily be derived. In such cases
it is often easier to resort to empirical models. Two approaches are followed in this
research: the development of fuzzy models and neuro-fuzzy models. Research focuses
on the techniques for the derivation of these models from industrial process data and on
the development of control schemes which make use of these models. The advantage of
this approach is that also non-linear phenomena can be modelled elegantly and in certain
cases these models are superior to linear models. It will be a major challenge to incorpo-
rate fuzzy constraints in the control strategy, and to extend the technology to processes
which are multivariable in nature.<P>

<B>Dynamic Optimization of Batch Operation</B><P>

The interest of batch processing grows with the increasing importance of products with
high-added value. As the operation is not stationary, automation of batch operation is
more complex than that of continuous operation. It requires another control filosofy (not
optimal at every moment but over a serie of batches) and models applicable over a large
operation trajectory. Issues being studied are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>design of a coordinator hierarchy based on the degrees of freedom at each control
level,
<LI>coordinator model assignment,
<LI>object oriented implementation.
</UL>
Generally, the coordinator hierarchy consists of one or more scheduler levels, a conditio-
ner determining the setpoints and a quality controller supporting the optimal operation.
In a batch distillation case study, different control hierarchies and strategies and diffe-
rent coordinator models are compared (first principles models against adaptive empirical
models).<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
